OptionB: An enlarged parotid gland which may elevate the ear lobe
Explanation:
A- a measles rash is usually first noticed on the face or neck and then spreads to the rest of the body

B- would be seen in someone who has mumps

Koplik spots are small greyish-white spots in the mouth of someone with measles.

D- a measles rash is usually red

E- has nothing to do with measles but indicates high lipids

Question: You are giving a Tetanus vaccination in a GP surgery when the nurse asks you about the different types of vaccines. You list off live attenuated vaccines, inactivated, subunit, inactivated toxoid and DNA vaccines. She then asks you what type of vaccine Tetanus is. Your reply is which of the following?
Explanation: Tetanus and Diphtheria are both examples of toxoid vaccines

Question:
An 18 year old student, suffering from melancholic depression, is rushed to A and E after his mother discovered him unconscious surrounded by several empty paracetamol packets. The toxic metabolite N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine is building up in his liver, resulting in damage to his hepatocytes. This metabolite is usually conjugated by glutathione. However, in the incidence of an overdose glutathione reserves are exhausted. 

  

 

What would you prescribe in order to raise glutathione levels to prevent further damage?
Explanation:
Acetylcysteine-

 

In the treatment of acetaminophen overdose, acetylcysteine acts to maintain or replenish depleted glutathione reserves in the liver and enhance non-toxic metabolism of acetaminophen. These actions serve to protect liver cells from NAPQI toxicity. It is most effective in preventing or lessening hepatic injury when administered within 8–10 hours after overdose.Research suggests that the rate of liver toxicity is approximately 3% when acetylcysteine is administered within 10 hours of overdose.

 

See CARDIFF CORE MEDICINESREFERENCE DATABASE4thEdition, October 2010(MBBCh YEAR 1 AND 2 MEDICINES) for more.

Question:
A diabetic, hypertensive 70 year old man presents for a follow up appointment 2 months after having a myocardial infarction. The GP performs an ECG and identifies that the patient has developed atrial fibrillation. You review his CHADVASC score and identify that he is at risk of having a stroke and therefore should be placed on an anticoagulant such as warfarin. Upon reviewing his medication, you spot a contraindication to warfarin, you point this out to the GP. 

 

Which of the following drugs is contraindicated with warfarin?
Explanation:
Since aspirin interferes with prostaglandin production, it puts patients at risk of a major haemorrhage. Hence interactions with warfarin, an anticoagulant, increases risk of a major haemorrhage. 

 

See CARDIFF CORE MEDICINESREFERENCE DATABASE for more. 

 

https://almostadoctor.co.uk/encyclopedia/myocardial-infarction-and-acute-coronary-syndromes-acs#MONA_Mnemonic_for_acute_management_of_MI

Question: A patient is admitted onto the respiratory ward after having a severe asthma attack. You are a 5th year medical student following an F1. The F1 asks you to take a NEWS score for the patient. When you take the patients blood pressure, you find her to be severely hypertensive with a blood pressure of 190 mmHg/ 120 mmHg. You mention this to the F1 who suggests anti hypertensive medication. Which of the following anti hypertensives should be avoided with an asthma patient?
Explanation:
Atenolol- Competitive antagonist sympathomimetic neurotransmitters such as catecholamines for binding at beta (1)-adrenergic receptors in the heart, and to a lesser extent at beta (2).

Also atenolol is said to be more cardioselective than other beta blockers, beta blockers are generally associated with bronchoconstriction and should be prescribed with extreme caution. 

 

The other anti hypertensives on this list are:

B- Calcium channel blocker

C- Loop diruetic. 

D- K+ sparing diruetic. 

E- ACE inhibitor.
Tags: Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13, Case 4, Case 5 revision

Question: On an ECG which one of these is considered normal?
OptionE: R wave greater than 40 small square on lead V1
Explanation:
The disrupted isoelectric could be as a result of AF or flutter, but it normal is down to people moving when having an ECG taken. 

 

A) delta waves, although not always pathological, are not normal on an ECG

B) correct

C) PR interval should be between 120-200m/s

D) QT interval should be less than 500m/s

E) QRS complex of 40 small squares is v large and signifies RV hypertrophy

Question: What is the mechanism of action of OSELTAMIVIR?
OptionA: a viral RNA nucleoside mimetic with base-pairing
OptionB: a thymidine analogue that inhibits viral reverse-transcriptase
OptionC: Acts as a guanosine analogue blocking viral DNA polymerase
OptionD: hepatically converted to oseltamivir carboxylate which acts as competitive inhibitor of viral neuraminidase
Explanation:
ACICLOVIR: converted to acyclovir triphosphate inside infected cells. Acts as a guanosine analogue blocking viral DNA polymerase (thereby limiting viral DNA replication & new virus manufacture)

 

OSELTAMIVIR: hepatically converted to oseltamivir carboxylate which acts as competitive inhibitor of viral neuraminidase (which blocks release of new virus particles from infected host cells)

 

RIBAVIRIN: a viral RNA nucleoside mimetic with base-pairing promiscuity (which causes viral hypermutation during viral RNA synthesis- lethal to viruses)

 

ZIDOVUDINE: a thymidine analogue that inhibits viral reverse-transcriptase (RT) (which can limit retroviral gene incorporation into host cell nuclear genome)

Question:
30-year old man presents with intensely itchy bullous rash in his elbow and knees. He reveals that he had the rash on and off for many years. On further questioning the man admits to also having periods of pale loose stools.

 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Celiac Symptoms: Skin Rash. For some people, celiac disease causes an itchy, blistering rash known as dermatitis herpetiformis. It may begin with an intense burning sensation around the elbows, knees, scalp, buttocks, and back.

 

Important to remember they do not always present with the classical abdominal symptoms.

Question:
A mother brings her 2 year-old child to the GP. She is worried about the development of her child. On examination, you notice that he has small, upwards slanting eyes, a flattened face and his hands have a single palmar crease.

 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
D- Down's syndrome

 

Common symptoms of Down's syndrome include:

 

Flattened nose and face, upward slanting eyes

Single palmar crease

Short fifth finger that curves inwards

White spots on iris of eye

Small ears

Skin flap on nape of neck

Question: Your are sitting in on a paediatric consultants clinic. A young mother comes in with her 1 year old child. She is worried because her son has had two seizures in the last week. On examination, the consultant observes that the child has microcephaly and an unusually happy demeanour. The consultant says he suspects a particular genetic condition, Angel man Syndrome and orders some genetic tests to confirms this. What mutation are the tests most likely to find?
Explanation:
Angelman Syndrome (AS)

Deletion inherited on MATERNAL chromosome 15

Symptoms: Microcephaly, gait ataxia, severe intellectual disability (ID), absent speech, seizures, happy demeanour.

~1:15,000–1:25,000

Question:
A 35 year-old woman is 13 weeks pregnant. She attends her dating scan and is offered a nuchal translucency scan.

 

What is the normal range for this measurement?
Explanation: Nuchal translucency scan is used to assess the risk of chromosomal abnormalities such as Down's Syndrome, Edward's Syndrome and Patau's Syndrome. It is done between 11-14 weeks. A normal measurement is between 2.5mm - 3.5mm, but anything less than 3.5mm can still be considered normal. A measurement of over 3.5mm can indicate a foetal abnormality.

Question:
You are in GP placement and encounter a 70 year old male patient who has Parkinson's disease. He experiences symptoms such as a tremor, muscle stiffness and slow movement. You notice that when he walks into the room he has a shuffling gait. 

 

 

Symptoms of this condition are caused by reduced levels of a neurotransmitter in the brain.

 

From what substance is this neurotransmitter directly formed?
Explanation:
The neurotransmitter involved in Parkinson's disease is dopamine.

 

Dopamine is synthesised from L-DOPA by the process described below.

 

 

 

Note: although dopamine is produced from tyrosine, the question specifies its direct precursor.

Question: What anion/cation is not measure in anion gap?
Explanation: ABDE= are all measured in anion Gap (potassium can occasionally be taken out of the equation as Na+ makes up the majority of the cation)

Question: What would not cause a high anion gap?
Which of the symptoms/syndromes below is NOT part of the FRIST RANK SYMPTOMS associated with schizophrenia?
Explanation:
The Schneider's first rank symptoms describe the most common characteristics of schizophrenia: 

- Delusional perception -> normal perception but comes to a bizarre conclusion 

- Passive experiences -> as if one's body is out of own control - > other external force/agency controlling it 

- Thought broadcasting -> as if people can read your thoughts 

- Thought withdrawal -> as if someone has taken thoughts out of your head 

- Thought insertion -> as if someone is planting ideas in your head 

 

 

 Word salad is also associated with schizophrenia 

 

Mania - great euphoria, excitement and erratic behaviour. Not considered a first rank of symptom of schizophrenia as such.

Question: Which of these is NOT a white matter structure?
Explanation:
The thalamus is a grey matter structure known to be part of the sensory gateway. 

It is connected to the maxillary bodies by the fornix - a white matter structure. 

 

The rest are all white matter tracts - so they are axons that connects one part of the brain to another. 

E.g the anterior & commissure and C Callosum connects corresponding gyri in the two hemispheres

Question: A man comes into A and E having suffered a gunshot wound to the abdomen. The man is bleeding profusely and is going into hypovolaemic shock. You begin to manage the patient by giving him oxygen and inserting an IV of Hartmann's solution into his left cephalic vein. In order to achieve the maximum flow rate of solution, which of the following gauges of peripheral cannula would you use to provide the fastest flow rate?
Explanation:
In order to achieve the fastest flow rate we must consider Poiseuille's law. 

This law states that the larger the radius of the tube, the greater the flow rate through the tube. Hence we want the largest gauge cannula. Confusingly, cannula gauges have smaller numbers the larger they get, hence 12 gauge would give the fastest flow rate.

Question: You are on a dialysis ward as part of your chronic illness placement block. A patient presents with peritonitis due to an infection of E coli as a complication of CAPD (continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis). Since the E coli has entered the peritoneal cavity, which of the following cells is most likely to encounter the bacteria first and secrete TNF alpha and IL8 in response to the infection?
Explanation:
Information taken from timeline of infection from case 9:

 

-Defence against bacterial infection as typified by Escherichia coli

-Intact barrier epithelia of intestinal tract acts as initial defence
-E.coli enters breach in the peritoneal cavity
-Resident macrophage activation through pattern recognition receptors leads to TNFalpha and IL-8 secretion
-TNFalpha makes local endothelium more permeable and IL8 directs recruitment of neutrophils
-Plasma leaks through leaky endothelium and lectin and alternative pathways of complement activation and deposition enhance neutrophil (and macrophage) phagocytosis leading to bacterial death in the phagolysosome
-Phagocytosis and pinocytosis of bacteria by resident conventional Dendritic Cells (cDCs) results in maturation of cDCs and their migration to draining lymph node
-Antigen presentation of bacterial surface antigen derived peptide/MHC class II complexes by cDCs to circulating naïve T cells occurs in draining lymph-node
-Naïve T cells with appropriate TCR are activated and clonally expanded in draining LN
-Effector CD4 TH17 cells are generated
-Effector CD4 TH17 T cells traffic to site of infection and release IL-17 that (indirectly) elicits further neutrophil recruitment and production in bone marrow
-Effector CD4 TFH T cells are also generated in draining lymph node
- Some intact bacteria and antigens of bacteria may also reach draining lymph node via lymph
- B cells with BCR capable recognising bacterial surface antigen are activated in draining lymph-node and secrete low affinity IgM
-B cells endocytose bacterial surface antigen and present peptide fragments of bacterial proteins on MHC Class II to cognate TFH cells
-TFH cells provides help to bacterial surface antigen-specific B cell to undergo somatic hyper-mutation and isotype switching of Ig genes
-Subsequently IgM and higher affinity IgGs act as opsonins for further phagocytic engulfment of bacteria
-Neutralising high affinity-IgG antibodies are important in defence against bacteria
-Regional lymphadenopathy results in infected tissues
-Pus formed in infections is a mixture of dead bacteria and dead phagocytes and release of lysosomal contents from phagocytes contributes to observed tissue damage
-Clearance of infection by neutralising and opsonising antibodies results in resolution of pathology
-Establishment of long-lived memory B and T cells against E.coli

Question: You are in practice as a GP. A patient comes to your surgery following a partial colectomy in an effort to reduce the spread of ulcerative colitis. In order to maintain remission of the disease you place the patient on adalimumab. What type of drug is this ?
Explanation: Adalimumab is a monoclonal antibody. You can tell this by the ending of the name 'mab'= monoclonal antibody. See NICE guidelines on ulcerative colitis for further treatment options. https://bnf.nice.org.uk/treatment-summary/ulcerative-colitis.html
Tags: Management of patient, Case 11, Immunology, NICE

Question:
A patient presents at A and E complaining of dizziness, light  headedness and palpitations. You record an ECG and receive the following results:

You decide to place the patient on digoxin in order to increase the force of myocardial contraction and reduces conductivity within the atrioventricular (AV) node. What is the mechanism of action of this drug?
OptionD: Inhibits Na+/K+ pump forcing the use of NCX pump instead.
OptionE: Causes vasodilation due to increased NO concentration.
Explanation: Digoxin is a cardiac glycoside that increases the force of myocardial contraction and reduces conductivity within the atrioventricular (AV) node.

Question:
A patient comes into your practice presenting with what you think is ulcerative colitis. She asks you what the main and most obvious diagnostic difference is between Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, she is curious as she explains her mother has suffered with Crohn's in the past.

You tell her....
OptionA: Crohn's disease inflammation is transmural, whereas ulcerative colitis isn't.
OptionB: Ulcerative colitis tends to affect the transverse colon the most extensively, but Crohn's affects all areas of the large intestine.
OptionC: Ulcerative colitis causes malabsorption of B12 and Crohn's doesn't.
OptionD: Symptoms are very different - ulcerative colitis causes mostly constipation whereas Crohn's causes diarrhoea.

Question:
You are shadowing a psychiatrist's outpatient clinic during your Case 12 placement.

 

You meet a 20 year old female patient. She has a 2 year history of severe depression and currently takes sertraline. She has tried several different drugs of this class and varying doses of these drugs, but her symptoms have still persisted. She has also tried CBT. The psychiatrist decides to try replacing her sertraline with duloxetine. 

 

 

In addition to the effect that the previous drug class had on neurotransmission in the brain, what substance will this new drug also affect?
Explanation:
Sertraline is an SSRI. This drug class selectively inhibits the serotonin transporter to increase synaptic levels of serotonin. Other SSRIs include citalopram, fluoxetine and paroxetine. 

 

Duloxetine is an SNRI. In addition to serotonin reuptake inhibition, these drugs also inhibit noradrenaline uptake. Another example of an SNRI is venlafaxine.

Question:
A 45 year old Caucasian man presents at his GP clinic.

 

He reports gradually worsening loss of appetite, nausea + vomiting and weight loss over several months. He says he feels weak and fatigued.

 

His wife persuaded him to see the GP as she is worried about his weight loss and has noticed a slight darkening of his skin colour, especially around his nails, gums and in the creases of his palms. 

 

He is not on any medications and has no relevant past medical history, but he has a family history of autoimmune disease. 

 

 

Which of these investigations would be most useful to support the GP in their diagnosis?
Explanation:
The most likely diagnosis for this patient is Addison's disease. 

 

Addison's disease = primary adrenocortical insufficiency. It is rare but can be fatal. Destruction of the adrenal cortex leads to glucocorticoid (cortisol) and mineralocorticoid (aldosterone) deficiency. It is caused by autoimmunity in 80% of cases in the UK. 

 

Addison's has an insidious onset of symptoms and often presents with non-specific symptoms e.g. fatigue, weight loss and nausea.

 

In primary adrenocortical insufficiency there is an excessive and ineffective amount of ACTH due to the failure of the adrenal gland to respond to ACTH. This can lead to the hyperpigmentation seen in this patient. 

 

A short ACTH stimulation test involves measuring cortisol levels before and after administration of synthetic ACTH. In a patient with Addison's, cortisol levels will start low and remain low, demonstrating failure to respond to the ACTH. 

 

(Information taken from Case 10 "Anatomy + Physiology of the Endocrine System" lecture and Oxford Handbook of Clinical Medicine pp. 218-219).

Question:
You are decide to go to the SU the night before placement, despite knowing that you'll have one hell of a hangover all day at Merthyr. 

 

You begin to wonder if this because you're a legend or if it is to do with you brain, after all, you are still an adolescent.

Interactions between which areas of the brain during adolescence leads to risk taking behaviour?
Explanation: Taken from Dr Hassoulas' lecture about the adolescent brain in case 12.

Question:
A 30 year old man falls off a ladder whilst painting the outside of his house. With your first aid training, you help immobile his neck before the paramedics rush him off to A and E. Once admitted, the SHO on the ward requests an X-ray of his cervical spine. 

The X-ray reveals a dislocation at the atlanto-occipital joint. With what bony feature on the occipital bone does the C1 spinal vertebrae articulate?
Explanation: The occipital condyles articulate with the C1 vertebrae to form the atlanto-occipital joint.

Question:
A 50 year old Caucasian male, Mr G, presents to his GP. He has noticed he's been gaining weight despite not changing his diet or lifestyle, along with feeling depressed and irritable most of the time. On further questioning he admits he has also been experiencing erectile dysfunction. He tells you that these physical and mental changes are affecting him emotionally and he feels it is putting a strain on his relationship with his wife.

 

On examination, Mr G displays central obesity and has a "moon faced" appearance. He has prominent purple striae on his abdomen. 

 

Mr G has a history of hypertension and asthma, for which he takes amlodipine, salbutamol and fluticasone. He has no relevant family or social history. 

 

The GP orders several investigations.

 

 

On Mr G's test results, which hormone is most likely to be elevated?
Explanation:
The most likely diagnosis for Mr G is Cushing's syndrome. This is the state caused by chronic glucocorticoid excess, and the loss of normal feedback mechanisms of the HPA axis and Circadian rhythms of cortisol secretion. 

 

Note that the patient is taking inhaled corticosteroids (fluticasone) for asthma: this could contribute to the Cushing's syndrome. You didn't need to know this to answer the question as the clinical features should've been enough!

 

Anything that causes ↑ cortisol levels can lead to Cushing's syndrome. This could be causes leading to ↑ ACTH e.g. ACTH-secreting tumours, or causes that directly increase corticosteroid levels e.g. pharmacological administration. 

 

Treatment involves reversing any reversible causes of glucocorticoid excess e.g. stopping medications or surgical interventions for tumours.

Question: Dr Smith is carrying out a back examination. He thinks back to his back anatomy lectures. What is the first vertebrae you can feel in your neck?
Explanation: If you put your hand on the back of your head just above your neck you will feel a large bump called the occipital protuberance. Run your finger directly towards your feet in the midline of your spine. The first large,hard bump you feel at the tip of your neck is the spinous process of C2 (axis).

Question: How many vertebrae are there?
Explanation:
7 Cervical

12 Thoracic

5 Lumbar

5 Sacral

4 Coccygeal

 

Gray's Anatomy Text Book!!

Question: What is the part labelled 6?
Explanation:
It is the lamina,

 

Pedicle= 4

Spinous Process=2

Transverse Process= 3

Facet for rib= 7

Question: This histology slide is taken from an intervertebral disc. What type of tissue is it showing?
Explanation:
A) Chondrocytes are the cells that make up cartilage. The extracellular matrix of cartilage is secreted by chondroblasts, (chondro = cartilage), which are found in the outer covering layer of cartilage. As the chondroblasts secrete matrix and fibres, they become trapped inside it, and mature into cells called chondrocytes.

 

B) Elastic cartilage is found in the external ear, epiglottis and larynx. 

 

C) Correct! Fibrocartilage is in intervertebral discs, joint capsules and ligaments. 

 

D) Hyaline cartilage is the most common type of cartilage found in the ribs, nose, larynx and trachea. It is a precursor to bone. 

 

E) Osteocytes are cells that maintain bone tissue. Fine processes from these cells ramify through bone, and form gap junctions with other osteocytes.

Question: Patient presents to A and E with a completely severed hand. You discuss with a multidisciplinary team on the likelihood of reattaching the hand. Among the many hurdles is the damage to the peripheral nerves of the hand. Which of the following best describes the Seddon and Sunderland classification of this particular nerve injury?
Explanation: In this incidence, the nerve has been completely severed, both the axon and the surrounding myelin sheath have been divided. In order to repair this injury, the surgeon will have to suture the epineurium to allow for the regrowth of axons.

Question:
You meet a 20 year old female patient on a surgical ward who is about to undergo a preventative total colectomy. She explains to you that although she doesn't have any symptoms currently, she has almost a 100% chance of developing colorectal cancer if she doesn't have her colon removed. 

 

 

Which of these is the most likely indication for her surgery?
Explanation:
Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) is an autosomal dominant condition resulting from mutations in the APC gene on chromosome 5. It is characterised by the presence of hundreds to thousands of colorectal + duodenal adenomas, giving the bowel an appearance similar to the image below.

 

 

The penetrance of this condition is virtually 100%. If untreated, the average age of adenoma development is 16 and the average age of colorectal cancer development is 39.

Question: Julius Caesar was stabbed to death on the Senate floor in Rome on the 15th March 44BC. Being stabbed directly in the back between the T5 and T6 would be rather difficult to achieve due to a feature unique to the thoracic vertebrae. Which of the following features described below would hinder a knife from piercing a thoracic intervertebral disc?
OptionA: Lack of a vertebral body, with an odontoid process instead
OptionB: Presents of a long spinous process slanting superiorly
OptionE: Presents of a long spinous process slanting inferiorly
Explanation: The thoracic vertebrae have long, inferiorly slanting spinous processes. These processes protect the spinal cord from external damage.

Question: You are inserting a central line into a patient's internal jugular vein. A few hours later you return to assess the progress of the patient. He complains that he is unable to shrug his shoulders bilaterally. You begin to panic and check to make sure your MPS membership is still in date as you realise that you have severed a nerve. What nerve have you likely severed?
Explanation: You have severed CN XI the accessory nerve, responsible for the innervation of sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.

Question:
James, a 12 year old boy, presents to your GP clinic with his mother. 

 

On appearance he seems lethargic, is hyperventilating and has hyperactive reflexes. 

 

James' mother tells you that he has had back pain for the past few weeks and she is worried that he may now have a back infection as in the last week or so he has developed a fever, has been vomiting and seems to be in a trance all the time. 

 

You ask if she has been giving James any pain relief for his back and his mother says he has been taking some aspirin that she bought over the counter as it works wonders for her headaches. 

 

What is the best management for James?
OptionA: Provide some stronger painkillers, such as morphine for his back as the vomiting etc could be due to pain
OptionB: Advise he stops taking the aspirin immediately and switch to ibuprofen or paracetamol to manage the back pain
OptionC: Prescribe antibiotics for the spinal infection he has
OptionD: Do nothing- he has influenza so it just needs bed rest
OptionE: Prescribe antivirals for the spinal infection- he has viral encephalitis
Explanation:
James is showing symptoms of Stage II Reye's Syndrome (vomiting, encephalitis induced stupour, hyperventilation, hyperactive reflexes, steatosis) which affects the liver and the brain.  

 

Reye's Syndrome can be caused by giving aspirin to children under the age of 16. He needs to stop the aspirin immediately and may need to be monitored in hospital to reduce the pressure in the cranium. Liver function tests can be used as a diagnosis.

Question:
You are part of a resuscitation team attending a crash call on a medical ward. When you arrive, you see Mrs P, a 50 year old female who is unresponsive and has no pulse. CPR has already been started by the time you get there, and you attach monitoring + defibrillation equipment while chest compressions are being carried out by another member of the team. The monitor shows the rhythm below. 

 

 

What is the best next step in managing Mrs P?
Explanation:
The rhythm that Mrs P is in is ventricular tachycardia.

 

This is a shockable rhythm and so the next step would be to deliver one DC shock, then resume CPR for 2 minutes, and repeat.
Tags: Clinical skills, ECG, Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13

Question: You are working in A and E when a 60 year old lady presents with a painful neck having fallen off a ladder. You treat the injury as if it were a spinal cord injury and immobile her neck in order to prevent any further damage. X-rays of the cervical spinal column reveal that a cancer has metastasised to her C4 vertebrae. You question the woman more with regards to her history of cancer. Which cancer from the following was she most likely to have been the primary site of the cancer?
Explanation:
•Breast 21%

•Lung 19%

•Unknown 10%

•Prostate 10%

•Lymphoma 8%

•Kidney 6%

•Myeloma 5%

 

1432 patients. Grant R. Neurolclin1991 

 

According to Serious Spinal Pathology 2 -Metastatic Spinal Cord Compression and Spinal Infections

Question: You are walking through your kitchen barefoot when you step on a piece of smashed glass. The somatosensory cortex is responsible for processing this pain and responding appropriately to it. Where would you find the somatosensory cortex?
OptionA: Post central gyrus of the parietal lobe
OptionB: Pre central gyrus of the frontal lobe

Question: What are the 3 major functions of the spinal column?
Explanation:
The three main functions of the spine are to: Protect the spinal cord, nerve roots and several of the body's internal organs, movements, and support.

 

From the first lecture.

Question: What is this X-ray showing?
Explanation: Lumbar spondylolysis, a unilateral or bilateral stress fracture of the narrow bridge between the upper and lower pars interarticularis, is a common cause of low back pain (LBP) in adolescent athletes.

Question:
The junction in Roath between Crwys Road, Albany Road, City Road, Mackintosh Place and Richmond Road is known as Death Junction. In 1679, two priests were hung, drawn and quartered at this junction. 

 

When hung, many people would jump, so their neck would break and they would die quickly. Part of the spinal vertebrae would snap, hit the medulla oblongata and cause instant death. 

 

   

 

Which part of the anatomy could cause this?
Explanation: The correct answer is E. The odontoid peg can snap and hit the medulla oblongata. All of the other processes are on the wrong side of the spinal cord to have this effect.

Question: An elderly female patient presents with cervical spondylosis. She describes a prior history of osteoarthritis. You perform a peripheral neurological examination and observe that she has lost function in various parts of her body suggestive of a central cord syndrome. Which of the following tracts within the spinal cord is most likely to remain functional?
Explanation: In a central cord lesion, the structures within the middle of the cord are more likely to be impacted. The peripheral structures are more likely to be preserved. Hence sacral tracts are more likely to continue to function.

Question:
20 year old male presents at your surgery after 6 weeks of lower back pain. He doesn't complain of any neurological symptoms or any loss of bowel/bladder function. He does however have tenderness around his sacroiliac joints and reduced lumbar flexion. Further history taking reveals a past history of inflammatory bowel disease. You decide to take a blood test which reveals the following notable features :

 

-Raised CRP

-Positive genotyping for HLA B27 

-No rheumatoid factor.

 

Which of the following most likely fits the diagnosis given this information?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Ankylosing spondylitis is a Seronegative Arthropathy, meaning that it is not associated with a raised rheumatoid factor. Another key feature of ankylosing spondylitis is its association with the HLA B27 gene. 

 

Typically effects young males and can result in the fusing of the lumbar spine, hence the reduced lumbar flexion.

Question: Parathyroid hormone is released in response to low levels in Ca2+ in the blood stream. Which of the following describes a mechanism by which parathyroid hormone acts in order to increase the Ca2+ concentration in the blood stream?
OptionD: Stimulating cardiac myocytes to dump Ca2+ stored in their sarcoplasmic reticula into extracellular space
Explanation:
PTH:

Increases osteoclast activity. This causes a break done in bone causing a release of stored calcium. 

Increases tubular reabsorption of calcium.

Increases intestinal absorption of calcium.

Increases 1 alpha-hydroxylation of vitamin D.

Question: A patient presents at your practice with a fractured radius. She is a 66 year old woman who frequently presents with bone fractures. You suspect osteoporosis and as such request a DEXA scan. Which of the following describes a diagnostic criteria indicative of a diagnosis of osteoporosis?
OptionA: T score below 1 standard deviation from the mean
OptionB: T score above 1 standard deviation from the mean
OptionC: T score below 2 standard deviations from the mean
OptionD: T score above 2 standard deviations from the mean
OptionE: T score below 2.5 standard deviations from the mean.
Explanation:
In a DEXA scan, a T score is difference in bone density between you and a health young adult (peak bone density in life) with gender and race adjusted. Whereas a Z score accounts for the difference in bone density between you someone of your age accounting for gender and race. 

 

A T score of below 2.5 standard deviations indicates osteoporosis. Between 1-2.5 standard deviations is defined as osteopenia.

Question:
You are a 2nd year Medical Student on your Case 14 CCL. You are practising lower limb neurological examinations on a 72 year old patient who has told you he suffers from a 'slipped disc'. 

On examination you find:

Normal hip flexion and big toe extension.

The patient expresses that his right knee is very sore when you ask his to extend it and ankle dorsiflexion is also difficult. 

 

You also notice that:

The knee reflex is dampened. 

Ankle Reflex and Plantar reflex is normal. 

 

What is the likely level of the patients Prolapsed disc?
Explanation:
On movement:

Knee extension is affected - L3

Ankle Dorisflexion is affected - L4

 

Reflexes -

Knee reflex is affected - L3/L4

ankle reflex is fine - S1

plantar relfex is fine - L5/S1

Question: Which of these structures below are made from primary ossification?
Explanation:
The centrum and 2 halves of each arch form from mesoderm in utero by the 14th week 

However, the tips of the spinous & transverse processes  and the articular surfaces all ossify at puberty by secondary ossification.

Question: Patient complains of a loss of sensation in their middle three toes of their right foot. Which dermatome is responsible for the innervation of this area?

The following are simplified results of CSF fluids 

 

Opening pressure: normal 

Appearance: clear

WBCs: ++ lymphocytes 

Glucose: normal 

Protein: slightly increased 

 

What type of meningitis is this?
Explanation:
Viral meningitis characteristic is clear fluid with a marked increased in lymphocytes 

Glucose, protein and RBCs can be slightly increased or normal 

 

Bacterial would have a turbid, yellow appearance with a high opening pressure, low glucose and high protein count. 

Gram stain usually positive as well 

 

TB/fungal have a yellow, fibrin like appearance with also a marked increase in lymphocytes 

Quite similar to viral tbh :)

Question: How does oestrogen protect against osteoporosis?
OptionD: It promotes release of osteoprotegrin by osteoblasts
OptionE: It promotes release of osteoprotegrin by osteoclasts
Explanation:
Oestrogen actually inhibits RANKL release from osteoblasts. 

RANKL usually binds to its receptor, RANK on the osteoclast precursors which, with the help of M-CSF allows it to mature into an osteoclast. 

 

Osteoprotegrin is also produced by osteoblasts and is a competitive inhibitor of RANKL so it down regulates osteoclast maturation but oestrogen does not directly act on this.

Question:
Dorothy Hamill is an ex-figure skater who won a gold medal in the 1976 Winter Olympics in Innsbruck, Austria. She competed in Dancing with the Stars in 2013, but had to drop out under the advice of a spinal surgeon. 

 

Hamill's scans showed a Scottie Dog sign. 

 

  

 

What does this sign show?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B, spondylolysis. This is defined as a defect or stress fracture in the pars interarticularis of the vertebral arch. This can lead to spondylolisthesis, a slippage of the vertebrae over one another. 

 

A - a painful condition of the spine resulting from the degeneration of the intervertebral discs. It is a broad term meaning degeneration of the spinal column from any cause. In the more narrow sense it refers to spinal osteoarthritis, the age-related wear and tear of the spinal column, which is the most common cause of spondylosis.

C - Spondylololysis - Made up 

D - Spondylolisthesis is the slippage or displacement of one vertebra compared to another. It can be caused by spondylolysis. 

E - Spondylolithesolysis - Made up

Question: What is 1 on the diagram?
Explanation:
The sheath of connective tissue surrounding a bundle (fascicle) of nerve fibres within a nerve.

In the peripheral nervous system, the myelin sheath of each axon in a nerve is wrapped in a delicate protective sheath known as the endoneurium. Within the nerve, axons targeting the same anatomical location are bundled together into groups known as fascicles, each surrounded by another protective sheath known as the perineurium.

Question:
A normally healthy child presents to clinic with an exaggerated lumbar lordosis and very tight hamstrings, apart from that the spine examination was normal. 

There is some radicular (nerve) pain but no urinary or bowel symptoms. 

The child has suffered from low back pain for the past 4 weeks. 

 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
According to Mr McCarthy's lecture, kids often suffer form spondylolisthesis where there is slipping forward of one vertebral body onto another - especially around L5/S1. It can be developmental or acquired. 

Characteristic feature: lumbar lordosis and tight hamstrings

Often LBP, radicular pain and +/- urinary/bowel symptoms. 

 

For acquired - can be due to spondylolysis which predisposes to spondylolisthesis. Spondylolysis is where the pars interarticularis weakens/breaks - especially in children who take part in sports like diving and gymnastics. Would usually treat non-operatively - e.g. braces. 

 

Indications for surgery:

- if conservative treatment fails 

- if the patient is immature - as they grow the slip will get worse and hurt more and possibly cause more nerve compression

- high grade slips

Question:
You are reviewing a patient who comes into your surgery 1 year after having an ileectomy. The patient complains of being 'tired all of the time' even during little exertion. Further history taking reveals weakness of legs, arms, trunk, tingling and numbness that has been getting progressively worse over the year. Examination reveals a positive Babinski sign. You are aware that in cases of B12 deficiency (pernicious anaemia) that myelin production maybe impacted. As such issues arise with the spinal cord. 

 

 

The patient complains of a lack of fine movement of ipsilateral limbs as part of their symptoms. Which tract is most likely to be affected by the pernicious anaemia giving rise to this particular symptom?
Explanation:
Since this symptom is referring to a loss of fine motor skill in the limbs the answer is the corticospinal tract. Movement is diminished in the limbs, the medial corticospinal tract is responsible for axial muscle fine motor movements. 

 

Other key points to note, the spinothalamic tract, the ventrolateral and the anterolateral system are synonymous and are ascending pathways for pain and temperature modalities. 

 

In this particular case, the patient developed pernicious anaemia as a result of an insufficiency in B12 absorption after the ileum was removed. B12 is required for myelin production, hence 'subacute combined degeneration of spinal cord'. In this condition the 'combined' refers to damage to the dorsal column and lateral corticospinal tracts.

 

Treatment involves B12 supplementation to prevent further damage.
Tags: Biochem, Neuroanatomy, Case 10, Case 11, Function of GI

Question:
Due to a saw accident, there is nerve damage in the hand. 

The whole trunk is divided and there is no axonal continuity. What is the Sunderland classification of this type of damage?
Explanation:
In neuropraxia, there is myelin sheath damage so conduction is slowed. This is class I. 

 

In axonotmesis, there is some form of damage to the actual axon so there is NO CONDUCTION:

- Class II: axon damage but endoneurium still intact. 

- Class III: axon damage but there is endoneurium damage 

- Class IV: axon damage but there is endoneurium and perineurium damage 

 

In neurotmesis, the whole axon is usually damaged right up to the epineurium 

- Class V: whole trunk is divided 

- Class VI: mixed nerve - hardest to recover. Varies from fascicle to fascicle.

Question:
Patient comes into your practice complaining of lower back pain for 6 weeks. They have been trying to self manage at home with NSAIDs and some exercises that a friend taught them at work. 'None of this is working', they complain of being tired and of 'heart burn' putting them off their food. They look really desperate and beg you to help. You order a full blood count which reveals:

 

-Raised CRP 

-Normal White cell count

-Hypochromic, microcytic anaemia

-MCV of 75fl 

 

What is the most likely explanation for microcytic anaemia in this patient?
Explanation:
This question highlights how one pathology can lead to another. In this case the patient has microcytic anaemia. This is generally associated with a deficiency in Fe. In the stem, the patient complains of 'heart burn' and has been taking NSAIDs for his back pain. This would put him at risk of a GI bleed and would explain the cause of the anaemia. 

 

Alcholism, B12 deficiency and hypothyroidism are all associated with macrocytic anaemia.
Tags: Case 10, Case 11, Function of GI, Case 14

Question: Which of these tumours are benign?
Explanation:
Benign - aneurysmal bone cyst, giant cell tumour, haemangioma, osteoid osteoma and osteoblastoma 

Malignant - chondrosarcoma, osteosarcoma (most common tumour of spinal cord), chordoma and myeloma (most common tumour in spine - arises from plasma cells). 

 

Extradural - schwannoma and meningioma 

Extra-medullary (so inside the dura but outside of spinal cord) - above and neurofibroma 

Intra-medullary (within spinal cord)- astrocytoma, ependymoma and haemangioblastoma

Question: You are running a sexual health clinic at a university campus. A 25 year old post-grad student comes in with a suspect Chlamydiatrachomatis infection. Whilst she is in the consultation, you notice that she seems to have difficulty getting out of her chair. Further questioning reveals that she has had painfully inflamed knees as well as conjunctivitis. Urinalysis does not reveal raised uric acid levels. What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The correct answer is reactive arthritis. This is a form of inflammatory arthritis caused by a primary infection somewhere else within the body. It is characterised by a triad of symptoms:

-Inflammatory arthritis in large joints.

-Inflammation of eyes, conjunctivitis 

-Urethritis/cervicitis. 

 

Often linked to intestinal/ GU infection. Tends to occur more in men than women, incidence 20-40 years old.

Associated with HLA B27 gene.

Question: What is the normal Atlas Dens Interval (ADI) in children?
Explanation:
It's about 3mm for adults but 5mm in children is still normal. 

Steel's rule of C1 - 1/3 peg, 1/3 cord and 1/3 CSF. 

 

AP view can't properly visualise C1 and C2 so a peg view is usually used for just atlas and axis. 

note: joints of luschka only really found in C3-C7 so you can't see it in PEG view

Question:
Gerald is a patient with known sensory problems and you have been asked to assess his dermatomes. He is very unhappy with your examination technique and raises his middle finger to you.

 

You rub cotton wool on his middle finger and he is shocked not to feel anything. 

 

 

Which dermatome is not functioning in Gerald?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C7, D. 

 

I really struggled with dermatomes before watching this video, which explains them very quickly and easily.

Question: Which of these is NOT a 1st or 2nd line treatment of osteoporosis?
Explanation:
From the bone health and disease lecture 

 

1st line medication: 

Bisphosphonates e.g. alendronate and risedronate 

- They basically inhibits osteoclast so inhibits boner resorption. 

- But more likely to get stress fractures as inhibits the physiological remodelling process  

 

2nd line medication:

- Raloxifene

- Strontium 

 

Specialist medication 

- Teriparatide 

This is a PTH analogue - basically stimulate bone production so acts on osteoblasts 

 

Best way to prevent osteoporosis really is to do more exercise - as this increases remodelling & strengthens bones 

Other ways - calcium and Vit D supplements 

Don't smoke! :)

Question: A patient in her third trimester comes into your practice complaining of lower back pain. You explain that some of the ligaments of her pelvis are beginning to soften to aid in labour. You also explain that due to the alteration of the normal line of gravity, that her vertebral column will begin to change to accommodate. Which of the following vertebral columns would you expect to see in a late third trimester pregnancy?
Explanation: In the late stages of pregnancy, the vertebral column accommodates by developing a temporary lumbar lordosis.  This is pathologically associated with weakened trunk musculature in the anterolateral abdominal wall.

Question:
A 38 year old man presents with back pain and hip pain. Upon examination, you see that he is febrile. He tells you that the pain is unremitting, even at night and after taking paracetamol. 

 

The man has no history of cancer and no family history of cancer. 

 

What is the most likely cause of his back pain?
OptionB: Staphylococcus aureus infection in the lumbar spine
OptionC: Staphylococcus aureus infection in the thoracic spine
OptionD: Escherichia coli infection in the lumbar spine
Explanation:
While all the answers are possible, B is the most likely cause of the man's back pain.

 

 

Patient and family history of cancer is the biggest indicator of tumour, therefore we can say it's more likely that this man has infection due to the lack of history of cancer. 

The most common cause of spinal infection is Staphylococcus aureus.

The most common site of spinal infection is the lumbar spine. 

The hip pain is likely due to the psoas muscle being infected by the organism. 

 

 

From Mr McCarthy's lecture on spinal infections (and tumour)

Question: You are given an ECG and are told that the patient has suffered from a LATERAL myocardial infarction, due to occlusion of the left circumflex artery. On which combination of leads would you most likely find ST elevation indicating this type of MI?
Explanation:
Inferior MI- II, III, aVF- Right coronary artery

Lateral MI- I, aVL, V5, V6- Left circumflex artery

Anterior MI- V3, V4- Left Anterior Descending artery

Question: A 45-year-old gentleman presents to the general practice complaining of hearing loss. This has occurred gradually over nine months. He works in construction and thought this was due to using loud power tools, though he always wears ear protection. For approximately the same amount of time, he has heard a high-pitched ringing in his ears.This past two weeks he has been getting episodes of dizziness, where he feels like the room is spinning. Otoscopy shows no abnormalities. On performing the Rinne and Weber tests, you find the Rinne test is positive bilaterally, and on Weber test, the sound is louder on the left. What can you deduce from this?
Explanation:
The Rinne and Weber tests are both tests for hearing loss. When used together they can direct the clinician to the affected side and the type of hearing loss that has occurred. However, when used separately, as in this question they give only limited information.

The Weber test involves placing a tuning fork on the forehead in the midline, the patient then reports if the sound is symmetrical or louder on one side. A normal patient, or a patient with an equal symmetrical hearing loss, will hear the sound equally on both sides. A patient with a conductive hearing loss on one side will hear the sound louder on the affected side, as the sensorineural system is exaggerated to accommodate the conductive loss. A patient with sensorineural loss will hear the sound louder on the non-affected side.

Question: Which of these myotomes correspond with the ANKLE jerk reflex?
Explanation:
From the ASIA chart and geeky medics:

 

Lower limb: 

L3/L4 - knee jerk reflex 

L5/S1 - ankle jerk reflex 

S1- plantar reflex

 

For the upper limb: 

C5/C6 - biceps reflex 

C7 - triceps reflex 

C6 - supinator

Question: What releases intrinsic factor in the stomach?
Explanation: Parietal cells (also known as oxyntic or delomorphous cells), are the epithelial cells that secrete hydrochloric acid (HCl) and intrinsic factor.

Question:
Wyn, a 58 year old man, is given some local anaesthetic for a minor operation. He tells you afterwards that he could feel different senses disappearing at different times. 

 

   

 

Which was the first sense Wyn would have lost?
Explanation:
The answer is A, sharp touch (pain).

 

The order is as they are laid out here, A B C D E.

 

These were listed by Ryan Trickett in his first lecture of Case 14.

Question:
Keith has recently picked up a nerve injury by falling onto the pointy side of his hammer while trying to build a stubborn Ikea bookshelf.

 

His medical notes from the neurologists say that he has "loss of axonal and endoneurial continuity". 

 

     

 

Using the Sunderland classification of nerve injuries, what is this injury described as?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C, Class III. 

 

This is the table from Mr Trickett's first lecture of Case 14.

Question:
You get a phone call from nurses in intensive care that one of the patients is in a state of shock. You remember that this is "Inadequate organ perfusion and tissue oxygenation". 

 

The nurse tells you that the heart rate is dropping and is now very low. 

 

   

 

What type of shock is the patient most likely to be in?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. 

 

Neurogenic shock is the only form of shock that causes a decrease in heart rate. This is because there is no sympathetic stimulation of the heart, but there is still vagal tone slowing the heart rate. It also causes hypotension due to loss of blood vessel tone. 

 

All of the other answers are forms of shock that cause tachycardia. 

 

This information is in Mike McCarthy's Serious Spinal Pathology 1 lecture.

Question:
Frank enters your surgery with a severe deformity in his back. His scans show that he had >5° anterior wedging of 3 contiguous vertebrae. His total angle of kyphosis is clearly more than 45°.

 

There are no stress fractures within his vertebrae, or tumours around them. 

 

   

 

What do you diagnose Frank with?
Explanation:
Frank has Schuermann's Disease, E. This was called Schuermann's Kyphosis in Spine Dragon's lecture, but all sources online seem to call it Schuermann's Disease. 

 

Marfan's disease, Ankylosing Spondylitis, Neurofibromatosis and Schuermann's disease can all cause kyphosis, but in different ways. 

 

 

Marfan's Disease is a connective tissue disorder rather than a disorder with the bone itself. It more often causes scoliosis than kyphosis. 

 

Ankylosing Spondylitis causes fractures in the vertebrae that could have been picked up on the scans. 

 

Neurofibromatosis causes kyphosis by inducing tumours close to the spine, causing malformations. 

 

Schuermann's disease has unknown cause, but is an error in the endplates fusing. It is characterised by

Question:
Dai Llewellyn (left) was a Welsh socialite, playboy and UKIP politician. He famously said "Some people may call being a playboy a useless occupation, but I'm not so sure. I've not only had fun myself, but there has been fun for many others."

 

 

He died in 2009 of metastatic bone cancer. 

 

      

 

In which part of the spine are metastases most likely to arise?
Explanation: The correct answer is B, thoracic. They account for 70% of spinal mets, particularly at T4-7. This is mainly because there are more thoracic vertebrae than lumbar or cervical vertebrae. Lumbar vertebrae house 20% of mets, with the other 10% in cervical vertebrae.

Question:
While tending to his snapdragons, Spine Dragon leaned too far and heard his back 'snap'. He loses sensory and motor function and you see him in A&E. 

 

You recognise spinal trauma as a serious cause of spinal injury. 

 

    

 

Which of the following is not considered a 'serious cause' of back pain?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. The mnemonic we were told was "Don't be ATIT".

 

The serious causes of back pain are:

- Abdominal/Retroperitoneal causes 

- Spinal Trauma

- Spinal Infection

- Spinal Tumour

 

Trauma could be included as mechanical, but the majority of low back pain is caused by non-trauma related mechanical back pain.

Question:
You carry out an abdominal examination on Jerry, a patient in the ward.

 

Jerry has a symptom known as Dupuytren's Contracture, as shown below.

 

 

What is the most likely cause of abdominal problems considering this sign?
OptionC: He has poor nutrition in his diet
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. Dupuytren's Contracture is linked with excessive alcohol consumption, which is likely to lead to liver cirrhosis and cause abdominal problems. 

 

It is also seen in smokers (A) but heavy alcohol consumption is more likely to cause abdominal disease than smoking is. 

Poor nutrition, C, could be seen as leukonychia (white marks) on the nails.

E, Iron deficiency anaemia, could be seen as koilonychia on the nails (Spoon shaped nails).

Question:
During a clinical examination of a patient you carry out the test for Murphy's Sign.

 

You place your hand at the right costal margin in the mid-clavicular line. You ask the patient to take a deep breath.


The patient suddenly develops pain and stops inspiring. When the test is repeated on the left there is no pain. 

 

   

 

What pathology is a positive Murphy test indicative of?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E, cholecystitis. Gallstones make the gall bladder tender. When it passes over the examiner's fingers, the patient will feel pain. 

 

This test can be used to differentiate cholecystitis from other sources of right upper quadrant pain, as A and C, ascending cholangitis and pyelonephritis can cause a similar pain but will give a negative Murphy's sign.

Question: ANP, atrial natriuretic peptide is being used to treat congestive heart failure in Japan. It acts to reduce expanded extracellular fluid and is secreted by the atrial in response to volume expansion. Which of the following best describes how ANP works to reduce excess venous blood volume?
OptionB: Stimulates the sympathetic nervous system supplying the kidneys
OptionD: Dilates the glomerular afferent arterioles and constricts the glomerular efferent arterioles.
OptionE: Increases renal sodium re absorption in the DCT.
Explanation:
ANP acts to increase sodium excretion by increasing the GFR, reducing the RAAS and reducing sodium re absorption. 

 

For more information 

https://academic.oup.com/cardiovascres/article/51/3/489/369493

Question: You visit a patient with heart failure at his home as he hasn't attended any of his appointments for several weeks despite previous engaging with health care providers. When you arrive, you find that he is lying in his bed with 4  pillows and has dyspnoea even at rest. According to the New York Heart Failure Classification, which of the following is most appropriate?
Explanation:
There are 4 classes in the NYHA:

 

New York (NYHA) classification of heart failure
Class I (Mild): Heart disease present, but no undue dyspnoea from ordinary activity.
Class II (Mild): Comfortable at rest; dyspnoea on ordinary activities.
Class III (Moderate): Less than ordinary activity causes dyspnoea, which is limiting.
Class IV (Severe): Dyspnoea present at rest; all activity causes discomfort.

 

See the first lecture of case 15.

Question:
As a GP, you receive blood results for Mr Griffin, whose BNP level is high. You remember that BNP stands for "Brain Natriuretic Peptide". 

   

 

Where is this hormone secreted?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. It is NOT secreted by the brain, but instead when stretch receptors are activated in the ventricles. 

 

BNP causes widespread vasodilation and as the 'natriuretic' part of its name says, it causes an increase in the excretion of sodium. This causes a decrease in blood pressure across the body and is one of the compensatory mechanisms of heart failure. 

 

It seems counterintuitive to activate RAAS to increase blood pressure and BNP to decrease blood pressure, but this is because a decreased ejection fraction results in more blood remaining in the ventricles, causing stretch.

Question:
Patient presents complaining of chest pain, dyspnoea and SOB on rest. They have a history of myocardial infarction as well as poorly controlled hypertension. An ECG reveals they are currently in atrial fibrillation. Respiratory examination reveals crackles in the lung bases indicative of pulmonary oedema, this is confirmed with a chest X ray. You treat this as decompensated heart failure and begin and initial pharmacological regime of ACE inhibitors and IV diuretics. 

 

  

When administering IV diuretics, which of the following is the most important to monitor with a heart failure patient?
Explanation:
When administering IV diuretics to a patient with heart failure we must consider that the patient might also have strained renal function. Monitoring renal function is important to ensure that diuretics do not cause further renal dysfunction. 

 

 

Check out NICE guidelines on the management of acute and chronic heart failure for more.

Question:
You are reviewing a 55 year old male patient with a previous history of severe hypertension. Renal function tests reveal a eGFR of 12mL/min/1.73m2. You explain to the patient that he is currently in stage 5 CKD and will have to commence dialysis within the next few months. You refer to a nephrologist who suggests a biopsy of the kidney. The biopsy reveals the following histological pattern. 

Which of the following explanations best describes the histological changes you would observe in hypertensive nephropathy?
OptionA: Deposits of fibrinogen in arterial walls and glomeruli leading to 'hylanisation'.
OptionC: Thinning of the arterial walls leading to haemorrhage.
OptionD: Plaque formation in the lumen of large arteries.
OptionE: Metaplasia leading to changes in the cell types in the epithelium.
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. High blood pressure leads to the depositing of fibrinogen in the arterioles and the glomeruli. This leads the thickening of media layer reducing the size of the lumen of the arterioles. This leads to artheriosclerosis which eventually leads to ischaemia of structures within the kidney. This leads to chronic kidney disease. 

 

B- Describes granuloma formation, where macrophages wall off infective material which can't be destroyed. E.g TB infection. 

C- Describes an aneurysm.

D- Describes atherosclerosis. 

E- Describes changes in the histology in the epithelium, numerous examples such as Barrett's oesphagus.

 

See Hypertension and the Kidney by Dr Tim Johnson for more.
Tags: Kidneys, Case 10, Case 15, Case 3 revision, Case 4

Question: Patient complains of persistent headaches for the last few weeks. You take his blood pressure and find him to be hypertensive 150/100 mmHg. Continuous ambulatory monitoring over 24h is consistent with the value obtained in practice. Life style changes and hypertensive therapy are suggested and prescribed. Several weeks later, despite compliance to therapy, the hypertension remains. You decide to take an aldosterone:renin ratio in order to screen for another cause. Which of the following would a high aldosterone:renin ratio be potentially indicative of?
Explanation:
Conn's syndrome/primary hyperaldosteronism 

 

Primary aldosteronism, also known as primary hyperaldosteronism or Conn's syndrome, is excess production of the hormone aldosterone by the adrenal glands resulting in low renin levels. Often it produces few symptoms.Most people have high blood pressure which may cause poor vision or headaches. Occasionally there may be muscular weakness, muscle spasms, tingling sensations, or excessive urination. Complications include cardiovascular disease such as stroke, myocardial infarction, kidney failure, and abnormal heart rhythms.

 

Primary hyperaldosteronism has a number of causes. About 66% of cases are due to enlargement of both adrenal glands and 33% of cases are due to an adrenal adenoma that produces aldosterone. Other uncommon causes include adrenal cancer and an inherited disorder called familial hyperaldosteronism. Some recommend screening people with high blood pressure who are at increased risk while others recommend screening all people with high blood pressure for the disease. Screening is usually done by measuring the aldosterone-to-renin ratio in the blood with further testing used to confirm positive results. While low blood potassium is classically described this is only present in about a quarter of people. To determine the underlying cause medical imaging is carried out.

 

Source glorious wiki. 

 

See Tim Johnson, hypertension and the kidney for more.

Question: Granular Juxtaglomerular cells are primarily found in which structure in the nephron
Explanation:
Juxtaglomerular cells release renin in response to low blood pressure via:

Sympathetic activation of beta adrenoceptors

Activation by the macula densa

Explanation: Case 7

Question: Semen contains high concentrations of which immunoglobulin?

Question: Which condition is characterised by a low sperm motility?
Explanation:
A) Azoospermia is when there is no sperm in the ejaculate 

B) Aspermia is when there is no ejaculate

C) Hypospermia is when there is low ejaculate volume (<1.5ml)
