Question: Miss Peg is fighting off an viral infection. What type of cell can activate her naive T-Cells?
Explanation:
CD8= Virus

 

A naïve CD8+ T cell requires co-stimulation (via B7-CD28) in addition to a signal through the TCR to become fully activated and this requirement can only be effectively satisfied by the conventional Dendritic Cell that expresses large amounts of B7 (otherwise termed CD80). Hence, the key role of cDCs in activating CD8 and CD4 T cells in the draining lymph node. However, once activated into a CD8 effector CTL, the CTL leaves the lymph node to traffic to infected tissues and the requirement for co-stimulation no longer applies. Hence, any infected cell expressing MHC Class I and presenting the appropriate peptide can now potentially be killed.

 

See 'Plenary Lecture Phase 3 ‘Adaptive immune response to viruses – Effector T and B cells’ for more information

Question: Patient presents with shortness as breath as part of their symptoms associated with left sided heart failure. Left sided heart failure results in pulmonary oedema. This occurs when additional fluid enters the interstitial space between the alveoli and the capillaries. This makes the diffusion of oxygen from the alveoli to the capillaries more difficult. Which of the following physiological changes in heart failure causes this pulmonary oedema?
OptionD: Increased fibroid deposits in the pulmonary interstitial space.
Explanation: In left side heart failure, there is a failure of the heart to achieve a cardiac output viable to support life. This inability of the heart to pump blood results in a back build of blood in the left ventricles, backing into the left atria, the pulmonary veins and into the pulmonary capillaries. This causes an increased oncotic pressure in the lungs, resulting in fluid entering the interstitial space.

Question: You are conducting a respiratory examination on a patient with a prior of Cor Pulmonale. The patient requests a proper explanation of what Cor Pulmonale is, to which you describe the following:
OptionA: Left ventricular enlargement secondary to a lung disorder that causes pulmonary hypertension
OptionB: Right ventricular enlargement secondary to a lung disorder that causes pulmonary hypertension
OptionC: Right ventricular enlargement secondary to a lung disorder that causes systemic hypertension
OptionD: Left ventricular enlargement secondary to a lung disorder that causes systemic hypertension
OptionE: Right atrial enlargement secondary to a lung disorder which causes systemic hypertension.
Explanation: Right ventricular enlargement secondary to a lung disorder that causes pulmonary hypertension. Taken from Case 5 lecture Pulmonary circulation and lung disease.

Question:
You take the history of Robin, a retired sailor in the Navy. When you ask about smoking he tells you he smoked 30 cigarettes a day for 25 years.

 

 

 

How many pack-years is this?
Explanation:
The answer is E. One pack year is smoking 20 cigarettes a day for one year. Robin has smoked 1.5 times this amount, so multiply the number of years by 1.5.

 

This means 25 (number of years) + 12.5 (Years/2) = 37.5 pack years. 

 

This is a straightforward question, but we need to be able to work it quickly for taking a respiratory history.

Question:
Cynthia comes to your private clinic. Her heart rate has risen in the last few months and she is worried how this may affect her blood pressure. 

 

 

Which of the following equations is the best way to calculate Cynthia's Mean Arterial Pressure, given all of the necessary measurements?
OptionE: Just use a blood pressure cuff like an actual doctor would
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. 

 

Of course in practice you would just use a blood pressure cuff and work it out using systolic and diastolic , but the equation for MAP is MAP = CO x TPR. 

 

B is the Cardiac output calculation. 

C & D are made up.

Question:
You are checking the notes for a patient with known congestive heart failure. 

 

A copy of the X-ray is shown below. 

 

 

Which sign of congestive heart failure do the arrows point to?
Explanation: The correct answer is C. Kerley lines are described as thin linear pulmonary opacities caused by fluid or cellular infiltration into the interstitium of the lungs. They are a sign of Stage 2 congestive heart failure.

Question:
Jessica Green is a 34 year old woman who has come to see you, her GP, because she is pregnant. You explain to her that her age makes her pregnancy high-risk for Down syndrome. You offer her screening for Down syndrome and she accepts it. 

 

Jessica has the quadruple screening test, where AFP is found to be increased and inhibin A levels are normal. What do you say to Jessica?
OptionA: Tell her her baby has an increased risk of Down syndrome and offer a diagnostic test
OptionB: Tell her there is nothing wrong and continue as a straightforward pregnancy
OptionC: Tell her her baby has a neural tube defect and not Down syndrome
OptionD: Tell her that her baby likely has a neural tube defect and not Down syndrome
OptionE: Tell her her baby has a neural tube defect and suggest termination
Explanation: In the quadruple test, elevated AFP is a marker of neural tube defects and inhibin A is a marker of Down syndrome. However, the quadruple test only has a 75% detection rate, so you couldn't tell Jessica her baby definitely doesn't have Down syndrome.

Question:
You're trawling through the various lectures from the year that you have yet to even look at as its Easter and its probably a good idea - you finally reach the physiology of the gut. 

You come across the following description of a condition, common in newborns, that you have never heard of: 

"Occurs when there is excessive contraction in smooth muscle cells due to the loss of ganglia in the myenteric plexus, which leads to the loss of inhibitory neurones and so unopposed contraction leading to the build up of a mass proximal to the effected region" 

 

Which of the following conditions is most likely being described?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B (taken from Dr Allen's lecture from case 11). 

 

A - obstruction of terminal ileum by abnormally viscous meconium, often present in newborns with cystic fibrosis 

C - inflammation and necrosis of cells of intestinal tract, often leading to intestinal perforation and common in neonates 

D - birth defect by which the neonate's intestines are found outside of their body 

E - this is made up

Question: As the sperm and egg meet meiosis II occurs to; restore diploid state, sex determination and cell cleavage. As the zygote forms into a morula and into a blastocyst the cell number increases, cell size increases but the embryo remains the same size. What stages of the cell cycle does the embryo miss out in order to allow this?
Explanation:
The key thing to remember is that the cell number increases, but the cell size decreases and hence the embryo remains the same size.

This occurs because the cells don’t go through G1 and G2 of the cell cycle involved in growth.

 

Professor Wilson's Lecture

Question: Lucy has just found out she is pregnant. When should she expect her dating scan?
Explanation:
All pregnant women in England are offered an ultrasound scan at around 8 to 14 weeks of pregnancy. This is called the dating scan. It's used to see how far along in your pregnancy you are and check your baby's development.

 

NHS website

Question:
Karolina goes to see an endocrinologist as her GP suspects she has hypoaldosteronism. She remembers that she is taking another medication that the GP didn't know about. 

 

The endocrinologist explains that this drug can simulate the symptoms of endocrine disease. 

 

   

 

Which drug can simulate hypoaldosteronism?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. This might seem simple as ACE inhibitors block the full function of the RAA system, but actually all of these answers apart from ARBs can simulate an endocrine condition. 

 

B, lactulose, is a laxative. It can lead to hypokalaemia. 

C and D are obviously diuretics that can cause hypokalaemia but also secondary hyperaldosteronism.

 

Eating a lot of liquorice can also cause hyperaldosteronism. 

 

This is found in page 1180 of Kumar and Clark's Clinical Medicine.

Question: My grandad (on my mother's side) is colour blind, my mum is not colour blind. My dad is also not colour blind. Assuming there are no new mutations, if I am female, what is my risk of being a carrier for colour blindness?
Explanation:
Colour blindness is X-linked recessive. Therefore my Mum is definitely a carrier (as her dad will have definitely given her an X chromosome). My dad cannot be a carrier as he is male and not colour blind, and so would be affected if he carried the mutation for colour blindness. 

So I have received a normal X chromosome from my dad, and there are 2 options from my mum: either an X with colour blindness or one without...therefore my risk of being a carrier is 50%.

Question: Which of the following is derived from the ectoderm during early human development?
Explanation:
B- mesodermal derivative

C- endodermal derivative

D- endodermal derivative

E- mesodermal derivative

 

These are all very hard to remember I know! I tend to think of ectodermal derivatives being generally to do with the nervous system, endodermal derivatives being to do with the epithelial layers of structures, and mesodermal derivatives just as everything else, but if anyone has any better ways to remember it please help!

Question: A pregnant woman comes to see you with flu with a raised temperature of 38.5 degrees. While you're hoping she doesn't give it to everyone else, you're also worried about what her raised body temperature could do to the foetus. You decide you should advise her to take something to bring the temperature down...but what will you suggest?
Explanation: Drugs should only given in pregnancy if absolutely necessary, and the benefit to the mother should be weighed with the risk to the foetus. As pyrexia can cause birth defects, you may suggest drug intervention in this case, and paracetamol is the most well researched and least risk for this. However, you should still give it in the lowest possible effective dose.

Question:
Gastrulation causes two layers in the blastocyst to change into three layers. These three layers go on to form the embryo. 

 

Only one of the original layers goes on to form the embryo, while the other has a more simple signalling role. 

 

 

Which of the original layers in the blastocyst will form the embryo?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D, the epiblast.

 

In gastrulation, the epiblast and hypoblast become the ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm.

Question: A child is born with hypotonia and has poor feeding early on. As he grows up he develops hyperphagia and becomes obese, has a short stature, hypogonadism, mild intellectual disability and behavioural problems. The consultant decides to put you on the spot because he want to embarrass you and tells you that the child has an inherited deletion on chromosome 15 but asks you whether it's on the maternal or paternal chromosome...what will say?
OptionC: I don't know stop asking me difficult questions
Explanation: A deletion at 15q13 on the paternal chromosome causes Prader Willi Syndrome as described above. If it were on the maternal chromosome it would have manifested as Angelman syndrome: characterised by microcephaly, ataxia, severe intellectual disability, absent speech, seizures, happy demeanour

Question: Mrs Jones has recently discovered that she is pregnant but is finding it difficult to recall when her last menstrual period was. What process occurs upon blastocyst implantation that may make it difficult to distinguish the last menstrual period?
OptionB: Spiral arteries leak blood so that glycogen stores can get to the developing blastocyst.
OptionC: Spiral arteries contract and rupture, causing shedding of the stratum functionalis.
OptionD: Syncitio-trophoblasts invade and rupture spiral arteries in the endometrium.
OptionE: A second bleed is indicative of abnormal implantation and ectopic pregnancy.
Explanation:
Syncitio-trophoblast cells are more invasive cells of the trophoblast layer, they have no cell boundary and create a syncitial mass- invasion upon blastocyst implantation ruptures maternal blood vessels forming trophoblastic lacunae. The leaking of blood means it is difficult to distinguish last period as it could be this process.

As the wall of the uterus is re-epithelialised, a fibrin clot forms- this shows that bleeding has occurred.

Cryotrophoblast cells have a definitive cell boundary and spawn the very invasive syncitio-trophoblasts in to the stromal layer.

Question: Which of the following sites of abnormal blastocyst implantation is associated with placenta previa?
OptionC: Interstitial implantation in the narrow portion of the uterine tube
Explanation:
The normal site for implantation is the posterior or anterior wall of the body to the uterus.

Placenta previa= placenta first, a low lying placenta that blocks the birth canal- implantation at the internal os of the uterus is associated with placenta previa

Question: The presence of which of the following markers from amniocentesis suggests a positive result for spina bifida?
Explanation:
Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) seeps out of a neural tube that hasn't formed properly into the amniotic sac, indicating spina bifida (failure of the neural tube to close). Spida bifida occulta, however, is not associated with an increase in AFP since the dural lining is maintained. 

 

In foetuses with down syndrome: Oestriol, AFP will be measured as lower, B-hCG and Inhibin A higher

Question: Lucy is pregnant and has just come into the clinic for her quadruple test (18-20 weeks). What four things are measured?
OptionA: Alpha fetal protein, UE3, PAPP-A, Inhibin A
OptionB: HCG, UE3, Inhibin A, Alpha fetal protein
OptionC: Alpha fetal protein, Inhibin A, Folic Acid Level, HCG
Explanation: Home / Prenatal Testing / Quad Screen Test. The quad screen test is a maternal blood screening test that looks for four specific substances: AFP , hCG , Estriol (UE3), and Inhibin-A.

Question:
The results from Lucy's quadruple test have just come back; 

 

- Increase HCG

- Alpha fetal protein is normal 

- UE3 is normal

- Inhibin A is normal

 


What does this suggest?
Explanation:
Human Chorionic Gonadotrophin Hormone (hCG) is unique to pregnancy. It is the hormone which is detected in the blood and/or urine of a woman who is pregnant.

Very high, elevated levels which may alert their healthcare provider to suspect a mother is pregnant with twins or triplets.

When a mother is carrying a twin pregnancy, she generally has higher hCG levels than a woman who is pregnant with one baby. But this is not a guarantee; there is a big cross over between singleton and twin pregnancy hCG levels and between individual women.

Question:
Gemma is an 18 year old suffering with a normocytic anaemia secondary to Hodgkins Lymphoma. Her consultant has recommended an urgent Red Blood Cell transfusion after a haemoglobin reading of 8g/dL as well as Gemma showing signs of decreased oxygenation. 

 

Gemma is known to be O- 

 

What must the doctors ensure regarding the type of Red Blood Cells she receives?
OptionA: Blood has been stored in fridge at 4 degrees for a maximum of 30 days
OptionB: should be transfused 3 hours after removal from storage
Explanation:
D: Hodgkins is a type of haematological malignancy.

 

Irradiated blood will not damage the RBC cells as they do not have any DNA but will damage any passenger lymphocytes that have not been filtered off by the transfusion service. 

 

This will prevent host vs graft disease 

 

A: Can be refrigerated for up to 35 days 

B: can be transfused up to 4 hours after being removed from storage 

C: Gemma will need blood from an O- individual 

E: CMV negative blood is really only indicated in intra-uterine transfusion

Question:
Sadie develops the flu and is livid as she has seen someone with a runny nose handling her food. 

 

You explain to her that the structure of the influenza virus means it cannot survive in the gut. 

 

 

What feature of the influenza virus prevents it from surviving in the gut?
OptionA: It is quite large at 80-120nm in diameter
OptionB: There is a viral envelope of glycoproteins
OptionE: It has viral surface proteins hemagglutinin and neuraminidase
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. 

 

The envelope cannot withstand changes in pH as found in the stomach. It is also sensitive to drying out. 

 

All of the options stated above are true. 

 

E talks about the H and N surface proteins that give influenza its "HXNX" codings, eg. H1N1 was responsible for swine flu in 2009.

Question: What 4 hormones released from the anterior pituitary are tropic hormones?
Explanation:
1. TSH
2. ACTH
3. FSH
4. LH
5. GH
6. PRL
7. MSH

 

The first four are “tropic” hormones, they regulate the function of other hormones

Question: What is the most likely pattern of inheritance in the family tree above?
Explanation:
The pattern shows pseudo-dominant inheritance. This pattern looks autosomal dominant however the fact there are some heterozygous individuals who are not affected rules out the idea it is autosomal dominant. 

 

Pseudo-dominant inheritance is where the condition looks dominant but it is actually RECESSIVE. A reason for this is co-sanguinuity, indicated by the double line between some of the people in the family tree.  Due to the high frequency of recessive alleles, the probability of producing an offspring with a recessive condition increases dramatically.

 

We can rule out any X linked diseases as father son inheritance is present in the family tree, which is not possible in X linked conditions as the father passes the Y chromosome to the son. 

 

autosomal recessive conditions can be ruled out as multiple generations with the disease are present.

Question: Which Toll Like Receptor (TLR) is important in recognising extracellular pathogens?
Explanation:
TLR 4 is present on the plasma membrane of cells and is therefore the correct answer.

TLR 3, 7, 8 and 9 are present within endosomes of cells (DC and macrophages) and so are involved mainly in recognising intracellular or internalised pathogens.

Question: Which of these is not a consequence of a virally infected cell releasing interferon alpha and beta?
OptionA: Activate cytotoxic T cells to kill virally infected cells
OptionB: Activate NK cells to kill viral infected cells
OptionC: Alter cellular metabolism of virally infected cells
OptionD: Increase expression of ligands for NK cells
OptionE: Induce resistance to viral entry and replication in all cells
Explanation:
Cytotoxic T cells require antigen presentation by macrophages/DC in order to be activated.

All other answers are correct.

Question: How to plasmacytoid DC differ from conventional DC?
OptionA: They produce massive amounts of interferon A
OptionB: They are unable to migrate from their tissue of origin
OptionC: They contain B7.1 and B7.2 whereas cDC do not
OptionD: They mainly use TLR 3 and 8 as PRR
Explanation:
pDC produce massive amounts of interferon A, and so also tend to be larger in size as they have a lot of RER.

 

They are present in blood and lymph nodes, hence B is incorrect.

 

cDC contain B7.1 and 2. They are mainly involved in antigen presentation to TCR, hence C is incorrect.

 

They mainly use TLR 7 and 9 as pattern recognition receptors. These are present in their endosomes (TLR 3 and 8 are also found in endosomes). Hence D is incorrect.

Question:
Chromosomal abnormalities, which can be numerical or structural, are significant causes of various birth defects. 

 

Which of the following conditions, associated with mental retardation, attention deficit disorder, large ears and a prominent jaw, with it affecting males more than females, is associated with a structural chromosomal abnormality involving microdeletions at regions of the CGG triplet?
Explanation:
The answer is D.  

 

A = partial deletion of short arm of chromosome 5 leading to cat-like cry, microcephaly, mental retardation and congenital heart problems 

B = affects females where there is 1 normal X chromosome with the other sex chromosome missing or structurally altered 

C = this is made up 

E = 47,XXY in males

Question:
You are examining a patient with a suspected spinal cord injury. On examination you find there is a reduced loss of sensation, particularly in the arms and hands but sacral sensation is still present and there is motor weakness which is much more pronounced in the patients arms than legs.

Which type of spinal cord injury is the patient likely to have?
Explanation:
Answer B - Brown-Sequard Syndrome - Contralateral loss of motor function, Ispilateral loss of pain / temperature 

Answer D - Complete spinal cord injury - complete loss of motor and sensory 

Answer E - Motor function preserved 

A and C therefore most likely - In Central cord syndrome loss of sensation and motor function is variable. Upper limbs are usually more effected than the upper limbs which this case indicates therefore C is the most likely answer

Question: You suspect a patient has damaged a certain spinal pathway in their lumbar spinal cord . The patient has decreased proprioception in their legs. Which spinal cord tract is most likely damaged?
Explanation: The dorsal column pathway is a sensory pathway transmitting information to do with proprioception, vibration and fine touch

Question:
You are performing an upper limb neurological examination in your ISCE. As part of this you ask your pretend patient to extend their hand at the wrist joint.

What is the myotome associated with this movement?
What is the most common opiate used for labour analgesia in the UK?
Explanation: From the Labour Analgesia lecture in case 8.

Question: a 32 year old man with a genetic disease comes into the practice. He has passed the gene onto his child, who is also male. What is the pattern?
Explanation: case 7 family history and probabilities lecture- states that if male to male transmission is seen it must be autosomal dominant

Question: An autosomal dominant disorder has a penetrance of 80%. What is the risk of the child of an affected parent of being affected by the disorder?
Explanation:
risk of being affected= penetrance x 0.5 

therefore 

risk=80 x0.5= 40%

Question: A 22 year old male presents to the A and E department of Prince Charles hospital Merthyr complaining of severe sudden shortness of breath and chest pain. You conduct a short history and find that the patient has suffered no recent trauma, is a frequent smoker and has no history of cardiovascular disease. After gaining consent you perform a respiratory examination and your findings include reduced breath sounds and hyper resonance on the left side. There also appears to be reduced chest expansion and no deviation of the trachea. You perform an X-ray of the patient to confirm the diagnosis. This is the X-ray. What diagnosis is made?
Explanation:
A - Would require some sort of trauma. This is also an emergency so should never be seen on an x-ray. 

B - No consolidation is visible.

C - This would give reduced not hyper resonance. 

D - This is the correct answer. Being a tall young male and smoking give the patient a predisposition to simple spontaneous pneumothoraxes.

C - The patient is only 22 so this is very unlikely!

Question: A brother of a baby girl who has just been diagnosed with cystic fibrosis comes to see you. They both have the same mum and dad. He asks you what his chances of being a carrier for cystic fibrosis are. What do you tell him?
Explanation:
cystic fibrosis is a autosomal recessive condition. 

there are 4 possible outcomes;

2 mutated genes passed on--> disease (this is the baby born with CF)

0 mutated genes passed on --> normal

1 mutated gene from mother, 1 normal from father --> carrier

1 mutated gene from father, 1 normal from mother --> carrier

 

this means that there is 2/3 chance that the brother is a carrier (as the child with the disease is known)

Question:
A 35 year old woman comes into the GP asking for advice on what supplements to take as her and her partner are trying to concieve their first child. She has type one diabetes. 

What advice do you give her?
OptionA: 400 micrograms of folic acid a day up until 12 weeks pregnant
OptionB: 400 micrograms of vitamin E a day up until birth
OptionC: 5 micrograms of folic acid a week up until birth
OptionD: 5 milligrams of folic acid a day until 12 weeks pregnant
Explanation: As she has diabetes you up the dosage a day from 400 micrograms to 5 mg a day until 12 weeks pregnant. You also advise those who have given birth to a  child with NT defects to have the higher dose of 5 mg a day or if either parent has diabetes.

Question: At what ages should a child have their MMR vaccinations?
Explanation:
Answer D is correct.

The rest are made up.

Question: Which of the following is not vaccinated for at 8 weeks?
Explanation:
At 8 weeks:

 

6 in 1 - diptheria, tetanus, polio, pertussis, Hib, hep B

 

Pneumococcal

 

Men B

 

Rotavirus

Question: What cell has the function of forming myelin sheaths for axons in the CNS?
Explanation:
A = Have many roles in the CNS - from the BBB, regulate homeostatic extracellular environment, remove excess neurotransmitters etc.
B = Ciliated cells that line the fluid-filled spaces of the brain 
C = Phagocytes of the CNS
E = Create myelin sheaths for axons in the Peripheral Nervous System.

D is the correct answer.

Question: You are a young lymphocyte who has decided to travel around the body via the lymphatic system before settling down and returning to the circulation. You find yourself in a lymph node in the leg and decide you've had enough, and wish to return to the bloodstream. Which route will you take?
OptionA: Lymphatics → right lymphatic duct → right subclavian vein
OptionB: Lymphatics → left lymphatic duct → right subclavian vein
OptionE: Lymphatics → right lymphatic duct → left subclavian vein
Explanation:
The lymph node that you're in is in the lower body, so you will get back to the circulation via the thoracic duct which empties into the left subclavian vein.

 

Information is from case 9 immunology lecture part 2.

Question:
I am a virus. 

 

I cause characteristic skin lesions. 

 

I am spread by sexual contact and by contact with blood or saliva.

 

I cause illness most commonly in immunosuppressed people, especially those with HIV/AIDS, or those who are genetically susceptible.  

 

To treat me and the condition I cause, you may need radiotherapy, chemotherapy, or HIV therapy if applicable.

 

Who am I?
Explanation:
I am Kaposi's sarcoma virus!!! 

 

Kaposi's sarcoma is a type of cancer that can be treated using chemotherapy, radiation or surgery. It can be localised or widespread. It usually involves the skin but can less commonly involve the lymph nodes or viscera. The skin lesions have a characteristic purple/red appearance. 

 

 

The condition is relatively common in patients with HIV/AIDS: over 35% may be affected. 

 

Information: case 9 virology lecture 1 + Wikipedia

Question:
You’re a medical student shadowing a consultant in A&E when a 23 year old male presents after falling from a ladder whilst cutting down some trees in his back garden.

 

The patient appears flushed and is brought in on a spinal board after a suspect serious spinal cord injury.

The patient has a heart rate of 42 bpm and his blood pressure is 90/60

 

The consultant tells you the patient is in shock. What type of shock is he most likely referring to?
Explanation:
Damage to the spinal cord can disrupt the autonomic pathways of the patient. Sympathetic outflow has been damaged and cannot be activated, meaning the parasympathetic pathway is unopposed, and hence the patient is in bradycardia. 

 

Vasodilation of blood vessels will also occur as consequence, and hence the patient appears flushed and hypotensive.

Question:
You’re an F1 working in A&E a busy saturday night shift, when a male patient aged 20 presents after getting into a fight in a club.


During the fight, he was punched from the front as an “upper cut” to the chin resulting in his head being flung backwards and over extended, before falling backwards to the floor.

 

A CT shows damage to C5 with no other injuries.

 

You complete an ASIA chart for the patient. Absence of which motor skill is consistent with damage to C5?
Explanation:
Wrist extension = C6

 

Finger abduction = T1

 

Finger flexion = C8

 

Elbow flexion = C5

 

Elbow extension = C7

Question:
A 30 year old male patient attends your GP with back pain he's been suffering for for a few weeks. Beginning socrates you ask him where the pain is. He struggles to describe where exactly the pain is and says "it's just spread across my whole back". He tells you he does get the pain at night and he wakes up feeling very stiff and has to move around to relieve the pain. As you examine him, his spine movements are less than expected. He also says he has been feeling very tired recently and has had a temperature. He has no family history of cancer.

Based on this information. What is the most likely cause of his back pain?
Explanation:
Spondylolysis - Pain usually lower back, 
Herniated Nucleus Proposus - Often asymptomatic and would most often cause radiation of pain in the appropriate dermatomes based on the affected nerves
Malignancy - His age and no family history of cancer makes this less likely
Acute Spinal Infection - Acute spinal infection would be more localised pain to begin with. 

A is the most appropriate answer - Ankylosing spondylitis usually has an onset at 20-30 year old, causes morning stiffness relieved by exercise. The pain can be local or spread across the back

Question: What is the risk of getting affected by a mutation from a parent affected by an autosomal dominant genetic disease?
OptionA: depends how badly the parent is affected
Explanation:
the risk of being affected is calculated by = 0.5 x penetrance

 

the risk of inheriting the mutation is 50% but the risk of being affected depends on the penetrance

Question:
An professor of embryology at the University of Cambridge comes into your clinic for his regular retinal checkup. He was diagnosed with a congenital retinal disorder which means he has structural changes to his retina, making him partially blind in both eyes. For some good old embryology professor fun, he decides to quiz you about his own illness! "From what germ layer is my broken retina most likely descended from?" he asks you with a huge grin on his face.

 

In order to not disappoint him, you think back to your case 7 days...

 

What is the most likely answer to his question?
Explanation:
Ectoderm derivatives:
Central Nervous System, retina, pineal body, posterior pituitary gland, cranial sensory ganglia and nerves, medulla of adrenal gland, melanocytes
Epidermis, hair, nails cutaneous and mammary glands, anterior pituitary gland, enamel of teeth, inner ear, lens

 

Mesoderm derivatives:
Cranium, connective tissue of head, dentine, muscles of head, dermis of skin, connective tissue, urinogenital system and accessory glands, connective tissue and muscle of viscera, serous membranes of pleura, pericardium and peritoneum, primordial heart, blood and lymphatic cells, adrenal cortex
Extraembryonic mesoderm turns into the placenta.

 

Endodermal derivatives

Epithelial parts of trachea, bronchi and lungs Epithelium of GIT, Liver, pancreas and urinary bladder
Epithelial parts of pharynx, thyroid, tympanic cavity, tonsils, parathyroid and glands

Question: Which syndrome is caused by the deletion of 15q11-q13 on the maternal chromosome?
Explanation: genetic imprinting--> when the disease manifestation depends on which parent the mutation has come from. PWS and Angelman syndrome are caused by the same deletion (15q11-q13) but PWS is on the paternal chromosome whereas Angelman syndrome is on the maternal chromosom.

Question: Theodore has come into the GP with his mum. His mum is dreadfully concerned as he has been under the weather since birth. The doctor diagnosis Theodore with Severe combined immunodeficiency, SCID. What cells are effected in this condition?
Explanation: Severe combined immunodeficiency, SCID, also known as alymphocytosis, Glanzmann–Riniker syndrome, severe mixed immunodeficiency syndrome, and thymic alymphoplasia, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the disturbed development of functional T cells and B cells caused by numerous genetic mutations.

Question: Ted, a 74 year old man, has blood in his faeces. It is suspected that he may have bowel cancer. He had a past medical history of heart block and subsequent heart failure. Which of the following techniques would be best to image his colon.
Explanation:
A - AXR are of better use in suspected bowel obstruction or perforation. They are not very specific for imaging cancers.

 

B - A barium enema is good at assessing he lining of the colon in detail. However, laxatives are also needed, so you have a similar problem as the CT. It also causes radiation exposure.

 

C - Although invasive, colonoscopy is the gold standard technique for imaging the bowel, especially with suspected cancer as you would be able to take a biopsy. Therefore C is CORRECT.

 

D - CT colonography requires strong laxatives to clear the bowels. This can lead to a fluid imbalance so is COI in patients with heart failure.

 

E - It is likely that with heart block, this patient has a pacemaker fitted. You cannot have an MRI with any metal present in the body. Even if this weren't true, MRIs are expensive and time consuming and so is not the best choice.

Question: A 21 year old woman is rushed into hospital via ambulance suffering from shock and haemorrhaging into her skin and ears. Her symptoms had a mild but then rather abrupt onset. Whilst trying to identify the cause, you learn that she has recently returned from travelling in South-East Asia for a few weeks, and whilst there she came down with a "bug". The symptoms of this bug included fever, headache, eye pain and malaise among other things. Her symptoms subsided after a few days but after a further few days of feeling fine, her previous symptoms returned but to a milder extent than in the first instance. After traveling South-East Asia she spent a week in Northern Australia before arriving back in the UK. During her time travelling she was bitten by mosquitoes on multiple occasions. She arrived back in the UK three days ago. What is this patients most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
A - This is correct. The biphasic nature of her first infection in SE Asia with the subsiding and then recurring symptoms is a classical characteristic of simple dengue fever. Her symptoms match dengue haemorrhagic fever though with the week in Northern Australia likely to be the cause of this. Dengue fever is also endemic to Northern Australia and during her time there she must have been bitten by another mosquito, infecting her with a different strain of the virus (there are 4 different strains). This was the cause of her then going on to develop the severe haemorrhagic form of the disease. Being infected with two or more different strains of the virus at the same time increases the risk of developing the severe haemorrhagic form, even though it is still very rare. Dengue fever is also transmitted by mosquitos as hinted at in the history. Her management will be supportive as there is no effective treatment for dengue haemorrhagic fever (DHF). 

B - Her symptoms seem reasonable, but Ebola is a disease confined to Africa and there is no mention of her travelling there.

C - Hanta virus is transmitted by rodents and is a reasonable answers, but the history best fits dengue fever.

D - Malaria would not give these symptoms.

E - Yellow fever is once again like Ebola, not found in SE Asia.

Question: Gemma is 4 years old and has come into the GP with her Dad. She has been suffering from a barking" cough, stridor, and a hoarse voice. The GP diagnoses her with Croup. What is the most common cause of croup?
Explanation: Viral croup or acute laryngotracheitis is most commonly caused by parainfluenza virus (a member of the paramyxovirus family), primarily types 1 and 2, in 75% of cases.

Question: Which of the following is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter in CNS?

When infected with mumps, the virus has an incubation period of around 2 weeks. This means there are clear waves of infection. 

 

Viruses have a basic reproduction number, R0, that represents the number of cases one case generates on average over the course of its infectious period. The R0 value of mumps is 5.

 

     

 

With 1 case in wave one, how many people do you expect to be infectious 8 weeks later?

 

Assume that nobody in the population is vaccinated against mumps.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. 

 

1 person in wave one (zero weeks)

5 people in wave two (two weeks)

25 people in wave three (four weeks)

125 people in wave four (six weeks)

625 people in wave five (eight weeks)

 

This is the same as 1 x 54. 

 

The formula for working this out quickly is Number at the start x R0(Number of waves -1)

 

If a disease's R0 value is less than 1, it will eventually burn itself out.

Question: What cell type influences the site of administration of a vaccination?
Explanation:
Info from second immunology lecture of case 9 

 

The location of cDCs influences the site of administration of a vaccine. From an immunological perspective, SC and IM are equivalent in that both sites are well served with cDCs. SC is more reactogenic. In contrast, the buttocks are not a good site of administration because adipose tissue is poorly vascularised and poorly served by DCs. Orally and nasally administered vaccines will ensure an IgA response and protection of the mucosal layers in the gut and upper respiratory tracts respectively. With both live influenza and rotavirus vaccinations you are mimicking the natural route of entry of the wild type virus.

Dendritic cells behave differently in distinct locations. Deltoid and quadriceps IM injection of inactivated polio virus leading to activation of cDCs in axillary and inguinal lymph nodes respectively will favour IgG generation. In contrast, activation of dendritic cells located in Peyer’s patches and mesenteric lymph nodes of the intestines following the live oral intake of the polio vaccine will direct the adaptive immune system to produce IgA. IgA is the neutralising antibody on mucosal layers that prevent polio entry.

Question:
A man has inherited hypophosphatemic rickets, a genetic condition, from his mother. He has 3 other siblings, 2 sisters and 1 brother. One of his sisters is also affected with the condition. 

 

What is the risk of this mans daughters inheriting the genetic condition?
Explanation:
Hypophosphatemic rickets has an X-linked dominant inheritance pattern. 

 

50% of the male offspring and 50% of the female offspring of affected females will inherit the condition. 

 

100% of the female offspring of affected males will inherit the condition (since the male will pass on his only X chromosome (affected) to his daughters).

Question:
Lorraine is a 2nd year medical student who woke up this morning after having 10 or so hours of plentiful sleep.

 

She checks her iPhone 6S™ and realises she had woken up an hour before her alarm was due. Despite having 10+ hours of sleep, Lorraine still felt extremely tired and groggy. On a normal day she would have gone straight back to sleep, but she had been having restless nights dreaming and lusting for a Victory Royale on Fortnite™.  She therefore decides to fire up her 42" plasma screen LG™ TV as well as her PS4™ in hopes of obtaining the unattainable Solo victory. 

 

After the super quick loading times, she was able to join a lobby on Solo mode. Lorraine is relatively bad, and fails to land at Junk Junction™ and so resorts to landing in an open field. Upon landing, she starts hearing sounds which resemble a nearby chest, in addition to seeing moving bushes in the corner of her eye (despite nothing being actually there). She decides to carry on playing and despite her best efforts, finishes with her personal best of 93rd place.

 

What type of hallucination was Lorraine experiencing?
Explanation:
A - Incorrect - Hypnagogic hallucinations are hallucinations one might experience as you're falling asleep. Easy way to remember is HypnaGOgic = GOing to sleep

 

B - Incorrect - Hyperbeam is a special Normal-type move in Pokemon™

 

C - Correct - Hypnapompic hallucinations are hallucinations one might experience as they're waking up. This hallucination may take the form of sounds or moving objects which is what Lorraine experienced whilst playing Fortnite™. Hypnagogic and Hypnapompic hallucinations are common in those with narcolepsy (suddenly falling asleep at inappropriate times) and is also common in those without any disorders at all.

 

D - Incorrect - Hippopotamus is a large, mostly herbivorous, semi-aquatic animal native to sub-Saharan Africa 

 

E - Incorrect - Hypnapogia is a made up word, made by mixing Hypnapompic and Hypnagogia together

Question:
You are an F1 doctor and you are asked to interpret some ABG results. The consultant tells you that the patient has metabolic acidosis caused by diabetic ketoacidosis but asks how the ABG results would indicate this. She goes as far as to tell you to look at the anion gap.

 

In a patient with diabetic ketoacidosis, what change would you expect to see in the anion gap?
Explanation:
The anion gap is an important diagnostic tool when investigating patients with metabolic acidosis (with regards to what is causing it). 

Put simply, the anion gap is-->  [sum of positive ions in the plasma (Na+/ K+)] - [sum of the number of negative ions in the plasma (HCO3- and Cl-)].

 

This difference is known as the anion gap.

 

Theoretically in the body, this value should be zero- but this equation fails to consider other negatively charged components of the plasma such as negatively charged albumin,  phosphate and sulphate ions.  Hence normal anion gap is positive- values range from 12-20mmol/L- this will vary between different hospitals/establishments.

 

In patients with metabolic acidosis there are 2 possible patterns with regards to the anion gap:

 

 

1) An increased anion gap 

 

 This usually happens when there is an increased amount of inorganic acid in the body- i.e- ketones.

A keto- acid will dissociate to form H+ and a negative charged ion. The H+ reacts with HCO3^- in the body and disappears- decreasing the amount of bicarb in the blood thus increasing the gap. At the same time- the negatively charged anion stays in the plasma therefore there is an increased amount of negative ions is the plasma that is not HCO3^- or Cl- thus is not accounted for in the equation.

 

Thus the answer to this question is B

I hope this makes sense- don't over think it!

 

 

2)  A normal anion gap

This usually occurs due to xs Bicarb loss. Such is seen in Diarrhoea/ renal tubular acidosis. The body then compensates for this massive loss in negative ions by retaining more chloride ions (kidneys to the rescue- again)- thus not affecting the anion gap.
Tags: ABG, Kidneys, Case 10, Case 5 revision, Tests

Question:
Dave goes on holiday to Gabon and contracts Ebola. He comes into your clinic quite unhappy, wanting to know what causes ebola. 

 

"It blocks part of your immune response that normally stops viral infections spreading around your body", you tell Dave. 

 

   

 

Which normal part of the defence does Ebola block?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. 

 

Ebola blocks the pathways of interferons in two ways. This is addressed in James Matthews' first Immunity lecture in case 9, as Learning Outcome 6. 

 

IFNs have 3 mechanisms: 

- Resistance to viral replication in all cells

- Increase ligand expression for receptors on NK cells

- Activate NK cells to kill virus-infected cells. 

 

Ebola stops these functions and leaves innate immunity significantly reduced.

Question:
Haemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN) occurs when a foetus is Rhesus positive and the mother is Rhesus negative - the mother creates anti-RhD antibodies against the Rhesus antigen upon a sensitising event. Generally, the mother doesn't produce these antibodies until childbirth, so it is her future pregnancies that risk HDN. 

 

Why is HDN associated with Rhesus antibodies, as opposed to antibodies for ABO blood types?
OptionA: ABO antigen epitopes are carbohydrates and thus are only recognised by B cell receptors, resulting in just IgM antibody production.
OptionB: Rhesus antibodies are high affinity antibodies, so they are more effective at destroying red blood cells than ABO antibodies are.
OptionC: Rhesus antigen epitopes are carbohydrates and thus are only recognised by B cell receptors, resulting in just IgM antibody production.
OptionD: The foetus already has ABO antibodies in its blood and so they are not harmful from the mother.
OptionE: There are more Rhesus antigens on the foetus' red blood cells than there are ABO antigens, resulting in increased destruction by antibodies.
Explanation:
Rhesus antigens are peptides 

ABO antigens are carbohydrates 

 

Epitopes recognised by B cells can be protein, carbohydrate, lipid or nucleic acid (basically, broad range)

Epitopes recognised by T cells can only be protein 

 

The recognition of an epitope by a T cell is necessary for the antibody to undergo class switching! When the helper T cell is stimulated, it unregulates the CD40 ligand and counter ligand - engagement of these receptors allows a signal within the B cell telling the B cell to produce AID, the enzyme that allows class-switching and somatic hypermutation. 

 

All antibodies start off as IgM. As ABO antigens are carbohydrate, there is no class-switching, so the antibodies remain IgM. The Rhesus antibodies do undergo class-switching, and switch to IgG. Remember that IgG can cross the placenta, which is the key reason that Rhesus antibodies are implicated in HDN!

Question:
An elderly gentleman, Harold, comes into your clinic to have a vaccination. To your confusion, he pulls his trousers down. 

 

When you ask why, he says "The nurse always injects me on the bum, so it'll be nice and easy for you". 

 

You explain to him that it is not the best way to have a vaccination administered. 

 

   

 

What is the main reason the buttocks are not used for vaccinations?
OptionB: Cytokines produced by the large muscle mass can inactivate cDCs.
OptionC: Its proximity to lymph nodes allow the innate immunity to destroy the vaccine, leaving no long lasting memory.
OptionD: There is too much fat, which doesn't have many dendritic cells.
OptionE: It is more likely to be painful for the patient.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. 

 

Adipose tissue is not well served by dendritic cells. This means the vaccine may not be picked up and an immune response may not form. 

 

A is also true I suppose - but not the reason. 

 

In general, injections in the buttocks are avoided to avoid damage to the femoral nerve and artery that pass nearby. 

 

B & C (and probably E) are completely made up.

 

This question comes from a comment made in RJM's Immunity 2 lecture in Case 9.

Maternal oxygen consumption increases during pregnancy to meet the increased oxygen requirement of the fetoplacental unit. By what mechanism is this acheived?
OptionE: Increasing partial pressure of oxygen in the blood
Explanation:
-Vital capacity, respiratory rate and inspiratory reserve volume remain unchanged in pregnant women
-Partial pressure of oxygen in the blood is unaffected by pregnancy (stays 100 mmHg)

-To meet the ~40% increase in oxygen requirement by the fetoplacental unit, the mother hyperventilates- increasing minute ventilation by ~40% by increasing tidal volume (to breathe more deeply is a more efficient mechanism than increasing respiratory rate as it means there is less 'dead space' in the lungs) 

-Small reduction in total lung capacity (5%) is caused by obstruction of the uterus as it pushes up on the diaphragm- the gravid uterus may restrict the movement of the diaphragm and cause breathlessness, a common symptom in pregnancy.

Question: You prescribe an oral iron replacement to a woman with iron deficiency anaemia, she is 28 weeks pregnant. By how much would you expect haemoglobin levels to improve each week?
Explanation:
Normal haemoglobin levels = 115 g/L - 165 g/L 

<115 g/L haemoglobin = anaemic 

In pregnancy haemoglobin levels may drop to 105 g/L and still be considered normal due to the increase in plasma volume causing dilutional anaemia. Red cell mass starts to increase after week 20 of gestation

 

A haemoglobin <105 g/L (consider if <115 g/L), (decreased MCV*) and serum ferritin <15 mcg/L would indicate iron deficiency anaemia in pregnancy

*Cannot exclude iron deficiency is MCV is normal

 

Treatment for iron deficiency anaemia is oral iron replacement, there is no advantage to using IV iron over oral iron and the use of IV iron carries the risk of anaphylaxis.

>Expect Hb to improve 10 g/L/week

Question:
While walking in Roath park, your friend is looking through an instagram page called 70borkborkstreet. He is so engrossed in the extraordinarily funny instagram page that he is not concentrating on where he is going. Soon, tears if pure laughter start to obstruct his view and he stands on a swan. It swiftly retaliates by hissing at him and bites him on the finger. After sprinting from the scene, you see a small spec of blood roll off his finger and drop to the floor. You immediately think "He needs a plasma transfusion". Being the excellent friend you are, you know that your friend's blood group is "O-".

 

 

Which blood group/groups can your friend safely receive fresh frozen plasma from?
Explanation:
It is all of the above! People with type O blood group do not have any antigens on their red cell surface.This means that they can receive the PLASMA from any blood group as the antibodies in that blood group will not attack their red blood cells.

 

HOWEVER, people who are O type blood group can only receive O blood group red blood cells. This is because they have both anti-A and anti-B in their plasma meaning that if any red blood cells were given which had an A or B antigen on, the antibodies would attack that red blood cell.

Question:
Daniel is a 14 year old who has been brought to A&E with his mother. He has a history of vomiting, excessive urination and feeling very thirsty. He has also lost weight recently. Daniel is currently very sleepy and confused; he does not respond to verbal commands but does show a response to pain. His heart rate is at 120bpm and he has a high respiratory rate.

 

Urinalysis shows that ketones in the urine are ++, and blood results reveal a pH of 7.0 (normal 7.35-7.45), HCO3 of 5mmol/L (22-26) and ketones of 6.3mmol/L (<0.6). His blood glucose is at 16mmol/L (4.4-7.8).

 

How should Daniel be managed at this point?
OptionA: Continue to monitor his blood glucose.
OptionB: Give intravenous glucose and monitor blood glucose.
OptionC: Give 0.9% saline intravenously with potassium and give short-acting insulin intravenously. Monitor blood glucose.
OptionD: Put Daniel onto a 4-daily subcutaneous insulin regime. Monitor blood glucose.
OptionE: Replace the deficient insulin with hourly intramuscular injections. Monitor blood glucose.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. 

 

Daniel is presenting with Diabetic Ketoacidosis - uncontrolled production of ketones caused by a high blood glucose levels due to a lack of insulin production (type 1 diabetes)

 

Management of ketoacidosis involves:

  • Replacing fluid loss with 0.9% saline intravenously. Give 500ml in the first 15 minutes and 1L in total over the first hour. In total give 6L of fluid over 6 hours.
  • Replacing deficient insulin by giving short-acting insulin intravenously (0.1U/kg/hr) OR as hourly intramuscular injections (20U initially followed by 6U hourly).
  • Giving potassium with the saline to replace electrolyte losses, as insulin therapy causes uptake of potassium into cells causing a fall in plasma potassium levels.
  • Monitoring blood glucose levels aiming for a fall of 3-6mmol/L per hour.

Answer A is partially correct - it is essential to continue monitoring his blood glucose levels, however you need to do more than just that!

 

Answer B is the management strategy for an unconscious patient with hypoglycaemia, the opposite of what Daniel has, so do not do this!

 

Answer C is correct.

 

Answer D is what Daniel would be put on once his diabetic ketoacidosis is managed and he is stable.

 

Answer E is partially correct however it is also vital to give fluids and potassium.

Question: In your hand, you're holding a transfusion for someone with aplastic anaemia. You know that the substance has a shelf life of 5 days and is stored at room temperature, but you can't quite remember what it is you've got. What is it?
Explanation:
Platelets are indicated in bleeding for people with aplastic anaemia, DIC, thrombocytopenia, platelet function disorders. It has a shelf life of 5 days and is kept at room temperature. 

 

RBC have a shelf life of 35 days and are kept at 4 degrees Celsius.  They must be transfused within 4 hours of removing from storage. Used for patients with anaemia, perioperative blood loss, ongoing GI blood loss. 

 

FFP has a shelf life of 24 months and must be kept at -30 degrees Celsius. It must be thawed before transfused. Used for DIC, immediate reversal of warfarin, and when there isn't enough of a specific single factors (if there is deficiency in a certain factor). 

 

Irradiated RBC are used for;

  • intrauterine transfusions
  • paediatrics
  • bone marrow transplants
  • transfusion from family or HLA matched donors
  • patients who have had treatment with purine analogues
  • hodgkins disease

E- a papule that contains a clear fluid (blister) e.g.. herpes simplex virus

Question: Which of these lymph nodes do most of the breast lymph drain into?
Explanation:
75% of breast lymph drains into the axillary lymph nodes--> this is a group of lymph nodes. 

 

extra note- lymph from the medial breast can drain into the opposite breast- this is how stage 4 breast cancer can initiate spread or metastasis

Question: cooper's droopers refer to the Cooper's ligaments in the framework of the breast. What is the action of Cooper's ligaments and why is the saying 'cooper's droopers' relevant?
OptionA: they hold the breast tissue tightly onto the chest wall. Cooper's droopers is a way to remember that these ligaments stop the droopiness of breasts
OptionB: They keep the nipple of the breast in the correct place on the breast tissue. Without the ligaments, the nipples would point downwards therefore--> coopers droopers
OptionC: cooper's ligaments flatten the breast onto the chest wall so that they don't fall down causing back problems. cooper's droopers saying is a way of remembering that without the ligaments the breasts would droop
OptionD: Cooper's ligaments hold the breast onto the chest wall. As a female gets older, there is lax in the ligaments, causing the breasts to droop, hence the saying cooper's droopers

Question: Where is the K+ concentration highest in the cochlear?
Explanation:
The Cochlear Duct (or Scala Media) is an endolymph filled cavity inside the cochlea, located in between the tympanic duct and the vestibular duct, separated by the basilar membrane and Reissner's membrane (the vestibular membrane) respectively.

 

Scala media is high in K+

Question:
Mr Wright is a 54 year old man with Type 2 diabetes. He is attending his yearly retinopathy screening clinic. The nurse produces this fundus photo.

 

 

What stage of diabetic retinopathy does Mr Wright have?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

This fundus photo shows a more aggressive picture than that in background diabetic retinopathy. There are hard exudates, blot haemorrhages, cotton wool spots and venous beading. However there is no growth of new blood vessels so it is not yet at the proliferative stage.

 

Stages of Diabetic Retinopathy

 

Background

  • Asymptomatic – picked up via screening.
  • Dot and blot haemorrhages and hard exudates.

Pre-Proliferative

  • A more aggressive version of the background DR, but without proliferation of new vessels.
  • Venous beading (lumpy vessels), cotton wool spots (areas of infarction), IRMA (intraretinal microvascular abnormalities).

Proliferative

  • Has all the signs of the previous stages.
  • Also includes growth of new vessels due to VEGF.
  • NVD = new vessels at the (optic) disc, NVE = new vessels elsewhere.
  • New vessels are weak and bleed, which causes blood to enter the vitreous.

Advanced/End Stage

  • Bleeding causes fibrosis of the retina and retinal detachment.
  • The eye becomes shrunken, soft, opaque and vascularised with no vision.
  • Eventually the eye needs to be removed.

Question:
You are with family over Easter weekend, and your drunk Aunt Tracy starts a conversation about your university course. 

Naturally, the rest of the family start asking you numerous medical questions regarding their bowel habits.

 

Your cousin mentions that she's been having problems with her IBS medication; she thinks it's been causing her some constipation and indigestion. 

You ask her what her medication is called but she can't remember.

 

Which of the following is it most likely to be?
Explanation:
• Loperamide: Mu-receptor agonist that relaxes smooth muscle tone and is most commonly used for acute non-infective diarrhoea. Can be used as an anti-diarrhoea medication in IBS, but it's ADRs are more like dizziness, nausea, flatulence and headaches
  • Mebeverine: An anti-spasmodic used to treat IBS. It's ADRs include constipation, dry mouth, dry skin and indigestion
  • Prednisolone: This is a glucocorticoid analogue anti-inflammatory drug used most commonly in IBD
  • Cinchocaine: A local anaesthetic used for haemorrhoids
  • Mesalazine: This is another anti-inflammatory drug used to treat ulcerative colitis. 

 

 

(All info taken from Case 11 Pharmacology lightbulb and Inflammatory Bowel Disease lecture)

Question:
Lorraine is a 2nd year medical student who finishes her revision for the day and decides to chill out. All her friends are busy revising and there's nothing to do in the countryside so she decides to play a bit of Fortnite™ to pass the time. Despite playing for 5 hours straight, she still hasn't managed to win a solo victory on Fortnite™. 

 

Before heading to bed she decides to play one more game, telling herself that "this is the one". Unlike her usual play style, she decides to spice it up and play Rambo-style; landing in Tilted Towers™ and heading towards gunfire. The odds were not in her favour, yet she manages to reach the last 2 against a player with the most terrifying skin in the game - John Wick. 

 

Battle ensues, and in a blink of an eye John Wick 360 no-scoped Lorraine with a green hunting rifle and she lost.  After crying over her inevitable loss, she realised her heart beating much more rapidly, and what felt like her heart thumping out of her chest.

 

Via what adrenoreceptor and what mechanism do catecholamines (like adrenaline and noradrenaline) exert its effects on the heart?
OptionA: α1 - Gi (Adenylate cyclase inactivated, cAMP decreases, intracellular Ca2+ decreases)
OptionB: β1 - Gq (Phospholipase C activated, PIP2 cleaved into DAG + IP3. IP3 causes increase in Ca2+)
OptionC: α1 - Gs (Adenylate cyclase activated, cAMP increases, intracellular Ca2+ increases)
OptionD: β1 - Gi (Adenylate cyclase inactivated, cAMP decreases, intracellular Ca2+ decreases)
OptionE: β1 - Gs (Adenylate cyclase activated, cAMP increases, intracellular Ca2+ increases)
Explanation:
Predominant beta-adrenoreceptor in the heart is β1-adrenoreceptor. Stimulation of this receptor causes positive chronotropic, dromotropic and inotropic effects which Lorraine experienced after facing off with Baba yaga (John Wick).

 

α1-adrenoreceptor effects - Smooth muscle contraction, mydriasis, vasoconstriction in the skin, mucosa and abdominal viscera & sphincter contraction of the GI tract and urinary bladder

 

GPCR mechanisms:

  • α1 - Gq (Phospholipase C activated, PIP2 cleaved into DAG + IP3. IP3 causes increase in Ca2+)
  • α2 - Gi (Adenylate cyclase inactivated, cAMP decreases, intracellular Ca2+ decreases)
  • β1 - Gs (Adenylate cyclase activated, cAMP increases, intracellular Ca2+ increases)
  • β2 - Gs (Adenylate cyclase activated, cAMP increases, intracellular Ca2+ increases)
  • β3 - Gs (Adenylate cyclase activated, cAMP increases, intracellular Ca2+ increases)

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrenergic_receptor

Question: One night you're having a dream (nightmare) about our formative anatomy quiz that we had last year. You remember at one station seeing a blob of circular shaped tissue and you guess quite confidently that the structure the pin is pointing to is 'lymph of the breast'. Turns out it was a cross section of the arm (true story). This blunder gets you thinking about drainage of the lymph in the breast. Into which nodes do the majority of lymph from the breast drain into?
Explanation:
75% of lymph form the breasts drains into the axillary nodes

 

The internal mammary nodes and internal thoracic nodes are the same nodes but just different names. 20% of lymph drains into these

 

Posterior intercostal and abdominal nodes also receive lymph from the breast but a significantly less amount than the others.

Question:
You are reviewing a 47 year old patient. You have been monitoring the patient's hypertension for a while now. The patient is currently taking an ACE inhibitor and a calcium channel blocker to reduce their blood pressure. However, upon reviewing the patient you find that they are still hypertensive. 

What would be the next most appropriate drug to prescribe the patient to lower their blood pressure (assuming there are no other contra-indications)?
Explanation:
The NICE guidelines for managing hypertension (for an under 55 yo) - First use a ACE inhibitor or angiotensin II receptor blocker. The next stage would be to use a calcium channel blocker. The patient is currently on these two drugs. After this the next stage is to use a thiazide-like diuretic. D is an example of a thiazide-like diuretic and is therefore the correct answer. 

A - Beta-blocker
B - Calcium channel blocker
C - Loop-acting Diuretic 
E - Example of an NOAC / DOAC (anti-coagulant)

Question: Which hormone stimulates the development of the spherical masses at the end of each duct in the breast (immature alveoli)?
Explanation:
Progesterone stimulates the formation of the immature alveoli at the end of each duct during puberty. They do not become mature alveoli until pregnancy/birth.

 

  • Oestrogen is the hormone that causes elongation and bifurcation of the ducts. 
  • Prolactin in the hormone for milk production (anterior pituitary gland). Prolactin is inhibited by dopamine. 
  • Oxytocin is the hormone for milk ejection (posterior pituitary gland)

Question: in breast development, what is oestrogen's role?
OptionB: during puberty, it bifurcates and elongates the ducts
OptionC: forms the immature alveoli at the end of each duct
OptionD: causes milk to be let down during breast feeding

Question: how many lobes are there is the breast?
which type of epithelium produces milk in the alveoli of the breast?
Explanation: it is the columnar cells of the alveoli that produce the milk. The alveoli are the place of milk production and temporary storage.

Question: contraction of _______ cells causes milk to be squeezed into a larger duct.
Explanation:
alveoli are surrounded by myoepithelial cells and a dense network of capillaries. The contraction of the myoepithelial cells causes milk to be ejected from the alveoli into larger ducts. 

 

Columnar cells in the alveoli are in charge of the milk production.

Question: A 29-year-old mother comes to see you with her 3-month-old baby. She is worried as she has not been having periods and is fearing that she has fallen pregnant again. She is exclusively breastfeeding her baby. You explain to her that this is called lactational amenorrhoea. What are the hormone levels?
Explanation: with lactational amenorrhoea, there is increased prolactin causing decreased LH. This means that there cannot be ovulation. The follicle is still being matured but there is no LH for ovulation to take place. Breastfeeding disrupts the pulsatile release of GnRH from the hypothalamus. The woman must be exclusively breastfeeding for this to occur.

Question: By what day, following birth, is milk removal from the breasts required to continue lactation?
Explanation:
Milk removal is the primary mechanism for milk synthesis, it must occur before 72 hours post partum. 

Suckling coordinates the release of prolactin and oxytocin- a switch from endocrine to autocrine control.

 

In the absence of suckling (during weaning), milk production ceases within 2-3 weeks

Question: How is full milk production inhibited by progesterone?
OptionB: progesterone interferes with upregulation of prolactin receptors
OptionD: progesterone interferes with the anatomy of the breast--> the ductal, lobular and lobe system
Explanation:
progesterone stops full milk production from occurring by interfering with the prolactin receptors at the alveolar cell level. If there is no receptor, the hormone won't work. Once progesterone drops, prolactin is allowed to take its effect and full milk production occurs.

 

  • in a situation of miscarriage or stillbirth, the removal of the placenta causes a decrease in the progesterone levels causing lactation to occur. To try to avoid this, dopamine agonists are given to the woman.

Question: What is the protein that is involved in the regulation of milk production in the breast? Involved in galactopoiesis.
Explanation: FIL is the feedback inhibitor of lactation. When the alveoli are full, there is increased FIL (whey protein), this causes milk production to slow down. When the breasts are empty, there is less FIL, therefore, increasing the speed of milk production.

Question: What is fat content of breast milk determined by?
Explanation: the emptiness of the breast determines the fat content of the milk, therefore, thoroughly emptying the breast is more important than frequency of milk removal in stimulating milk production and its removal.

Question: embryological development of the cardiovascular system is a derivative of which germ layer?

Sally is a 47 year old woman who presents at A&E with acute abdominal pain. She has been vomiting and has not been able to pass any stools. Her abdomen is somewhat distended.

 

Which of the following imaging techniques should be carried out first on Sally?
OptionD: CT Scan
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

Sally is presenting with symptoms that suggest bowel obstruction. 

 

Abdominal X-rays are carried out when a patient has acute abdominal pain to identify bowel obstruction and to analyse gas patterns. They only have a 50% sensitivity for detecting obstruction, however they are inexpensive and easy to carry out which is why they are used before CT scans or MRIs.

 

 

A chest X-ray is useful to see pneumoperitoneum - gas in the peritoneal cavity below the diaphragm caused by perforations in the bowel. However it is not useful to see bowel obstruction.

 

Barium studies are not often used as they are semi-invasive and do not show surrounding structures. However they are accessible, cheap and quick and so may be used if the abdominal X-ray is inconclusive.
Tags: Abdomen, Management of patient, Case 11, Imaging

Question: While on placement on a gastro ward one of your patients develops profuse diarrhoea. Where in the gastrointestinal tract is the majority of water absorbed?
Explanation:
99% of the water that is delivered to the gastrointestinal tract is absorbed, this is powered by the absorption of ions across cell membranes. Most of the water is absorbed in the small intestine with the majority in the jejunum not in the other options suggested.

During a 24 hours period the average person will ingest up to 2000ml of liquid orally. In addition a further 8000ml of fluid will enter the small bowel as gastrointestinal secretions. Intestinal water absorption is a passive process and is related to solute load. In the jejunum the active absorption of glucose and amino acids will create a concentration gradient that water will flow across. In the ileum most water is absorbed by a process of facilitated diffusion (with sodium).

Question:
Dave is a 24 year old man who visits his GP complaining of rectal bleeding, bloody diarrhoea and abdominal pain. He says that he had similar symptoms a few months ago but that they disappeared after a couple of weeks. The GP sends off a stool sample and arranges blood tests.

 

Dave returns a week later to review the results which show that he has anaemia, a rising platelet count, high CRP, low albumin and is positive for the faecal calprotectin protein. 

 

The GP refers Dave to a gastroenterologist who performs a colonoscopy. 

 

Which of the following features would the gastroenterologist expect to see in Dave's colonoscopy?
OptionA: Areas of inflammation unevenly distributed in the colon.
OptionB: Fistulas.
OptionC: Narrowing of the lumen and strictures.
OptionD: Ulceration and bleeding throughout the distal part of the colon and the rectum.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. 

 

The blood and stool results suggest that Dave has inflammatory bowel disease and not IBS. The fact that he suffered a flare up a few months ago further indicates that his current symptoms are probably not caused by an infection.

 

Furthermore, the rectal bleeding and bloody diarrhoea suggests that Dave has Ulcerative Colitis rather than Crohn's Disease. 

 

All answers other than D are signs of Crohn's Disease therefore D is the correct answer.

Question: cells from which embryological structure form the SA node in the heart?
Explanation:
it is the cells of the sinus venosus that form the SA node.

 

  • At around 5 weeks, the cardiomyocytes in the sinus venosus spontaneously depolarise at a faster rate than other cells.
  • They are then incorporated into the right atrium and form the SA node.
  • The AV node and Bundle of his are derived from cells from the sinus venosus and cells of the atrioventricular canal,

Question: It is the 13th June 2018 and you are on your last ISCE station. The previous five stations have gone surprisingly well and this final station revolves around a patient with jaundice. You are on the data interpretation section, and these are the patients blood results; positive for HBs-Ag, HBe-Ag, Anti-HBc and Anti-HBc IgM. What is the patients diagnosis?
Explanation: The answer is an acute Hepatitis B infection due to the presence of IgM antibodies. IgM antibodies are present in large numbers only during the acute phase of an infection.

Question: Which component of human milk causes bacteria cell wall lysis, binds endotoxin, increases IgA production and contributes to macrophage activation?
Explanation:
Lysozyme is an enzyme found in human breast milk which causes bacteria cell wall lysis (principally gram positive bacteria*), binds endotoxin, increases IgA production and contributes to macrophage activation

 

*"Lysozyme, an enzyme found in the human milk whey fraction, is capable of degrading the outer cell wall of gram positive bacteria. It is also capable of killing gram negative bacteria in vitro synergistically with lactoferrin"
Source: https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/0d0a/00e7d3ea928f6bde340cb77ba0b2a093e4cf.pdf

 

Lactoferrin= iron binding glycoprotein (iron chelator), binds to iron and deprives microorganisms of the iron that is essential for their multiplication.
-Lactoferrin blocks the adsorption/penetration of viruses (rotavirus) and the adhesion of bacteria (Vibro cholerae, E.coli).
-Lactoferrin contributes to intestinal cell growth and repair
-Suppresses inflammation by modifying cytokines (decreases IL-1, IL-2, IL-6 and TNF-alpha)

 

Alpha-lactalbumin= whey protein that promotes the growth of bifidobacterium to help establish a normal gut flora. Lactose synthesis in the mammary galnd is dependent on the presence of alpha-lactalbumin.

 

Casein is a protein found in human milk (35% human milk is casein soft curds) which inhibits the adhesion of various bacteria in epithelial site and promotes growth of bifidobacterium

Casein is also present in cows milk (80% cow milk is casein hard curds) which is difficult for babies to digest

 

Beta-lactoglobulin is a whey protein that is present in cow and sheep milk, not human milk.

Question: What is a virus capsid composed of?
Explanation: All viruses contain a nucleic acid genome and a protein capsid that covers the genome- this is known as a nucelocapsid (genome + capsid). Many animal viruses have an envelope too which contains viral glycoprotein, allowing the virus to bind to receptor sites on the hosts membrane and invade cells.

Question: What bacteria infection is most associated with colorectal cancer?
Explanation:
Gram positive, spore forming, anaerobic bacteria
Gas gangrene without trauma
Haematogenous spread
Myonecrosis through release of endotoxins

Associated with colorectal cancer

Question: Blood flows to the foetus from the placenta via which blood vessel?
Explanation:
• blood flows to the baby from the placenta via the umbilical vein (1)
  • blood flows back to the placenta via umbilical arteries (2)
  • oxygenated blood flows in the umbilical vein
  • deoxygenated blood flows in the umbilical artery

Question: What is the reason that blood flows from the pulmonary trunk through the ductus arteriosus and into the descending aorta?
OptionA: easier route to go to the aorta
OptionB: resistance is high in the pulmonary circulation
OptionC: there is already blood in the lungs from elsewhere
OptionD: the pulmonary vessels are too narrow for blood to enter
Explanation:
A- partially right but this is due to the increased resistance in the pulmonary circulation. if there is increased resistance, the other route is the easier choice. 

B- Correct- there is increased resistance in the pulmonary circulation and therefore the blood leaves through the ductus arteriosus and into the descending aorta

C- made up

D- also made up

Question: in a grown adult, there is no umbilical vein. What structure does it create?
Explanation:
• umbilical vein creates ligamentum teres
  • ductus arteriosus creates ligamentum arteriosum
  • foramen ovale creates fossa ovalis
  • ductus venosus creates ligamentum venosum

Question: in the fetus, blood bypasses the liver. What is the structure that causes this and what does it become after birth?
Explanation: the ductus venosus shunts blood from the umbilical vein straight to the IVC. After birth, this structure becomes the ligamentum venosum.

Question:
There are 4 modalities for the developmental milestones. 

3 of these are;

  • Gross motor function
  • communication and social
  • hearing and vision

Which one is left?
A mother comes to you and asks if you know what stage of development her child is in. The child is 4 months old. What is your response
Explanation:
These are the stages of development

 

  • prenatal--> embryonic (conception to 8 weeks), foetal (8-40weeks)
  • infancy--> neonate (birth to 1 month), infant (1 month to 1 year)
  • early childhood--> toddler (1-3years), preschool (3-4years)
  • mid childhood--> school age (4-12 years)
  • late childhood --> adolescence (12-18 years)

Question: when do the primitive reflexes disappear?
OptionB: before birth- they are only seen on the early anomaly scan
OptionD: as the child starts to develop new skills
Explanation:
The primitive reflexes are;

  • grasp reflex
  • stepping reflex
  • crawl reflex
  • tonic neck reflex

these reflexes are present from birth but they disappear as the child starts to develop new skills (around 2-6 months)
