Question:
Mr C, a 68 year old man, presents to your GP surgery. 

 

He has shortness of breath when he walks up the stairs and when he lies down, swollen ankles and is feeling really tired all the time. 

 

You order some investigations: 

 

Blood test: raised BNP

 

Chest X-Ray:

 

 

What medications are you most likely to prescribe Mr C as first line treatment?
Explanation:
Mr C is suffering from congestive heart failure.

 

A - incorrect. adrenaline would NOT help Mr C, digoxin is not a first line treatment, propanolol is not cardioselective

 

B- unlikely as digoxin is not a first line treatment

 

C - correct. Ramipril to prevent pathological consequences of angiotensin II, bisopropolol to limit heart rate and contractility (again prevents hypertrophy), spirnolactone to get rid of the excess fluid 

 

D - incorrect. Propanolol not cardioselective, furosemide is a potential but is not tolerated well by patients, digoxin is not a first line treatment

 

E - unlikely. Candesartan is not a first line treatment as it is much more expensive than ACE inhibitors

Question: You are in A&E analysing an abdominal x-ray that was indicated for an elderly patient with bloating and abdominal pain. Your SHO rushes up to you and starts to look over your shoulder at the film. She asks you what it is you can see on the film. You take a punt at Rigler's sign. She then asks you to explain why you think the x-ray shows Rigler's. You say....
OptionA: You can see both sides of the abdominal wall so free air must be present in the abdomen.
OptionB: Both sides of the bowel wall are visible due to air on the luminal and peritoneal side.
OptionC: You know that the patient recently had an operation to remove a colonic cyst.
OptionE: You notice parts of the bowel twisting in on itself in multiple areas.
Explanation: Rigler's sign is both sides of the bowel wall being visible due to air in the abdomen, both the luminal and peritoneal sides of the bowel wall, so both sides are visible. This is often due to perforation due to recent operation or over distension but as an SBA, this points to what Rigler's is visible as on the X-Ray and not what we might speculate to be the cause. Answers C and D could be correct but are not Rigler's sign = both sides of the bowel wall visible.

Question: Where is the main site of colorectal cancer?
Explanation: The majority or cancers in this area are in the rectum - 27%. Next on this list is sigmoid colon (20%) and caecum (14%), Tv colon (5%) and descending colon is the least common site at 3%.

Question: A 65-year-old man comes into your practice. He has a rash on one patch of skin. You suspect VSV which is a virus that gets more severe with age, and the risk increases with age too. What is the name of the illness?
Explanation:
Shingles is the reactivation of VSV many years after the initial chicken pox episode.

Severity and risk increase with age. 

There is a live attenuated vaccine that is given as a 1 off IM injection

All people aged > 70 get the vaccine.

Question:
A patient comes to your practice asking for some advice on flu. 

 

He says "I had flu last year so I've got an immunity, why do I need the flu jab again this year?"

 

You try to explain to him about how some small mutations take place, meaning that the subtype of flu this year could be slightly different from last year, causing reinfection. 

 

What is the name of this process?
Explanation: Antigenic drift is when there are small changes in the envelope proteins due to mutation. This could cause epidemics such as the flu epidemics seen on an annual basis.

Question: SSPE (subacute sclerosing panencephalitis) is caused by a virus that can be immunised against. Which virus is this?

Steve is a 17 year old boy who has been peer pressured into taking recreational drugs with his friends. At first he feels euphoric, has a surge of energy and feels that he has lost all inhibition. Steve feels like he needs to drink a lot of water but is unable to urinate. He has no motor symptoms and does not experience any delusions or hallucinations.   However after several hours the drug begins to wear off and Steve becomes irritable and more anxious than usual. 

 

What drug has Steve most likely taken?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. 

 

MDMA is a psychotomimetic drug which and so affects though, perception and mood without causing psychomotor stimulation or depression. It inhibits the re-uptake of serotonin and causes the release of more serotonin, and therefore induces euphoria, loss of inhibitions and an energy surge. Side effects include irritability, anxiety and aggression. Adverse drug reactions include acute hyperthermia and excess water intake and retention. 

 

Although Amphetamines and Cocaine cause similar psychological symptoms of euphoria etc. these are psychomotor drugs and so cause motor symptoms as well. Steve has no motor symptoms so MDMA is more likely than these answers.

 

LSD causes altered perceptions such as hallucinations or delusions, which Steve is not experiencing.

 

Cannabis has similar but less pronounced effects than psychotomimetic drugs and has a relaxing effect. Steve's symptoms suggest that he has taken a more powerful psychostimulant than cannabis.

Question: Which part of the heart tube eventually forms the SA node?
Explanation: The sinus venous starts to undergo waves of depolarisations at faster rates than the rest of the heart tube. The sinus venosus gets incorporated into the right atrium and then part of it forms the SA node.

Question: What channel is associated with LQT3?
Explanation: Jeff Allens Lecture

Question:
A 28-year-old woman attends her GP surgery as she is concerned that she hasn't had a period in the 2 months since she gave birth to her first child. 

She explains that she has experienced no other associated symptoms and that she has been breastfeeding since the birth, with no complications or difficulty. 

The GP then assures the patient that what she is experiencing is normal as the breastfeeding has led to a phenomenon called lactational amenorrhoea. 

What is most likely to be the main underlying cause of this amenorrhoea?
OptionA: Breastfeeding disrupts the pulsatile release of GnRH from the hypothalamus and so the release of LH from the pituitary, suppressing ovulation
OptionB: The patient has experienced severe weight loss and so is no longer having periods due to increased levels of ghrelin which can alter the HPO axis
OptionC: Lactation has put the patient's body under increased stress and so the patient is experiencing phantom amenorrhoea as a result
OptionD: Breastfeeding has led to reduced levels of the enzyme plasmin in the endometrium, which normally prevents the blood from clotting, meaning a large clot has formed
OptionE: Breastfeeding each day has led to the patient experiencing post-natal depression which has disrupted the normal menstrual cycle
Explanation:
The correct answer is A - this is the recognised mechanisms of lactational amenorrhoea. 

 

B and E may well be plausible explanations in certain circumstances, however the question says that the patient has experienced no other associated symptoms and that the breastfeeding has produced no complications. 

 

C is made up -  although increased stress levels can lead to amenorrhoea, phantom amenorrhoea is not a known phenomenon. In addition, the patient has had no difficulty breastfeeding.  

 

D - although this is true regarding the function of the plasmin enzyme, there has been no significant evidence showing that breastfeeding can alter the levels of the enzyme in the endometrium and so is not as plausible an answer as A.

Question:
Mr BorkBork, 70, a Caucasian man, comes into clinic feeling very unwell. Immediately you notice he is itching the right side of his abdomen and looks unwell. He says he has been feeling quite feverish for a few days and has been having headaches. He then tells you that a rash has started to come up this morning. He removes his top and you see a blister-like rash covering the right half of his abdomen.

 

He tells you he suffered from cold sores every now and then and his past medical history indicates that he was hospitalised at the age of 19 for chickenpox. He is a diabetic and also has a family history of testicular cancer. What virus is likely causing Mr BorkBork's rash and general discomfort?
Explanation:
The answer is E. The symptoms described are those classic of Shingles. Shingles is the reactivation of VZV after an infection of chicken pox. The likelihood of getting shingles increases with age and that is why all people over 70 are recommended to get the shingles vaccine. The rash tends to not cross the midline of the patient. 

 

Cytomegalovirus does not usually cause any symptoms unless immunosuppressed, which this man isn't. This is the same for Kaposi's Sarcoma virus which tends to only become a problem in those who are immunosuppressed or are of Mediterranean, Jewish or African descent.

 

Measles usually causes a widespread maculopapular rash, different to the blister-like rash shown in Mr BorkBork. Furthermore, Mr BorkBork has no other symptoms of measles such as a runny nose, koplik spots or conjunctival suffusion.

Question: Different TLRs are used to identify different microbial products inside and outside the cell. Which TLR is located on endosomes?
Explanation:
TLR 1, 2, 4 and 6 are located on the plasma membrane and therefore detect extracellular pathogens or microbial products. 

 

TLR 3, 7, 8 and 9 are located on endosomes and therefore the pathogen must have moved intracellularly.

Question:
Mrs Jones has just given birth to her first child: a 5lb baby boy.  However, upon examination, you realise that the baby's feet are pointed down and inwards at an unusual angle.  You suspect that her child has clubbed feet and reassure Mrs Jones that it is a common and curable condition.  She asks why this condition occurs, and you inform her that it is a result of compression in the amniotic cavity over a prolonged period of time.  

 

Considering this, what type of abnormality are clubbed feet?
Explanation:
Disruption: alterations of pre-existing structures due to destructive processes (eg. Amniotic band syndrome)

Deformation:Deformations – mechanical factors that mould fetal parts over prolonged periods (eg. Clubfeet result from compression in the amniotic cavity)

Malformation: occur during formation of structures (eg. organogenesis), usually due to environmental and/or genetic factors (most originate during the 3-8th weeks of gestation)

Chromosomal breakage: Usually due to environmental factors (virus, drugs, radiation) and results in the loss of a broken piece of chromosome (e.g Cri du Chat)

Mitochondrial disorder: disorder caused by the dysfunction of mitochondria (not the case regarding clubbed feet)

 

From Dave Wilson's case 7 lecture on congenital malformations and teratology

Question:
3 months ago Jill, a 48 year old woman, was diagnosed with hypertension. Her GP started her on a standard dose of Ramipril which has been reasonably effective at reducing her blood pressure. However Jill has returned to the GP complaining of various side effects that she has been experiencing since starting the drug such as a dry, tickly cough which has not gone away, frequent headaches and occasional diarrhoea and vomiting. The GP decides to start Jill on a different medication. 

 

Which medication would the GP be most likely to prescribe?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

Ramipril is an ACE inhibitor and is the first drug you will try to manage hypertension because it is effective and inexpensive. However it can have several side effects which may not be tolerated by the patient. 

 

Lorsartan is an Angiotensin II Receptor Blocker. It is very effective at managing hypertension and has very few side effects. The only reason that it is not used as a first line therapy is because it is more expensive than Ramipril. Of all of the options this is the most likely option that the GP would try after Ramipril. 

 

Pharmacological Management of Hypertension

 

ACE Inhibitors - e.g. Ramipril

  • ACE inhibitors block the enzyme which produces angiotensin II.
  • This has an effect on the kidney, RAAS, cardiac and vascular components.
  • These are often the first drugs you will try.

Angiotensin II Receptor Blockers - e.g. Losartan

  • ARBs prevent angiotensin II binding to its receptors.
  • This also has an effect on all 3 systems, and has few side effects.

Diuretics - e.g. Furosemide

  • These prevent water re-absorption in the kidney by trapping electrolytes in the urine.
  • Side effects include needing to go to the toilet more often.

Ca2+ Channel Blockers e.g. Nifedipine

  • These prevent Ca2+ entering smooth muscle cells, reducing the amount of vasoconstriction.

Beta Blockers e.g. Atenolol

  • Block β-1 adrenoreceptors to reduce the amount of Ca2+ entering cardiomyocytes and pacemaker cells, which reduces the heart rate and force of contraction.
  • Ideally you want cardio-selective β blockers.
  • These are not the first line therapy for hypertension.

Nitrates e.g. Glyceryl trinitrate (GTN)

  • Mimic the effects of NO; they cause vasodilation due to effects on myosin light chain phosphatase.
  • Only good for occasional use, as the patient can become nitrate tolerant.

Question:
Creating an antiviral state;

 

This process starts with virus entry into the body.

PRRs or RLRs detect the viral presence which causes the activation of interferon response factors (IRFs) that enter the nucleus and initiate transcription of IFN alpha/beta. 

IFN alpha/beta then bind to IFN receptors that are found on most cells. 

This triggers the JAK/STAT activation.

 

What is the next step in the process?
OptionA: The IRF directly create the antiviral state as the IRF multiply extremely quickly. The main action of IRF is to suppress viral replication in the host cell.
OptionB: Transcription of the alpha and beta IRF to get several hundred IRFs which cause an antiviral state by suppressing viral entry, alter cell metabolism and suppress viral replication.
OptionC: Transcription of the alpha and beta IFN forming an antiviral state by suppressing viral entry
OptionD: Transcription of several hundred ISG (IFN stimulated genes) which create an antiviral state by suppressing viral entry, alter cell metabolism and suppress viral replication.
Explanation:
This process starts with virus entry into the body.

PRRs or RLRs detect the viral presence which causes the activation of interferon response factors (IRFs) that enter the nucleus and initiate transcription of IFN alpha/beta.

IFN alpha/beta then bind to IFN receptors that are found on most cells.

This triggers the JAK/STAT activation.

 

The next step is the transcription of several hundred ISGs which create an antiviral state by suppressing viral entry, suppressing viral replication and altering cell metabolism. 

 

IFNs can act in an autocrine, endocrine or paracrine fashion

Question:
On March 4th 2018, Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were found unconscious slumped on a bench in Salisbury. They has been poisoned with a nerve agent called Novichok. Question:
Mrs. Chinn is a 69-year-old that presents to your clinic complaining of fatigue and dizziness. She has no history of other medical conditions. You order a blood test which shows:

 

Hb: 9.8 g/dL (11.5-13.5)

MCV: 86fl (80-100)

Platelets: 49 x 10^9 L (150-400)

Neutrophils: 1.3 x 10^9 L (2-7.5)

Ferritin: 120ug/L (41-400)

 

What type of anaemia is Mrs. Chinn suffering from?
What is the incidence of a very rare autosomal recessive disorder with a carrier frequency of 1 in 30?
Explanation:
Need to use the Hardy-Weinberg Equation: p2 + 2pq + q2 

 

The carrier frequency is derived from 2pq --> 2pq = 1/30 --> pq = 1/60

as the autosomal condition is very rare, we can assume that p = ~1, so q = 1/60

 

The incidence of the autosomal disease is = q2 therefore (1/60)2 = 1/3600 --> the answer is 1/3600

Question:
Mr Priest, a 59 year old man, has just received a knee replacement operation. The anaesthetist gives him a local anaesthetic to prevent post-operative pain, and explains to Mr Priest that although this particular anaesthetic takes a little time to work, the pain relief will last for several hours. 

 

Which drug is the anaesthetist most likely to have administered?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

 

Atracurium, Botox and Suxamethonium are all examples of neuromuscular blockades and so are not local anaesthetics. 

Lidocaine is a local anaesthetic however it has a quick acting effect and only lasts for 30 minutes. 

Bupivacaine takes longer to work but lasts for several hours. 

 

A local anaesthetic reduces or abolishes sensation in a particular area or region of the body by reversibly binding sodium channels involved in depolarising the cell membrane which inhibits the conduction of impulses.

 

A neuromuscular blockade causes paralysis of the affected skeletal muscles and prevents spontaneous movement of muscle during surgical operations. They do this by preventing the interaction of neurotransmitters with ion channels of the post synaptic membrane.

Question:
Jemima is a 14 year old girl who visits her GP with low back pain which started around a week ago and has been steadily getting worse, especially when she does activities such as cheerleading. The pain is especially bad on the left side and it radiates into her left buttock and leg. On examination she has  lordosis of the lower spine and tenderness in her lower back on palpation. The GP arranges an X-ray to be taken of the spine and suggests that she reduces the amount of gymnastics and cheerleading she does.

 

What is the most likely cause of Jemima's back pain?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. 

 

Spondylolysis is a bony defect in the vertebra between the lamina and transverse process. It is thought to be a stress fracture and is common in children, particularly gymnasts. It is the most common cause of low back pain in children.

 

A disc prolapse (or 'slipped disc') is protrusion of the inner nucleus pulposus through a tear in the outer annulus fibrosus. It results from sudden twisting/bending of the backbone or heavy lifting, so could potentially be the cause of Jemima's pain, however in children it is less common than Spondylolysis therefore is not the 'most likely' cause of her pain. 

 

Inflammatory spondyloarthropathy is a chronic disease of the joints. It again has similar symptoms to spondylolysis but is less common.

 

Kyphosis is an outward curving of the spine, particularly the upper spine. Jemima has a lordosis of the lower spine and so does not have kyphosis. 

 

Scoliosis is a lateral deviation of the backbone.

Question: What mechanism does HCMV use to evade the immune system?
OptionA: Blocks the interferon receptors, down-regulating the production of interferon stimulated genes
OptionB: Infects cDCs so it can traffic to the draining lymph node and infect CD4 T cells
OptionC: Downregulates MHC class I by inhibiting peptide loading
OptionD: Prevents interferon response factors entering the nucleus, hence preventing interferon generation
OptionE: Blocks release of cytokines IL-1 and IL-6
Explanation:
HCMV attempts to evade the immune system by down regulating MHC class I as HCMV protein US6 inhibits peptide loading. The groove of MHC class I will not be filled by peptide in the endoplasmic reticulum and will not be trafficked to the plasma membrane. 

This however, is dealt with by NK cell response- since there is no MHC class I displayed on the plasma membrane of the infected cell, there is no engagement of inhibitory receptors on the NK cell. Activatory receptors on the NK cell predominate, resulting in full activation of NK cell, granule production and release of granzymes and apoptosis of the cell infected by HCMV.

 

B= Action of HIV, exploiting the adaptive immune response use of CCR7 on cDCs that directs the cDCs to the nearest draining lymph node. DCs follow the trail of the CCL21 chemokine.

 

D= Action of Ebola- Ebola virus protein VP35 prevents IRF generation, IRF ability to enter the nucleus and hence generation of interferons. Any interferons that are produced are blocked by Ebola protein VP24 which prevents signal release from interferon receptor activation (so no JAKSTAT activation and no transcription of interferon stimulated genes). The action of the Ebola proteins shuts down the interferon response that would usually reduce viral mRNA translation and prevent replication, allowing unchecked replication of EBola and rapid dissemination through the body. 

The most pathogenic viruses shut off the supply of interferons and prevent the anti-viral state.

Question: What is the most common immunoglobulin isotype found in the blood serum?

Type Frequency Shape Notes
IgG 75% Monomer • Enhance phagocytosis of bacteria and viruses

IgA 15% Monomer/ dimer

Pentamer when secreted

IgE 0.1% Monomer • Mediates type 1 hypersensitivity reactions
• Binds to Fc receptors found on the surface of mast cells and basophils
• Provides immunity to parasites such as helminths
• Least abundant isotype in blood serum

Question: What happens at C on the JVP graph?

You are assessing the ECG for a patient in an ambulance alongside a paramedic. You notice that the QRS complex in Lead 1 is positive whereas in lead aVF is negative. Which of the following would explain this pattern on an ECG?
Explanation:
This ECG is an example of left axis deviation. When determining the axis deviation on an ECG, one method we can use is the quadrant method. The idea is that Lead 1 is at 0 degrees whereas lead aVF is at +90 degrees. Since a normal QRS axis fits within -30 degrees and +90 degrees, this would mean both QRS complexes would be positive in lead 1 and aVF normally. 

 

In left axis deviation, we would see a negative QRS in aVF whereas lead 1 would be positive.

Question:
A 32 year old female, Judith, has come into clinic feeling extremely tired with very low mood. 2 months ago she gave birth to a baby girl, little baby Betsy, and is the sole carer for her child. She finds her low mood and fatigue is stopping her from being the best mother she can be for Betsy. 

 

Having asked if anything else is troubling her she replies, "I have noticed I have been getting pains in my joints, especially my knees. Even the short walk from my house has caused me to have knee pain and my muscles have started to cramp up. I'm no longer getting my periods and I've put on weight but I guess that's just because I'm breastfeeding and have kept the baby weight. I just feel so down all the time"

 

You notice that, she appears to be shivering and rubbing her hands together while telling you this story. On examination, you notice that she is bradycardic.

 

Without doing further investigations, what is the most likely cause of Judith's symptoms?
OptionC: Increased cortisol levels owing to the stresses of having to care for a newborn.
Explanation:
Post partum hypothyroidism is a form of hypothyroidism that women can experience usually within the first year of giving birth. It is thought to be linked to the changes in hormone levels during pregnancy. It is vital that you request a thyroid function test as many people with postpartum hypothyroidism are misdiagnosed with postnatal depression.

 

Euthyroid sick syndrome is when there are abnormal thyroid levels that are not due to thyroid disease. This can only be eliminated by thyroid function tests. The fact that Judith has just given birth makes it more likely that she has hypothyroidism rather than Euthyroid sick syndrome.  

 

Increased cortisol levels do cause lots of the symptoms above such as mood swings and depression, weight gain and problem with muscles. However, cortisol increases your heart rate and would not cause bradycardia. Furthermore, clues such as cold sensitivity indicate hypothyroidism.

 

You are more at risk of getting rheumatoid arthritis after giving birth, however her other symptoms do not line up with this being solely arthritis.

 

Note, you can get menstrual irregularities with hypothyroidism but Judith won't be having periods anyway due to her breastfeeding.

Question: Which of these tests give an estimate of the length of time that glucose has been high?
Explanation: HbA1c is glycosylated haemoglobin- the amount of Hb that is attached gives an idea of how long the glucose levels have been high.

Question:
Earnest is a 78 year old man who presents at his GP complaining of breathlessness, trouble breathing whilst lying down, weight loss and needing to go to the toilet frequently. On examination he has jugular venous distension, ascites, hepatomegaly and tachycardia.

 

The GP suspects that Earnest has heart failure and arranges for him to have echocardiography to determine his systolic and diastolic left ventricular performance.

 

Which of the following would be indicative of low systolic function?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

Low systolic function is defined as an ejection fraction of less than 40%. 

 

Cardiac output potentially could be used as an indicator of systolic function, however in the lecture 'Pathophysiology and Imaging of Heart Failure' ejection fraction was mentioned far more often, and so may be a more accurate measurement? Normal cardiac output is 4.0 - 8.0 L/min.

Question: The synthesis of serotonin originates from which dietary amino acid?
Explanation:
Tryptophan is the correct answer. 

 

Serotonin synthesis:

Trytpopha from diet >> 5HT (hydroxytryptophan) >> Serotonin. Serotonin can then be converted to melatonin in the pineal gland to aid with slee. This is why people who are depressed with low serotonin, are also sleeping badly because of low levels of melatonin.

Question: The synthesis of catecholamines originates from from which amino acid?
Explanation:
Tyrosine is correct. 

 

Tyrosine is consumed in food. 

 

It is converted to L-DOPA and from here there is a pathway to generate the different catecholamines

 

Dopamine:

L-DOPA >> Dopamine in dopaminergic neurons

 

Noradrenaline:

L-DOPA >> Dopamine >> Noradrenaline (in NA neurons)

 

Adrenaline 

L-DOPA >> Dopamine >> Noradrenaline >> Adrenaline (in adrenergic neurons and adrenal medulla)

Question: Which dopaminergic pathway transfers dopamine from the ventral tegmental area to the nucleus accumbens?
Explanation:
Mesolimbic

 

A: mesocortical transers dopamine from VTA to cortex. It is normally involved in thinking and planning. In schizophrenia, dopamine is low in this pathway and it causes the negative symptoms.

 

B: Mesolimbic transfers dopamine from VTA to nucleus accumbens which is involved in the reward pathway. In schizophrenia, dopamine is increased in this pathway and causes the positive symptoms

 

C: Nigrostriatal transfers dopamine from substantia nigra to basal ganglia. It is involved in movement, as well as addiction. Antipsychotics increase dopamine in this area and cause parkinsonism >> tremor and bradykinesia.

 

D: Tubuloinfundibular pathway moves dopamine from hypothalamus to anterior pituitary gland and regulates the release of prolactin. Antipsyhotics can cause blockage of D2 which increases release of prolactin in the blood and causes abnormal lactation in men.

 

E is made up.

Question:
During fertilisation, fusion of the sperm and egg cell membranes causes an increase in the intracellular Calcium of the oocyte. This causes the Cortical reaction.

 

Which of the following describes the cortical reaction?
OptionA: The breakdown of the acrosomal cap causing a release of enzymes
OptionB: Depolarisation of the egg cell membrane preventing membrane fusion with further sperm - Primary block to polyspermy
OptionC: Granules that lie just below the cell membrane fuse with cell membrane and release enzymes hardening the zona pellucida - Secondary block to polyspermy
OptionD: Meiosis is resumed and the second meiotic division of the egg is completed, forming the definitive oocyte and the second  polar body which is extruded
OptionE: Glycoprotein coat of spermatozoa is removed, initiating a change in surface charge and reorganisation of the sperm cell membrane
Explanation:
Before fertilisation:

  • The sperm is subject to capacitation in the female reproductive tract (E- Glycoprotein coat of spermatozoa is removed, initiating a change in surface charge and reorganisation of the sperm cell membrane) which causes a change in the tail movements increasing forward propulsion and preparing the sperm for the acrosomal reaction.
  • Acrosome reaction (A- The breakdown of the acrosomal cap causing a release of enzymes)   --> this occurs when the capacitated sperm meets the zona pellucida.  The enzymes are released extracellularly to break down the zona pellucida and facilitate fusion

After Fertilisation 3 key events occur in the egg:

  1. B-Depolarisation of the egg cell membrane preventing membrane fusion with further sperm - Primary block to polyspermy
  2. C- Cortical Reaction - Cortical granules that lie just below the cell membrane fuse with cell membrane and release enzymes altering the binding proteins of the zona pellucida preventing further binding of sperm- Secondary block to polyspermy
  3. D-Meiosis is resumed and the second meiotic division of the egg is completed, forming the definitive oocyte and the second polar body which is extruded

Polyspermy would cause triploidy and likely result in miscarriage and so depolarisation of the membrane and the Cortical reaction are very important processes in mammalian reproduction
Tags: Complications in pregnancy, case 7, Pregnancy, embryology, fertilisation

Question:
Ellie is a 18 year old who presents at her GP. She explains that she gets particularly breathless and squeezing chest pain when she plays football and other sports, which disappear once she rests. She also mentions that she often faints for no apparent reason. 

 

The GP carries out an ECG which has a particularly deep S wave in the V2 lead and a particularly tall R wave in the V5 lead. 

 

Ellie is then referred for an echocardiogram which shows thickened walls, diastolic dysfunction and outflow obstructions.

 

What condition does Ellie most likely have?
OptionC: Dilated Cardiomyopathy
OptionD: Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

Angina-like pains are a symptom of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, however Ellie is unlikely to have angina itself because she is young. Also the ECG and echocardiography findings point to HCM rather than angina.

 

Atrial fibrillation can be a symptom of HCM, but again is not the primary cause of her signs and symptoms.

 

Dilated cardiomyopathy is cardiac enlargement with reduced systolic function. It would not usually present with thickened walls in the echocardiogram therefore HCM is more likely. However HCM can lead to cardiac dilation.

 

Wolff-Parkinson-White Syndrome is when there is an accessory cardiac conducting pathway between the atria and ventricles. It presents in young people and the ECG will show delta waves. 

 

 

Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy

 

HCM is a condition characterised by unexplained hypertrophy of the wall of the left ventricle. It generally presents at adolescence and is more common in women. 40-60% of cases are genetic.

 

Features include thick ventricle walls, particularly in the proximal septum, fibrosis/scarring, reduced cardiac output, obstruction of the left ventricular outflow tract, mitral regurgitation and abnormalities in microvascular circulation.

 

Generally patients are asymptomatic, but can present as above. Echocardiography, ECG, MRI and gene testing are used in diagnosis.

 

HCM is the leading cause of sudden death in young adults. 

 

Treatment include beta blockers, diuretics, anticoagulants, treatment for arrhythmias, surgery and pacing strategies.

Question:
Miss X was diagnosed with pre-eclampsia at week 24 of her pregnancy. She developed eclampsia at week 32 and her foetus died. At week 37, labour was induced and Miss X had a still birth.

 

After this traumatic incident, Miss X did not want to wait until she stopped producing milk naturally. She asks you, the doctor, if there were any drugs that could stop her form lactating sooner. 

 

What hormone/synthetic form of the hormone is most likely to be present in these drugs?
Explanation:
Dopamine acts on a pituitary level to prevent the release of prolactin from the anterior pituitary gland. Therefore, no prolactin reaches the alveoli in the breast and no milk is produced. 

 

Oxytocin causes the ejection of milk

 

Oestrogen and progesterone both suppress milk production during pregnancy by interfering with prolactin receptors. It is for this reason why taking the combined pill after giving birth can cause problems with breastfeeding. There have been some trials with oestrogen based drugs to stop milk production, however they are not as effective as dopamine based drugs and they increase the mother's risk of cardiovascular problems 

 

somatostatin inhibits growth hormone at a pituitary level, not prolactin.

Question:
Philip is a 81 year old who has atrial fibrillation and left-sided systolic heart failure. His cardiologist explains to him that one of his main problems is that the left and right sides of his heart do not contract at the same time, and explains that there is a treatment which can solve this problem.

 

Which treatment option is the cardiologist referring to?
OptionE: Myosplint
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. 

 

Ablate and pace is a treatment for atrial fibrillation which involves destroying the atrioventricular node and inserting a pacemaker. Although Philip has does have AF, the treatment that the cardiologist is explaining to him is not ablate and pace, but cardiac resynchronisation therapy.  

 

Cardiomyoplasty involves wrapping anther muscle in the body (e.g. latissimus dorsi) around the heart. A specialised pacemaker is then implanted to make the skeletal muscle contract. 

 

Cardiac resynchronisation therapy involves a small pacemaker being put in the heart to improve heart rhythm and match left and right contraction.

 

An implantable cardioverter defibrillator is used to treat people with dangerous arrhythmias. When an arrhythmia occurs the ICD attempts to correct the rhythm by pacing, cardioversion or defibrillation. It is not usually used for patients with AF.

 

A Myosplint involves three tensioning rods put through the left ventricle to reduce the radius of the chamber wall to reduce wall stress.

Question: What mechanism results in ANTIGENIC SHIFT?
Explanation:
Antigenic drift is due to small MUTATIONS 

 

Antigenic Shift is due to large changes by REASSORTMENT

you see a diabetic man in the diabetic retinopathy clinic. 

 

He has dot and blot haemorrhages as well as hard exudates. 

 

Which category of diabetic retinopathy is this?

this is background diabetic retinopathy.

Proliferative--> new blood vessels--> NVD (new vessels in disc) and NVE (new vessels elsewhere)

End stage--> soft, shrunken eye, corneal vasculatrue, opaque, no vision potential

Question: You are reviewing a patient with a Staphylococcus aureus infection. Think back to PCS and the classification of bacteria. Which of the following images is most likely to depict a staphylococcus aureus infection?
Explanation:
When classifying bacteria we can consider 3 main factors:

-Gram staining. Whether positive or negative.

-Shape. Cocci (as depicting in B), bacilli as (depicted in A), spirilla (depicted in C)

-Metabolism. Aerobic, anaerobic. 

 

Bacteria can also be classified by factors such as:

Mycoplasma, no cell wall

Mycobacterium, complex cell wall.

Whether they are intracellular etc.

Question: In a healthy individual, what is the molecular switch that triggers insulin release from pancreatic beta cells during the fed state?
Explanation:
Although carbohydrate intake following a meal will trigger the release of insulin, the best answer to this question is glucose-6-phosphate.

 

 

High blood glucose in the fed state activates GLUT2 glucose transporters found in the liver and pancreatic beta cells. Glucose is absorbed from the blood into the cells against its concentration gradient via secondary active transport as GLUT2 is coupled with Na+/K+-ATPase. Glucose is broken down by glycolysis, which is unrestricted in the liver and pancreatic B-cells since they possess the enzyme glucokinase to convert glucose to glucose-6-phosphate which does not have product inhibition (unlike hexokinase found elsewhere).

Since the reaction is not inhibited, it is the concentration of glucose-6-phosphate that signals the release of insulin from pancreatic beta cells. 

 

Insulin directs metabolism towards storage and synthesis (anabolism); increasing glucose uptake into cells in exchange for K+, increasing glycolysis, glycogenesis and lipogenesis (TAG synthesis). It down-regulates the action of glucagon and inhibits the reciprocal pathways.

 

Protein kinase A and fructose-2,6-bisphosphate are both involved in the substrate cycle in the liver- ultimately glycolysis is accelerated in the liver in the fed state.

Question: Which of the following best describes the general purpose of (pattern recognising receptors) found on macrophages and dendritic cells?
OptionA: To detect self-antigens to distinguish pathogen from self.
OptionD: To detect double stranded RNA of pathogens
Explanation:
Presence of pathogen is first detected using pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) on surface of macrophages and dendritic cells. PRRs recognise pathogen associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) such as cell wall constituents of bacteria and alien nucleic acids of viruses. For example TLR4 responds to LipoPolySaccharide (LPS) and TLR3 responds to double stranded RNA.

 

Taken from RJM PCS 2 lecture

Question: Jim (89 years old) has come into the clinic as he is overweight and wants a health check up to make sure everything is running smoothly. The doctor requests a blood test to measure his HBA1C. His results are back and the HBA1C is high. What do you do next?
OptionA: Request another HBA1C test- as it must be wrong as Jim has no symptoms
OptionB: Tell Jim everything is great- no need to worry
Explanation:
Answer is E.

 

A HBA1C test alone cannot be used as a diagnosis even if the patient is asymptomatic. 

 

Is a patient is symptomatic: only one test has to be done from; 

 

Fasting plasma glucose > 7.0mmol/L
Random plasma glucose > 11.1mmol/L
(2hr glucose post 75G GTT > 11.1)

 

If asymptomatic: two tests need to be done on two separate days. 

 

HBA1C is really only used as a long-term marker- to potential see how much damage has been done.

Question: Atypical antipsychotics like Olanzapine and Clozapine can cause weight gain. Via which receptor does this work?
Explanation: Blocking H1 receptors in the hypothalamus activates 'AMP activated protein kinase' which is feeding regulator. It increases the demand for calorific intake and also decreases lipolysis and increases lipogenesis in white adipose tissue causing weight gain.

Question: Which of the following is a secondary preventative measure for Diabetic Retinopathy?
Explanation:
Prevention
• Primary
o Blood sugar and BP control
• Secondary prevention
o Annual screening
• Tertiary Prevention
o Laser, anti-VEGF and vitrectomy

Question:
"One kiss is all it takes, fallin' in love with me"

 

Whilst listening to this banger, One kiss by Calvin Harris feat. Dua Lipa, you imagine kissing Dua Lipa. Unfortunately, this fantasy doesn't last for long as revision takes over your mind.

 

In the fantasy, Dua Lipa stops kissing you and says "I hope you don't have glandular fever! It's known as 'the kissing disease'! I have a show coming up in Cardiff on 18th April and I've heard you have to avoid vigorous exercise for 2-3 months after the infection. I wouldn't be able to perform!"

 

Why would Dua Lipa say that you have to stop any vigorous exercise after glandular fever?
OptionA: She just wants a reason to stop kissing you because you're a terrible kisser
OptionB: Over stimulation of sympathetic nervous system may cause the infection to return from its dormant state
OptionC: The virus may spread to others through your sweat
OptionD: A side effect of glandular fever is an splenomegaly, making the spleen susceptible to rupture.
OptionE: Extreme fatigue after glandular fever makes you susceptible to syncope
Explanation:
Glandular fever can leave the patient with splenomegaly making the spleen more susceptible to rupture. This is a medical emergency. Usually, the spleen has returned to normal size after a month but most doctors recommend not doing vigorous exercise for 2 months. 

 

Other complications of mononucleosis are hepatitis and jaundice.

Question:
Mrs Thomas, a 26-year-old, comes to the surgery. She says she feels down, is gaining weight unintentionally, sensitive to the cold, is tired and her periods are irregular. You instantly think of hypothyroidism as she is displaying all of the usual symptoms. She says that her sister and mother also have hypothyroidism. 

 

Levothyroxine is the drug given to people with hypothyroidism. What is levothyroxine?

Question:
Matthew, a 14-year-old boy comes into the surgery. He says that he is eating a lot but losing weight, is sweating all the time, cannot concentrate and feels increasingly anxious. You wonder if this is the effects of him going through puberty. 

 

Nevertheless, you do a thyroid function test to check. 

 

The results come back;

T4- high

TSH- low

 

What is the most common cause for this outcome?
OptionE: toxic multinodular and solitary toxic nodular goitres
Explanation:
The high T4 level and low TSH point towards hyperthyroidism

 

Grave's disease is the reason for hyperthyroidism in 80% of cases. This is followed by toxic multinodular and solitary toxic nodular goitres. 

 

Hashimoto's is the autoimmune disease that is responsible for hypothyroidism

Addison's is increased cortisol production

Question:
You have just finished your lunch break and go back to the GP you are on placement with. She is in the middle of the consultation with a 20 year old female when she tells you to join. 

 

From your initial observations, she looked overweight, tired and had a hoarse voice. The GP then does some of her reflexes and she has a delayed relaxation of the ankle jerks and when looking at her face you notice that the outer third of her eyebrow has gone. 

 

Which disease are you thinking of?
Explanation: these are the clinical signs of hypothyroidism

Question:
Mrs Shelley has addison's disease and is feeling particularly unwell however, she is interested to know what her adrenal glands would look like due to this condition. The cause of the addison's disease is TB. 

 

What is the morphology of the adrenal glands in TB?
Explanation:
The answer is C. In TB, fungal infections and sarcoidosis you get granulomas in the adrenal glands. 

 

A= secondary adrenal insufficiency due to a problem in the pituitary gland

B= metastatic cancer

D= autoimmune adrenalitis

Question:
It is the happiest day of you and your husband's blonde haired lives.

You're giving birth to your first child when suddenly, the baby's ginger head crowns.

"I knew you'd had an affair with the neighbour" shouts your husband.

 

Quickly you try to explain the complications of monogenic inheritance patterns in a last ditch effort to deny it.

 

Which of the following is not a complication of monogenic inheritance?
Explanation:
Confounding factors in monogenic (‘Mendelian’) inheritance

Variable expression
-Same mutation expressed as different disease phenotypes.

Reduced penetrance (“false-negative”)
Can be age-related.

Sex limitation
A mutation predisposes to disease/phenotype in one sex rather than the other.

Phenocopy (“false-positive”)
An occurrence of a disease in a family unrelated to a familial mutation (more relevant to common disease phenotypes).

Copied from Unusual Patterns of Inheritance Lecture

 

Genetic drift occurs in small populations in which uncommon alleles can become extinct

This can cause complications when calculating allele frequencies in a population and so when using the Hardy Weinberg Law , it is required to have a large population size.

 

 

Disclaimer: hair colour is not actually a monogenic phenotype

Question:
Mrs Jenkins has Addison's disease. She looks well in herself due to the hyperpigmentation of her skin and has lost some of the extra weight she was carrying. However, she feels terrible. 

 

From this information, can you deduce what type of Addison's Mrs Jenkins has got?
OptionA: Addison's due to a primary adrenal disease
OptionB: Addison's due to secondary disease (problem with the pituitary gland)
OptionC: can't tell from the information given in the question
Explanation:
Mrs Jenkins has Addison's disease due to a primary adrenal problem. 

 

We can tell this due to the hyperpigmentation (and weight loss due to anorexia). 

This mechanism occurs due to increased amounts of ACTH produced due to the decreased negative feedback. 

The precursor for ACTH stimulates MSH. 

This then decreases appetite and stimulates melanocytes causing the hyperpigmentation of the skin. 

 

In a secondary adrenal disease, there is a problem with the pituitary gland, and therefore the increased amounts of ACTH will not be seen. In fact, ACTH as well as cortisol will be decreased in this situation.

Question: Which of the following is derived from the ectoderm?
Explanation: The adrenal cortex, cranium, dermis of the skin, and blood and lymphatic cells are all mesodermal derivatives

Question:
A patient comes into your GP surgery with intellectual disabilities, they have been suffering with frequent infections. Which of these is another common name for 22q11.2 deletion syndrome?

1 in 5000 people are affected by this.

The inheritance pattern is autosomal dominant

 

Characteristic features:

  • Heart abnormalities
  • Characteristic faces
  • Palatal abnormalities
  • Immune deficiencies - T cell deficiency
  • Short stature
  • Long thin fingers
  • Conductive deafness
  • Psychiatric illness
  • Renal abnormalities

 

 

William's Syndrome - 7q11 deletion

Cri du chat syndrome- 5p deletion

Edward's Syndrome - Trisomy 18

Wolf-Hischhorn - 4p deletion

Question:
Mrs Jones, a 47 year old woman presented complaining about a series of symptoms.  After taking a detailed history, you decide order a Thyroid function test.  The results of the test reveal the following: 

 

Serum TSH:  High

 

Serum free T4: High 

 

Serum T3: High

 

What type of abnormal thyroid function does Mrs Jones most likely have?
Explanation:
As Mrs Jones' T3 and T4 were raised, it is hyperthyroidism rather than hypothyroidism.  As her TSH was also raised, it is suggestive of a secondary cause such as pituitary adenoma resulting in over stimulation of the thyroid gland rather than primary hyperthyroidism. 

 

Graves disease is caused by autoimmune thyroid stimulating antibodies and is responsible for 80% of hyperthyroidism cases but as her TSH was raised this was not the case.  

 

Hashimoto thyroiditis is the most common autoimmune disease to cause primary thyroid failure and hypothyroidsim.

Question: the concentration of ________ is the signal to release insulin
Explanation: The concentration of glucose-6-phosphate is the signal to release insulin from the pancreas.

Question: Which of these does insulin do?
OptionA: increases the uptake of glucose into adipocytes
OptionB: increases the breakdown of glycogen to glucose
OptionC: increases the release of glucose from the liver into the blood
OptionD: down regulates the uptake of glucose into muscle cells
Explanation:
the actions of insulin in the absorptive state are;

  • increases the uptake of glucose into the liver to be stored as glycogen
  • up regulates the uptake of glucose into muscle cells and increases glycogen production in muscle
  • dwon regulates the release of glucose from the liver into the blood.

 

Glucagon is involved in the post absorptive and starvation states and does the opposite to insulin

Question:

Jim goes to Tesco and sees Sue taking the trolley behind him, he goes in to get some eggs and 'sees the same person' 'Sue' next to him taking some eggs

Question: Spondylolysis is the most common cause of significant lower back pain in children. However, it can often be asymptomatic. It is frequently associated with activities that involve hyperextension of the spine. In which part of the vertebra is the defect that causes spondylolysis?

Question: How does insulin regulate glycogen synthase?

Question: What uses fatty acids as it's main source of energy?
Along with ATP regulating glycolysis, what is the other regulator?

You see a 14-year-old girl with very high blood sugar. She has just been diagnosed with diabetes type 1. 

 

When thinking about how glucose regulation works in your own body, you start thinking of PFK2 and PBPase2. 

 

If you have high blood sugar, insulin is released, turning phosphoprotein phosphatase on. 

 

What does this action do and what is the consequence?
OptionA: Phosphoprotein phosphatase dephosphorylates things so the phosphatase is now switched off and kinase switched on. Fru-2,6-BP is converted to Fru-6-P as you want decreased glycolysis and increased gluconeogenesis, which increase blood sugars.
OptionB: Phosphoprotein phosphatase phosphorylates things so the phosphatase is now switched on and kinase switched off. Fru-6-P is converted to Fru-2,6-BP as you want more glycolysis and decreased gluconeogenesis, which increases blood sugars.
OptionC: Phosphoprotein phosphatase phosphorylates things so the phosphatase is now switched on and kinase switched off. Fru-6-P is converted to Fru-2,6-BP as you want more glycolysis and decreased gluconeogenesis, which decreases blood sugars.
OptionD: Phosphoprotein phosphatase dephosphorylates things so the kinase is now switched on and phosphatase switched off. Fru-6-P is converted to Fru-2,6-BP as you want more glycolysis and decreased gluconeogenesis, which decreases blood sugars.
OptionE: Phosphoprotein phosphatase phosphorylates things so the phosphatase is now switched off and kinase switched on. Fru-6-P is converted to Fru-2,6-BP as you want decreased glycolysis and increased gluconeogenesis, which increases blood sugars.
Explanation:
This is from Andrew Shore's lecture. 

 

To get a break down of glucose (to decrease blood glucose) you need a higher concentration of fru-2,6-BP as this is what regulates glycolysis.

Insulin turns phosphoprotein phosphatase on--> dephosphorylates the kinase--> kinase on, phosphatase off--> conversion of fru-6-P into fru-2,6-BP--> increase in glycolysis, decrease in gluconeogenesis

Question: Glucagon is released from the pancreas, like insulin. But from which cells is glucagon released?
What is the optimal time period for the foetal anomaly scan during pregnancy?
Explanation:
A = crown-rump measurement

B = nuchal translucency test

Question:
The GP you're observing tells you about a 19-year old female patient who came in a few months ago with a range of symptoms. She said her treatments for UTIs just don't seem to be working as she kept getting recurrent infections. 

In addition to this, she could barely go an hour without going to the toilet to pass urine, and she was constantly thirsty. Her BMI is normal. 

 

When asked about her family history, she said she thought her dad and paternal grandfather had diabetes, but she can't remember which type. 

 

Her blood tests came back with fasting glucose at 8 mmol/L, increased GTT and increased random plasma glucose. They tested negative for pancreatic auto-antibodies. 

The blood was then sent off for genetic testing. 

 

Which diagnosis is most likely?
Explanation:
I wrote this question as I was confused about MODY, which was discussed in our Overview of Diabetes lecture in Case 10. 

 

A: Unlikely to be DM Type 2 as her BMI is normal. 

B: Unlikely as her blood tested negative for auto-antibodies

C: Correct. There is a strong family link, the patient is at an age where MODY diagnosis is more likely

D: LADA is otherwise known as type 1.5 diabetes. Unlikely as blood tested negative for auto-antibodies

E: Impaired fasting glucose is a type of pre-diabetes. In this case, fasting glucose is above 7.0, which is the threshold for diabetes. If it was between 6.0 and 7.0, then we would consider pre-diabetes. 

 

 

MODY:

  • Symptoms tend to be similar to other types of diabetes i.e polydipsia, polyuria, recurrent infections
  • Age of diagnosis under 30
  • Caused by gene mutations that follow an autosomal dominant pattern, meaning a child of a person with MODY has a 50% chance of having the mutation too

Any questions or corrections pls let me know!

Question:
A 62-year-old male presents to the GP with diplopia when looking to the right.

 

On examination, he is unable to move his right eye laterally past the midline.

 

 

Damage to which of the following nerves would produce this clinical presentation?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D, Abducens.

 

Abducens originates from the word ‘abduct’ - move away from the midline. The abducens nerve innervates the lateral rectus that moves the eye laterally.

 

Palsy results in the eye being unable to be abducted past the midline.

 

Common causes of abducens nerve palsy include:

- Vasculopathic disease (diabetes, hypertension)
- Trauma

 

Less common causes include:

- Raised intracranial pressure
- Temporal arteritis
- Multiple sclerosis

Question: Which of the following describes the genetic basis of CRC with Lynch Syndrome?

Explanation:
Lynch syndrome is also known as Hereditary Non-Polypsosis colon cancer (although it can cause other types of cancer).

Question: Mrs X attends her GP after experiencing pale, offensive smelling diarrhoea, as well a some bloating. She has just returned from a trip abroad. You decide to perform stool microscopy. What do you expect to see?
OptionA: Using iodine crystals, you will see cysts present
OptionC: There will be microscopic blood present in the stool
OptionD: Oocysts will be visible with a modified ZN stain
Explanation:
Answer A is correct. These cysts are formed from the protozoa Giardia and are highly infectious. It is a common protozoa cause of diarrhoea in returning travellers and the diarrhoea tends to be bulky, pale and offensive smelling in nature.

 

Answer B would suggest inflammation. This is used to differentiate IBD from IBS.

 

Microscopic blood present in the stool is often use to identify if cancer may be present.

 

Answer D is relevant for Cryptosporidium. This sporozoa causes diarrhoea, abdominal cramps and weight loss. It is often self limiting in healthy patients but may have other complications in AIDS patients (cholangitis, cholecystitis, disseminated disease)

 

There are lots of species of salmonella, either resulting in food poisoning or typhoid (enteric) fever. Other symptoms would be present.

Question: A 76 year old gentlemen presents to A&E with severe chest pain and breathlessness. An ECG tracing shows that he has an acute myocardial infarction. What is often the earliest ECG change seen during myocardial infarction?
Explanation:
Tall peaked T-waves can suggest a number of abnormalities. If seen in all leads then they usually suggest the individual has hyperkalaemia. However if tall T waves are seen in a particular group of leads it suggests early MI/ ischaemia. The tall T waves are due to potassium leaking through the damaged membrane over the infarcted area.

 

ST depression is also seen in ischaemia 

ST elevation is seen later on in infarction 

prolonged QT intervals are seen in Long QT syndrome 

Tall p waves 'P pulmonale' are seen in right atrial hypertrophy

Question:
You are in clinic speaking to a 40 year old pregnant woman. She has had a nuchal translucency scan at 11 weeks gestation which suggested an increase nuchal translucency.  She is concerned for the risk of Down's syndrome in her foetus and has asked if there are any tests that can be performed to quantify this risk. You suggest a quadruple screening test at 20 weeks gestation. 

 

Which of the following would we expect to see an increase of during the quadruple test?
Explanation:
The components of the test are:

Inhibin-A-Inhibin is produced in the gonads, pituitary gland, placenta, corpus luteum and other organs. Its role is to inhibit the release of FSH. Increased inhibin A is a marker for trisomy 21.

 

Oestriol- It is one of three major endogenous oestrogens, the others being oestradiol and oestrone. Produced by the placenta during pregnancy. Abnormally low levels can be indicative of Down's syndrome.

 

hCG- Produced, first by the corpus lutetium, then by the placenta. Ensures progesterone levels are maintained during the pregnancy to prevent myometrial contraction. Abnormally high in a Down's foetus. 

 

Alpha fetoprotein. This is thought to be an analogue of serum albumin in a foetus. Binds copper, nickel, fatty acids and bilirubin. It is produced by the yolk sac. Low levels detected in Down's syndrome. Higher levels detected in conditions such as gastroschisis or neural tube defects.
Tags: Clinical Tests, Complications in pregnancy, case 7, case 8, embryology

Question: A 43 year old woman, with a BMI of 40, is discussing her pregnancy with her obstetrician. This is is her second pregnancy, her first pregnancy was terminated after 20 weeks after amniocentesis confirmed trisomy 21. The obstetrician is discussing screening tests available to the patient since she has an increased risk of a foetus with Down's. Why would the combined test not be suitable for this particular patient?
OptionA: The patient has had a termination of pregnancy, combined test would not be too risky for the foetus.
OptionB: Increased body mass would mean that serum levels of hCG, AFP, inhibin-A and oestriol will be inaccurate.
OptionC: Increased BMI will make ultrasound scans to measure NT and CRL inaccurate
OptionD: The patient is too old, combined test not recommended in patients aged 40 or above.
OptionE: If the last foetus had Down's, the chance of this foetus having Down's is a 100% therefore a pointless test.
Explanation:
The combined test involves using ultrasound to check the Crown to Rump length, the nuchal translucency and the nasal bone. In morbidly obese patients such as in this example, the ultrasound tests will not be accurate enough to come to a conclusion. In which case, the quadruple test is indicated.

 

The following tests meet current standards:
From 10 weeks + 0 days to 14 weeks + 1 day the combined test (maternal serum - hCG and PAPP-A and nuchal translucency scan) is the recommended screening strategy
the blood sample (or serum sample) can be taken between 10 weeks and 0 days and 14 weeks and 1 day's gestation. The blood sample uses a combination of free beta-hCG and placenta associated plasma protein A (PAPP-A)


the NT and CRL measurement can be taken between 11 weeks and 2 days and 14 weeks and 1 days gestation


From 14 weeks + 2 days to 20 weeks + 0 days, the quadruple test (maternal serum - hCG, AFP, uE3, inhibin A)) for those presenting later is the recommended screening strategy

Question:
You are reviewing a 60 year old patient who comes into your practice complaining of exhaustion on exertion, chest pain, pedal oedema and shortness of breath. She scores a 3/4 on the NYHA scoring system and you recommend a transthoracic ultrasound scan of her heart to observe a cause as well as a CXR. Family history reveals that her brother had muscular dystrophy and died during childhood. Ultrasound scan and CXR reveal that the patient has a reduced ejection fraction as well cardiomegaly, mitral valve regurgitation. 

  

Which of the following conditions would best fit this presentation?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer. Dilated cardiomyopathy. Reduced ejection fraction is indicative of systolic dysfunction as observed in dilated cardiomyopathy. Other indications such as cardiomegaly, mitral valve regurgitation point to dilated cardiomyopathy. 

 

Although heart failure is technically correct, based on the information given in the stem, this is not the best explanation. 

 

This question also alludes to an X linked recessive condition in muscular dystrophy. In accordance with the Case 7 lecture on unusual patterns of inheritance, X linked recessive conditions can present in females as more mild forms of the disease that appear in males. Females with male relatives with muscular dystrophy should be examined regularly for developing dilated cardiomyopathy.

Explanation:

B- Describes S2

C- Correctly describes the physiology behind the development of S3 in mitral valve regurgitation.

D- Mitral valve stenosis leading to a loud S1

E- Describes the development of S4, immediately before systole as the blood vibrates against a stiff wall.

I am a gram-negative, rod-shaped bacteria that causes infectious intestinal disease.

My incubation period is 8-48hrs. Outside of the GI tract, this can cause osteomyelitis in sickle cell patients, focal infections e.g. arterial aneurysms, otitis media in neonates and meningitis.

 

Usually, it is a self-limiting illness but antibiotics can be given if the patient is unwell. 

 

What bacteria am I?

I am a spore-forming, gram-positive rod-shaped bacteria. I am usually contracted after a dose of antibiotics, penicillin and clindamycin in particular. I strip the normal gut flora causing disease.

 

In under 2-year-olds, I am part of their normal gut flora. 

 

What bacteria am I?

Question:
Sarah is a 45 year old woman. Her mother and her aunt have both had breast cancer, and Sarah is visiting her GP to ask whether she is able to have breast cancer screening. 

 

The GP explains that normally the NHS Breast Screening Programme is only for women aged 50 - 70.

 

Why are mammograms not usually recommended for women under 50?
OptionA: Younger women have stronger Coopers ligaments and so their breasts are not as 'droopy', therefore their breasts do not fit into the X-ray as well.
OptionB: Younger women have more glandular tissue in their breasts and so compression of their breasts in the X-ray is very painful.
OptionC: There is more fatty tissue in the breasts of younger women therefore tumour shadows are obscured.
OptionD: Younger women have more glandular tissue in their breasts and so the breasts are more dense on mammograms, so it is harder to pick up tumour shadows.
OptionE: Women under 50 do not get breast cancer therefore there is no point screening for it.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. 

 

A - it is true that breasts get more 'droopy' with age as Coopers ligaments are stretched and gradually lose strength, however this has no effect on whether a woman can have a mammogram or not. 

 

B - younger women do have more glandular tissue in their breasts which may make mammograms more painful, but this is not the main reason why younger women are not on the breast screening programme. 

 

C - this is incorrect as younger women have less fatty tissue and more glandular tissue than older women. 

 

D - this is correct.

 

E - women under 50 can get breast cancer however their risk is generally very low. 

 

In Sarah's case her risk is higher due to her family history of breast cancer, therefore she may be offered screening earlier. 

 

This website has lots of helpful information about breast screening - http://www.cancerresearchuk.org/about-cancer/breast-cancer/screening/breast-screening

Question:
Charlotte is an 18 year old girl who visits her GP complaining of occasional breast tenderness. She is very worried because her Grandma recently died of breast cancer, and Charlotte is worried that she may also have breast cancer. 

 

The GP reassures Charlotte that at the age of 18 breast cancer is extremely unlikely and that the breast tenderness is more likely due to the effect of a hormone involved in menstruation which stimulates the formation of epithelial cells at the end of breast ducts and so can cause tenderness. 

 

Which hormone is the GP referring to?
OptionA: LH
OptionB: Oestrogen
OptionC: Oxytocin
OptionD: Progesterone
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. 

 

  • At puberty there is rapid growth of the breasts.
  • Oestrogen stimulates the rudimentary lactiferous ducts to elongate and bifurcate.
  • Progesterone stimulates the formation of immature alveoli at the ends of the ducts.
  • The ducts further develop during pregnancy.
  • Breast tenderness can occur monthly due to the influence of progesterone in the luteal phase of menstruation.
  • Breast size is caused by the deposition of fatty tissue, which is influenced by oestrogen.
  • Prolactin, growth hormone, insulin, cortisol and thyroxine are also involved in the development of the breasts.

Question:
One morning the Dursleys find a baby left at their doorstep with nothing but a note, which explains that this baby boy is their nephew Harry. The Dursleys reluctantly take him in, but are mildly concerned as they cannot remember when Harry was born and so do not know which developmental milestones they should be looking out for to make sure that he is developing properly.

 

 

They take Harry to the GP to have a check up. Harry is able to walk around 1-2 steps independently, can pick up toys with a 2 finger pincer grasp, can say the word 'mama' and is able to play with the Dursley's 1 year old son Dudley. He also occasionally emits magic sparks from his toenails...

 

What approximate age is Harry based on these developmental features?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D - Harry is showing developmental signs of a child who is 1 year old. 

 

 A 1 month old should be able to lift their head, track objects with their eyes, recognise their parents and communicate through cooing and crying.

 

A 6 month year old should be able to sit up, can grab at certain objects with a 'raking grasp', babbles and has stranger anxiety.

 

A 9 month old should be able to walk with assistance, pick objects up with a 3 finger grasp, can wave bye bye and may be able to say 'mama' or 'dada'.

 

A 1 year old should be able to walk, pick up things with a 2 finger pincher grasp, can say 'mama' and 'dada' and can imitate parents. (walking and talking may appear later so if they cannot do this it is not necessarily abnormal development. 

 

A 2 year old should be able to walk 2 or more steps independently, start using 2 word phrases, follow certain commands and build towers of around 6 blocks high.

Question: You are reviewing a patient who is undergoing hypertensive therapy. The patient takes his systemic blood pressure 4 times a day for you to review. The last reading he produced gave a systemic blood pressure of 160/90mmHg. You are quite concerned by this measurement and begin to interpret it. What is the ' systemic pulse pressure' in this individual?
Explanation:
Pulse pressure is measured by subtracting the diastolic systemic pressure from the systolic blood pressure. 

In this case 160-90= 70mmHg.

 

This is a clinically significant measurement as it can be said to be proportional to the stroke volume of the left ventricle. 

 

If the pulse pressure is 25% or less of the systolic value, it is said to be narrow. This is a sign of low stroke volume. Causes could include severe blood volume loss or congestive heart failure.

 

Pulse pressure increases physiologically during exercise. Up to 100mmHg can be normal as exercise results in a higher systolic pressure with little change in the diastolic pressure. Consistently high pulse pressure maybe an indication of reduced compliance in the aorta or major arteries.

Question: A 26-year-old man with schizophrenia who started clozapine 3 weeks ago comes in for his weekly blood test. Which of the following is an established life-threatening side effect of clozapine?
Explanation: Agranulocytosis is an acute condition in which a severe neutropenia occurs. This is thought to occur in approximately 1% of those taking clozapine - an antipsychotic medication used to treat refractory schizophrenia. Therefore, patients taking clozapine require ongoing monitoring which involves weekly blood tests for the first 18 weeks, every 2 weeks until 1 year and every 4 weeks thereafter.

Question: An 84-year-old male is on your ward for community-acquired pneumonia. He was diagnosed with Parkinson's 5 years ago. He is now getting very agitated on the ward. You notice his prescription chart where he is prescribed haloperidol for agitation. After being given this, his Parkinson's symptoms dramatically worsen. What is the presumed method of action of haloperidol?
Explanation:
Haloperidol is a typical antipsychotic. All antipsychotics act via blocking the dopamine receptors in the brain.

 

There are two main classes of antipsychotics, typical and atypical. Typical antipsychotics are not selective and block a wide variety of dopamine receptors in the brain. This non-selective blockage is thought to result in unwanted side effects, including parkinsonism.

 

Parkinson's disease is a result of depletion in dopaminergic neurones. If you add an antipsychotic which blocks any remaining dopamine transmissions then this will exacerbate symptoms.

Question:
A 22-year-old woman comes to see you complaining of a cough and runny nose that has been ongoing for 2 days. She would like some treatment for this but you advise her that she has a common cold, the symptoms of which will improve with time.

 

Which one of the following is the common cold most commonly caused by?
Explanation: The common cold is caused by rhinoviruses. Bronchiolitis is commonly caused by the respiratory syncytial virus. Flu is caused by the influenza virus.

Question: You are presented with this barium follow through radiograph and identify 'rosethorn ulcers' (as indicated by arrows). What condition would you suspect following this radiological finding?
Explanation:
Rosthorn ulcers are deep liner ulcers formed as a result of transmural inflammation and penetrating ulceration from Crohn's disease. These ulcers become filled with barium to produce the characteristic appearance. 

 

Barium follow through studies are good for detecting Crohn's. The disease typically affects the terminal ileum with other radioogical findings such as; nodularity, ulceration, narrowing, irregularity of the lumen- 'string sign' due to transmural thickening and irritative spasm, 'cobblestoning'- areas of extensive fissures and ulceration with intact but edematous mucosa between.
Tags: Abdomen, X-rays, Case 11, Function of GI, Imaging

Question:
The Pressure Volume loop can be used to demonstrate changes in the left ventricle throughout the cardiac cycle.

What changes would you expect to see if preload is increased (assuming that inotropy and afterload are constant)?
OptionA: The loop will become wider to the left hand side
OptionB: The loop will become wider to the right hand side
OptionC: The loop will become taller and narrower
OptionD: There will be no change whilst the afterload and inotropy remain constant
OptionE: The loop will shift to the right hand side without increasing width
Explanation:
The increased preload will lead to increase end diastolic volume and pressure. Based on the Frank Starling mechanism,  the ventricle will contract and expel blood so that the end systolic volume remains constant (there is increased stroke volume)

Point D will be further to the right with the increased preload. Point A and B remain at the same position as the end systolic volume is constant.

Question:
A 42 year old woman comes to visit you in the GP complaining of shivers, cough, fatigue and pain in her arms and legs. You take her temperature and see that she has a high fever and as a result suspect that this is a certain type of virus. This virus will elicit an immune response due to it binding to a specific receptor on NK cells, but to aid her recovery you also prescribe her some antivirals.

 

Which receptor recognises this virus and which antivirals are you most likely to prescribe?
OptionA: TLR 7 recognises the virus and aciclovir is prescribed.
OptionB: TLR 8 recognises the virus and oseltamivir is prescribed.
OptionC: TLR 4 recognises the virus and ribavirin is prescribed.
OptionD: TLR 3 recognises the virus and aciclovir is prescribed.
OptionE: TLR 7 recognises the virus and zidovudine is prescribed.
Explanation:
The symptoms described were common symptoms of the influenza virus. Influenza is recognised by TLR 8 receptors on NK cells and therefore TLR 8 was the correct answer. The antivirals prescribed would most likely have been oseltamivir. 

 

Aciclovir is used to treat herpes simplex and varicella zoster.
Ribavirin is used to treat hepatitis C.

Zidovudine is used to treat HIV.

 

These antivirals are all found in the case 9 pharmacology lightbulb.

Question:
Sandra is a 63 year old woman who comes into the GP. She recently read in the Daily Mail that eating sausages and bacon can increase the risk of bowel cancer. Sandra is very worried that she may have colon cancer because she has eaten a full English breakfast every day for the past 40 years!

 

The GP asks her various questions about recent symptoms such as changes in bowel habits, blood in stools, abdominal pain or weight loss. Sandra has no symptoms, but because she is over 60 the GP offers her a faecal occult blood test which is used to screen for bowel cancer. 

 

There are various risk factors for bowel cancer. Which of the following is not a risk factor?
OptionB: Having a close relative who has also had bowel cancer
OptionC: Having fewer than 40 bowel cancer SNPs.
OptionE: Smoking
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

 

There are a variety of environmental, familial and genetic risk factors for bowel cancer. 

 

Environmental risk factors include eating red meat and wheat bran, and smoking. A high BMI increases risk in males, but decreases risk in females. Eating fruit/veg and oily fish, use of NSAIDs and exercise decreases risk. 

 

1 in 5 colorectal cancer patients have a close relative who also has colorectal cancer, and the more affected relatives there are, the greater the risk. 

 

SNPs are single-nucleotide polymorphisms - a change in a single nucleotide in a DNA sequence. There are around 57 SNPs across the genome which ca predict the risk of bowel cancer. Most people have around 40 of these. Above this, the more of these SNPs you have the higher the risk of bowel cancer.

 

Lynch Syndrome is a dominantly inherited condition which causes people to have a higher risk of developing cancers, specifically colorectal and endometrial cancers.

 

This is all from the 'Genetics and the GI Tract' lecture in Case 11.

Question:
Supernanny Jo Frost is on a mission to help desperate parents with their badly behaved children. 

 

She visits the Davies family. Their 6 year old boy Jimmy is a manipulative so and so, who rules the house with ridiculous temper tantrums. One particular problem is that the only food Jimmy will eat are dinosaur chicken nuggets... he has not eaten any fruit or vegetables for the past 4 months. 

 

 

 

Recently Jimmy has been feeling achy and unwell. He has been more tired and irritable than usual, resulting in even more tantrums. He often complains that his gums very sore and sometimes bleed.

 

Which vitamin is Jimmy deficient in?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D - Vitamin C.

 

Jimmy is suffering from scurvy, due to his poor fruit and vegetable intake. Symptoms include feeling tired and weak all the time, feeling irritable and sad, severe joint or leg pain, swollen, bleeding gums, red/blue spots on the skin and skin that bruises easily. 

 

A - Niacin deficiency causes Pellagra. Symptoms include inflamed skin, diarrhoea, dementia and sores in the mouth.

 

B - Riboflavin deficiency causes various symptoms such as cheliosis (sores in the corners of the mouth), sore throat, redness/swelling in the mouth and of the tongue and moist scaly skin.

 

C - Thiamine deficiency causes Beri Beri. Signs and symptoms include difficulty breathing, enlarged heart, pulmonary and peripheral oedema, tachycardia, confusion and memory loss, neurological problems. 

 

E - Vitamin D deficiency causes rickets in children and osteomalacia in adults. It can cause skeletal deformities, bone pain, poor growth and an increased risk of fracture. 

 

Remember... Nutrition = Life.

 

This is from the 'Fundamentals of Nutrition' Lecture in Case 11.

These DCs migrate to mucosal lymph such as Peyers patches to generate an IgA response.
