Question:
Mrs. McDougal storms into her GP surgery with her 14 year old son Dougal McDougal. She is very angry because Dougal has started smoking and staying out late with his friends after school, and she wants the GP to explain to Dougal how stupid that is..

 

The GP is annoyed that Mrs. McDougal is wasting an appointment, and explains to her that Dougal is simply exhibiting classic adolescent risk-taking behaviour, which is part of his psychological preparation for adulthood.

 

Which adolescent brain changes are responsible for this increase in risk taking behaviour?
OptionB: Development of the limbic system at a faster rate than the prefrontal cortex.
OptionC: Increase in white matter volume.
OptionD: Mental health problems such as depression or schizophrenia.
OptionE: Synaptic pruning.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

Adolescents and Risk-Taking

  • Risk-taking behaviour is part of preparing for adulthood, as adolescents put themselves in novel situations in order to learn. 
  • It is caused by the interaction of the prefrontal cortex, which is involved in executive functions, and the limbic system, which is involved in social and emotional drive.
  • The emotional network in the limbic system develops faster than the prefrontal cognitive control network, which causes an increase in reward-seeking behaviour and explains why adolescents are so bad at anticipating and planning for the outcomes of these risky behaviours.
  • Social changes such as peer pressure also drive risk-taking behaviours.

Answers A, C and E are all examples of hormonal and brain development during adolescence, however they are not specifically responsible for risk taking behaviours.

 

Adolescence is a time of increased risk for the onset of mental health problems as it is a period of heightened vulnerability.

 

This is from the 'Adolescent Neurocognitive Development' Lecture in Case 12.

 

This video gives a basic overview of brain changes in adolescence.

Question: A 60-year-old lady with a history of heart failure attended the emergency department with palpitations. When taking a history you discover that she regularly takes ramipril and paracetamol but her cardiologist prescribed a further medication a week ago. She does not know what the medication is called but describes it as a 'water tablet'. A subsequent electrocardiogram shows abnormal tall T waves. What 'water tablet' has been started recently?
Explanation:
The effect of spironolactone (a potassium-sparing diuretic) can be potentiated by ramipril causing hyperkalaemia. Patients with hyperkalaemia may experience palpitations and may develop characteristic electrocardiogram (ECG) changes including peaked T waves (early sign) and bizarre QRS complexes which slur into the ST segment.

 

Mannitol is an osmotic diuretic that is used to lower intracranial pressure following a head injury. Furosemide acts on the thick ascending loop of Henle to prevent reabsorption of potassium, sodium, and chloride. Bendroflumethiazide acts on the sodium-chloride transporter in the distal convoluted tubule. Acetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor that is used to treat acute angle closure glaucoma.

Question:
Dilys is a 76 year old woman who has been recently diagnosed with persistent atrial fibrillation. She has occasional palpitations but these do not particularly bother her. She has no significant medical history and is reasonably fit and well. 

 

How should Dilys be managed?
OptionC: No treatment.
Explanation:
The correct answer is E.

 

Because Dilys is over 75 and is female she has a CHADSVASc score of 3, therefore she requires anticoagulation, either a NOAC (e.g. rivaroxaban, dabigatran) or warfarin. 
Although she seems fit and well and her AF symptoms do not bother her, NICE recommends rate-control as a first line therapy in people with AF. This would be beta blockers or rate-controlling calcium channel blockers, or digoxin in sedentary individuals.

 

Ablate and pace is used for patients in which drug treatment has failed to control symptoms of atrial fibrillation or if drugs are unsuitable. 

 

This is a link to the NICE flowcharts, which are very helpful!

Question:
Dopamine is synthesised in several parts of the brain.

 

The degeneration of dopaminergic neurones in which part of the brain is implicated in Parkinson's disease?
Explanation:
The Substantia Nigra synthesises appx 80% of the brains dopamine. It is the degeneration of this structure that is implicated in parkinson's disease. 

 

The Nigrostriatal pathway is important for the stimulation of purposeful movement which is why one of the symptoms of parkinson's include bradykinesia/ slow movement.

Question:
During a placement in the Antenatal ward, you are asked by the consultant about the local anaesthetics used in (and after) labour. 

Somewhere at the back of your tiny year 3 brain, you remember learning about Lidocaine from year 2. 

 

The consultant reminds you that Lidocaine can be potentiated with another drug, making it have more effect and last longer. 

 

What drug is the consultant referring to?
Explanation:
Bupivacaine:

  • Local anaesthetic
  • Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels in nociceptive axons
  • Given in IV infusion
  • Contraindicated in patients with arrhythmias
  • Can cause dizziness, convulsions and arrhythmias

Nitrous Oxide (aka gas & air):

  • Used for contraction pains
  • Stimulates endorphin and endomorphin secretion
  • Causes transient euphoric feelings, but can make a woman feel sick
  • Contraindicated in pneumothorax
  • May be neurologically toxic if used too much
  • Can cause B12 inactivation 

Pethidine:

  • Very commonly used in obstetrics
  • Mu-opioid receptor agonist in the CNS
  • Causes hyperpolarisation to reduce nerve impulses and pain
  • Contraindicated if patient is in respiratory depression
  • Can cause bradycardia, confusion, constipation and biliary spasm

Fentanyl:

  • Used for very strong labour pain, but should be avoided where possible
  • Same MOA as pethidine
  • Same COI as pethidine
  • Same ADRs as pethidine

Adrenaline:

  • Potentiates Lidocaine
  • Vasoconstriction caused by the adrenaline means the local anaesthetic is trapped at the injection site, so less LA can be used
  • Prolongs duration of Lidocaine

 

Info taken from Local Anaesthetic Drug Practical, Labour Analgesia Lecture and Pharma Lightbulb. If you have any corrections or additions pls comment x

Question: You are looking at a histological sample of healthy human duodenum. In the sample you notice Brunner's glands found in the submucosa of the duodenum. Which of the following best describes the main role of Brunner's glands in the duodenum?
OptionA: To secrete acidic mucin in order to lower the pH of chyme entering the duodenum from the stomach.
OptionB: To secrete alkaline mucin in order to raise the pH of the chyme entering the duodenum from the stomach.

Question:
The number of Caucasian individuals with cystic fibrosis (an autosomal recessive condition) has been estimated to be 1/2500. Using the Hardy Weinberg equation, work out the carrier frequency in the population?

 

Assume dominant alleles p=1
Explanation:
The answer is 1/25. 

 

p2 + 2pq + q2 = 1

 

If the population sees 1/2500 individuals with CF. Then using the Hardy Weinberg equation q2 = 1/2500.

Therefore the number of recessive alleles present in the population must be q= 1/50.

The number of dominant alleles is 49/50 therefore can be assumed to be 1. 

 

Hence to work out the number of carriers for the recessive allele in the population. 2pq. 2 x 1 x 1/50 = 1/25

Question: A 17-year-old girl has missed her period by 6 days, which is unusual given her regular 30-day cycle. She buys a pregnancy test and tests positive. On fertilisation of the egg, the sperm stimulates the release of which substance to prevent polyspermy?
Explanation:
The sperm penetrates the corona radiata (outer layer of ovum) via membrane-bound enzymes in the plasma membrane of the head of the sperm.
These bind to the ZP3 (zona-pellucida sperm binding protein 3) receptors on the zona pellucida (next inner layer of ovum).
Sperm binding to these receptors triggers the acrosome reaction.
Acrosomal hydrolytic enzymes digest the zona pellucida creating a pathway to the ovum plasma membrane.
The sperm enters the ovum cytoplasm.
The two cells of the sperm and ovum fuse (syngamy) to produced a diploid zygote
The sperm stimulates the release of calcium ions (in the cortical granules of the ovum) which inactivate the ZP3 receptors to prevent polyspermy
After fertilisation, rapid mitotic cell divisions occur of the zygote to produce an embryo

Question: Dysfunction in which dopamine pathway is thought to cause the positive symptoms of schizophrenia?
Explanation:
Mesolimbic pathway= from the ventral tegmental area (VTA) to the nucleus accumbens, hypothalamus, amygdala and hippocampus. Excessive activation of this pathway (i.e. too much dopamine)- particularly hyperactivation of the D2 receptors in the mesolimbic pathway- results in the positive symptoms associated with schizophrenia.

Positive symptoms of schizophrenia = pathological by their presence, i.e; hallucination, delusions, thought disorder, bodily movements, insight (the lack of).

 

Hypoactivation of the mesocortical pathway (particularly underactivation of D1 receptors)= negative symptoms associated with schizophrenia-  the 5 A's; affective flattening, alogia, anhedonia, avoliation/apathy, attention (poor). 

 

The nigrostriatal (substantia nigra) dopaminergic pathway is unaffected in schizophrenics.

Neuronal loss in the substantia nigra is associated with Parkinson's

Question: In appetite control, the reward circuitry modifies food intake. The prefrontal cortex, the hippocampus and what other brain area is involved?

You see a friend who has been diagnosed with a lateral hypothalamus lesion about 3 months ago. She looks very different now than what she did last time. What affect will this lateral hypothalamus lesion have on the weight and appetite of your friend?
OptionA: obesity even though she does stop eating when she is full. She retains a lot of weight even if she tries to lose weight
OptionB: She has put weight on and is now obese because she doesn't have the signal to tell her to stop eating (fullness signal)
OptionC: Although she is hungry and eats she cannot put weight on as she has increased metabolic demand
OptionD: She will look thin as she does not have the signal to tell her that she is hungry
Explanation:
the hunger signal is in the lateral hypothalamus and therefore if she has a lesion there, she does not know that she is hungry and therefore loses a lot of weight. 

If the lesion was in her middle- lower hypothalamus, she would be obese due to the absence of the satiety/fullness signal. 

 

the hypothalamus feeds these signals into the nucleus accumbens, PFC and hippocampus.

Question:
Glutamate is the main excitatory neurotransmitter of the CNS whereas GABA is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter. 

 

Although they have opposite effects, they are derived in the same way. 

 

What are glutamate and GABA derived from?
Explanation:
Both are derived from glucose within the brain. Glutamate cannot cross the blood brain barrier. 

 

GABA is formed from decarboxylation of L glutamate.

Question: What does the abnormally high cAMP from using opiates cause?
Explanation: opiates act on mu opioid receptors which cause decreased presynaptic neurotransmitter release through cAMP production. Functional changes in cAMP pathway with repeated exposure causes adenylyl cyclase and PKA for the gradual recovery of cAMP. The abnormally high cAMP contributes to tolerance and withdrawal.

Question: what does the chemical hypothesis of depression state?
OptionA: that decreased levels of dopamine, serotonin and noradrenaline cause depression
OptionB: that impaired function of particular molecules e.g. SNPs on chromosome 11 increase chances of depression
OptionC: that depression is due to impaired neuronal activity
OptionD: that depression happens by chance and there is no explaination

Question:
In clinic you see a 20 year old man who has schizophrenia.

 

He seems much better regarding his psychotic symptoms however you notice that he his twitching uncontrollably, is drinking lots of water during the consultation and he tells you that he has not opened his bowels for a week. 

 

From the choices below, what is going on with your patient?
OptionB: side effect of conventional antipsychotic drugs e.g. chlorpromazine
OptionC: viral illness happens to be the same time as the schizophrenia
Explanation:
ADR of conventional antipsychotics are acute dystonia and tardive dyskinesia which resemble Parkinson's disease. Also, dry mouth, blurred vision, urinary retention and constipation. 

 

Conventional antipsychotics target dopamine receptors in order to reduce the positive symptoms of schizophrenia (hallucinations etc). Dopamine receptor antagonists. However, due to the blockage of the dopamine D2 receptors of extrapyramidal motor systems, the dystonia and tardive dyskinesia occur. 

 

chlorpromazine targets both D1 and D2 receptors meaning that positive symptoms get better as it is the D2 mesolimbic system that is hyperactive, but the negative symptoms get worse as the D1 mesocortical system is already hypoactive meaning that the drug will make the already hypoactive system even more so.

 

haloperidol is more selective for D2 receptors and therefore doesn't cause the worsening of the depressive (negative) symptoms.

Question: You awake this morning hungry, thirsty and with an almighty headache after a night of alcohol debauchery post Varsity. This headache is unlike anything you've experienced before and you start to worry that this is more than a hang over. Being the hypochondriac you are, you think of all the causes of raised inter-cranial pressure and wonder whether there is a blockage between your 3rd and 4th ventricles causing a build up of CSF. If so, what structure is being blocked?
What is the active ingredient in St John's Wort which is a drug used in mild depression?
Explanation:
Hyperforin is the active ingredient in St John's Wort. It is used for mild depression. 

 

SIDE EFFECT- can induce drug metabolising enzymes e.g. oral contraception. contraception will be metabolised quicker than intended due to the induction of the enzymes.

Question: A patient presents with vertebro-basilar insufficiency. Which of the following structures is most likely to have been impacted?
Explanation:
The vertebro-basilar system is response for the blood supply to the base of the brain. Structures supplied include: cerebellum, brain stem, occipital lobe. For more:

 

http://www.neuroanatomy.ca/flex_labs/VB_System/story_html5.html

Question: There are many different types of antidepressants, many of them causing side effects such as a dry mouth, constipation and drowsiness. Which atypical antidepressants does NOT cause weight gain and does NOT interfere with sexual function?
Explanation: A,B and C are all SSRIs, the side of effects of which include sexual dysfunction, weight gain and N+V. Buproprion, however, is an atypical antidepressants whose side effects include dry mouth, sweating and potentially seizures, but does NOT cause weight gain or sexual dysfunction.

Question: Some patients choose to use herbal remedies, such as St Johns Wort, to treat mild depression. What is the chemical in St John's Wort which acts as an anti-depressant?
What increases the GFR?
Explanation:
The hormone atrial natriuretic peptide (ANP) is a factor that can increase GFR

Adenosine is released from the macula densa to signal to the juxta-glomerulus to decrease GFR.

Question: A patient comes to A and E having had a vicious blow to the pterion of the skull. During your neurological examination of the patient you notice that patient vital signs begin to change. The patient becomes hypertensive, bradycardiac and exhibits irregular respiratory rate. Noting this as Cushing's triad, you decide to send to radiology for imaging and refer to neurosurgery. The radiological findings produce this image. What is the most likely diagnosis and what was the most likely modality used?
Explanation:
Typically lentiform (lens-shaped, biconvex, lemon-shaped) and do not cross sutures as the periosteum crosses through the suture continuous with the outer periosteal layer. Hence epi/extradural haematoma. 

This is also a CT scan. In a CT scan, denser objects appear brighter. Bones and acute blood appear bright, whereas softer tissue appears dark. CT scans are far quicker to arrange in an emergency situation. They are also highly sensitive at picking up acute bleeds such as in this image. For more information:

 

https://radiopaedia.org/articles/extradural-haematoma-vs-subdural-haematoma

Question:
You are a GP that has just moved to a new area. You meet your first patient, Grace McCartney, a 35 year old single mother who brings in her 2 year old son, Lionel.

 

Grace mentioned during your consultation that she believes that Lionel may have problems with his sense of sight, as he continuously finds it difficult to find his toys and walk through her house. She also mentions that he does not respond when she calls his name.

 

Later in your history, you find out that Grace contracted Rubella during her pregnancy.

 

What other issue do you think Lionel may be at high risk for?
(Note, which of the following would be the most significant?)
Explanation:
Here, the question draws you to consider Congential Rubella Syndrome.The classic triad of symptoms include:

Sensorineuronal Hearing Loss

Eye Abnormalities (cataracts, glaucoma)

Congenital Heart Disease

 

Other associated issues occur at a later onset: DM2, Mental retardation, bladder and bowel incontinence, thyroid malfunction etc...
Tags: Complications in pregnancy, Pregnancy, Case 9, Child development

Question: Some people take illegal recreational drugs to effect the body and mind. Some of these drugs can be classified as either a psychotomimetic or a psychomotor drug. Which of the following is a psychomotor drug?
Explanation:
Amphetamine (answer D), as well as cocaine, are psychomotor drugs. The effects of psychomotor drugs are to increase motor activity and to cause excitement/euphoria.

 

The remaining answers (A,B and C), are psychotomimetic drugs. The effects of psychotomimetic drugs are to create profound changes in though patterns and mood.

Question:
Dr C. Zome is examining a karyotype for a child who potentially has Down's syndrome. He observes that each chromosome has a site of constriction. This is where the two sister chromosomes join during cell division, and where the chromosome joins to the spindle, therefore it is essential for cell division.

 

What is the name of this area of constriction?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

 

 

Human chromosomes are classified into three types depending on the position of the centromere during metaphase:

  • Metacentric - the centromere is in the very centre of the chromosome so each arm of the chromosome is the same length (e.g. Chromosomes 6-12 and X)
  • Sub-Metacentric - the centromere is off centre in the chromosome so the arms are slightly different lengths (e.g. Chromosome 1). The short arm is the p arm and the long arm is the q arm.
  • Acrocentric - the centromere is very close to one end (e.g. Chromosomes 14, 21 and Y)

Question:
Sarah is a 37 year old primagravida who is at her 14th week of pregnancy. She recently had her combined test, which involves ultrasound for nuchal translucency and blood tests for free β-hCG and PAPP-A, and has received an 'increased risk' result for Down's syndrome.

 

Sarah decides to have Amniocentisis and a metaphase karyotype is produced. The karyotype is 47, XX, +21.

 

What is the most accurate description of the foetus?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

The foetus is female because there are 2 X chromosomes. There is trisomy 21 (+21) which is indicative of Down's syndrome, and therefore there are 47 chromosomes in total (1 more than the normal 46).
Tags: Karyotypes, antenatal screening, case 7, Chromosomal abnormalities

Question:
Josie is a 28 year old woman who is 12 weeks pregnant. She has the combined test for Down's syndrome, which involves looking at 2 maternal serum blood biomarkers - PAPP-A and free β-hCG - as well as nuchal translucency, an ultrasound marker.

 

Which of the following combined test results are indicative of an increased risk of Down's Syndrome?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

PAPP-A is decreased in Down's Syndrome.

Free β-hCG is increased in Down's Syndrome.

The nuchal space is over 3.5mm in Down's Syndrome, because there is increased fluid due to congenital heart defects.

 

Screening is not diagnostic; it just determines high and low risk pregnancies.

 

Overall the combined test has a detection rate of 85% for a 2.5% screen positive rate. This means that 85% of Down's syndrome babies are identified, and 2.5% women of women screened are given an 'increased risk' result.

 

The combined test is carried out at 11-14 weeks. It cannot be done in obese women, who have the quadruple test instead.
Tags: antenatal screening, case 7, Pregnancy, Chromosomal abnormalities

Question:
Sasha is a 32 year old primagravida. She has her fetal anomaly scan at 19 weeks, which show an extremely small foetus with a small, dainty placenta. The doctors explain to her that they believe that her foetus has a rare chromosomal abnormality of triploidy, in which there are 3 sets of chromosomes, caused by a process called Digyny.

 

Which of the following explains the process of Digyny.
OptionB: Post-zygotic errors such as non-disjunction or trisomy rescue occurring in mitosis.
OptionD: Problems in female meiosis cause a diploid egg which is fertilised by one sperm.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

Triploidy is when there are 3 sets of chromosomes, e.g. 69XXX, 69XXY, 69XYY. Very few triploidy pregnancies survive to term. Triploidy can be caused by diandry or digyny.

 

Diandry is when the egg is fertilised by 2 sperm.

  • This occurs in 60-80% of cases.
  • A very overgrown, large placenta develops.
  • There is a small foetus or sometimes even no foetus.
  • The large placental mass can become cancerous – choriocarcinoma.

 

Digyny occurs when something has gone wrong with female meiosis so there is a diploid egg which is fertilised by a single sperm.

  • This occurs in 20-40% of cases.
  • There is a small dainty placenta and a very small foetus.

Answer B describes how mosaicism occurs. Mosaicism is a condition in which the cells of an individual do not all contain identical chromosomes, causing two or more genetically different populations of cells.

 

Answer C + E describes how Trisomy occurs. Trisomy is when there are 3 copies of same chromosome. Trisomy 18 causes Edward's Syndrome, and Trisomy 13 causes Patau's Syndrome.
Tags: antenatal screening, case 7, Pregnancy, Chromosomal abnormalities

Question: It's Friday night and your friends are all going out to Revs. They encourage you to come along for a couple of rounds, but you decide to get an early night in instead. Your friend reminds you of how many rounds or cycles of sleep you typically go through each night-around 4 or 5 sleep cycles per night. How long does the first sleep cycle last?
Explanation:
The first sleep cycle is around 90 minutes. After this, the sleep cycle may increase to around 100-120 minutes. The stages of sleep cycle are:

stage 1-->stage2-->stage3-->stage2-->stage1-->REM then repeat.

Question:
Jeremy is a 48 year old man presents at A&E with a 3 day worsening history of haematemesis and abdominal pain. He is pale, sweating and restless. Jeremy mentions that he has been having black tarry stools. The only medication he takes is twice-daily ibuprofen for his bad back, which he has been taking for the past year.

 

Suddenly Jeremy collapses. His blood pressure is 90/60mmHg, he has a high heart rate and abnormally rapid breathing. The A&E consultant arranges an urgent blood transfusion.

 

Which of the following blood products should be used for this transfusion?
OptionB: Irradiated Red Blood Cells
OptionD: Red Blood Cells and Fresh Frozen Plasma
OptionE: Solvent-detergent plasma
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

Jeremy is suffering from a GI bleed due to his use of ibuprofen which is an NSAID. This is now causing him to go into hypervolaemic (haemorrhagic) shock due to blood loss, which is why he requires an infusion.

 

Red blood cells are produced from whole blood donations. They are used to raise the oxygen carrying capacity of the blood to prevent tissue hypoxia. They are used for bone marrow failure, perioperative blood loss or ongoing GI blood loss. 

 

Fresh frozen plasma is produced by rapidly freezing plasma from whole blood from a single blood donor. It contains clotting factors. It is often given alongside RBCs for major blood loss to provide additional blood volume.

 

Irradiated red blood cells is when the blood is radiated to damage DNA (i.e. that found in WBCs). This is only required for haematological malignancies, e.g. transfusion from family or HLA matched donors.

 

Solvent-detergent plasma is given to people born after 1996, because they are not allowed to receive FFP. It comes from  many non-UK donors.

 

Platelets is pooled from 4 whole blood donors or one apheresis donor (specific platelet donor). It is used for people with a low platelet count (thrombocytopenia), e.g .in chemotherapy patients. It is also used for patients with aplastic anaemia (bone marrow damage) and for patients with platelet function disorders.

Question: There are 4 stages to Non-REM sleep. How do you differentiate between stage 3 and stage 4?
OptionA: N3 has delta waves, N4 has theta waves
OptionB: both N3 and N4 have delta waves, but N4 lasts much longer.
OptionC: N3 has 20-50% delta waves, N4 has >50% delta waves.
OptionE: N3 has delta waves, N4 has delta and gamma waves.
Explanation: Both N3 and N4 have delta waves, but N4 is characterised by more delta waves than N3.

Question:
Joyce attends her local blood donation service in Cardiff to donate blood. However when she arrives she is told that she is not allowed to donate because she has recently had a tattoo.  She is told that she has to wait until 120 days after the date that she got the tattoo before she can give blood.

 

There are many reasons why people are unable to donate blood. Which of the following people would be able to donate blood?
OptionB: Susan, a 25 year old woman who is currently pregnant.
OptionC: Jack, a 48 year old man who has visited Uganda (a malarial area) in the last month.
OptionD: Lionel, a 37 year old man who is HIV positive.
OptionE: Theo, a 63 year old man who is in good health.
Explanation:
The correct answer is E.

 

A - blood donors have to be over 17 years old, and there are height and weight restrictions for girls aged 17-19.

 

B - Pregnant women cannot give blood until 6 months after their pregnancy, as pregnant women often lose iron and can be anaemic.

 

C - There are various travel restrictions which limit if you can give blood, such as visiting a malaria area  in the last 4 months.

 

D - HIV positive people cannot give blood because HIV is a blood born disease.

 

E - People under 66 who are in good health are able to donate blood. People over 66 can give blood if they are healthy and have given blood before.

 

The welsh blood website explains all the reasons why you may not be able to donate.

 

Although we have not been taught the specific restrictions for giving blood and probably do not need to know them for the exam I think it is a good idea to have a general idea of why some people cannot give blood. We do need to be aware of the potential risk to the future blood supply, and increasing reasons for deferring blood donation, such as the reasons above, is a risk to the blood supply.

Question:
Jason is a 68 year old man who requires an urgent blood transfusion due to perioperative bleeding. The blood product he needs has to be stored at 4 degrees Celsius and can be stored for a maximum of 35 days.

 

Which of the following blood products does Jason require?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

Red Blood Cells

  • Red Blood Cells are produced from whole blood donations. 
  • The platelets and plasma are removed by centrifuging and the WBCs are filtered.
  • The RBCs are then suspended in an optimal additive solution and stored in the fridge to maintain the half life.
  • RBCs can be stored for up to 35 days, but must be used within 4 hours of removal.
  • They must be compatible with the ABO blood group.
  • RBCs are used to raise the oxygen carrying capacity of blood – they prevent tissue hypoxia.
  • They tend to be given for bone marrow failure, perioperative blood loss or ongoing GI blood loss.

 

Answer A - CMV (cytomegalovirus) negative blood cells are used in immunocompromised patients, in women who are 20 weeks pregnant or for intra-uterine transfusion (giving the fetus an infusion). They are stored in the same way as normal blood cells.

 

Answer B - Fresh frozen plasma is often given alongside RBCs for major blood loss to provide additional blood volume. It is stored at -30 degrees Celsius, and can be stored for up to 24 months.

 

Answer C - Platelets are used for people with a low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) e.g. in aplastic anaemia, platelet function disorders and for prevention of bleeding in chemotherapy patients. They have to be kept at room temperature and can be stored for up to 5 days.

 

Answer E - Solvent-Detergent Plasma is used for people born after 1996 who are not allowed to have FFP.

Question:
85 year old female presents at A and E with a severe headache, nausea and vomiting. Patient history reveals a stiff neck and cranial nerve examination reveals photophobia. As you monitor her vital signs you notice an irrregular respiratory rate, hypertension and bradycardia. You send her for an urgent CT head with no contrast and receive the following image: 

 

Based on these findings, you refer to neurosurgery. What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
This image depicts a subarachnoid haemorrhage. In such a scenario, the haemorrhage allows is within the arachnoid space. This allows blood to encase the entire brain. Whereas in a epidural haemorrhage the blood pools in a concave fashion. 

Symptoms of a subarachnoid haemorrhage include:

Thunderclap headache.

Seizure

Nausea and vomiting 

Menigismus. 

 

Tends to occur as the result of a cerebral artery rupture, common examples being a rupture of a saculum aneurysm.
Tags: Cardiovascular system, Neuroanatomy, Case 16, Progress Test revision, Imaging

Question: A 89 year old man suffers an ischaemic stroke leading to the occlusion of his right middle cerebral artery. The ischaemia prevents the recycling of glutamate, the main excitatory neurotransmitter in the brain. High levels of glutamate are neurotoxic. What cells are response for the recycling of glutamate to prevent neurotoxicity.
Explanation:
Glutamate is the main excitatory transmitters in the CNS

Its action is terminated by re-uptake via glutamate transporters into the nerve terminal or into glial cells (astrocytes)

Extracellular glutamate concentration is normally 0.6 μmol/L ; it becomes excitotoxic at 2-5 μmol/L

Traumatic brain injury can raise extracellular levels locally to 10μmol/L if neurones are ruptured

Astrocytes can metabolise glucose anaerobically for prolonged periods, but lactic acid builds up. If pH falls below 6.6, glycolysis ceases and irreversible damage ensues.

 

In this case, the patient suffered an ischaemic stroke, hence the metabolism of the astrocytes was compromised. This led to the build up of glutamate.

 

See Dr Watson's lecture from Case 16

Question: A patient comes into your practice having felt a lump in the upper quadrant of her right breast. You confirm the presents of the lump and refer for a mammogram. Investigation reveals a ductal carcinoma in situ. You prescribe tamoxifen as part of the medical regime for this patient. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of action of tamoxifen?
Explanation:
Tamoxifen works as a selective oestrogen receptor modulator. It competes with endogenous oestrogen for oestrogen receptors. In so doing, it inhibits the transcription of oestrogen-responsive genes. 

 

Side effects include:

PV bleeding

Flushes

Changes to endometrium

 

See core formulary for more.

Question: You are reviewing a patient with a history of asthma. Having reviewed the gentleman's history, you decide to prescribe him Prednisolone. This is a glucocorticoid used to treat autoimmune diseases as well as inflammatory diseases. Which of the following best describes its mechanism of action?
OptionA: inhibit leukocyte infiltration at the site of inflammation
Explanation:
Glucocorticoids (GCs) are a class of corticosteroids, which are a class of steroid hormones. Glucocorticoids are corticosteroids that bind to the glucocorticoid receptor (GR), that is present in almost every vertebrate animal cell. The name glucocorticoid (glucose + cortex + steroid) is composed from its role in regulation of glucose metabolism, synthesis in the adrenal cortex.

 

Glucocorticoids such as Prednisolone can inhibit leukocyte infiltration at the site of inflammation, interfere with mediators of inflammatory response, and suppress humoral immune responses. The antiinflammatory actions of glucocorticoids are thought to involve phospholipase A2 inhibitory proteins, lipocortins, which control the biosynthesis of potent mediators of inflammation such as prostaglandins and leukotrienes. Prednisolone reduces inflammatory reaction by limiting the capillary dilatation and permeability of the vascular structures. These compounds restrict the accumulation of polymorphonuclear leukocytes and macrophages and reduce the release of vasoactive kinins. Recent research suggests that corticosteroids may inhibit the release of arachidonic acid from phospholipids, thereby reducing the formation of prostaglandins. Prednisolone is a glucocorticoid receptor agonist. On binding, the corticoreceptor-ligand complex translocates itself into the cell nucleus, where it binds to many glucocorticoid response elements (GRE) in the promoter region of the target genes. The DNA bound receptor then interacts with basic transcription factors, causing an increase or decrease in expression of specific target genes, including suppression of IL2 (interleukin 2) expression.

 

See Cardiff Core formulary for more.

Question: how many Calcium ions does the SERCA transporter carry per ATP?
Explanation:
PMCA transporter carries 1 calcium per ATP

SERCA transporter carries 2 calciums per ATP

Question: What is the effect of sympathetic stimulation on ryanodine receptor regulation?
OptionA: sympathetic stimulation dissociates calsequestrin meaning that less calcium gets bound to it. Therefore, as there is less bound to calsequestrin, more can leave and increase the force of contraction
OptionB: sympathetic stimulation dissociates FKBP (calstabin) which makes the probability for an open ryanodine receptor increase. More calcium can leave and therefore increase the force of contraction.
OptionC: sympathetic stimulation decreases the probability for the ryanodine receptor to be open, meaning that there is an increase in calcium in the SR/sarcolemma, so more contraction can take place.
OptionD: sympathetic stimulation increases the probability for the ryanodine receptor to be open, due to the increased calcium binding to the receptor.
Explanation:
• Ryanodine receptors are calcium release channels. 
  • The RyR2 is opened by increased Ca2+ concentration in the dyadic cleft. 
  • The RyR2 is inhibited by calstabin (FKBP) and calsequestrin. 
  • Therefore the calcium inside the SR will increase as the RyR2 is closed so calcium can't leave. 
  • The calcium then binds to calsequestrin as the Ca2+ concentration rises. 
  • The inhibition of RyR2 is relieved meaning that calcium can exit the SR. 

 

*As the SR fills with calcium, the more likely for RyR2 to be open and release Ca2+ *

 

Sympathetic stimulation dissociates FKBP (meaning that it can't inhibit the RyR2). There is an increased probability for the RyR2 to be open, meaning more calcium can leave and be a part of the contraction. More calcium leaving= more calcium available for contraction= more forceful contraction

Question: A mother presents at your practice with her 2 month old baby. The baby receiving its first dosage of vaccines today as part of the UK vaccination schedule. One of these vaccines is Hib (Haemophilus Influenzae Type B) which is part of the 6 in one vaccine. The mother asks whether the Hib vaccine is effective, she remembers reading about it wearing off after some time. You assure her that it is effective, subsequent vaccines have been edited to provide a more effective immune response. Which of following describes the Hib vaccine given today ?
OptionB: A conjugated poylsaccharide with a covalently linked protein carrier.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. HIb is offered as part of the 6 in 1 vaccine. When it was first made available it was in the form of a pure polysaccharide vaccine. This polysaccharide was polyribosyl ribitol phosphate, part of the polysaccharide capsule of the bacteria. This resulted in the formation of anti-PPR antibodies to provide resistance. This vaccine was ineffective as T cell response was limited. MHC class II receptors on T cells were not recognising the polysaccharide. 

Hence future iteration of the vaccine were conjugated to a protein. This allowed for T cell recognition.

Question: You are working with Medicins sans frontiers in Pakistan issuing polio vaccinations. You are giving the Sabin attenuated vaccine (first produced in 1961). How is this different to the Salk inactivated vaccine (first produced in 1954)?
OptionA: The Sabin vaccine is given orally offering both IgA and IgG antibody protection.
OptionB: The Sabin vaccine is given orally offering IgA protein to the gut only.
OptionE: The Salk vaccine is no longer used any where in the world.
Explanation:
The Salk vaccine was first produced in the 1950s. It was an inactivated virus, being inactivated with formaldehyde. This prevented it from being infectious. It was administered as an injection resulting in the production of IgG antibodies. These IgG antibodies would prevent further contact with Polio virus resulting in damage to the CNS. However, this vaccine still allowed for infection via the GI tract and as such would not offer herd immunity. 

 

The Sabin vaccine, created in the 1960s was administered orally. This allowed for protection of the GI tract with IgA antibodies as well as IgG anitbodies protecting the CNS. The vaccine was attenuated. This means that it was still infectious, just less virulent. Potentially, in areas of poor sanitation the vaccine could be shed in fecal matter and spread through communities. This would be even more effective at providing herd immunity.

 

Currently, there is a small risk that the Sabin vaccine might recombine to form a live virus. Although a small risk, since the cases of Polio are now very rare, the UK now offers the Salk vaccine to mitigate this risk. 

 

For more refer to case 9 tutorial and lectures regarding vaccination as well as this helpful video.

Question: You are visiting doing a home visit to assess the development of an infant. As you walk through the door, the infant tracks you walking through the room. He goes from babbling and clapping to crying at your presents. His mother comforts him and he stops. As you are chatting to his mother, he crawls around the room on his hands and knees. Based upon this information, what is the most likely stage in development for this child?
Explanation:
Here are the development goals taken from the Case 9 lecture:

 

Gross Motor Function- 

Rolls supine to prone
Crawls on hands on knees
Pulls to stand with support

 

Fine Motor Function-

Eyes move in unison following activities across the room. Purposeful alertness. Palmar grasp. Transfers objects. Finger feeding. Casting

 

vision-

Tracks objects. Interested in pictures. Peek-a-boo. Recognises hidden objects.
Develops stranger anxiety

 

Personal/ social- 

Joint attention. Proto-imperative pointing. Recognises & responds to own name. interested in watching other children. Puts arms out to be held

 

Communication-

Waves and claps, babble, responds to ‘no’ and name.

Question: A fracture in the pterion can cause a rupture of which underlying artery?
OptionA: Anterior branch of the middle meningeal artery.
OptionC: Posterior branch of the middle meningeal artery.
OptionD: Anterior branch of the middle cerebral artery.
Explanation: The anterior branch of the middle meningeal artery is a branch of the maxillary artery and runs under the pterion, the most fragile part of the skull. A fracture here, damaging the anterior branch of the middle meningeal artery, can result in an epidural haematoma. The haematoma may occur under the temporalis muscle causing swelling or may move intracranially, putting pressure of the precentral gyrus (motor strip).

Question:
A 55 y/o non-symptomatic female patient comes into the clinic worried that she may have colorectal cancer. You assess the patient for any symptoms and ask about her social habits. You find out that she smokes 40 cigarettes a day and loves to eat steak every night with her partner. 

You explain that now she is 55 y/o she will start the bowel screening programme and you helpfully give some lifestyle advice that may decrease her risk of developing colorectal cancer. Which of the following does not protect against colorectal cancer?
Explanation:
Eating a low fibre diet may increase your risk of developing CRC

Note: that the patient is female so being overweight actually decreases the risk of CRC however if the patient was male then being overweight woud be another risk factor to consider.

Question:
Mr Bridges is a 57 year old man attending a football match at Cardiff City Stadium. During the game, he suddenly feels dizzy and lightheaded. His heart feels as if it is racing and he gets an angina-like pain in the centre of his chest.

 

Mr Bridges pulls out and uses his GTN spray which was given to him 2 years ago when he suffered a heart attack, but it has no effect. He tries to get up to visit the first aid station but suddenly collapses. Medics are called over and discover that Mr Bridges is in cardiac arrest, caused by an arrhythmia.

 

Which type of arrhythmia is responsible for 85% of sudden cardiac death?
OptionB: Bradyarrhythmia
OptionC: Ectopic Beats
Explanation:
The correct answer is E.

 

Ventricular tachyarrhythmia is a fast heart rate (>100bpm) which arises from an abnormal focus of electrical activity in the ventricles. Because the electricity does not pass through the normal channels the contraction and pumping action of the heart is not as efficient as normal. This can cause a sudden drop in blood pressure or even cardiac arrest. 

 

85% of all sudden cardiac death is caused by ventricular tachyarrhythmias.

Question:
Mary is a 68 year old woman who presents at her GP complaining of occasional palpitations. She has no other symptoms, but is worried because her mother died of a cardiac arrest due to ventricular tachycardia. The only past medical history is that Mary has high blood pressure, which is well controlled with Ramipril.

 

Mary has a pulse rate of 110bpm, a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minutes and a blood pressure of 128/90. The GP organises an ECG.

 

 

What is Mary's most likely diagnosis?
OptionB: Ectopic Beats
OptionD: Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

  • AF is the most common arrhythmia. It is an irregular uncoordinated rhythm arising from the atria.
  • It is often asymptomatic, but symptoms can include palpitations, breathlessness, chest pain, T-LOC or cerebral thromboembolic events (stroke, TIAs)
  • Slow conduction through the AV node acts as a safety mechanism and prevents ventricular fibrillation.
  • On an ECG the heart rhythm is irregularly irregular with no visible p-waves and a chaotic baseline.
  • AF can be paroxysmal (last for <48 hrs), persistent (over 48 hrs but < 1 week) or permanent.
  • It can be fast, rate controlled or slow depending on ventricular rate

B - Ectopic beats are extra heart beats caused by impulses generated somewhere in the heart outside the SA node. Symptoms include feeling an occasional 'thudding' in the chest. On an ECG the p wave before the ectopic is different and it is followed by a compensatory pause.

 

 

C - Heart block occurs when the conduction of electrical impulses through the AV node is impaired of completely block. FirstFirst degree heart block has a slowing of conduction between the atria and the ventricles, causing a long PR interval.

 

D - Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathies is unexplained hypertrophy of the wall of the left ventricle. It usually presents at adolescence, and is often genetic. Most patients are asymptomatic, but may present with breathlessness or atrial fibrillation as a symptom. An ECG will often show a abnormally tall S wave in V2 and an abnormally deep R wave in V5.

 

E - Ventricular tachycardia is a type of fast arrhythmia arising from the ventricles. It is common with a history of heart disease. It is often asymptomatic but can present with breathless, palpitations, chest pain etc. It can cause sudden death (cardiac arrest)

Question:
Carol is a 57 year old woman, who has suffered from neck and shoulder pain for the last 1 1/2 years which comes and goes, and often has headaches which start at the back of her neck. The GP has diagnosed her with cervical spondylosis and she manages her pain with regular paracetamol.

 

One day Carol finds that she is not able to move her arms or hands, and that there is also some loss of motion in her legs. She is taken to A&E by her husband. They assess her and find that there is bilateral loss of motor function, pain, light touch, proprioception and vibration in her arms, and some loss of these functions in her legs. There is no loss of bowel or bladder function.

 

What is Carol presenting with?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

  • Central cord syndrome is the most common cord syndrome.
  • It is often caused by damage to the blood supply, causing ischaemia.
  • This can be due to cervical spondylosis (degeneration of cervical vertebrae and discs).
  • This affects the spinothalamic, corticospinal and dorsal column pathways.
  • There is often ‘sacral sparing’ (remember ATLS)
  • Prognosis is fair, because there is some function below the level of injury. Sacral sparing indicates that there are intact long tract neurons, and so has a better prognosis.

A - Anterior cord syndrome is usually the result of a vascular event (anterior spinal artery). It takes out the spinothalamic and corticospinal pathways. This causes bilateral loss of motor function, pain, temperature and light touch sensation below the lesion.

 

C - Complete spinal cord injury results in no sensation or voluntary motor function below the level of the injury.

 

D - Brown-Sequard syndrome is loss of function in half of the spinal cord. There is loss of motor function and proprioception/vibration sensation below and on the same side as the lesion, and there is loss of pain, temperature and light touch sensation below and on the opposite side of the lesion.

 

E - Posterior cord syndrome is rare, and is often caused by syphilis or a posterior tumour pressing on the SC. It takes out the dorsal column, causing loss of proprioception, vibration and discriminative touch.

Question: what is the half life of adenosine?
Explanation: adenosine is administered through quick IV and has a half life of 10 seconds.

Question: A 24 y/o patient comes into your clinic complaining of confusion, hyperthermia, mania, tachycardia and diarrhoea. You note on examination that she has a very hyperactive reflexes (i.e. hypereflexia). You are very worried and realise that it may be due to overdose of a particular drug that she is taking. Which drug would likely point you to this decision?
Explanation:
This young women has SEROTONIN SYNDROME - caused by excessive central and peripheral serotonergic activity e.g. overdose of citalopram (an SSRI).

Can also be due to a range of other drugs that increase the levels of serotonin in the body such as MDMA.

Question: A 23 y/o woman comes into your clinic complaining of stomach pain however you note that she is also on Citalopram. What medication must you not give her due to a serious side effect of both medications?
Explanation: You cannot give NSAIDs with citalopram (an SSRI) due to the risk of GI bleeding. NICE advises 'do not normally offer SSRIs with NSAIDs', but if given co-prescribe a proton pump inhibitor.

Question: What is cocaine's mechanism of action?
OptionA: Cocaine inhibits dopamine reuptake and acutely increases firing rate of noradrenaline
OptionB: Cocaine inhibits serotonin reuptake keeping it in the synapse for longer
OptionC: Cocaine inhibits monoamine reuptake (DA, NA and 5HT) and acutely increases firing rate of serotonin.
OptionD: Cocaine inhibits monoamine oxidase reuptake and acutely increases firing rate of noradrenaline
Explanation: Cocaine inhibits monoamine reuptake (DA, NA and 5HT) and acutely increases firing rate of serotonin. It also has effects in the peripheral nervous system mimicking sympathetic actions - tachycardia, vasoconstriction and increased blood pressure.

Question: Currently what are the 2 proposed theories for the cause of psychosis?
Explanation:
Dopamine theory - positive symptoms are as a result of excessive activity in the mesolimbic dopaminergic pathways.

Glutamate theory - excessive elimination of cortical synapses in psychosis suggests a role for glutamate; NMDA receptor antagonists also found to produce psychotic-like symptoms and post-mortuem studies have found reduced glutamate levels and receptor densities in patients with psychosis.

Question: Mr MJ Fox presents to your practice with a short, shuffling gait and hypokinesia. Further history taking suggests a differential diagnosis of Parkinson's disease. Parkinson's disease is characterised by a deficiency of dopamine in the basal ganglia leading to motor defects. You decide to treat Mr Fox with L-DOPA in an effort to increase levels of Dopamine. Why is L-DOPA used as treatment as opposed to Tyrosine?
OptionA: The conversion of Tyrosine to L-DOPA is the rate limiting step in the production of Dopamine.
OptionB: Tyrosine can't be absorbed by the intestines.
OptionD: Tyrosine can't cross the blood brain barrier
Explanation:
Extract taken from case 12 lecture slides.

 

DA, NA and A have a catechol nucleus and an ethyl-amine group attached at the 1 position and are all derived from one biosynthesis pathway, the Catecholamine synthesis pathway.

All are derived from the amino acid tyrosine in the diet. Tyrosine is actively transported across the blood brain barrier (BBB), which is fully saturated with typical daily intake. This is part of the rate limiting step of this pathway. (Note: It is also the reason why we have to treat Parksinson’s disease with L-DOPA rather than tyrosine supplements, to avoid this step.)
In the brain tyrosine at the 3 position is hydroxylated by tyrosine hydroxylase (TH) which requires Fe2+, a molecular oxygen and a hydrogen donor (tetrahydrobiopterin) to form Levodopa (L-DOPA). Increased release of catecholamines leads to an increase in TH activity which is regulated at transcriptional, translational and posttranscriptional levels.

In dopaminergic neurons L-DOPA is converted to DA by the enzyme L-aromatic amino acid decarboxylase (AADC) which can be found in the cytoplasm of these neurons. AADC requires a co-factor derived from Vit B6.

 

In noradrenergic neurons DA is converted to NA by the enzyme dopamine-β-hydroxylase (DBH). DBH requires Cu2+ and VitC as co-factors and is linked to the synaptic vesicles that store NA.

 

In the few neurons found in the adrenal medulla and brainstem that produce Adrenaline an additional enzyme Phenylethanolamine-N-methyltransferase (PNMT) is expressed. For this step a methyl donor is required.

Question: You a reviewing the progress of a patient who has just had their pineal gland removed to treat an astrocytoma. The patient complains of interrupted and erratic sleeping patterns. What neurotransmitter is most likely to be deficient in this patient?
Explanation:
Serotonin is an indolamine with a hydroxy group at the 5 position and a terminal amine group on the carbon chain.

 

Serotonin is synthesised from the amino acid tryptophan. Tryptophan is also actively transported across the blood brain barrier, where it is hydroxylated by tryptophan hydroxlase (TPH) to produce 5-hydroxytryptophan (5HT). TPH regulation is similar to TH.

 

5HT is decarboxylated by AADC (the same enzyme that converts L-DOPA to D) to form 5-hydroxytryptamine (5-HT).

This biosynthesis pathway goes one step further in the pineal gland, where 5-HT is converted to melatonin.

OptionB: mu opioid receptor agonist- activation of GPCR causes efflux of K+ and closure of Ca2+ channels which suppresses the release of pain neurotransmitters
Explanation:
A- triamcinolone

B- correct--> oxycodone

C- ibuprofen

D- just wrote anything

E- naproxen

Explanation: It is the thalamus that is the gatekeeper for sensory information going to the sensory cortex in the brain. this is where the fibres of the spinothalamic and dorsal column tracts go before going to the sensory cortex

Question:
You walk into the Cochrane building and see that they are testing for your blood type. You have your blood tested and this is the result:

What are all the blood types you could receive during a blood transfusion?
Explanation:
Your blood type is B+ so you would be transfused with B+/- or O+/- blood.

 

You have B antigens on your RBCs, which will coagulate with the B antibodies on the test plate.

You also have D antigens, which will also coagulate with the D antibodies on the test plate.

 

You have anti-A antibodies in your serum so will not be able to receive A or AB blood.

A rhesus positive person can receive both positive and negative blood.

Question: A patient comes presents to A and E after their son calls and ambulance. 'He's had a stroke' the son exclaims reciting FAST. You begin a cranial nerve examination and note a loss of sense of smell (anosmia). Left hemiplagia is present, as well as urinary incontinence. The patient is referred for an MRI where an ischaemic stroke of the right anterior cerebral artery is identified. Based on this MRI, which area of the brain is vascularised by the anterior cerebral artery?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. 

The anterior cerebral artery:

The anterior cerebral artery (ACA) is one of a pair of arteries on the brain that supplies oxygenated blood to most midline portions of the frontal lobes and superior medial parietal lobes. The two anterior cerebral arteries arise from the internal carotid artery and are part of the circle of Willis. The left and right anterior cerebral arteries are connected by the anterior communicating artery.

 

LOCATION OF INFARCT
Left ACA

Right leg upper-motor neuron weakness due to damage to motor cortex and right leg cortical sensory loss due to damage to sensory cortex. Grasp reflex, frontal lobe behavioral abnormalities, and transcortical aphasia can also be seen if the prefrontal cortex and supplemental motor areas are involved.

 

Right ACA

Left leg upper-motor neuron weakness due to damage to motor cortex and left leg cortical type sensory loss due to damage to sensory cortex. Grasp reflex, frontal lobe behavioural abnormalities and left hemineglect can also be seen if the prefrontal cortex and non-dominant association cortex are involved.

Question: Which of the following best applies to the function of the Thalamus.
OptionA: Primary and secondary visual areas. Functions in the sensation and interpretation of visual input.
OptionB: Contains descending fibers of the lateral and ventral corticospinal tracts.
OptionC: Relay centre for descending and ascending information between cerebral cortex and rest of CNS
OptionD: Expressive speech area. Integration with other language areas.
OptionE: Receptive speech area. Integration with other language areas.
Explanation:
A- Occipital lobe

B- Internal capsule posterior limb

C- Thalamus

 

All supplied by the posterior cerebral artery.

 

D-Broca's area

E-Wernicke's area

 

http://www.neuroanatomy.ca/stroke_model/mca_info.html This website is legendary.

Question: A patient suffers from an infarct of the posterior cerebral artery. This presents as homonymous hemianopsia as the occipital lobe becomes ischaemic resulting in damage to the visual areas. Which of the following describes homonymous hemianopsia with macula sparing? Black represents blindness in that field.
Which of the following most accurately describes the allocortex?
OptionA: An area of the cortex with a prominent sulcus
OptionB: An area of the cortex with fewer than 6 layers
OptionC: An area of the cortex with fewer than 8 layers
OptionD: An area of the cortex with more than 6 layers
OptionE: An area of the cortex with more than 8 layers
Explanation: The neocortex (involved in higher functions) has 6 layers. An area of the cortex with any fewer than 6 is called the allocortex.

Question:
Dopamine, Noradrenaline and Adrenaline are all synthesised via the same biochemical pathway, which begins with the amino acid tyrosine. Decreased dopamine in the nigrostriatal pathway is implicated in Parkinson’s Disease, so patients with Parkinson’s are prescribed Levodopa (L-DOPA) to attempt to restore dopamine levels.


Why is it that patients are given Levodopa rather than tyrosine, the L-DOPA precursor?
OptionA: Tyrosine cannot cross the blood brain barrier
OptionB: Conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA is the rate-limiting step
OptionC: Giving tyrosine will only produce noradrenaline and adrenaline
OptionD: L-DOPA is only converted to dopamine in the CNS
Explanation:
A. This is not true, tyrosine is actively transported across the BBB
B. This is the correct answer, the conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA, by tyrosine hydroxylase, is the rate limiting step, so L-DOPA is given to avoid this step (From Neuropharmacology 1 Plenary)
C. This is not true, they are all produced as part of a sequential biochemical pathway (see diagram) – NOTE: Each one will only be produced in its specific neurone (i.e. noradrenaline will only be produced in a noradrenergic neurone, etc.)
D. This is not true, L-DOPA can be converted to dopamine outside the CNS so is often administered with a dopamine decarboxylase inhibitor to prevent this
E. This is not true, conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA is rate limiting step in the pathway (see diagram), so would not produce enough dopamine

Question:
You are the F1 doctor on call on a busy Friday night and are just about to finish when an unconscious 27-year-old male is brought into the Emergency Department. On examination you notice that he has ‘pin-prick pupils’ and a respiratory rate of 7 breaths/min, leading you to suspect an opioid overdose.


His ABG showed the following:
- PaO2 8.3 kPa         (11-13 kPa)
- pH 7.29                   (7.35-7.45)
- PaCO2 8.1 kPa      (4.6-6.0 kPa)
- HCO3- 23mmol/L   (22-26mmol/L)
- BE +1                     (-2 to +2)

 

What type of acid-base disorder does this suggest and what type of respiratory failure would it be?
OptionA: Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation & type II failure
OptionB: Respiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation & type I respiratory failure
OptionD: Respiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation & type II respiratory failure
Explanation:
A. Incorrect – this is an example of respiratory acidosis, CO2 is elevated which is innkeeping with the decreased pH, suggesting a respiratory cause. Also the metabolic markers (HCO3- & BE) are still within their normal values
(The second part is correct, it is type II respiratory failure)


B. Incorrect – although it is respiratory acidosis there is no metabolic compensation (metabolic markers still within normal values)
(The second part also incorrect, as this is type II respiratory failure)


C. This is the correct answer


D. Incorrect – there is no metabolic compensation (metabolic markers normal). This is because metabolic compensation for a respiratory cause takes several days to occur, as the kidneys are slower at adjusting HCO3 levels in accordance with changes in CO2 levels


E. Incorrect – The pH <7.35 so is acidotic not alkalotic

 

Type I Respiratory Failure:


- Hypoxia but normal/low CO2
- Due to V/Q mismatch – e.g. pneumonia, PE, pulmonary fibrosis


Type II Respiratory Failure:


- Hypoxia & hypercapnia (high CO2)
- Due to alveolar hypoventilation – e.g. opioid overdoes (respiratory depression), chest wall deformities, severe lung disease

ABO antigens are IgM which means that cannot cross through the placenta to the foetus.

Question:
GROUP 67 question:

 

Alice received an elbow to the head whilst playing football. She briefly lost consciousness for a few minutes then carried on playing. An hour later she began to develop a headache and was nauseous. Her left pupil became fixed and dilated. She was rushed into A&E by Arash after being erratic. A non-contrast head CT was taken. This is shown below:

 

 

What blood vessel is most likely affected?
Explanation:
The CT shows that Alice has had an extradural haematoma. The most likely blood vessel ruptured would be the middle meningeal artery

Bridging veins are ruptured in a subdural

The cavernous sinus is behind the eye and cranial nerves III,IV, V and VI. This is usually associated with thrombosis

Question:
Dr Marcus is examining Hannah in Heath hospital after she was admitted to the stroke ward. here is their conversation:

 

Dr Marcus:"Hello Hannah, How are you today?"

Hannah: "I'm........well....wwell"

Dr Marcus: "Repeat after me: here we recognise the thoughts of our childhood"

Hannah: "Here....I'm well"

Dr Marcus: " Raise the number of fingers on your left hand that correlates to the order In the alphabet of the first letter of the city in which we are in"

Hannah: *raises three fingers*

 

Which blood vessel if most likely affected?
Explanation:
Hannah has Broca's aphagia. Broca's area is located in the region that the left middle cerebral artery supplies. Damage to this blood vessel may cause problems with expressive language. she is able to follow instructions but not respond with language.

Question:
You are asked to assess a patient in A&E after he suffers a head injury, he is sleeping when you walk in. You greet him, but he does not respond, however when you apply supraorbital pressure he opens his eyes, mumbles a few sounds and swats your hand away with his left arm.

 

What is his GCS score?

Georgina is a 42 year old woman attending her GP. She has found that recently she has had difficulty concentrating and occasionally has memory lapses. She has also been having mood swings, and overall feels in a low mood. She mentions that something similar happened to her mother, and that it developed into a much more serious condition so that her mother required full time care.

 

The GP refers Georgina for a Clinical Genetics appointment. Here they produce a family pedigree.

 

 

What type of genetic disease does this pedigree indicate that Georgina has?
OptionD: Pseudo-Dominant
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

Georgina is presenting with early signs of Huntington's disease, which is an autosomal dominant condition. Autosomal dominant means that only one abnormal gene needs to be inherited from one parent for the disease to occur. There is a 50% offspring risk for any parent with the gene. Autosomal dominant diseases are generally seen in adulthood.

 

An autosomal dominant pedigree is easy to recognise:

  • Many generations are affected.
  • They are transmitted from parent to child.
  • Men and women are equally affected.

B - Autosomal recessive conditions usually affect one generation and generally occur in childhood. Unaffected parents are asymptomatic carriers.

 

C - Co-dominant inheritance is when two different alleles influence a genetic trait, e.g. in ABO blood groups.

 

D - Pseudo-dominant inheritance is when a recessive condition appears to transmit dominantly, because there are people affected in multiple generations. However this is often due to co-sanguinity (incest) within families.

 

E - X-linked recessive conditions usually only affect men as they only have 1 X chromosome.

Question:
Nia is a 34 year old mother who is about to have her 2nd child. She has a clinical genetics appointment, because she suffers from long QT syndrome, an autosomal dominant condition. At the appointment they explain that her child has a 50% chance of inheriting the abnormal gene, however the risk of her child being affected by long QT syndrome depends on the penetrance. 

 

The penetrance of long QT syndrome is 90%.

 

What is the risk that the child will be affected by long QT syndrome?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

  • Penetrance is ‘the frequency with which the characteristic controlled by a gene is seen in the individuals possessing it'.
  • Complete penetrance is when the characteristic is seen in all individuals who possess the gene.
  • Incomplete penetrance is where someone has a mutated gene but never develops signs of and is not affected by it.

The likelihood of a family member being affected by a mutation in an autosomal dominant condition can be figured out by 50% multiplied by the penetrance (50% because this is the chance that the abnormal gene will be passed down)

 

An 90% penetrance means that the risk = 90% x 50% = 45%

Question: A 34 y/o woman comes into your clinic complaining of a sharp pain at "McBurney's point", which was first felt in her umbilical region. She has also been suffering from nausea and vomiting. After making a diagnosis with her CT scan and blood results (showing elevated white blood cells), you decide what to do next....
OptionC: Send home and tell her to rest for a few days
Explanation:
Treatment of appendicitis is surgical - it MUST be removed due to a high chance of perforation!

Patients are started on intravenous fluids and antibiotics pre-surgery - usually metronidazole, ampicillin and ciprofloxacin (if appendix hasn't already ruptured!)

Question: A 23 y/o man comes into your clinic complaining of SOB and swollen face, lips and tongue. He is planning on going travelling around Thailand in a couple of months so earlier today he had his Hepatitis A injection. You suspect that he is suffering from anaphylaxis, what do you do next?
OptionA: Discharge and tell him to come back tomorrow as it is the end of your shift
Explanation: Anaphylaxis is a life-threatening allergic reaction that requires IMMEDIATE treatment of adrenaline! If it is not treated it can lead to death!

Question:
Christie is a 24 year old woman who marries her cousin Barry (her mother's brother's son). Christie is pregnant with her first child. Barry has a sister who suffers from cystic fibrosis, and so they are referred to clinical genetics to work out the probability of their baby also suffering from this condition.

 

Cystic fibrosis is an autosomal recessive condition. The risk of a child being affected by an autosomal recessive condition from two unaffected parents can be worked out by: Mum's carrier risk x Dad's carrier risk x 1/4

 

What is the risk of the child having cystic fibrosis?

 

(Clue: Barry's carrier risk is 2/3)
OptionA: 1/24
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

Barry's carrier risk is 2/3. This is because both of his parents are definitely carriers (as his sister has CF). When two carriers have children there are 4 options: 

  1. Both parents pass on a normal gene – child is unaffected.
  2. Dad passes on a mutated gene but Mum passes on a normal gene – child is unaffected but is a carrier.
  3. Mum passes on a mutated gene but Dad passes on a normal gene – child is unaffected but is a carrier.
  4. Both parents pass on a mutated gene – child is affected.

Because Barry is unaffected option 4 is no longer an option. Therefore out of the other 3 options 2 of them involve him being a carrier, so Barry's carrier risk is 2/3.

 

Christies carrier risk is harder to work out. Because Barry's father is definitely a carrier, Barry's aunt (aka Christie's mother) has a 1/2 chance of being a carrier because Barry's/Christies grandparents each have a 1/2 risk of being a carrier as one of them passed it on to Barry's father.

 

This means that Christie has a 1/2 x 1/2 chance of being a carrier - so Christie has a 1/4 carrier risk.

 

2/3 x 1/4 x 1/4 = 1/24 chance that the baby will be affected.

 

This pedigree shows the different carrier risk for each member of the family.

Question:
You shine a light into both pupils, but only the right constricts. There is no response in the left pupil.

 

Where does this nerve exit the cranium?
Explanation:
Lesion in the left CNIII.

The oculomotor nerve exits through the superior orbital fissure.

Question:
Jack brings his son Henry in to the GP surgery to get his routine immunisations. The nurse explains that the vaccines she is giving Henry today are:

  • Hib/MenC
  • PVC (pneumococcal)
  • MMR
  • Men B booster

How old is Henry most likely to be if he is being given this combination of vaccinations?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

The main clue is that Henry is receiving the MMR vaccine. This is not given before 1 year old, so answers A-C are all wrong. 

Although the MMR is also given as a booster at 3 years 4 months, there are a reasonable amount of vaccines on the list. Children are generally given as many vaccines as possible in the early years of life, therefore it is more likely that Henry would be given all of these at 1 year rather than at 3 years 4 months.

Question:
Tallulah is a 25 year old new mother. Her daughter Blossom is happy and healthy. During one of the meetings with her health visitor the topic of vaccinations arises. Tallulah is sceptical of vaccinations, because 6 years ago her sister's best friend's cousin's son got a mild fever when he was given his vaccinations.

 

Tallulah explains that she has carried out extensive reading on the internet, and that she has decided that she is happy for Blossom to have the inactivated vaccines, but will not allow her to have any of the live attenuated vaccines.

 

Which of the following vaccines is a live attenuated vaccine?
OptionC: Influenza (injected)
OptionE: Typhoid (injected)
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

  • Live attenuated vaccines contain live organisms in a weakened form.
  • They can cause mild illness, and cannot be given to immunocompromised individuals as this can cause severe disease.
  • Inactivated vaccines contain killed organisms, and cannot give symptoms of the disease.
  • Usually live vaccines provoke a stronger immune response as they are more similar to the real disease.
  • However there is a balance – ideally the vaccine will be as similar to the disease as possible, but not so much that it will cause harm and give people the illness.
  • Other vaccines include protein-based toxoids/subunits, and polysaccharide-based cell walls.
  • All vaccines will cause symptoms at the site of injection, and can cause fever – this is an antigenic challenge.

Live Attenuated Vaccines

  • MMR (measles, mumps and rubella)
  • BCG (TB)
  • Influenza (nasal)
  • Rotavirus (oral)
  • Typhoid (oral)
  • Varicella zoster (VZV)
  • Yellow fever

Killed Vaccines

  • DTaP (diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis)
  • IPV (inactivated polio vaccine)
  • Hib, Men B, Men C (haemophilus influenza type B, Meningitis B&C)
  • Influenza (injected)
  • Pneumococcal
  • Typhoid (injected)
  • Hepatitis A
  • Hepatitis B
  • HPV (human papilloma virus)

Question:
Charlie is a 67 year old man who visits his GP surgery for his yearly flu jab. His 63 year old wife Denise asks whether she can also have her flu jab, however the nurse explains that because Denise is under 65 and has no significant health problems she is not eligible for a influenza vaccination on the NHS.

 

Which of the following people is also NOT eligible for the NHS flu vaccine?
OptionA: Annabel, a 24 year old woman who is pregnant.
OptionC: Christopher, a 45 year old who has HIV.
OptionE: Eliza, a 23 year old who is overweight with a BMI of 31.
Explanation:
The correct answer is E.

 

All of the people in options A-D would be eligible for the influenza vaccine.

 

Only seriously overweight individuals with a BMI over 40 are eligible for the vaccine. 

 

Influenza Vaccine

  • Influenza is highly infectious and easily spread, and so poses the highest threat for public health.
  • Seasonal increases in flu give rise to a large number of cases and can cause several thousand deaths.
  • People with flu also take up GP slots, hospital beds, etc.
  • The influenza vaccine contains 3 viral strains (4 strains in the nasal vaccine) and is given annually.
  • These are usually 2 group A strains and 1 group B strain, decided on using data from the southern hemisphere.
  • Routine nasal flu vaccines are given to children aged 2-9 .
  • Other high risk groups (pregnant, over 65, carers, etc.) and clinical risk groups also receive an annual flu vaccine.
  • Clinical risk groups include those with a chronic respiratory disease, chronic heart disease, diabetes, chronic renal disease, chronic liver disease, chronic neurological disease or weakened immunity

The full list of people who are eligible to receive the flu vaccine is here.

Increased levels of cAMP occur in regular opiate use leading to...

  • TOLERANCE (due to increased cAMP in VTA and Nucleus Accumbens)
  • WITHDRAWAL (due to increased cAMP in in locus coeruleus, brainstem and noradrenergic nucleus)

The symptoms of withdrawal come about due to the actions of increased NA:

Question:
Lizzie is a 23 year old who comes into her GP. Last year she was diagnosed with schizophrenia and was put on Clozapine. Although her schizophrenic symptoms have reduced, Lizzy has noticed that she has gained a lot of weight.

 

The GP is concerned that Lizzie may develop metabolic syndrome. This is a combination of biochemical and physiological symptoms which can lead to development of cardiovascular problems and type 2 diabetes. It is common in people who have schizophrenia.

 

What is the estimated average prevalence rate of Metabolic syndrome in patients with Schizophrenia?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

The set of risk factors for Metabolic syndrome are:

  • A large waistline
  • High triglyceride levels
  • Low high density lipoprotein (HDL cholesterol) level
  • High blood pressure
  • High blood sugar level

Weight gain is a common side effect associated with antipsychotic drugs, particularly Clozapine and Olanzapine. Hyperlipidaemia and hypertension are also associated with Clozapine. Moreover, these symptoms can also be attributed to the negative symptoms of psychosis (e.g. anhedonia and avolition), which can result in unhealthy behaviours such as lack of exercise, poor diet and smoking.

 

The best management of Lizzy is screening and monitoring, as well as attempting lifestyle changes. If this is unsuccessful, then Aripiprazole can be used to reduce Clozapine-induced side effects.

Question: You are writing PeerWise questions in your room when you hear an almighty bang. The workmen gutting the house next door have dropped something, propelling a fine mist of debris into your room via your open window. Being the hypochondriac you are, you suspect you've inhaled some dodgy Cathays asbestos. You day dream about your lungs, wondering if you're developing a mesothelioma. You think back to case 5 and the interpretation of X rays.  When interpreting a CXR, positioning is important. Describe the positioning of the following CXR.
Explanation:
This image depicts a posterior anterior CXR. PA CXR is preferred over AP CXR as it allows for the assessment of cardiomegaly. In an AP CXR, the heart can appear bigger than it is anatomically making diagnoses based on heart size invalid. 

 

When assessing the adequacy of a CXR use the RIPE system. 

Rotation: medial borders of clavicles equidistant from a spinous process

Inspiration: at least 5-6 anterior ribs visible above diaphragm

Picture area: lung apices, costodiaphragmatic recesses, scapula out of the way

Exposure: vertebral bodies should be just visible through lower part of cardiac shadow

 

For more on CXR interpretation :

Dopamine- Usually inhibitory, involved in the reward system (nucleus accumbens, striatum), cognition (frontal lobe, prefrontal area). Movement (basal ganglia)

 

GABA- Major inhibitory neurotransmitter of the brain. 

 

Glutatmate- Major excitatory neurotransmitter in the brain. 

 

Serotonin- Involved in mood, appetite, sensory perception. In spinal cord inhibits pain pathway.

Question: Whilst in the St David's Centre on a Saturday afternoon you encounter a member of the public who looks extremely confused and seems to be clammy and agitated. You ask them what is wrong and they say they are a diabetic and they may have forgotten to take their insulin. They don't have a blood sugar monitor on them but they do have a few preparations of insulin. Which of the following would be best to give in this situation?
Explanation:
The symptoms of this patient are more suggestive of a hypoglycaemic event. The fact that the patient is telling you that they missed their insulin is not enough of a reason to give insulin especially considering they are confused. If this patient was indeed having a hypo giving them insulin could kill them and so without a blood sugar reading giving insulin is a bad idea. Giving them lucozade will help bring them out of a hypo if that's what they have but even if they're having a hyperglycaemic event, lucozade will do little to exacerbate the condition.

Calling 999 would probably be advised in this situation especially if they did not respond to the lucozade.

Question: A patient comes into your practice with Achondroplasia. This is an autosomal dominant condition which results in dwarfism as seen in Peter Dinklage. Those homozygous for the mutation do not survive meaning that the only genotype producing achondroplasia is Tt. Since the condition is autosomal dominant, only one copy of the gene is required to produce the affected phenotype. Hence, according to this Punnett square the phenotype is 50% affected, 50% unaffected. 

 

Carriers don't occur in autosomal dominant conditions.

 

Answer A would describe the phenotype where both parents have achondroplasia.
