Question:
A 20 year old male who has very recently been diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes mellitus presents to the Emergency department having been unwell for 48 hours and with a gradually increasing blood sugar concentration, despite him saying he has taken his insulin. He is tachypnoeic and tachycardic. His blood glucose is measured at the hosptial and is found to be 25 mmol/L.

 

Analysis of an arterial blood sample while breathing oxygen, 6L/min1 via a facemask shows:
PaO2: 22.2 kPa (FiO2 40%)
pH: 7.34 [7.35-7.45]
PaCO2: 3.8 kPa [4.7-6.0 kPa)
Bicarbonate: 19.1 mmol/L (22-26 mmol/L)
Base excess: -7.9 mmol/L (+/- 2 mmol/L)

Interpret the arterial blood gas results.
OptionD: Acute metabolic acidosis with compensatory respiratory alkalosis
OptionE: Chronic metabolic acidosis with a compensatory respiratory alkalosis
Explanation:
From the history the most likely problem is that the patient is developing a diabetic ketoacidosis i.e. a metabolic acidosis. However, the fact that he is tachypnoeic suggests that he is trying to compensate by reducing his PaCO2. This will cause a respiratory alkalosis. If there are no abnormal signs in his chest, oxygenation should be relatively normal. Breathing 40% oxygen we would expect a PaO2 around 30 kPa however, with tachypnoea, the facemask is probably delivering less than 40% oxygen and so his oxygenation is unimpaired. The patient has a borderline acidaemia with a pH
just below the normal range. The PaCO2 is decreased, causing a respiratory alkalosis and therefore not the cause of the primary disturbance. The base excess and bicarbonate are both decreased confirming that there is a metabolic acidosis. However, the pH is not as low as would be expected for
this degree of change.

 

In summary, the patient has a metabolic acidosis (as a result of impaired glucose metabolism and the production of ketoacids) with a compensatory respiratory alkalosis. It is an Acute problem as he has only recently been diagnosed with Type 1 Diabetes and therefore may need a higher dosage of insulin or there may compliance issues with taking the insulin in young people which is something health care professionals need to pick up on.

Question: You are sitting at your desk working trying to write some Peerwise questions. The frustration of trying to write some half decent question drives you to bang your head against your desk. The resulting coup contra-coup injury leads to you developing raised intracranial pressure. One way to observe this is by doing an fundus examination with an ophthalmoscope. You get your Law flat mate to perform the examination. You guide her through the examination, you show her a picture of Papilloedema and ask her if your retina looks like that. Which picture below depicts papilloedema?
Explanation:
A- Cotton wool spots as seen in diabetic retinopathy. Indicative of retinal ischaemia. 6 or more in one eye is indicative of pre-proliferative state.

B- This is papilloedema, you can identify this by the blurred margins between the optic disc and the rest of the retina. As opposed to the sharp margins seen in normal examination. 

C- Intraretinal haemorrhages may be ‘dot’ or’ blot’ shaped (termed ‘dot/blot haemorrhages’) or flame shaped depending upon their depth within the retina. The capillary network in the posterior retina is found in two layers; a superficial one in the nerve fibre layer and a deeper on within the inner nuclear layer. Again, a sign of pre-proliferative diabetic retin

D- Hard exudates are distinct yellow-white intra-retinal deposits which can vary from small specks to larger patches to circinates to eventually form large confluent plaques. Formed of leaked extracellular lipids. Hard exudates are found principally in the macular region and as the lipids coalesce and extend into the central macula (fovea), vision can be severely compromised.

E-As the retina becomes more ischaemic new blood vessels may arise from the optic disc or in the periphery of the retina. The vessels usually originate from large veins and are initially seen as fine tufts on the surface of the disc or from the vessels of the major arcades of vessels. The new vessels are fragile and bleed easily, hence the importance of proliferative retinopathy.

 

http://www.glycosmedia.com/education/diabetic-retinopathy/diabetic-retinopathy-features-of-diabetes-neovascularisation/

Question:
A 50-year-old Polish man presents to the A&E department with slurred speech and dry mouth increasing over the past 12 hours.

 

The history reveals the man had been celebrating at a wedding the night before, drinking lots of alcohol and eating traditional Polish meats. On examination, he is alert and afebrile, but there is weakening of the eye muscles. 

 

 

The man soon begins to lose head control, and you suspect descending paralysis.

 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Correct answer: E) Botulism

 

Botulism is caused by Clostridium botulinum, a gram +ve, rod-shaped bacterium.

  • secretes a toxin (Botulinum toxin, or Botox)
  • commonly found in soil, more rarely in canned food
  • the toxin was ingested in this case
  • symptoms: descending paralysis (presents in upper limbs before lower limbs), including respiratory failure; blurred vision + pupil dilatation; dry mouth, nausea, diarrhoea
  • treatment: mainly supportive, including intubation and administering anti-toxin
  • the most common form in Western countries is infant botulism, but other causes include food, wound, inhalation, and injection (injecting too much Botox, incredibly)

 

If you're interested, this article is useful: https://academic.oup.com/jpubhealth/article/28/4/337/1622732 

  • "Even small outbreaks of food-borne botulism can precipitate a national emergency and inundate public health and acute care provision."
  • "Botulism differs from other causes of flaccid paralysis in that it affects the cranial nerves more severely; it is symmetrical and shows an absence of sensory signs and symptoms."

 

Main info was taken from the above article, Wikipedia (naughty, I know) + the plenary from Case 16 (Infections of the CNS 2017).

 

Other options

 

Answer A) Alcohol intoxication

Although a good suggestion, the symptoms are not as indicative of alcohol intoxication as perhaps later signs of botulism e.g. difficulty walking due to weakness.

 

Answer B) Guillain-Barré syndrome

This is an autoimmune muscle weakness syndrome that has a very rapid onset. Main symptoms include numbness, tingling and pain, followed by weakness of the limbs (symmetrical) that gets worse over time. Very similar to botulism, but the difference is that Guillain-Barre is characterised by ascending paralysis.

 

Answer C) Stroke

There are many possible symptoms and signs of stroke, so this would be a good fit, but in most cases, the symptoms (e.g. weakness, numbness, reduced sensation) affect one side of the body. I hopefully also gave a few clues with the history (12hr onset, consumed meat).

  

Answer D) Salmonella

Plausible considering the ?meat, ?cheese consumed and the rapid onset, but symptoms of a salmonella infection include: fever, abdominal cramps, vomiting, all of which are absent here.

 

 

 

Author's note: I will admit this is a hard question, as it's a little beyond the scope of what we're meant to know, and diagnosis of botulism can be difficult. However, I tried to apply the concept of descending paralysis to how it may present, and hopefully, you were able to work out the answer through a process of elimination. I also surprised at the botulism cases in the UK (see article) - only 62 cases since 1922, and 2 of those were due to meat sourced from Poland! (Niech yje Polska!) Hope you learned something new...

Question: A secundigravida woman visits your clinic for her first scan. She asks you about the vaccinations she will need. When would you vaccinate against Bordatella Pertussis (Whooping Cough)?
OptionA: She does not need the vaccine as she would have received this with her first pregnancy
OptionB: She may not need the vaccine dependent on when her last pregnancy was
Explanation:
You should get the whooping cough vaccine while pregnant to pass protection to your baby
Early, short-term protection is critical. Your baby will not get her first whooping cough vaccine until she is 2 months old.
After receiving a whooping cough vaccine, your body will create protective antibodies (proteins produced by the body to fight off diseases) and pass some of them to your baby before birth. These antibodies provide your baby some short-term protection against whooping cough in early life. These antibodies can also protect your baby from some of the more serious complications that come along with whooping cough.
Your protective antibodies are at their highest about 2 weeks after getting the vaccine. So you should get the vaccine late in your pregnancy, preferably during your 27th through 36th week, to give your baby the most protection when she is born.
The amount of whooping cough antibodies in your body decreases over time. When you get the vaccine during one pregnancy, your antibody levels will not stay high enough to provide enough protection for future pregnancies. It is important for you to get a whooping cough vaccine during each pregnancy so high levels of protective antibodies are transferred to each of your babies.

Question: Your friend Jess is planning a postgrad gap year travelling Southeast Asia next summer. She is slightly worried about dengue as she has heard it is common in areas that she is planning to visit. What do you advise her?
OptionA: Jess needs to receive the 2-course live-attenuated dengue virus vaccination, finishing the course 2 weeks before she leaves
OptionB: Jess will need to carry 30-50% DEET mosquito repellant spray and continuously reapply it
OptionC: There is nothing to worry about as Dengue fever is relatively harmless, giving cold-like symptoms
OptionD: Jess needs to reevaluate her travel route to avoid places which have a dengue risk
OptionE: Jess will have to be sure to only drink bottled water whilst travelling and to avoid ice in drinks
Explanation:
Dengue virus is transmitted by the human-mosquito-human route (and therefore mosquitos are the virus vector). In most cases, the infection is mild and passes. However, the haemorrhage form of the virus can be fatal.

 

Symptoms:

  • high temperature
  • muscle pain 
  • headaches
  • rashes 

There is no vaccine for dengue virus due to antibody enhancement: there are 4 subtypes of the virus and your are initially infected with subtype 1. There is an antibody response. If you are reinfected with subtype 1, your antibodies destroy the virus. However, if you are infected with subtype 2, your antibodies still bind to the virus but don't inactivate it, and your macrophages are recruited but become infected. 

 

A - no vaccine 

B - correct - virus spread is controlled through mosquito control 

C - although it is normally fairly harmless, it  can be fatal 

D - it may be worth avoiding areas with particularly high risk, but so long as you take the appropriate precautions you wouldn't be advised to not go 

E - this is irrelevant as it isn't transmitted through the faeco-oral route

D- the average incubation period of rubella is 14 day

E- The incubation period for mumps is 14-21 days, averaging at 17 days

Question: Which of the following is a cause of a urticaria rash?
Explanation:
A urticaria rash, also known as Hives appears as raised itching bumps, that blanch and can appear anywhere in the body. Their causes include drug poisioning and histamine poisioning.

 

A- Meningococcal septicaemia is a cause of a petechiae rash (non-blanching area of haemorrhage)

C- Herpes simplex is a cause of vesicles (small fluid filled blisters)

D- Warts are a cause of papules (small, palpable, circumscribed lesion)

E- Psoriasis is a cause of plaques (large, flat-topped, elevated palpable lesion).

Question: Where is the majority of Noradrenaline made?
What drug is more commonly used in Ulcerative colitis and not so much in Crohns disease?
Explanation:
A) IBS

B) More crohns

C) More crohns

D) Can be used in both 

E) more commonly used in UC

Question: A patient on the ward has just been pronounced dead. What is her GCS?
Explanation:
Think of GCS like an advanced method of AVPU; it's an accepted assessment tool for evaluating response ability. It's primarily used in head trauma to convey the possible extent of injury. You can transfer a lot of information about your patient in a very short amount of time. It's like saying "this patient is responsive to pain, and also exhibits this specific type of response." The type of response, itself, is shorthand between providers that implies the severity of the injury or illness. Giving GCS in a radio report tells the hospital what they are likely to encounter upon your arrival.

 

A dead person has a GCS score of THREE, not ZERO! This seems counter-intuitive because we naturally think of ZERO as NONE.

Question:
Velma had a BBQ with her friends yesterday and now is starting to feel very unwell. She has got bloody diarrhoea with severe cramps and fever. The doctor is worried as this bacteria can cause guillain barre syndrome.

 

What is the bacteria?
Explanation:
Campylobacter
Gram negative rod that is motile and curved, bacteria
Transmission: Contaminated food that is often undercooked, not usually person-person
Causes: contaminated food which is infected with campylobacter (a lot of food is)
Symptoms: inflamm, bloody diarrhoea with cramps and fever
Complications: can sometimes be linked to development of Guillain-Barre syndrome or reactive arthritis
Treatment: usually lasts 5-7 days and is self-limiting with ORS etc.
Commonest cause of IID in the UK
90% are due to C. jejuni (campylobacter jejuni) and 10% to C. coli
Comes from zoonosis (jejuni from birds and coli from pigs)
Need special culture conditions (low O2 and high CO2)
Low infective dose (500+ organisms) but depends on host’s gastric PH etc.
Mediated by toxin production
Erythromycin may shorten length of disease but bacteria are becoming more resistant
Prevention is isolation of symptomatic patients and good hygiene

Question:
A 64-year-old man is admitted to A&E with central crushing chest pain. As the nurse is taking his observations he has a cardiac arrest. Thankfully CPR was started immediately and after 6 minutes he regained spontaneous circulation.

Based on this information, which of the following conclusions would you most likely draw from his ABG?
Explanation:
This patient had a cardiac arrest which meant there was a period of impaired ventilation end-organ perfusion. This led to hypercapnia causing a respiratory acidosis, in addition to the accumulation of products of anaerobic respiration (as a result of hypoxia and reduced end-organ perfusion) causing metabolic acidosis.

 

See Geeky Medics for this and more useful questions! https://geekyquiz.com/learn/quiz/abg-interpretation/

Question:
A 9 y/o patient comes into your clinic complaining of hearing difficulties and impaired speech development as a result. Her mother is very worried and asks you to examine her ears. The view of your otoscope is as follows...

 

What is your diagnosis and the most likely cause of this presentation?
OptionB:
Perforated tympanic membrane 

Caused by frequently cleaning ears with Q tips
OptionC:
Otitis media 

Caused by an upper respiratory infection
Explanation:
This is serous otitis media which is a problem with drainage along the Eustachian Tube commonly caused by respiratory infections. 

Treatment requires grommets to provide an alternative drainage route for the accumulation fluid - this will then drop out as the tympanic membrane heals. 

 

Grommet inserted:

Question:
A 21 y/o patient comes into your clinic complaining of a loss of hearing. During your medical history you find out that her mother suffered from otosclerosis and now has a prosthetic ________ inserted. You think that your patient may have the same thing.

  • What is otosclerosis
  • Fill in the missing word above
OptionA:
Otosclerosis is calcification of the ossicle joints, particularly of stapes on the oval window 

Stapes
OptionB:
Otosclerosis is calcification of the ossicle joints, particularly of incus on the oval window

Incus
OptionD:
Otosclerosis is a fracture of one of your ossicles, commonly seen in incus 

Incus
Explanation:
Otosclerosis is calcification of the ossicle joints, particularly of stapes on the oval window

Stapes is the missing word as it is the most likely ossicle to be affected

Question:
You are a GP, and Mr Rodgers, a 49 year old gentleman, has just come in to see you to complain about a change in his bowel habit. Through further discussion, you decide that a blood test is the correct next step, and while you're at it, you decide to take check his blood glucose level. His random plasma glucose is currently 17.0mmol/L .

 

 

What is the correct next step in his management?
OptionA: Tell Mr Rodgers that he has diabetes and recommend some lifestyle changes.
OptionB: Tell Mr Rodgers that he has diabetes and start him on Metformin.
OptionC: Ask Mr Rodgers to come back in a couple of days, and check his fasting plasma glucose
Explanation:
The current WHO diagnostic criteria for diabetes should be maintained – fasting plasma glucose ≥ 7.0mmol/l (126mg/dl) or 2–h plasma glucose ≥ 11.1mmol/l (200mg/dl) or impaired oral glucose tolerance test

If a patient is asymptomatic, they must fulfil at least two of the criteria mentioned above. 

 

 

Probably also worth knowing that 50% of people with T2DM are asymptomatic.

Question: A few months ago, your flatmate bursts into your room in a great panic.' I think that I may have contracted an STI from a public toilet seat'. In a half slumbering stupor, you set her nerves at easy. You start by explaining some key differences between different STI's. Which of the following best fits the description of Chlamydia?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C:

 

Chlamydia is caused by the gram negative Chlamydia Trachomatis bacteria. 

It is non-motile and is an obligate intracellular pathogen. This means that the bacteria can only survive and reproduce inside a host cell. 

Symptoms include:

Males: urethritis, proctitis and epididymitis

Females: Urethritis, cervicitis 

Newborns: Conjunctivitis, pneumonia

 

Treatment includes:

 

First line antibiotics doxycycline or azithromycin.

Advise to avoid sexual intercourse with partner(s) for 7 days after their treatment.

Advise they go to a screening clinic to check for other STI's.

Refer to GUM if other complications arise such as PID in females. 

 

https://cks.nice.org.uk/chlamydia-uncomplicated-genital#!scenario
Tags: NICE, Case 2, Immunology, Infection, Infectious Diseases

Question:
You are sitting at your desk in the library. Bored of procrastinating, you decide to go and get some lunch from the IV lounge. You despair at the selection of unappetising, overpriced sandwiches on offer and regret not just making a packed lunch. All of this talk of food makes you think of GLUT transporters. 

 

GLUT2 transporters are responsible for the uptake of glucose into the pancreas and liver. Which of the following features would be most suitable for GLUT 2 to perform this role?
OptionA: GLUT2 has a low kM for glucose.
OptionB: GLUT2 is dependent on ATP and Na+ for transport
OptionE: GLUT2 has a low affinity for glucose.
Explanation:
GLUT2 is found in the liver and pancreas. It is independent of Na and ATP unlike SGLT found in intestinal epithelial cells and kidney tubules. 

It is responsible for the uptake of glucose into the liver and pancreas. It has a high kM meaning that it has a low affinity for glucose. After eating, glucose levels in the blood rise. Increased concentration of glucose requires uptake by the pancreas in order to produce insulin. If the kM was low and affinity higher, insulin would be released inappropriately. 

 

GLUT4 found in muscles and adipose is insulin dependent. This is why in diabetes mellitus with impaired insulin response/absent insulin, patients experience lethargy.

Question: You are conducting an abdominal examination on a 40 year old female patient. In axilla of the patient, you notice Acanthosis nigricans. Further investigations reveal a blood pressure of 150/100mmHg. You notice that the patient has an increased body habitus as well as noticeable facial hair for a female. Fasting glucose is 5.5 mmol/L. Further history taking reveals bitemporal hemianopia. Which of the following differential diagnosis fits this patient?
Explanation:
Acanthosis Nigricans is seen in a myriad of conditions. It can be familial, endocrine driven, as a consequence of metabolic syndrome, malignancy or drug induced. 

 

Answers Type 1 and Type 2 diabetes mellitus are unlikely. A fasting glucose above 5.6mmol/L is seen as prediabetes and two separate measurements of 7mmol/L fasting glucose is seen as diagnostic criteria for DM by the WHO. 

 

Hydrocephalus is unlikely. 

 

Addison's disease is hypocortisolism, as such you would see a lower blood pressure and weight loss. Although skin pigmentation is seen in Addison's. 

 

The correct answer is Cushing's disease, this is caused by an overproduction of adrenocorticotropic hormone by the anterior pituitary gland. This is secondary hypercortisolism. Commonly caused by a pituitary adenoma, hence the bitemporal hemianopia. Other symptoms include: weight gain, increased hair growth, hyperpigmentation, irritability, hypertension etc.

Question: Which part of the small intestine would you find the major duodenal papilla?

A patient presents with vomiting, abdominal pain, abdominal swelling and constipation. After performing an abdominal X-Ray, you diagnose the patient with a small bowel obstruction. What is the most likely cause of her SBO?
Explanation:
Adhesions are the most common cause of SBO

D and E are also common causes of SBO.

B is the most common cause of LBO.

C and D are also common cause of LBO.

Question: Selective Serotonin Re-Uptake Inhibitors act on serotonin transporters (SERT). In addition to this, they are also thought to act upon a certain structure in the central nervous system. Which of the following structures are SSRI's most likely to have a significant affect upon?
Explanation:
Raphe Nuclei is the correct answer as serotonin neurons are confined here. It has extensive projections to other parts of the brain. Since SSRI's affect serotonin, this structure is most likely to be affected by them.

A = GABA mainly
C = Dopamine 
D = Noradrenergic neurons 
E = Dopamine / Glutamate

Question: Which of the following is an accurate description of Hep A?
OptionA: DNA virus, transmitted via blood, semen, saliva etc. Also shows vertical transmission (mother--> child) Vaccine available.
OptionB: RNA enterovirus, faeco-oral transmission, gives rise to acute hepatitis. Vaccine available
OptionC: RNA virus, can only cause infection in the presence of Hep B, high rate of developing cirrhosis.
OptionD: RNA virus, blood borne, high risk in IV drug users. likely to become chronic
OptionE: RNA virus, faeco oral transmission, no vaccine
Explanation:
A; Hepatitis B

B; Hepatitis A

C; Hepatitis D

D; Hepatitis C

E; Hepatitis E

Question: Which of these is not a mechanism for G cell mediated gastrin release?
OptionA: Presence of peptide fragments in the duodenum
OptionD: D cell mediated somatostatin release due to a drop in gastric pH
Explanation: A low gastric pH negatively feedsback on G cells. Somatostatin inhibits Gastrin release in order to prevent the gastrin stimulating parietal cells to produce more acid.

Question: When treating H.pylori infection, what does the 3,2,1 rule mean?
Explanation: 3 drugs; a PPI and 2 antibiotics, usually amoxycillin and clarithromycin or metronidiole. If penicillin allergy, give both clarithromycin and metronidiole

Question: You are reviewing a patient who has just been diagnosed with a parathyroid adenoma. She presents with symptoms of nausea, lethargy and confusion as well as a history of numerous bone fractures. Neurological examination reveals slower reflexes and muscle weakness. ECG reveals bradycardia, AV block and Osborn waves. You explain to the patient that she is hypercalaemic due to an overproduction of PTH. Which of the following is an appropriate treatment for hypercalcaemia?
Explanation:
The correct answer is bisphosphonates. There are 3 ways in which PTH can cause hypercalcaemia:

 

1. Increase osteoclast activity and decrease osteoblast activity. Bisphosphonates decrease bone resorption

2. Increase Ca2+ reabsorption from the kidney tubules. Thiazide diuretics are responsible for this. 

3. Increase absorption of Ca2+ in the GI tract. Vitamin D is responsible for this. 

 

For more on the parathyroid gland, refer to the lecture in Case 14 on the topic.

Question: By which of the follwing mechanisms does St John's Wort interact with the combined oral contraceptive pill?
OptionA: decreases the pH, making the CYP enzymes less active, raising circulating levels of the drug.
OptionB: Inhibits the CYP enzyme that metabolises the COCP and raises circulating levels of the drug.
OptionC: Induces other isoforms of CYP enzymes to metabolise the COCP consequently causing low circulating levels of the drug.
Explanation:
A is an example of antacids' effects in the stomach. This can inhibit absorption of certain drugs e.g. tripanavir - used to treat HIV 

B is true of erythromycin's interaction with the COCP

C; correct answer

Question:
A patient attends your clinic complaining of sore throat, fatigue, swollen glands and diarrhoea. She has been experiencing palpitations, and has felt anxious and irritable, she reports having snapped at her husband over a silly disagreement.

 

You diagnose her with hyperthyroidism due to acute thyroiditis, what treatment do you offer her?
Explanation:
Acute thyroiditis is usually self-limiting. Palliative beta blockers are prescribed to manage the anxiety and palpitations.

 

Antithyroid drugs are used for hyperthyroidism either to prepare patients for thyroidectomy or for long-term management. In the UK carbimazole is the most commonly used drug. Propylthiouracil should be reserved for patients who are intolerant of carbimazole or for those who experience sensitivity reactions to carbimazole (sensitivity is not necessarily displayed to both drugs), and for whom other treatments are inappropriate. Both drugs act primarily by interfering with the synthesis of thyroid hormones.

 

Radioactive iodine therapy is used for Graves disease which doesn't respond to pharmacological treatment, or for toxic multinodular goiter and solitary adenomas

 

Thyroidectomy can also be performed in patients with Graves disease

Question: Tom, a 17 year old male comes into the GP surgery after having recently being diagnosed with type 1 diabetes. He had his HbA1c tested and has been called back for the results. His results show that he is controlling his diabetes well. He asks what the level of HbA1c needs to be in order to be diagnosed with diabetes. Which of the following do you respond with?
Explanation:
a) Wrong as it needs to be more than 6.5%

b) > 7.0 mmol/L of fasting blood glucose can be used as one measurement if the patient presents with symptoms.

c) HbA1c can also be expressed in mmol/mol, however, to confirm the diagnosis of diabetes, it needs to be > 48mmol/mol

d) Correct answer

e) This is correct, but indicates a measure of random plasma glucose, and not of HbA1c.

 

These are the ranges for HbA1c:

 

Normal - Below 6.0% OR Below 42 mmol/mol
Pre-diabetes - 6.0% to 6.4% OR 42 to 47 mmol/mol
Diabetes - 6.5% or above OR 48 mmol/mol or above

Question:
If a person consumes 4 pints of beer, 3 VKs and 2 tequila shots... How many units have they consumed? (round up to the nearest unit) Are they over their recommended weekly allowance?

Fosters; 5%

Pint = 568ml

VK = 4%  volume= 275ml

Tequila = 40% volume = 25ml
Explanation:
Fosters; 568 x 4 =2,272

2272 x 5 = 11,360

11,360 / 1000 = 11.36

 

VK; 275 x 3 = 825

825 x 4 = 3,300

3,300/1000 = 3.3

 

Tequila; 25 x 2 = 50

50 x 40 = 2000

2000/1000= 2

 

Total; 11.36 + 3.3 + 2 = 16.66 so round up to 17

 

Guidance says 14 units per week max for men and women, spread out over a week and ideally with at leasst 2 alcohol free days.

Question: What dopamine receptor is excitatory?
Explanation: D1 and D5 are excitatory.

Question: Which one of the following is the reason for 'calor' during injury?
Explanation:
Calor- heat- caused by vasodilation and perfusion

tumour- swelling- caused by proteins and WBC in the area

Rubor- redness- caused by vasodilation

dolor- hurting- sensory nerves in the area and prostaglandins

functio laesa- loss of function- due to chronic inflammation

Question: In the cervix, there is a junction of different epithelial cell types. What is this junction?
the first arrest of oogenesis happens in prophase 1, when is the second arrest?
Explanation:
the arrest at prophase 1 occurs at birth

the arrest at metaphase 2 occurs during puberty. 

the only way the oogenesis carries on passed metaphase 2 is if fertilisation has taken place

Question: A 3-year-old boy is referred to a community paediatrician for assessment. The boy has moderate developmental delay, speech problems, a sub-mucous cleft palate and a history of frequent respiratory infections. A genetic diagnosis is made by array comparative genomic hybridisation (array-CGH) testing. Which of the following chromosomal abnormalities is the most likely explanation for the boy’s development problems?
Explanation: DiGeorge syndrome – mild-mod dev delay/LD, cleft palate, heart defects, immune problems

Question: You are conducting a breast examination on a patient.  From where does 75% of the lymph of the breast drain?
Explanation: 75% of breast lymph is drained by the axillary nodes. This is why it is important in a breast examination to observe and palpate the axilla for lymphoedema. For more see the breast anatomy lecture in case 8.

Question:
34 y/o type 1 diabetic patient comes into your clinic complaining of hyperhidrosis, diarrhoea, palpitations and weight loss. You do a FBC and thyroid function test. Results are as follows:

  • Increased fT4
  • Decreased TSH 

What’s your diagnosis?
Explanation:
The patient has presented with hyperthyroidism 

Grave‘s disease is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism - esp. as patient already has type 1 diabetes (another autoimmune condition)

Question: A 24y/o newly diagnosed type 1 diabetic is rushed into A&E suffering from fits and speech difficulty. You are very worried that he may comatose and quickly take his blood glucose measurement. What result are you likely to see?
Explanation:
Remember 4 is floor = this is indicative of hypoglycaemia however 2 is the most likely answer as he is about to comatose! 

 

Treatment plan for this patient: 

  1. 20% glucose (70-100ml over 15 mins)
  2. Glucagon 1mg IM 
  3. Wait 15 mins for glucagon to take action 
  4. Recheck blood glucose 
  5. Repeat if blood glucose still < 4 (do not admin. more glucagon)

Question:
A 14 y/o type 1 diabetic comes into your GP surgery as he has just had an argument with his parents as he has been researching the genetics behind his condition and so blames them for giving it to him.

A).  What is the main genetic link in type 1 diabetes?

B).  Which type of diabetes (type 1 or 2) has a higher inheritability (shown by twin studies)?
OptionA:
GLUT transporter gene 

Type 2 diabetes has a higher inheritance rate (70-100%)
OptionB:
HLA Class II gene 

Type 2 diabetes has a higher inheritance rate (70-100%)
OptionC:
Leptin gene 

Type 1 diabetes has a higher inheritance rate (35-50%)
Explanation:
There is clearly a genetic linkage in Type 1 Diabetes and it has been indicated that it is to do with HLA II DLR3/4 pre-disposition 

HLA genes are found on chromosome 6 and they are highly polymorphic 

Type 2 diabetes has a higher inheritance rate at 70-100% - but you must reach the threshold weight/age/other environmental factors for it to occur!

Question: A 16 year old girl presents at your clinic with her mother. She has only just commenced the menarche and is concerned about her body image. She wants to know more about breast development. She has learnt about oestrogen in GCSE biology and wonders if it has a role in breast development. Which of the following best describes this role?
OptionB: Stimulates myoepithelial cells to contract resulting in the secretion of milk
OptionC: Stimulates the production of milk by epithelial cells
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. 

 

Oestrogen stimulates ductal elongation and bifurcation. 

Progesterone stimulates the formation of spherical masses of epithelial cells at the end of each duct (immature alveoli).

The size of breasts is determined by the fatty tissue volume stored within the breast. In pregnancy, glandular tissue increases the mass of the breast. In old age the glandular tissue is replaced with fat, this makes the detection of breast cancer on a mammogram easier in the elderly. 

 

For more see the lecture from case 8 on breast anatomy.

Question: Which of the following features is unique to the histology of the duodenum?
Explanation:
• Plicae Circularis are large circular folds in the mucosa, most numerous in the upper parts of the small intestine 
  • Villi are smaller folds in the mucosa called, which are finger like mucosal projections, about 1mm long
  • Between the villi there are crypts, called crypts of Lieberkuhn, which extend down to the muscularis mucosae. These crypts are short glands.
  • Lymphoid aggregations are commonly found in the sub-mucosa of the small intestine. The larger aggregations of lymphoid tissue are known as Peyer's Patches. These are most common in the ileum.

 

Both Brunner's glands, and the goblet cells in the duodenum secrete mucus. The mucus secreted by Brunner's glands is alkaline, and helps to neutralise the acid chyme produced by the stomach, to produce chyme with a pH suitable for the digestive enzymes of the small intestine.

 

How does the Duodenum differ from the rest of the small intestine?

  • The villi are broader
  • Peyers Patches are less common
  • Unique feature: Brunner's glands, which are found in the sub-mucosa.

Question: You are giving an antenatal class to first time mothers. In the class, one of the mothers asks about breast feeding. She asks about how much she should feed her baby and how frequently the baby should feed. You give the following advice:
OptionA: Feed little and often, this is to ensure that the breast milk has a low fat content.
OptionB: Doesn't particularly matter, milk fat content doesn't vary.
OptionC: You shouldn't breast feed, formula milk is better.
OptionD: If you don't breast feed once every few hours, galactopoiesis will stop.
OptionE: Fully empty the breast with each feed. This ensures that the fat content is higher in the milk.
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. Galactopoiesis is regulated by rate and quantity of feeding.

 

Continuous suckling activates mechanoreceptors in the nipple. This signals to afferent pathways to the hypothalamus, this stimulates the anterior pituitary to secrete prolactin. Prolactin stimulates acini cells to produce milk. 

Prolactin receptors change shape when the alveoli become distended with milk. This acts to negatively feedback on milk production. 

Whey protein acts as to locally control milk production in each breast. When a breast is emptied, the fat content in the subsequent milk is increased. Milk production increases the more empty the breast. This is why emptying the breast is desirable. 

 

Galactopoesis does require constant nipple stimulation for lactation to occur. However it takes much longer than a few hours before milk production stops. 

 

Stages of lactation:

1. Mammogenesis, glandular tissue develops. Finished by week 22. 

2. Lactogenesis stage 1. Oestrogen and progesterone inhibit lactation by inhibiting prolactin, products are reabsorbed into the blood.

3. Lactogenesis stage 2. Post-partum, drop in progesterone and oestrogen, 30-40 hrs after birth milk volume increases, increase in lactose, IgA, lactoferrin and oligosaccharide. Within 3 days breast feeding must commence, otherwise milk production will cease. 

This moves to lactogenesis 3 which occurs indefinitely.

Question: You are on placement in Newport. You are discussing breast milk versus formula milk with a mother with her newborn baby. You are explaining the benefits of breast milk over formula. Which of the following products is the main immunological component in formula milk?
Explanation:
Breast is best. 

 

Breast milk contains IgA, this helps the developing immune system in the destruction of pathogens. 

Lactoferrin is a Iron chelation useful in the development of commensal bacterial flora. Also useful in reducing inflammatory markers and useful in blocking viral penetration.

α-Lactalbumin: promotes growth of bifidobacterium.

Lysozyme causes bacterial cell wall lysis, binds endotoxin (limiting it’s effect), increases IgA production and contributes to macrophage activation.

Casein: inhibits adhesion of various bacteria in different epithelial sites and promotes the growth of bifidobacterium

 

For more see case 8 breast anatomy lecture.

Question: You are on placement with a midwife. One patient presents to the ward in the first stage of labour. The midwife inspects her cervix to find it 5cm dilated. You ask the patient if she is in any pain. She describes the pain as crampy and hard to localise. Which of the following afferent fibres would synapse to the spinal cord in order for this pain to be detected?
Explanation: The answer is C fibres. These fibres are unmyelinated and have a slow conduction rate. They are responsible for signalling for poorly localised visceral pain. During the first stage of labour, the head of the foetus is distending the lower uterine segment. This along with uterine contractions causes the visceral pain in the first stage of labour.

Question: What spinal level is the hyoid bone?

A 50 y/o patient in a wheelchair comes into your clinic with several burns and complaining that they cannot feel pain so frequently injure themselves. You take a focused neurological history and find out that your patient has recently suffered from severe meningitis and is on cefotaxime and ampicillin. After filling out the ASIA chart, you suspect that your patient is suffering from incomplete SCI. What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
Anterior Cord syndrome is usally caused by vascular events (involving anterior spinal artery) or from severe meningitis that is compressing the anterior spinal Cord. 

 

Features:

  • Bilateral spastic paralysis 
  • Loss of motor function (Px is in a wheelchair)
  • Loss of pain (Px explains this in history - frequently injure themselves/burns) 
  • Loss of temperature (Px has lots of burns) 

Not stated but patient would retain proprioception, vibration and joint position sense as posterror column pathways are still intact.

Not Brown-Sequard syndrome as this is usually caused by a penetrating injury!

Question: A 44 y/o patient comes into your clinic complaining of difficultly coordinating muscle movements, numbness and loss of vibration sense. You take a history and find out that he is very sexually active but always forgets to wear a condom. You suspect that he may have an STI however his neurological findings (loss of vibration and 2 point discrimination) suggest that he may also be suffering from an incomplete SCI. What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
Posterior cord syndrome occurs in syphilis and tumours that compress the Posterior aspect of the spinal cord. 

This would lead to loss of the posterior column pathways involved in vibration, proprioception (coordination of movements) and 2 point discrimination. 

His motor function remains intact however he finds it difficult to coordinate his muscles.

Question: At what level is the cricoid cartilage?

A man has come in to A&E with back pain and loss of sensation in his legs. He said he has struggled with incontinence over the past few days. You look at his health records and see that he had prostate cancer 2 years ago. 

 

What scan would you recommend to do first?
Explanation:
Serious Spinal Pathology 2 -
Metastatic Spinal Cord
Compression and Spinal
Infections- lecture

 

Suspected MSCC with neurological signs
and symptoms = urgent MRI of whole
spine within 24 hours
• Suspected Spinal Mets (no neurology) =
MRI whole spine within a week of
suspected diagnosis

Question: Which TLRs are expressed by plasmacytoid dendritic cells?

A 60 y/o febrile patient comes into your clinic complaining of lower back pain for the past 3 months. You complete neurological history and examination of this patient and find out that he was in hospital 4 months ago due to a pneumonia infection. No family history of cancer. What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
Most likely diagnosis is spinal infection with staph. Aureus because...

  • Patient is over 50 yrs
  • Patient has recently been in hospital (Staph. Aureus is the MOST common healthcare associated infection) 
  • Patient has lower back pain - indicative of lumbar spine (most common site for infection) 
  • Symptoms present for 3 months

These are all in the RULE OF 50!

Question: A lack of which of the following causes beri-beri?
Explanation: Thiamine = vitamin B1

Question: What organ converts VitD into active VitD?

A 60 y/o patient comes into your clinic with loss of all motor function and sensation except in their peri-anal area (which you discover after carrying out a PR exam). You suspect that the patient is suffering from central cord syndrome. What is the pattern of recovery in these patients?
Explanation: CORD SYNDROMES TUTORIAL

Question: What is B9 also known as?
Explanation: Folate, distinct forms of which are known as folic acid, folacin, and vitamin B9, is one of the B vitamins.

Question:
A patient has recently been diagnosed with neuropraxia and has motor weakness and sensory disturbance in his arm. He wants to know more about the condition as he is worried because after 3 weeks the symptoms have not gone away.

Which of the following is your most likely response to this patient?
OptionA: He may need surgery to repair the damaged nerve.
OptionB: Recovery takes up to 12 weeks while the nerve axons are remyelinated.
OptionC: Nerves do not repair themselves so he won't see any improvement.
OptionD: Nerve fibres regenerate at an inch per month.
OptionE: The length of recovery time depends on the amount of scarring.
Explanation:
Neuropraxia is a first degree nerve injury. It results in some demyelination but the axon is not damaged. Within 12 weeks the remyelination should be complete and he should make a full recovery.

Nerve repair does happen in peripheral nerves. In more severe injuries the amount of scarring is significant and surgery is necessary sometimes. Nerve fibres do regenerate at 1 inch per month but no regeneration is needed in neuropraxia because the nerve axon is not damaged, only demyelinated.

Question: A 23 y/o is rushed to A&E with severe neck pain. What is your diagnosis from the cervical spine x-ray below?
Explanation:
This is a Hangman’s fracture - fracture to the pars interarticularis on the axis (C2). 

Pars interarticularis refers to a small segment of bone that joins the facet joints in the back of the spine. A defect in this portion of the spine leads to a condition called spondylolysis.

Question: You are in Lidl when a woman suddenly goes into labour in front of you. You ring an ambulance and attend to the woman while it comes. She is in an incredible amount of pain and as a result is hyperventilating. You encourage her to copy your breathing to prevent respiratory  alkalosis. Why would maternal respiratory alkalosis be bad for the foetus?
OptionA: Alkalosis would result in an increase of CO2 concentration causing hypercapnia
OptionB: Maternal alkalosis would cause uterine artery vasodilation.
OptionC: Hyperventilation would result in increased cardiac output in the mother
OptionD: Maternal alkalosis would reduce O2 delivery to the foetus.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. 

 

Pain during labour results in increased anxiety and lower morale in the mother. It also activates the sympathetic nervous system to increase maternal cardiac output, blood pressure and increase vasoconstriction. This results in a build up of lactic acid as well as a fall in O2. The body also goes into a state of hyperventilation. 

 

This leads to respiratory alkalosis. due to a lower PaCO2. 

This can affect the foetus in two ways:

1- Alkalosis causes uterine artery vasoconstriction, this reduces uteroplacental blood flow. 

2- Alkalosis causes a Bohr shift, shifting oxygen dissociation curve to the left. This results in increased affinity for maternal Hb for O2. As a result the foetus receives less O2.

 

The net result is foetal hypoxia. 

 

For more see the pain in labour lecture. Case 8

Question:
Charcot Marie Tooth is an inherited progressive condition where there is distal muscle wasting and sensory loss. Symptoms usually start to appear between 5-15yrs and include weakness and paraethesia distally, abnormal gait and highly arched feet.

Is this condition associated with loss of function in upper motor neurones or lower motor neurones?
Explanation: CMT is a LMN condition - hence the loss of function distally (focal weakness)

Question:
A 44 year old woman, Mrs B, presents in the surgery with episodic bouts of dizziness, palpitations, headaches and anxiety over the past few days. 

On examination, her blood pressure is 138/90 and she appears pale and sweaty. 

The GP you're shadowing sends her home with an ambulatory blood pressure monitor, which, sure enough, shows periods of high pressure over the 24 hours. 

 

When Mrs B comes back, the GP reads her medical history and refers her for an abdominal CT scan. 

 

What pathology does the GP suspect?
Explanation:
Sorry if this is a bit of a headache of a question but I was confused about all of this so thought a question might help! These were all mentioned in Tim Johnson's lecture too, so we are probably expected to know a bit about each of them. 

 

Renal Artery Stenosis:

  • Renal cause of secondary hypertension
  • 2 forms:
  • -Atherosclerosis: stenosis of the renal artery leads to increased renin and aldosterone, which cause increased vasoconstriction and ECF and therefore high BP
  • Fibromuscular dysplasia: abnormal growth in the wall of the artery
  • More severe RAS could present with more kidney-related symptoms e.g urinary changes, itching, peripheral oedema etc.
  • Usually diagnosed using doppler ultrasound or angiogram

 

Renal Parenchymal Disease:

  • Another (most common) renal cause of hypertension 
  • Causes unopposed vasoconstriction and salt/water retention, leading to increased BP
  • Most commonly investigated using urinalysis and ultrasound

Liddle's Syndrome:

  • Non-modifiable risk factor for essential hypertension
  • Overexpression of sodium channels in the collecting duct, causing high BP in early life
  • Usually recognised as a child

Conn's Syndrome:

  • Adrenal cause of hypertension
  • Increased aldosterone causes increased ECF volume and therefore high BP
  • Would usually present with more symptoms e.g moon face, frequent urination, increased thirst, truncal obesity etc. 
  • Detected using blood test

 

Phaechromocytoma:

  • Another adrenal cause of hypertension
  • Tumour of the adrenal gland secreted adrenaline and noradrenaline, which causes the palpitations, sweating and anxiety
  • Associated with labile hypertension (BP measures that fluctuate, abruptly and repeatedly from normal to high)
  • Most common in people aged 30-50
  • Most commonly found incidentally, except when the patient has known previous endocrine problems or diabetes, in which case CT is advised

Question: You are giving neuraxial analgesia for a patient in the 1st stage of labour. In order to do so you must not damage the spinal cord. Below which of the following vertebrae is injection safe?
Explanation:
The conus of the spinal cord lies at about L1-L2 vertebrae. Any higher than this and there is a risk you might pierce the spinal cord. 

S3 is also an incorrect answer. You cannot pierce the sacrum to reach the subarachnoid space. 

 

Spinal injections have minimal foetal transfer, better than IV/IM opiates. 

When performing a spinal injection, it is important to aspirate to ensure CSF is present. Important not to inject into vasculature. 

 

See case 8 on analgesia for more.

Question: Which of these drugs (used as anti-coagulation for CVA prophylaxis in patients with AF) is a direct thrombin inhibitor?
Explanation:
Dabigatran (correct answer), Rivaroxaban and Apixaban are DOACs (direct oral anti-coagulants), but Rivaroxaban and Apixaban are inhibitors of factor Xa.

Warfarin is an inhibitor of vitamin K epoxide reductase. 

 

Anti-arrhythmic drugs lecture Case 13

Question: Which of the following best meets the definition of vasculogenesis.
OptionA: De novo development of blood vessels from epithelial cells.
OptionB: Formation of new blood vessels from sprouting of new capillaries from pre-existing vessels (importance of so-called ‘angiogenic diseases’)
OptionC: De novo development of blood vessels occurs from endothelial cells differentiating in situ
Explanation:
Vasculogenesis: de novo development of blood vessels occurs from endothelial cells differentiating in situ

Angiogenesis: formation of new blood vessels from sprouting of new capillaries from pre-existing vessels (importance of so-called ‘angiogenic diseases’)

 

Case 8 lecture on heart embryology for more.

Question: You are given the ECG of a patient who has suffered an anterior myocardial infarction. You see ST elevation in leads V3 and V4. Which artery is most likely occluded in this patient?
Explanation:
Anterior MI shows ST elevation V3, V4. LAD occlusion.

Inferior MI II, III, aVF. RCA occlusion.

Lateral MI I, aVL, V5, V6. Left circumflex artery occlusion.

Question:
A 12 y/o patient is rushed into hospital after being in a traumatic car crash. He presents with severe pain in his tibia and loss of sensation in his left foot but with no obvious lacerations. You suspect that there is a potential left tibial fracture and request imaging immediately. 

 

However, the consultant neurosurgeon is worried that he has suffered from severe neurological injury as Tinel’s sign is present. You complete a full peripheral neurological examination and find that Tinel‘s sign is NOT advancing (i.e. it is stationary) in his left lower limb. You quickly tell the consultant neurosurgeon that the young boy requires surgery as if not, there will be no nerve recovery. According to the Sunderland Classification, what has happened to this boy’s nerve?
Explanation:
This is an example of axonotmesis (Class IV Sunderland Classification) because there are no obvious lacerations so the nerve has not been severed (which would indicate neurotmesis). 

 

Common causes of axonotmesis include motor vehicle accidents and displaced bone (both potential options if he has fractured his tibia!).

Surgery is required - nerve repair, graft or transfer.

Question: At which stage does inactivation of one X chromosome take place?
Explanation:
The inactivation of one X chromosome takes place during the blastocyst stage. 

All daughter cells have the same X inactivated. 

 

This is important in X linked lethal conditions such as incontnentia pigmenti where if the mutated NEMO gene is switched off, the individual is ok but if the normal X is switched off then you get the disease.

Question: Haemophilia B is caused by a lack of which clotting factor?
Explanation:
Haemophilia A = lack of factor 8

Haemophilia B = lack of factor 9

Haemophilia C = lack of factor 11

Question: What is an adult's recommended daily intake of salt?

A 38 year old, pregnant lady comes into the antenatal clinic for her checkup.  She tells you she is a bit worried as she was taking a lower dose than she should of folic acid. 

 

You look at some of her results;

  • hCG increased
  • UE3 decreased
  • AFP decreased
  • Inhibin A increased

What would the findings from the blood results suggest?
OptionC: that the foetus has an open neural tube defect
OptionD: that the foetus is at an increased risk of down's syndrome
OptionE: that the foetus is at an increased risk of an open neural tube defect
Explanation:
The foetus is at an increased risk of Down's syndrome but as these tests would be done as part of the screening program, we can't say that the foetus definitely has Down's syndrome. For this, diagnostic tests like chorionic villus sampling or amniocentesis would have to be carried out. 

 

I put the comment about folic acid in to bring in different aspects to the history--> folic acid does decrease the chance of getting a neural tube defect but doesn't mean that the foetus has that. 

 

By looking at the blood results, it is the down's syndrome risk that is the most appropriate answer

Question: Which chromosomal abnormality is caused by uniparental disomy of chromosome 11 (maternal)?
Explanation:
Maternal UPD Ch 11= Silver russell

Paternal UPD Ch 11= beckwith widemann

maternal deletion of 15q11-13 Angelman 

Paternal deletion of 15q11-13 PWS

Monosomy X- turner syndrome

 

* genetic conflict hypothesis- this is the hypothesis that states that if there is UPD of the maternal chromosome then the mother is trying to save her resources for the next foetus, leading to a small baby, with low sub cut fat (like in silver russell).If there is UPD of the paternal chromosome, the father is trying to maximise the resource for the foetus, leading to large baby (like in beckwith widemann)

Question: A 24 y/o male patient comes into your clinic complaining of lower back pain with stiffness that is worse in the morning and on rest. He frequently gets out of bed during the night to relieve the pain by walking around his bedroom. You complete a spinal examination and discover that he has reduced forward flexion (Schober’s Test). You prescribe NSAIDs and refer him to physiotherapy. What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
This is a typical presentation of Ankylosing Spondylitis 

  • Onset 20-30yrs (more commonly in males) 
  • Lower back pain with gradual onset 
  • Stiffness worse in the morning and at night and improves with exercise 
  • Reduced forward flexion (Schober’s test - i.e. 2 fingers on lumbar spine and ask the Px to touch their toes and your fingers should move apart in a normal, healthy spine).

NSAIDs are the 1st line treatment (sulphasalazine is only useful if there is peripheral joint involvement and research is on-going about whether anti-TNF therapies should be used earlier on in disease presentation).

 

On X-ray you would see a ”bamboo spine” appearance (as below):

Question:
An upset 16 y/o patient comes into your clinic demanding to know why she has got scoliosis. You explain to the young girl that there are many causes of scoliosis - it may be congenital, developmental, neuromuscular, tumour-associated or most commonly for young females it is idiopathic. She beleives that it is developmental as she had hip dysplasia at birth.

Thinking about the development of the spine, which process is most important for the organisation of the axial skeleton?
Explanation:
• Somitogenesis is the formation of whorls of concentric paraxial mesoderm which gives rise to somites. 
  • A SOMITE = a paired block of mesoderm arranged on either side of the neural tube which have unique positional values (specified by Hox Genes). 
  • Somites are critical for the organisation of the axial skeleton

Note: sclerotome > cartilage > bones of the axial skeleton (endochondral ossification)

Question:
A 40 year old woman, Mrs C, comes into your surgery for a consultation. At the end of the consultation, she mentions that she and her new partner have talked about having a baby, since they have both always wanted children. 

She asks about the possibility of Downs Syndrome if she were to get pregnant now. 

 

You explain to her that at 40, the average risk of having a child with Downs Syndrome is around 1 in 100. 

What would the risk increase to if she waited until she was 45 years old?
Explanation:
At 20: 1 in 1500

At 30: 1 in 900

At 40: 1 in 100

At 45: 1 in 30
Tags: Congenital malformations, case 7, Genetics, Pregnancy, embryology

Question: A 25 y/o patient has just undergone thyroid surgery due to multinodular goitres. However your patient is now presenting with muscle spasms, tetany and paraesthesia around the mouth and feet. What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
Hypoparathyroidism can be a complication of thyroid surgery due to injury of the parathyroid glands which lie in close proximity to the thyroid glands. This causes HYPOcalcaemia which is causing the symptoms of muscle spasms, tetany etc. 

Note: hypocalcaemia is the most common complication of thyroid surgery.

 

Other complications of thyroid surgery include:

  • Recurrent laranygeal nerve damage - leads to characteristic hoarse voice 
  • Infection 
  • Haematoma

Question:
45 y/o patient comes into your clinic complaining of a low mood, abdominal pain and pain when passing urine. You decide to take a FBC to see what is going on. The blood results show:

 

Ca                  Slightly high 

Phosphate     Normal 

Alkaline Phosphatase    Slightly high 

 

However annoyingly the printer has missed off the results for PTH!

From the symptoms and blood results above, would you expect PTH to be raised, normal or low?
Explanation:
This patient is suffering from primary hyperparathryoidism.

His symptoms are classically described as “bone, moans, groans and stones”

  • raised alkaline phosphatase = “bones” i.e. damage to bone as ALP is being released 
  • low mood = “moans”
  • abdominal pain = “groans”
  • and kidney “stones” - pain when passing urine. 

So, you would expect to see a raised PTH!

Question: A 14 y/o patient comes into your clinic with varus deformity of her lower limbs. She is diagnosed with cystic fibrosis and is worried that she may suffer from osteoporosis when she is older. What treatment do you give this patient as prophylaxis?
Explanation:
Oral D2/D3 is the correct answer as this patient has rickets (vitamin D deficiency before the growth plates have dissappeared). Rickets causes bones to be more pliable and softer.

 

It is also a secondary cause of osteopororis so left untreated this young girl has a high risk of developing osteoporosis with age. 

 

Cystic fibrosis is important in this case as it causes malabosption in the gut so will cause the vitamin D deficiency. 

 

This is what the child’s varus deformity would look like on an X-ray:

Question: Nancy, a 78-year old former crime author stumbles into A&E. She is worried that she may be having an upper heart attack. You reassure her that this is very unlikely and ask her what she is feeling. She says her heart is going ’19 to the dozen’ and she feels a fluttering in her chest. On examination she is hypertensive, 155/128, and she has type 2 diabetes and peripheral vascular disease. Based on this information and her ECG, what is the most appropriate management?
OptionA: Beta blocker, 24-hour blood pressure monitoring and suitable anticoagulant
OptionC: Beta blocker, alterations to blood pressure medication and suitable anticoagulant
OptionE: Reassurance and schedule a GP appointment for very soon
Explanation:
Following the NICE CKS guidelines for atrial fibrillation, Nancy should be given a rate control drug (beta-blocker). Given her PMH and the new AF diagnosis she is at an increased risk of clotting and so should also be placed on a suitable anticoagulant to reduce this risk.

 

In terms of the blood pressure, it is high and if this was a consistent reading then anti-hypertensive therapy should be reviewed, but given the situation it could just be due to stress so a longer term measurement would be useful before any alterations.
Tags: ECG, Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13, Heart

Question:
You observe a newborn baby who turns very blue while crying.

 

A history also confirms the mother does not have the rubella vaccine, is high risk for rubella and also has had a long term addiction to alcohol before and during the pregnancy.

 

Further to this you conduct examinations. This shows blood flow from both ventricles into the aorta, with a hole in the ventricular septum and some form of increased muscle density in the right ventricle. Other observations of the heart are unclear.

 

Regardless, these signs are highly likely of a rare condition you realised you had learnt back in case 8.

 

What is the most likely condition being presented in the newborn?
Explanation:
(A - correct) Tetralogy of fallot presents exclusively which allows blood to flow from both ventricles into the aorta, along with a hole in the ventricular septum. The other two abnormalities also present that would make it tetralogy of fallot would be pulmonary stenosis and right ventricular hypertrophy. However, enough information was provided to rule out the other conditions.

 

(B -wrong) - Possible blue baby, but blood would not flow into aorta from both ventricles

(C -wrong) - During left ventricular contraction, the right ventricle would not contribute blood into the aorta.

(D -wrong) - This could be right, but there would be no hypertrophy or right ventricle.

(E -wrong) - Foramen ovale is present in the atrium - would not affect aorta.

Question:
35 year old Connie Long was diagnosed with Crohn's Disease at 26. She presents at A+E tachycardia with a nose bleed for an hour an a half.

 

Blood tests show low red blood cells, white blood cells and platelets.

 

You suspect aplastic anaemia, which Crohn's medication is likely to have caused this?
Explanation:
Azathioprine- Immunomodulator, second line therapy if patient is steroid dependent. Slow onset effect (two to three months). Side effects: Bone marrow suppression, nausea and vomiting and pancreatitis.

Budesonide- Corticeroid therapy for mild to moderate ileal disease

Hydrocortisone- IV 100mg given 6hourly until desired result. In-patient treatment of severe disease

Prednisolone- Severe disease or non-ileal Crohn's

Sulfasalazine- First line treatment, initiates remission in mild to moderate disease. Sulfapyridine component potentially hepatotoxic.

Question: You are reviewing the drugs of a patient at your practice. The patient is hypertensive with a blood pressure of 160/100mmHg and has diastolic heart failure. You started the patient with ramipril in order to reduce the hypertension. ' I can't take those pills Doc, they gave me a terrible cough'. You decide to switch them to candesartan. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of action of candesartan?
OptionA: Calcium channel blocker. Negative iontropic and chronotropic impacts on the heart.
OptionB: Angiotension converting enzyme inhibitor. Preventing the action of angiotensin 2.
OptionC: Angiotensin 2 receptor blocker, blocking AT1R shifting angiotensin binding to AT2R
Explanation:
Candesartan acts by blocking AT1R receptors for angiotensin 2. This causes angiotensin 2 to bind to AT2R receptors. 

 

AT1R effects on the body:

Dipsogenic response (thirst)
Vasoconstriction (direct and via NorAd/sympathetic NS)
(Longterm) ventricular hypertrophy
Aldosterone secretion (Na+ uptake)
GFR maintenance
ADH secretion from posterior pituitary

 

Active AT2R receptors cause opposing effects to those of AT1R receptors.

 

ARBs tend to end with sartan at the end of their name. Typical examples include:

Azilsartan 
Candesartan 
Eprosartan.
Irbesartan 
Losartan 
Olmesartan 
Telmisartan
Valsartan
Tags: Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13, Case 15, Pharmacology

Question: It is understood that blood groups A and B are co-dominant, as a medical student Susan is well aware of this and knows that she is AB+. Her friend Brian is in hospital and needs an urgent Red blood cell transfusion. Given that his mother is O- what is the probability that Susan can donate blood to be used by her friend?
Explanation:
People with AB+ blood can only donate to other people who are AB+.

 

A and B are co dominant, so for an offspring to be AB blood type, their parents have to be A and B respectively. Given that Brian's mother is O- we know that he cannot be AB+ and therefore can't receive blood from his friend Susan.
Tags: Blood transfusion, Data interpretation, case 8, Haematology

Question: BNP and ANP are released in response to overfilling of the ventricles. In heart failure, ANP and BNP act to increase GFR and to cause vasodilation, this lowers blood pressure. When diagnosing heart failure, we can measure serum concentrations of ANP and BNP as a clinical marker. Which of the following drugs acts to prevent the breakdown of ANP and BNP?
Explanation:
SACUBITRIL is a drug used in combination with valsartan to treat cardiac failure. VALSARTAN blocks angiotensin-II receptors, SACUBITRIL acts as a neprilysin inhibitor that stops breakdown of BNP and ANP. 

 

See Dr Coffee's lecture case 15

Question: An 18 year old A level student comes into your practice with severe anxiety for his upcoming examinations. He complains that he hasn't slept for days, vomits before each exam and can barely hold his pen to write his name on the paper. He asks about any short term medication he could use to help him calm down through the 3 week examination period. You suggest a class of drugs called benzodiazepines. Which of the following best describes their mechanism of action?
Explanation:
Benzodiazepine works by selectively facilitating GABAa receptors. GABA is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain.

 

Benzodiazepine is not good for long term anxiety such as in GAD, it acts rapidly on the brain to sedate the patient. However, this rapid action makes it very addictive. Best used to treat an acute case of anxiety over a short period of time. 

 

Anxiolytic, sedative, muscle relaxant, anti-convulsant. 

 

Must be recorded when conducting ECT as it raises seizure threshold.

Question: Which of the following dopamine pathways is associated with the positive symptoms of psychosis.
Explanation:
There are 4 dopamine pathways:

 

The mesolimbic. Increased levels of dopamine in this pathway are responsible for the positive symptoms of psychosis

The mesocortical. Associated with the negative symptoms of psychosis

Nigrostriatal. Involved in motor control, insufficient dopamine in this pathway sees Parkinsonian symptoms such as Tardive dyskinesia 

Tuberoinfundibular pathway. Dopamine released at this site regulates the secretion of prolactin from the anterior pituitary gland.

 

See case 12 lecture on neurophysiology for more.

Question: You are on a psychiatric placement block where you are sitting in with a patient with schizophrenia and a consultant. Patient has had an acute exacerbation of the positive symptoms of schizophrenia. She has been treat with clozapine in the past, but has a history of agranulocytosis. The consultant decides to prescribe Risperidone. One week later, the patient complains that they are lactating. Which explanation best fits this?
OptionA: Risperidone stimulates the production of oestrogen from the ovaries.
OptionC: Decreased dopamine levels in the Tuberoinfundibular pathway leads to hyperprolactinemia
OptionD: Decreased dopamine levels in the mesolimbic pathway causes hyperprolactinemia
OptionE: Decreased levels of dopamine in the nigrostriatal pathway cause hyperprolactinemia.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. Decreased dopamine levels in the Tuberoinfundibular pathway leads to hyperprolactinemia. 

 

Risperidone is an atypical anti psychotic. Its mechanism of action is unknown, however it is suspected to decrease dopamine and serotonin levels. By reducing excessive dopamine levels in the mesolimbic system, you decrease positive symptoms of schizophrenia. However, dopamine as negatively feeds back on prolactin in the tuberoinfundibular pathway, this causes hyperprolactinemia. Prolactin stimulates the epithelial cells of the alveoli of the breast to produce milk, hence lactation. 

 

For more see the neurophysiology lecture from case 12.

Question: Iron is contained mainly within haemoglobin. Excess iron is stored as ferritin in the liver and where else?
OptionA: no where- ferritin is the only iron store
Explanation: iron is stored as ferritin and haemosiderin.

Question:
Mrs James is a 60 year old woman who is visiting her GP for a routine check up. It is the first time she has visited the GP in over 30 years because she has an irrational fear of doctors. All of her results come back as normal, other than a high blood pressure reading of 141/90mmHg.

 

What should the GP do next?
OptionA: Explain various life-modifiable factors to reduce blood pressure, e.g. losing weight or taking salt out of the diet.
OptionB: Give Mrs James a non-invasive intermittent blood pressure (NIBP) monitor.
OptionC: Order blood tests to investigate possible causes of secondary hypertension.
OptionE: Prescribe a calcium channel blocker such as Nifedipine.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

Mrs James has an irrational fear of doctors, and therefore may be suffering from 'white coat syndrome', which could be the cause of her raised BP. A NIBP monitor will measure her blood pressure every hour for 24 hours and so can give an average blood pressure.

 

If her average blood pressure is still high then the GP can consider the other management options such as those listed above.

 

Note: If Mrs James was to be prescribed an anti-hypertensive drug she would initially be prescribed a calcium channel blocker or a diuretic rather than Ramipril, because she is over 55.

Question:
A 56 y/o patient comes into your clinic complaining of a constant, dull pain at the top of her thigh, near to her hip joint. You notice that she is also very out of breath and her heart rate is 110bpm.

Her blood results indicate: 

 

Calcium - normal

Phosphate - normal 

ALP - high

PTH - normal 

 

What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
Correct answer is Paget's Disease

Blood results and symptoms point towards Paget's disease 

 

Symptoms of Paget's Diease include: 

  • Bone pain which is deep, dull and constant - also worse on weight bearing 
  • Pathological frature 
  • Sarcomatous changes 
  • A high CO - so tachycardia, tachypnoea 
  • Compression effects depending on the site 

Most common site of Paget's disease - proximal femur

Question:
72 year old Gina Atlas attends the GP surgery with her daughter. Gina takes L-DOPA to treat her Parkinson's disease. Her daughter says that Gina is not herself anymore. She has been looking online and has found that dietary tyrosine supplements can increase dopamine levels in the blood. She'd much rather that her mother took these supplements instead of the nasty medication she's currently on.

 

Explain to the daughter why tyrosine supplement are not suitable.
OptionA: Drug manufacturers selling supplements online are not as strongly regulated as drugs prescribed by doctors
OptionB: Tyrosine is hepatotoxic if consumed at high dosages
OptionC: Tyrosine is involved in the serotonin pathway, not the catecholamine pathway and so would not effect dopamine levels
OptionD: Tyrosine is actively transported across the blood brain barrier, the transporters are already saturated by normal daily intake of tyrosine
OptionE: Tyrosine delivered by supplements cannot be converted to L-DOPA by the tyrosine hydroxylase enzyme
Explanation:
Tyrosine is actively transported across the blood brain barrier (BBB), which is fully saturated with typical daily intake. This is part of the rate limiting step of this pathway. (Note: It is also the reason why we have to treat Parksinson’s disease with L-DOPA rather than tyrosine supplements, to avoid this step.)


In the brain, tyrosine, at the 3 position, is hydroxylated by tyrosine hydroxylase (TH) which requires Fe2+, a molecular oxygen and a hydrogen donor (tetrahydrobiopterin) to form Levodopa (L-DOPA).

Question: Which of these currents do not respond to Ca concentration or sympathetic stimulation
Explanation:
Jeff's lecture

ICaT - inwardly rectifying Cav3 channels. They activate at more negative potentials, rapidly inactivate and are not influenced by Ca concentration or sympathetic stimulation

Question: You are on an A and E placement when a patient presents with a catastrophic haemorrhage. After loosing 500ml of blood, the patient is now hypotensive. What are the cells responsible for detecting a change in Na+ concentration which can be used as a measure for blood pressure?
Explanation:
The macula densa cells are responsible for detecting a drop in blood pressure. They are located in the distal convoluted tubule. Lower blood pressure results in lower glomerular filtration rate. This results in a lower concentrations of Na+ ions as they are reabsorbed due to slower filtration rate. 

 

Once detected, the macula densa cells produce prostaglandins which signal to the Juxtaglomerular cells to produce Renin.

Question: Which of these GI infections is associated with osteomyelitis, arterial aneurysm and meningitis in neonates?
which of these GI infections causes constipation, a cough and a stepwise fever

Miss H is an 18-year-old female who presents at her GP appointment practically giddy. She tells you she's very pleased to be coming to the GP today, but is not so happy about the fact she's putting on lots of weight and is hungry all the time. She also complains that she constantly sleeps through her alarms and misses things, and her legs have been feeling really heavy. What's the most likely diagnosis from these symptoms?

Question: Which section of the mental health act allows a single doctor to detain a patient for 72 hours in an emergency situation?
Explanation:
Section 2 = can be kept in hospital for up to 28 days

Section 3 = can be kept in for up to 6 months

Section 4 = emergency detention which only 1 doctor has to approve, for 72hrs. Used when finding another doc would be too much of a delay

Section 5.2 = doc’s holding power – can keep in hospital for 72hrs if there's a written report on why the patient should be detained. An AMHP (approved mental health professional) should then assess this ASAP to see it Pt should be detained under sec 2 or 3

Section 5.4 = nurses holding power – up to 6 hrs

Question: A patient presents with a large swollen calf having been hit by a car. They are taking warfarin as part of a pharmacological regime for atrial fibrillation. The patient describes being in a huge amount of pain, with altered sensation in their leg. You try to palpate a pulse distal to the site unsuccessfully. You diagnose the patient with acute  compartment  syndrome and immediately act by doing the following:
OptionC: Prescribe loop diuretics to reduce circulating volume
OptionD: Offer continuous doses of morphine until pain has gone.
OptionE: Tourniquet proximal to the site in question.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B, a fasciotomy is required in order to release the intracompartmental pressure. This prevents ischaemia to the structures within the compartment. 

 

Although pain relief would be suitable, we must first abide by the pain pyramid of gradually increasing the potency of the analgesic. Just giving morphine would not resolve the issue. 

 

A tourniquet would cause ischaemia. Ultimately might lead to full amputation.

Question: You are reviewing the ECG of a patient with Wolf-Parkinson White syndrome. The patient asks you how this arrhythmia comes about. Which of the following explains the pathology behind this arrhythmia?
Explanation:
This is an example of an atrioventricular re-entrant tachycardia. Specifically, this is a supraventricular tachycardia as it occurs above the ventricles. Wolf-Parkinson White syndrome occurs due to an anatomical variant in the hearts conductive tissue called the Bundle of Kent. This Bundle of Kent results in the formation of an anatomical re-entrant circuit. 

 

An AVNRT is a atrioventricular nodal re-entrant tachycardia, this is caused by an issue within or around the AV node. 

 

LBBB occurs when the right atrium depolarises before the left. 

 

Third degree heart block occurs when there is no communication between the electrical signalling between the SAN and the AV node.

 

Atrial fibrillation occurs when the atrial tissue has multiple sites of excitation. Causes the atria to fibrillate and not contract in unison.

Question: You are treating a patient with with Wolf Parkinson White syndrome with Amiodarone. This is a Vaughan-Williams class 3 drug. Which of the following describes the mechanism of action of such drugs?
Explanation:
Nigel Better Kill Carol

Na+ Beta K+ Ca2+ 

 

Class I agents are divided into three groups (Ia, Ib, and Ic) based upon their effect on the length of the action potential.

 

Ia lengthens the action potential (right shift)
Ib shortens the action potential (left shift)
Ic does not significantly affect the action potential (no shift)

 

Class II agents are conventional beta blockers. They act by blocking the effects of catecholamines at the β1-adrenergic receptors, thereby decreasing sympathetic activity on the heart. These agents are particularly useful in the treatment of supraventricular tachycardias. They decrease conduction through the AV node.

 

Class II agents include atenolol, esmolol, propranolol, and metoprolol.

 

Class III agents predominantly block the potassium channels, thereby prolonging repolarization. Since these agents do not affect the sodium channel, conduction velocity is not decreased. The prolongation of the action potential duration and refractory period, combined with the maintenance of normal conduction velocity, prevent re-entrant arrhythmias. (The re-entrant rhythm is less likely to interact with tissue that has become refractory). The class III agents exhibit reverse-use dependence (their potency increases with slower heart rates, and therefore improves maintenance of sinus rhythm). Inhibiting potassium channels, slowing repolarization, results in slowed atrial-ventricular myocyte repolarization. Class III agents have the potential to prolong the QT interval of the EKG, and may be proarrhythmic (more associated with development of polymorphic VT).

 

Class III agents include: bretylium, amiodarone, ibutilide, sotalol, dofetilide, vernakalant and dronedarone.

 

Class IV agents


Class IV agents are slow non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers. They decrease conduction through the AV node, and shorten phase two (the plateau) of the cardiac action potential. They thus reduce the contractility of the heart, so may be inappropriate in heart failure. However, in contrast to beta blockers, they allow the body to retain adrenergic control of heart rate and contractility.

 

Class IV agents include verapamil and diltiazem.

Question: You are treating a patient with atrial fibrillation, you decide to put them on anti-coagulation therapy after reviewing their CHA2DS2VASc score. You prescribe Heparin. Which of the following describes the mechanism of action of heparin.
