Question:
Astrocytes are a type of neuroglia responsible for a whole host of functions in the CNS. They lie in between blood vessels and the anterior environment of the brain. A pair of astrocytes are coupled by ~200 gap junctions. 

 

You're doing some revision of cells in the CNS, and start to remember that astrocytes are usually a certain shape. Which one of these songs off my secondary school SpotifyTM playlist best describes the shape of astrocytes?
Explanation:
Yes it's another question tenuously linking revision to my spotify playlists. Sorry about it.

 

Case 6 lecture on CNS cells and synaptic transmission.

 

Astrocytes
• Astrocytes in between blood vessel and anterior environment of the brain
• Star-shaped, interconnected neuroglial cells that can be visualised with antibodies to GFAP (glial fibrillary acidic protein)
• Calcium ions regulate almost all intracellular processes (but not AP’s)
• Intracellular Ca2+ concentration must be kept low
• Intracellular Ca2+ waves provide long distance communication within astrocyte networks. Main signal for NT to be released from vesicles

Question: Neuroglial cells have a wide variety of functions, and can also be involved in a number of pathologies. Which of the neuroglial cell types can have a role in epilepsy?
Explanation:
Case 6 lecture on CNS and synaptic transmission. 

 

Astrocytes

Roles in disease/pathology:
- Astrocytomas
- Astrogliosis (isolation of damaged area, rebuilding blood-brain barrier, rebuilding new circuitry)
- Epilepsy

Astrocytes directly take up K+ from extracellular space by K+ pumps.

Redistribute K+ within the glial syncitium for subsequent discharge into the extracellular/perivascular space (elevated K+ leads to dyshomeostasis as seen in epilepsy)

Question: What is the most common extra-colonic manifestation of inflammatory bowel disease?

Question:
A 45 year old colour-blind man comes home to be surprised by his wife, who tells him she is pregnant. Delighted to hear this, he vows to accompany her to each and every appointment. At his wife's mid-trimester scan, the doctor tells them they are going to have a baby boy. The man breaks down crying, upset that he may be responsible for their child being red-green colour blind, just as he is and be put off following in his steps as a painter.

 

What should the doctor tell the man?
OptionA: Reassure the man that his son will be fine, colour blind or not.
OptionB: Ask the wife if she is a carrier, to determine the likelihood of their son being colour blind too
OptionC: Assure the parents and tell them to worry about this later down the line, as it is not until age 5 that both colour vision and the ability to name colours is fully developed
OptionD: Tell the painter that he doesn't need to worry as there is no chance his son will inherit his colour-blindness from him
OptionE: Explain to the patient that colour-blindness is a polygenetic condition and whether his child has colour blindness depends on a combination of alleles from both him and his wife
Explanation:
Red-green colour blindness is an X-linked recessive condition. The painter and his wife are going to have a boy which means that even though the father is colour blind, the child cannot inherit colour blindness from his father.

 

Remember: All daughters of affected men are carriers and all sons are unaffected as the gene is carried on the X chromosome.

Question:
On placement you meet Mr Gary who has has presented with hypertension and hypokalaemia.

 

His arterial blood gas results are:

  • pH: 7.47 (7.35 – 7.45)
  • PaCO2: 5.0kPa (4.7-6.0 kPa)
  • PaO2: 12 kPa (11-13 kPa)
  • HCO3-: 28 (22-26 mEg/L)
  • Base excess: +3 (-2 to +2 mmol/L)

What condition does he most likely have?
Explanation:
• Conn's Syndrome is an adenoma (tumour) secreting aldosterone
  • Aldosterone is secreted in the adrenal gland in response renin
  • It binds to receptors in the DCT
  • This causes Na+ reabsorption and K+ excretion via the Na+/K+ pump
  • The increases Na+ in the blood causes water to be drawn in by osmosis which causes hypertension
  • The K+ loss causes hypokalaemia
  • As written in the acid-base lecture, K+ loss stimulates H+ loss, leading to a pH rise and therefore metabolic alkalosis

Question: Gilly is a 24 year old female who has come to the GP complaining of hearing loss. She tells you that unfortunately, she can still hear the high pitched cries of seagulls outside her room at 4am, but has lost hearing at lower frequencies. She says it's mostly in her left ear. You ask about her general heath and she tells you she has recently recovered from a nasty bout of flu, and is 12 weeks pregnant. What is the most likely diagnosis?
OptionA: Conductive hearing loss in her Left ear
OptionB: Sensorineural hearing loss in her Left ear
Explanation:
Otosclerosis is a disease which causes conductive hearing loss, starting in 1 ear but eventually affecting both.

Low-frequency hearing is lost first; high-frequency is later on so this is opposite to Presbycusis.

There are genetic susceptibilities, if inherited a virus or other trigger e.g. pregnancy, will set off the disease pathway.

Typically, it’s young women affected, but can be anyone.

The actual mechanism of damage involves 2 bits:

  • Fixation of the Stapes to the oval window of the cochlea, which impairs transmission of sound into the inner ear – ‘ossicular coupling’
  • Sclerosis of the round window, which impairs sound movement through the inner ear – ‘acoustic coupling’

Question: Conventional dendritic cells (cDC) are the only cells which can activate naive T cells. They do this by binding a receptor on their surface to the CD28 receptor on the T cell. What is the name of this receptor on the cDC surface?
Explanation:
Activation of a naive T cell occurs when two receptors are bound:

  • T cell receptor (TCR) binds to MHC/peptide complex 
  • CD28 (receptor on T cell) binds to B7 (on cDC) 

CCR7 (increased by TLR activation in cDCs) produces a chemotactic trail for cDCs to follow to the draining lymph node. 

CD40 (B cell) binds to CD40L (T cell) to allow the B cell to undergo class switching and somatic hypermutation (helped from T cell).

Question: Clostridium difficile infection classically effects the elderly, hospitalised patients and patients taking antibiotics. Which of these phrases best describes Clostridium difficile?
Explanation:
C. diff is a part of the commensal flora which becomes pathogenic in the absence of competition. It is spore-forming and the spores persist. The disease is toxin-mediated and classically affects the large bowel. It is spread by the faecal-oral route. 

 

C is the description for Campylobacter (Salmonella, Shigella, Vibrio Cholerae and E. coli are also gram-negative rods though) 

 

D is the description for Norovirus.

Question: Metabolic acidosis is caused by an accumulation of non-volatile acid in the body. Which of these conditions could lead to an increased anion gap metabolic acidosis?
Explanation:
The anion gap is made up of negatively charged proteins that aren't bicarbonate and chloride. It is the difference between the anions (bicarbonate and chloride) and cations (sodium and potassium). 

 

Lactic acidosis is the only example of increased anion gap:

  • Accumulation of organic acid 
  • Bicarbonate levels reduce to buffer the increasing levels of acid 
  • There is no change to chloride levels 
  • This means anion gap has to increase to balance the charge difference between anions and cations 

The other options are all examples of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis. In normal anion gap, bicarbonate reduces and chloride increases, so the anion gap stays the same:

  • Diarrhoea causes loss of bicarbonate (chloride increases because exchanged for bicarbonate)
  • Ingestion of hydrochloric acid causes increased chloride 
  • Reduced acid secretion causes build-up of H+ (bicarbonate acts as a buffer so levels reduce) - this is often due to defective H+ ATPase pump 
  • Reduced bicarbonate reabsorption causes bicarbonate loss

Question:
A patient comes into A+E with abdominal cramps, diarrhoea, and a high fever. After taking a history, you find out they have been clindamycin for the past 3 weeks for a skin infection. Results from FBC show high white blood cell count.

 

You suspect that the patient's symptoms may be caused by an anaerobic gram positive bacteria. What is the name of this bacteria?
Explanation:
Clostridium difficile infection commonly occurs when gut flora has been destroyed by antibiotics. Clindamycin is one of the most likely antibiotics to cause destruction of gut flora. 

 

Campylobacter, salmonella, E.coli, and shigella all cause cramps and diarrhoea, but they are all gram positive bacteria, not gram negative.

Question: You are reviewing a 55 year old diabetic patient. He is in stage 5 chronic kidney disease and is beginning preparation to undergo peritoneal dialysis. The patient complains of being tired and confused and has noticed that he has been having palpitations recently. You decide to conduct and ECG and observe tall peaked T waves. Which of the following electrolyte abnormalities is generally associated with tall peaked T waves?
Explanation:
Tall peaked T waves are associated with hyperkalemia. Potassium is vital for regulating the normal electrical activity of the heart.
Increased extracellular potassium reduces myocardial excitability, with depression of both pacemaking and conducting tissues.


Progressively worsening hyperkalaemia leads to suppression of impulse generation by the SA node and reduced conduction by the AV node and His-Purkinje system, resulting in bradycardia and conduction blocks and ultimately cardiac arrest.

 

Hypercalcaemia. The main ECG abnormality seen with hypercalcaemia is shortening of the QT interval
In severe hypercalcaemia, Osborn waves (J waves) may be seen
Ventricular irritability and VF arrest has been reported with extreme hypercalcaemia

 

 

Hypokalemia Potassium is vital for regulating the normal electrical activity of the heart
Decreased extracellular potassium causes myocardial hyperexcitability with the potential to develop re-entrant arrhythmias. 

Increased amplitude and width of the PR interval, flattening/ inverting of T waves. ST depression

 

 

Hyponatraemia Non ischaemic ST elevation.

Question:
A self administered cognitive screening test called TYM is being trialled for identifying patients who may need assessment for Alzheimer’s disease.

 

In the study, researchers perform the screening test on all patients enrolled, and then identify disease against a "gold standard test". Disease presence was determined using Addenbrooke’s cognitive exam and the Mini Mental Score.

 

A hypothetical table of results is provided:

 

What is the specificity of the TYM screening test?
Explanation:
D) 97.0% is correct.

 

Specificity is the ability of the screening test to correctly identify negatives i.e. patients without Alzheimer's disease.

 

In this case, that is 97 patients out of the 100 participants without disease. 97/100 = 97.0%

 

 

A) is the NPV/PV- Negative prediction value i.e. the probability that a patient with a negative result doesn't have disease (97 correctly identified negatives) / (the 104 negatives)

 

B) isn't even calculated - just the number of correctly identified positives with a percentage stuck on the end

 

C) is sensitivity (87 correctly identified with positives)/(94 total positives that could have been identified)

 

E) is the percentage of patients in the study with negative screen results
Tags: Data interpretation, Case 14, case 6 revision, EBM

Question:
You're a 2nd year medical student attending a placement with the health visitor when you go on a home visit to couple in their late 20's in order to assess the development of their son Isaac. 

 

On arrival you see him crawling around his play mat on his hands of knees with dad near by. Isaac looks at as you walk in but you sense he is anxious at your presence.  When his mum calls his name, he turns to look, but just babbles in response.

When playing with some building blocks on his play mat, you notice he can hold them in the palm of his hand and throw them. 

 

In discussion with the health visitor, you over hear mum mention that Isaac can pull to stand with support.

 

How old is Isaac?

You are a second year medical student on placement in a GP surgery.

Question:
Glpitins are a class of drugs that can be given to diabetics to increase insulin release.

 

Gliptins are DDP 4 inhibitors. GLP-1 is a powerful peptide that that acts to increase insulin release. DDP4's act to inhibit GLP-1 in order to reduce insulin secretion after the carbohydrate containing food has been broken down in order to turn off insulin release. 

 

DDP-4 inhibitors provide a double negative and so prevent the inhibition of GLP1 and so insulin continues to be produced. 

 

Which of the following drugs belongs to the class of gliptins?
Explanation:
Metformin - belongs to the biguanides

Exenatide - belongs to the GLP1 receptor agonists (incretin mimetics)

Pioglitazone - thiazolidinedione 

Saxagliptin - correct. DDP4 inhibitor (Gliptin)

gliclazide - sulphonylureas

Question:
A 16 year-old girl has come into your GP practice with weight loss, bloating and abdominal pain.

On examination, you see she has dermatitis herpetiformis. 

 

You believe she has coeliacs disease.

 

What test/investigation would most likely confirm your diagnosis?
Explanation:
Anti-tTG (anti-transglutaminase) has a sensitivity of 98% and 95% specificity so is the best test for coeliacs disease. Anti-gliadin antibodies are also found in wheat intolerances, however, anti-tTG is more sensitive and specific, and is therefore the best answer.

 

Dermatitis herpetiformis is an itchy rash that 1 in 5 coeliacs get.

 

Faecal calprotectin is the test for IBD - ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease

Anti-TPO is the test for Hashimoto's thyroiditis - it stops the conversion of T4 to T3 resulting in hypothyroidism.

Question:
While shadowing a consultant paediatrician at St David's Children's Hospital, you meet Dylan, a seven year old boy, and his mother Judy. Judy explains that Dylan has come in for a regular check up and review of his medication. One of the tests carried out is a blood pressure check.

The consultant mentions that Dylan was born with a condition known as Liddles Syndrome. What is the main abnormality caused by this condition?
OptionA: Increased secretion of ADH from the Posterior Pituitary Gland, leading to an increase in blood volume
OptionB: Chronically increased levels of Angiotensin Converting Enzyme in the Liver
OptionC: Increased expression of sodium channels on the collecting duct apical membrane
OptionD: Increased smooth muscle sensitivity to adrenaline/NA at the adrenoceptors
OptionE: Reduction in the production of hypothalamic Natriuretic Peptide
Explanation:
Liddles Syndrome is a rare inherited cause of essential/primary hypertension. The condition is classified by elevated BP from early life (hence the link to Dylan's young age) due to the increased number of sodium channels expressed on the apical membrane of the collecting duct.

 

This increase in sodium channels allows more Na+ to move from the filtrate (i.e. urine) into the tubule cell and eventually back into the blood. By osmosis, the water will follow the Na+, leading to an increase in blood volume.

 

Although all of these options above would potentially cause an increase in BP, C is the correct answer.

 

(Information taken from Dr Johnson's Lecture - Case 15)

OptionA: All individuals belong to one of a number of classes/categories of personality

D - Psychodynamic Theories

Question:
Bernie is a 74-year-old man in heart failure who has been prescribed a medication at a dose so it can act as an anti-arrhythmic to extinguish the atrial fibrillation he is currently experiencing. 

The drug is able to cross the blood-brain-barrier and inhibit the Na+/K+-ATPase in regulatory neurones of the brainstem cardiac centre in order to increase vagal activity to the AVN of the heart and so extinguish the arrhythmic electrical current. 

Which of the following drugs has Bernie been prescribed?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.  

 

In heart failure, digoxin can be used as an anti-arrythmic to treat AF or atrial flutter, or as a positive inotrope, depending on the dose prescribed. 

It can work as an anti-arrhythmic via the mechanism described above. This leads to an increase in the refractory-characteristic of the AVN in order to return the heart to sinus rhythm. 

 

Valsartan is an angiotensin II receptor blocker. 

Adenosine can be used as an anti-arrhythmic to manage supra-ventricular tachycardias by binding to A1 receptors in cardiac tissue. 

Bisoprolol is a beta-1 adrenoceptor blocker used as a negative chronotrope and negative inotrope in heart failure.

Bretylium is an anti-arrythmic used to treat life-threatening ventricular tachycardia and fibrillation - it works as a K+-channel blocker and also inhibits the release of noradrenaline from nerve terminals.

Question: You are an F1 on a haematology ward. A patient with Hodgkin's disease required a blood transfusion of RBCs. Which of the following additional special considerations must be implemented before the patient receives the RBCs?
OptionC: Must not be left out the fridge for longer than 4 hours
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. 

 

Although all other answers are correct as well, these are not special considerations for patients with Hodgkin's disease. These are standard practice for RBC. 

 

RBCs are taken from whole blood donations with the plasma and platelets removed. 

They must be stored at 4 degrees C to prevent bacterial growth and to reduce basal metabolic rate of cells within the solution. 

Donations have a shelf life of 35 days and must be used within 4 hours of leaving the fridge. 

 

Case 8 Blood Grouping system lecture.

Question: What is the recommended treatment for an accelerated idioventricular rhythm?
Explanation:
An accelerated idioventricular rhythm has a ventricular focus with an intrinsic frequency of discharge faster than that seen in complete heart block, associated with acute MI. It is benign, and should not be treated.

 

ECG findings include a wide QRS complex and abnormal T waves.
Tags: ECG, Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13, Case 4

Question: You are giving a patient who is A+, type B+ blood. Since the patient is A+ this means that they will produce anti-B antibodies. Hence the patient rejects this blood transfusion. Which of the following antibody types is produced against the B+ donor blood?
Explanation:
IgM anti B antibodies are produced against the donor blood. IgM antibodies are pentamers. These are the first antibodies produced when exposure to antigen occurs. 

 

Anti-A and anti-B antibodies (called Isohaemagglutinins), which are not present in the newborn, appear in the first years of life. It is possible that food and environmental antigens (bacterial, viral or plant antigens) have epitopes similar enough to A and B glycoprotein antigens. The antibodies created against these environmental antigens in the first years of life can cross react with ABO-incompatible red blood cells when it comes in contact with during blood transfusion later in life. Anti-A and anti-B antibodies are usually IgM type. O-type individuals can produce IgG-type ABO antibodies.

You are working in the radiology department when you receive the following CT scan:

https://images.radiopaedia.org/images/11322330/87b48b2537817b5cde16405deba36a.jpg

 

Which of the following best describes the type of herniation seen on this scan?

Central herniation occurs when the brain herniates through the tentorial cerebelli downwards.

Uncal herniation occurs when the brain moves towards to the tentorium and often compresses the midbrain. 

Cerebellar tonsilar herniation occurs when the cerebellum herniates through foramen magnum.

Cerebellar transtentorial herniation occurs when the cerebellum herniates through the tentorium.

Question: A patient presents with upper back pain and an asymmetrical neck line. On inspection there is loss of muscle mass around the shoulders and their left shoulder is drooping. You note that the patient had a cervical lymph node biopsy taken a couple of weeks prior. You ask the patient to shrug their shoulders but they are unable to do so. You suspect the patient has some muscle paralysis due to damage to a particular nerve. What nerve is this most likely to be?
Explanation:
The patient most likely has Trapezius muscle paralysis (and sternoclamastoid muscle paralysis) which would explain the patient's signs and symptoms. These muscles are innervated by the accessory nerve. Therefore A is the right answer.

The classic sign is an inability to shrug their shoulders. The most likely cause of this nerve damage is due to medical procedures which the patient had been through.

Dorsal Scapula Nerve = Rhomboids / Levator Scapulae 
Long Thoracic Nerve = Serratus Anterior 
Suprascapular Nerve = Supraspinatus 
Thoracodorsal Nerve = Latissimus Dorsi

Question: You are treating a patient with Liver failure who is unable to produce any clotting factors. You give the patient fresh frozen plasma which contains clotting factors. This is an emergency situation and you haven't got sufficient time to ascertain the blood group of the patient. Which of the following plasma transfusions is safe to give to the patient?
Explanation:
When giving RBCs we must remember that the plasma has been removed. As such the anti-bodies against other ABO blood groups are not present. Hence when giving RBCs we must consider how the donor RBCs will react to the antibodies present in the recipient blood. If an individual is AB, this makes them a universal recipient since they produce no antibodies against either A or B blood.

 

When giving fresh frozen plasma however, the reverse is true. Since AB plasma contains no anti A or anti B antibodies, they are the universal donor.

Question: What is the mechanism of action of Metformin?
OptionA: INSIDE BETA CELL -Binds to receptor on potassium channel, blocking it, causing accumulation of potassium inside the cell. This causes influx of Ca2+, causing release of insulin.
OptionB: Increases AMP-dependant protein kinase which in turn decreases hepatic gluconeogenesis, increases insulin sensitivity and increases GLUT-4 activity.
OptionC: Inhibitor of DDP4, so GLP-1 activity it extended (not broken down by DDP4), causing increased insulin secretion.
OptionD: Activates the GLP-1 receptor which enhances insulin secretion from beta cells
OptionE: Complexes with PPAR-gamma, which upregulates adipocyte gene transcription
Explanation:
A - Sulfonylurea e.g. gliclazide or glibenclamide. This has a big ADR of weight gain. It is also able to cause hypoglycaemia.

B - correct. Biguanide is the class name for metformin. This has a big ADR of lactic acidosis, as it forces tissues to pick up lots ogf glucose. This can cause metabolic acidosis.

C-Glliptins e.g. Saxagliptin. This can causes dyspepsia, fatigue and headache

D - INCRETIN mimetic e.g. exanatide. 

E - Thiazolidedione .e.g pioglitazone. These have a big ADR of increasing the risk of bladder cancer

Question: What is the mechanism of action of saxagliptin?
OptionA: Drug binds to sulfonylurea receptor on K+ ATP channel, blocking K+ efflux. B-cell depolarises causing Ca++ influx which triggers IP3 mediated insulin release.
OptionB: Inhibitor of DPP-IV. This normally rapidly degrades GLP-1 (incretin) so if DPP-IV is inhibited, GLP-1 has longer effect on insulin secretion.
OptionC: Activates the GLP-1 receptor. Enhances insulin secretion from Beta cells; supresses glucagon secretion and slows gastric emptying.
OptionD: complexes with the PPAR-gamma. Complex is an adipocyte gene transcriptional regulator
OptionE: Activates AMP-dependent protein kinase (hepatically) to reduce glucogenic processes and potentiates effects of endogenously secreted insulin
Explanation:
A - SULFONYLUREAS e.g. gliclazinde

B- Gliptin e.g. saxa gliptin  ---> remember it that GLiPtins work with GLP

C - Incretin mimetic e.g. exonatide

D - Thiazolidedione .e.g pioglitazone

E - Biguanides e.g. Metformin

Question:
You see a patient who has been diagnosed with Epstein Barr Virus. You notice on examination that they have swelling in their lymph nodes on the neck.

 

What is likely to have caused this swelling?
OptionA: increase in number of all cells circulating through the lymph node in order to try to get interaction between B and T cells
OptionC: increased lymph node density due to the expansion of T cells
OptionD: increase in number and size of NK and cDCs to kill the pathogen
Explanation:
I understand that more than 1 of these may be correct, but C is the most correct answer. 

 

 

There is full T cell activation taking place due to costimulatory signals which then causes expansion in numbers of CD8 T cells (which will become CTL). The swelling seen in the neck and groin is due to increased lymph node density during infection and the expansion of CD8 T cells.

Question:
Fluoxetine, a SSRI anti-depressant, has lots of possible side effects such as sexual dysfunction, sleep problems, headaches, tremors and dry mouth.

Another one of the possible side effects is nausea and vomiting. What is the most likely mechanism behind this side effect?
OptionA: Overactive 5-HT2A receptors in the spinal cord and nucleus accumbens
OptionC: Overactive 5-HT2A receptors in the central nervous system
OptionD: Overactive 5-HT3A receptors in the hypothalamus and brain stem
OptionE: Overactive 5-HT3A receptors in central and peripheral nervous system
Explanation:
D - Overactive 5-HT3A receptors in the hypothalamus and brain stem

The chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) is found in the area postrema of the medulla oblongata (which is a part of the brain stem). It contains 5-HT3A receptors (a sub type of serotonin receptors) which will stimulate the nausea and vomiting response. The hypothalamus seems to be indicated in this response to.

 

A - Overactive 5-HT2A receptors in the spinal cord and nucleus accumbens

This response is actually the mechanism behind sexual dysfunction as a side effect. Patients may have diminished libido, anorgasmia, impotence and delayed ejaculation.

 

B - Overactive 5-HT2A receptors in the basal ganglia

The basal ganglia is involved in movement and over stimulation will cause akathisia (pathological feeling of restlessness), psychomotor retardation, parkinsonism and distonic movements. However, these are very rare side effects.

 

C - Overactive 5-HT2A receptors in the central nervous system

This will cause side effects such as mental agitation, anxiety and panic attacks. However, this is also very rare.

 

E - Overactive 5-HT3A receptors in central and peripheral nervous system

This will cause the common side effects of increased GI motility and GI cramps. 5-HT4 receptors are also implicated.
Tags: Mental health, case 12, Neuroanatomy, Pharmacology, neurotransmitter

Question:
You are on a placement in a small hospital with a blood bank when an emergency case is brought in. A 19 year old man has lacerations and abrasions down his side and internal bleeding is strongly suspected after he had a violent BMX crash in the nearby woods.

 

 

Your seniors tell you he is indicated for transfusion, but which combination of blood components is most strongly indicated?
Explanation:
The patient has already lost blood from his injuries and without treatment will probably continue to do so because of the extent of his injuries and the risk of GI bleeding. Red blood cells are indicated because in a situation of acute blood loss (especially GI blood loss) we want to reduce the risk of tissue hypoxaemia/ischaemia. This means the answer cannot be 'A'.

 

The patient also needs plasma. Plasma contains clotting factors, and without clotting factors his transfusion of red blood cells will bleed out of him and be wasted. This means the answer cannot be 'E'.

 

However, there are different types of plasma given: two types include standard Fresh Frozen Plasma (FFP) and solvent detergent plasma. Solvent detergent plasma is preferred for use in those born after 1996 (or in 2018 21/22 years old), and our patient is only 19 years old so it is indicated above FFP.

 

Whilst 'B' and 'C' both have the correct combination of red cells and plasma, the SBA is 'B' because of the indication for solvent detergent plasma over FFP.

 

Platelets do help prevent bleeding, but they are indicated in specific groups of patients: for example, those with thrombocytopenia or those with platelet function disorders. Without knowing the patient has a condition such as these from the question, I don't think platelets are indicated in this situation.

 

The indications for the above reasoning are all taken from the Case 8 lecture 'Blood Transfusion'.

Question:
Miss Z, a 24 year old woman, presents to your GP with a fear she may be pregnant. After taking 5 pregnancy tests (just to make sure), she wants your input to confirm whether she is or not. You carry out a pregnancy test and see that her suspicions are true.... She is pregnant.

 

Although daunted by the surprise, Miss Z is confident that she wants to keep the baby and would like to do everything she can to make sure that the baby is born happy and healthy. While discussing how she can do this, you ask Miss Z a few simple questions on her lifestyle. You find out that she does not smoke, although she did in university, and drinks alcohol only on special occasions. She explains that she takes paracetamol daily for stress headaches, the combined oral pill (when she remembers...) and a drug for her acne that she doesn't remember the name of. Her diet consists of lots of vegetables and leafy greens, as she has recently become a vegetarian.


Which aspect of this lifestyle history would you advise her to stop?
OptionA: Stop eating excessive amounts of green vegetables
OptionD: Continue drinking at special events - you only go to your cousin's wedding once!
Explanation:
The correct answer here is to terminate her use of her acne medication.
Isotretinoin and Accutane are two drugs used to treat acne. They are Vitamin A (Retinol) analogues that act by activating the Sonic the Hedgehog protein. Although effective at controlling acne, the drugs are extremely teratogenic; severe risks of birth defects!

Question:
A 36 year old black female with a BMI of 31 has had an ambulatory 24-hour blood pressure monitor and her average blood pressure reading has come back as 142/90. 

 

She is worried as her father takes blood pressure medication. 

 

What is your management plan for this lady?
OptionD: Repeat the blood pressure readings and then decide what to do
Explanation:
Before pharmacological intervention you should address patient-modifiable factors. These include diet high in salt and saturated fats, obesity, smoking, drinking and a sedentary lifestyle. 

 

A - Bisoprolol is a B1 adrenoceptor antagonist. It is a negative chronotrope and a negative inotrope, but it is not first-line for hypertension.

 

B - Nifedipine is a Ca2+ channel blocker, which is effective in black patients and patients > 55. 

 

C - Ramipril is an ACE inhibitor. It is a good first-line therapy and it is also protective of diabetic nephropathy in diabetic patients.

 

D - you don't really need to repeat the BP readings again before deciding a management plan as the 24-hour BP monitor will have given a representative/accurate reading. It is good practice though to routinely check BP.

 

E - Correct! Lifestyle intervention is the first step, particularly as this patient is young and her BP is only just classed as hypertension.

Question:

She is aware that her age means her baby has a higher risk of having a chromosomal abnormality.

OptionB: Single palmar crease, sandal gap deformity, low set ears
OptionD: Clenched hands, rocker bottom feet, cleft palate
OptionE: Low birth weight, very small head, low set ears
Explanation:
The correct answer is B - features of Trisomy 21. Risk of Trisomy 21 increases with maternal age. 

 

A -  Cri du Chat

C-  Prader Willi Syndrome 

D-  Patau Syndrome (trisomy 13)

E-  Edwards Syndrome (trisomy 18)

Question:
You are working in the Obstetrics Department when a 19 year old man comes in with his partner. Your colleague takes a history and examines the man's girlfriend. You are told she is 18 years old, pregnant primigravida, red blood cell type Rhesus D negative and ABO blood group A. Her partner is Rhesus D positive.

 

 

She was previously told she had placenta previa and was indicated for Caesarian section. If there were complications during the C-section operation, she might require a blood transfusion - but which of the following would be the most suitable?
Explanation:
To treat this patient in the event of complications we have to give her blood components that will not only stop her showing negative consequences of blood loss like hypoxaemia and tissue ischaemia but more specifically she needs compatible blood components.

 

  • The patient needs red blood cells to transport oxygen in her tissue, but they must be ABO and Rhesus D compatible. She is ABO type A and Rhesus D negative, so Red cells need to be A-ve.
  • She also needs plasma with the transfusion. This will stop the new blood transfused to her bleeding out and being wasted. Because she is born after 1996 (she is less than 21/22 years old), solvent detergent plasma is preferred over fresh frozen plasma (FFP). This means the best answer will have solvent detergent plasma instead of FFP.
  • Because our patient is Rhesus D negative (RhD-ve) and her partner is RhD+ve there is a real risk that her foetus is RhD+ve; this risks sensitisation to RhD+ve blood cells and a bleed is a typical sensitisation event. She therefore requires Anti-D treatment to prevent her from being sensitised.
  • She is not noted as having thrombocytopenia or a platelet disorder so I do not think platelets are indicated for this patient's transfusion.

These different indications combined should suggest 'E' as the best answer to give in this patient's situation. The indications are all taken from the lecture 'Blood Transfusion' in Case 8.

Question:
You are doing rounds in the recovery ward when you hear an alert. The relevant patient is Mrs Jones, a 70 year old woman recovering from GI surgery which finished about 4 hours ago.

 

On the basis of her symptoms she is given a chest X-ray, and when the consultant takes a look they say its shows signs of 'bilateral pulmonary infiltrates'. It looks like this:

  • There was a bleed during the operation which required a transfusion, which was successful
