  • She is now dizzy, nauseous and says she has chest pain
OptionD:
• Mrs Jones has had a cough for a month
  • She required a transfusion because of a bleed during the surgery
  • She is dyspnoeic and hypoxic
OptionE:
• Mrs Jones says he had a 'bit of a cough' recently
  • There were complications during the surgery but no transfusion was given
  • She is showing signs of hypoxia and has dyspnoea
Explanation:
Mrs Jones is likely suffering from a Transfusion Related Acute Lung Injury, or TRALI. TRALI might occur when a patient receiving a transfusion has also had a mild chest infection and the white blood cells in the lungs come into contact with the blood cells from the transfusion. Specifically, if neutrophils were recruited to the site during infection and were already 'primed', they can react with the transfusion - in which case they will degranulate.

 

TRALI shows symptoms within six hours of transfusion, normally acute dyspnoea and hypoxia as well as the signs on the Chest X-ray above (bilateral pulmonary infiltrates - a diffuse and bilateral increase in density in the lungs which shows as slightly whiter than normal lung tissue).

 

This means that the best answer here will show a previous medical history of respiratory infection, a transfusion during her surgery (which only finished four hours ago) and now hypoxia and dyspnoea. The combination of all three of these together is only present in 'D', making it the best answer.

 

It is possibly the most common cause of death directly from transfusion but is sometimes missed or misidentified and so perhaps under-reported.

 

All the information on the mechanism, symptoms/signs etc. for TRALI were taken from the lecture 'Blood Transfusion' from Case 8.

Question: Vitamin K is a fat soluble vitamin integral for the synthesis of several clotting factors. Which of the clotting factors requires vitamin K for its synthesis?
Explanation:
Vitamin K is involved in the synthesis of: factor II (thrombin), VII, IX, X as well as protein C and S.

 

This is why warfarin is such a potent anticoagulant, by inhibiting vitamin K uptake, you inhibit the production of numerous clotting factors.

Question: Which of the thyroid hormones is the predominant circulating hormone?
Explanation:
T4 is the predominant circulating hormone and it is deionated to T3. 

 

I just made T2 up. 

 

T3 is biologically more active but has a shorter half life.

Question:
A 25-year-old woman comes to see you. She is feeling unwell and has the following symptoms;

weight gain, irritable, constipation, cold intolerant and menstrual irregularities. 

 

From these symptoms, what would you predict is the causative agent? (most common)
Explanation:
The symptoms described were referring to hypothyroidism and therefore the best answer is hashimotos thyroiditis as this is the most common cause for hypothyroidism. 

 

Hashimoto's is a autoimmune disorder.

Question: A 15 year old girl comes into your practice feeling tired and fatigued. A history reveals she has recently become a vegan and hasn't properly modified her diet to ensure that she makes up for her dietary deficiencies in iron. She asks whether the body can store iron, you explain that it can. Which is the principle organ responsible for storingiron?
Explanation:
Iron is ingested as Fe3+ it is then reduced to Fe2+ by vitamin C ferric reductase. 

Fe2+ taken up by divalent metal transporter with H+ into enterocytes. 

Fe2+ is transported out of the basal side by ferroportin into the blood stream whereby it is converted back into Fe3+.

Two molecules of Fe3+ bind to transferrin which transports the iron around the body. 

Most of this iron will go to long bones for erythopoeisis. 

Around 10-20% will be stored in the liver as a ferritin. 

 

Transferrin concentration is regulated by hepcidin which acts on feroportin channels, preventing excessive concentrations from being absorbed in the small intestines.

Defects in the HFE gene results in defective hepcidin leading to hereditary haemochromotosis. 

 

For more see case 8, haematology in pregnancy.

Question:
A 65 year old male with chronic hypertension and heart failure is currently taking multiple medications including an ACE-i, Beta-blocker and a potassium sparing diuretic spironolactone.

 

Which of the following is not an important side effect of potassium sparing diuretics?
Explanation:
Aldosterone
antagonists:

 

Indication:
(1) Primary
hyperaldosteronism
(2) Secondary
hyperaldosteronism
(a) Heart failure
(b) Cirrhosis
(c) Nephrotic syndrome
(3) Polycystic ovarian
syndrome

 

MOA:

Antagonist of the
intracellular
mineralocorticoid
receptor.

 

Important side effects:


• Hyperkalaemia
• Hyponatraemia
• Hepatotoxicity
• Gynaecomastia

Question: Patient presents with aplastic anaemia. You take a full blood count. Which of the following sets of results fits with a diagnosis of aplastic anaemia?
OptionA:
Reduced: platelet count

Normal: RBC count

Increased: WBC count
OptionB:
Reduced: Platelet count

Reduced: RBC count

Reduced: WBC count
OptionC:
Increased: Platelet count

Reduced: RBC count

Reduced: WBC count
OptionD:
Increased: Platelet count

Increased: RBC count

Increased: WBC count
OptionE:
Increased: Platelet count

Decreased: RBC count

Increased: WBC count
Explanation: Aplastic anemia is a rare disease in which the bone marrow and the hematopoietic stem cells that reside there are damaged. This causes a deficiency of all three blood cell types (pancytopenia): red blood cells (anemia), white blood cells (leukopenia), and platelets (thrombocytopenia). Hence in a full blood count, all three types of blood cell will be reduced in quantity.

Question:
You are doing a placement in Obstetrics when an expectant mother comes in to see you, and you decide to take a history.

 

Here is what you gather from her. She is 29 years old, 10 weeks pregnant, G2 P1 and carrying twins. Her BMI is 22 (18.5-24.9), she is active in her day-to-day normally and she eats a healthy, balanced diet. She's had quite severe morning sickness with this pregnancy, but more recently she has been suffering with some newer symptoms: a sore tongue, fatigue, breathlessness and also sometimes faintness. It's getting her mood down and means she can't be as active and her husband suggested she come in to get checked.

 

 

You talk to someone more senior, who asks you to take a blood sample and bring them the results - which are as follows:

  • Hb  98g/L                          (115-165g/L)
  • Ferritin 90μg/L                   (40-200μg/L)
  • MCV 110 fL/red cell          (80-100 fL/red cell)
  • WCC  8.0 x 109/L              (4-11 x 109/L)
  • Platelets 220 x 109/L        (150-400 x 109/L)

Which of the following diagnoses is the best supported by your findings?
Explanation:
• The patient is breathless and breathlessness is a relatively common symptom of a pulmonary embolism (though they can be completely asymptomatic); however, neither her investigations nor her other features such as the sore tongue and her active lifestyle support a PE, so 'B' is not a wrong answer but it is not the best.
  • The platelet count is completely normal so 'D' is a wrong answer.
  • 'A', 'C' and 'E' are all supported by her low Haemoglobin result, but 'C' is unlikely because her ferritin result is normal as well.
  • 'A' and 'E' are hard to distinguish. However, B12 stores last for up to 2 years in the body and she has said she has a balanced diet (incidentally if she was a vegan 'E' might be more likely); though folate stores usually last for up to 4 months without sufficient intake and 4 months have not gone by, our patient is carrying twins and she has also had very severe morning sickness; both of these increase risk of a folate deficiency.

In summary, though iron deficiency anaemia is generally the most common cause of anaemia (75% of cases), in this scenario 'A' is best supported by the clinical picture.
Tags: Complications in pregnancy, case 8, Pregnancy, Serology, Tests

Question: HELLP syndrome is a life-threatening pregnancy complication usually considered to be a variant or complication of pre-eclampsia. What does HELLP stand for ?
OptionA: Haemostasis, Elevated Lung function, and Low Platelet count.
Explanation: See case 8 haematology for more

Question:
26 year old pregnant woman comes into practice. You conduct a full blood count and find the following results: 

 

Hb 118g/L (115-165)

WCC 6.0 x 109 /L (4-11)

Platelets 100 x 109 /L (150-400)

MCV 92 fL (77-93 fL) 

 

Platelets of various sizes, some larger platelets are seen. 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The correct answer is gestational thrombocytopenia. The platelet count is low indicative of thrombocytopenia, Hb level is normal hence unlikely to be iron deficiency anaemia. Aplastic anaemia would see a drop in WBC, RBC and platelets hence not aplastic anaemia. MCV is normal, therefore not macro or microcytic anaemia. It is normal for MCV to increase slightly during pregnancy. 

Other causes of thrombocytopenia are:

 

See case 8 haematology lecture for more.
Tags: case 8, Haematology, Pregnancy, Progress Test revision, Clinical Tests

Question: Mr Jones, a 65 year old man has come to the centre for his annual eye screening test. He was diagnosed with type 1 diabetes when he was 18 years old. He is adamant that his vision is fine and being here is a waste of time. Upon taking some images of his eyes, you find the following result. What do the results indicate?
OptionC: There is no problem. This is a healthy eye.
Explanation:
Image shows the features of background DR.

 

A - Wrong as there is no neovascularisation.

B - Wrong as pre-proliferative shows evidence of venous beading and cotton wool spots as well as the other features.

C - There is evidence in the image of dot haemorrhages and hard exudates, so it is not a normal result.

D - Correct answer.

E - Has not progressed to this stage. Would see retinal detachment, pre-retinal fibrosis, and Rubeosis Iridis, as well as the other features.
Tags: Clinical skills, Eye, Case 10, Case 17, Diabetes

Question:
A man presents with weakness in his right upper and lower facial muscles. He is unable to close his eye, lift his eyebrow or smile on the affected side. He also complains of increased sensitivity to sound and impaired taste.

 

Where is the facial nerve lesion?
Explanation:
This is a classic case of Bell’s palsy and the answer is A. 

 

Firstly you can rule out an UMN lesions because he is not able to lift his forehead/eyebrow. The upper facial muscles are bilaterally innervated by UMNs. Therefore, a unilateral UMN lesion would only affect the lower facial muscles on the contralateral side. 

 

Lesions to the LMN affect both the upper and lower facial muscles on the ipsilateral side. Therefore the answer is A

 

A bilateral LMN lesion would affect both sides of the face. Hence this answer is incorrect. 

 

P.S. I would like to put in a diagram but haven’t worked out how to do it on here yet 😅 For more information see the case 16 anatomical work book

Question: If one of your parents is blood type A and the other is type B, which of the following blood types could he be?
Explanation: Since you could inherit A or O alleles from one parent and B or O alleles from the other, you could be any of the 4 ABO types.

Question:
A 56 year old patient on peritoneal dialysis for stage 5 chronic kidney disease self administers erythropoietin in order to generate more RBCs. The patient miscalculates his dosage accidentally injects 10 times to prescribed amount. You take a blood sample from the patient and find that he has a haematocrit of about 77%. The blood sample looks like this under the microscope:

 

 

What is the term used to describe an elevated haematocrit?
Explanation:
Polycythemia (also known as polycythaemia or polyglobulia) is a disease state in which the hematocrit (the volume percentage of red blood cells in the blood) is elevated.

It can be due to an increase in the number of red blood cells("absolute polycythemia") or to a decrease in the volume of plasma ("relative polycythemia").Polycythemia is sometimes called erythrocytosis, but the terms are not synonymous, because polycythemia refers to any increase in red blood cells, whereas erythrocytosis only refers to a documented increase of red cell mass.

 

See case 8 haematology in pregnancy for more.

Question:
You are examining a patient who was diagnosed with type two diabetes 10 years ago. The patient has been complaining of pain around her foot and has noticed breaks in her skin on the lateral side of her foot. You examine her foot. Her foot feels cool and you cannot feel all her foot pulses. 

What type of pathology is the patient most likely to have?
Explanation:
Breaks in the skin indicate an ulcer.
Neuropathic = the feet are well perfused and so are warm and you can feel the feet pulses.

Answer is therefore D = Neuroischaemic ulcers = cool, pulseless feet.

Question:
A 35 year old lady presents to your clinic with declining conginition and motor ability. You run a couple of tests - including an MR to mesure the gap between the heads of the Caudate Nucleus. ULTIMATELY she is diagnosed with Huntingtons disease.

Huntingtons disease is due to a mutation on which Chromosome?
Explanation:
Huntingtons is an autosomal dominant mutation of Chromosome 4. 

It is typically displayed later in life 30-40s and is a degeneration of nerves in the brain.

 

Mutation on Chromosone 7 is associated with Cystic Fibrosis

Mutation on Chromosome 11 is associated with sickle cell anaemia

Question: What term is used to describe a change in total chromosome number due to addition or deletion?
Explanation:
The answer is aneuploidy. This is typically presented in Sex chromosome aneuploidy such as Klinefelters; 47XXY and Turners 45,X

Polyploidy is a term used to describe when the total chromosome number is changed due to addition of an entire set; such as Triploidy 69, resulting from diandry or digyny.

Question: What is used to describe the change in sexual characteristics of someone with Klinefelters
Explanation: Klinfelters suffer from primary hypogonadism. This is due to diminished ability of the testes. The HP axis therefore pumps more FSH/LH into tthe blood in an attempt to increase the testosterone levels.

Question: What is the cause of Cri du Chats syndrome?
OptionB: Imprinting of deletion of Chr 15 from father
OptionC: Imprinting of deleteino of Chr 15 from mother
OptionD: Partial deletion of short arm of Chr 5
Explanation:
A) DiGeorge syndrome. This is detected using FISH. Causes heart anomalies, intellectual disability and increased risk of schizophrenia.

B) Prader-Willi syndrome. This leads to obesity and hypogonadism

C) Angelman Syndrome. This leads to microcephaly, seizures and intellectual disability.

D) This is Cri du Chat. This is due tot eh characteristic cat like cry from infants. This leads to intellectual disability, weak muscle tone in infancy and delayed development. It occurs due to a balanced translocation occurring in a parent, which is then unbalanced when inherited by baby

E) This is huntingtons

Question: Tim has just eaten a cream cake and has got a surge of insulin running through his body and therefore an increase in glycolysis. How does insulin regulate glycolysis?
OptionB: Insulin increases the amount of Fructose 1, 6 bisphosphate and therefore increases glycolysis
OptionC: Insulin dephosphorylates PFK1 and thus increases glycolysis
OptionD: Insulin phosphorylates PFK1 and thus increases glycolysis
OptionE: Insulin dephosphorylates PFK2 and thus increases glycolysis
Explanation:
A) is true but does not answer the question

B) Not true 

C) Again not true

D) Not true 

E) True

 

Explanation:

When you eat sugar insulin is released. Insulin wants to decrease the amount of sugar in you blood and does this by varies methods including: increasing glycolysis, increase protein synthesis, increase glycogen synthesis etc. 

 

Insulin dephosphorylation PFK2 which is an enzyme that converts; fructose 6 phosphate into fructose 2 6 bisphosphate.

 

Fructose 2 6 bisphosphates upregulates PFK1 which is an enzyme that is used in glycolysis to convert fructose 6 phosphate into fructose 1 6 bisphosphate.

 

Therefore, that is how insulin upregulates glycolysis.

Question: Alice, a 22 yr old woman has been prescribed a new antidepressant by her psychiatrist. She is also given a diet to follow and is told to avoid foods such as Marmite and cheese. What drug has she most likely been prescribed?
Explanation:
D - Phenelzine is a MOAI and therefore interacts dangerously with any food containing tyramine

 

A - SNRI

B - NRI

C - TCA

E - SSRI 

(none of the other antidepressant drugs have any diet limitations part from alcohol)

Question: Bob is being treated for severe depression. All the therapy and pharmacological treatments he has been tried on have failed to help. Which is the mostly like next stage of his treatment?
Explanation:
Whilst its use in the UK is decreasing and the treatment is controversial - ECT is still considered an effective treatment for severe, life threatening depression. 

 

TMS shows moderate success but is rarely used. Psychosurgery is only used as a very last resort after all options fail. St Johns Wort is a popular herbal remedy used to treat mild depression and shouldnt ever be prescribed. Vagal nerve stimulation may be highly effective but definitive trials are awaited so it isnt common place yet.

Question:
It is the end of the academic year.

You are becoming more sleepy.

You are becoming more interesting in why you are sleepy.

 

You want to recall the final mechanism in your brain that will causes you to sleep after a 'sleep/wake' cycle.

 

Which of the following signals causes the brain to sleep?
OptionA: Adenosine (ADP) build up in the ventrolateral pre-optic nucleus.
OptionB: ACh production from upper pons acting on the thalamus and cerebral cortex.
OptionC: Serotonin production from pons priming signals from thalamus to cerebral cortex.
OptionD: Melatonin production from pineal gland acting on the supra-chiasmatic nucleus (SCN).
OptionE: GABA production from ventrolateral pre-optic nucleus acting on hypothalamus and pons.
Explanation:
All answers are related to the explanation below. E is the correct answer, as GABA is inhibitory, and stops the ascending arousal pathway involved in wakefulness.

 

Stages of wakefulness and sleepiness:

 

Waking up signals: neurons in the upper pons produce acetylcholine, which activates areas of the thalamus, responsible for channelling signals to the cerebral cortex – the site of consciousness.

• The ascending arousal system neurotransmitters including noradrenaline, serotonin, histamine and dopamine are produced in the pons, hypothalamus. They prime the cerebral cortex to receive signals from the thalamus. Orexins: peptides produced in the lateral hypothalamus, reinforce the arousal system.


The brain tires.
• Homeostatic control: As the energy carrier ATP breaks down, adenosine builds up and triggers neuron activity in the ventrolateral preoptic nucleus (VLPO).
• Circadian control: The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN), is the brain’s master clock, containing neurons that fire in a 24-hour cycle to influence the VLPO. It is controlled by signals from the retina during the day, and by melatonin from the pineal gland at night.

 

The brain sleeps

• When the ventrolateral preoptic nucleus neurons are activated, they release GABA and galanin. These bind to receptors in the hypothalamus and pons to inhibit the ascending arousal system.

Question: You are performing a cranial nerve examination on a patient complaining of 'hearing changes'. She is moaning that the truck outside is being so loud she can't think, yet you have forgotten about the noise. You suspect some damage to the stapedius muscle resulting in a condition called hyperacusis. This occurs when the stapedius muscle cannot regulate the oscillation of the stapes. This results in heightened reaction of the auditory ossicles to sound. Which nerve innervates the stapedius muscle?
Explanation:
The correct answer is CN VII, the facial nerve. This nerve is responsible for the motor innervation of the upper and lower face. During a cranial nerve examination you test this nerve by testing the power in the muscles of the face. Seeing if the patient can shut their eyes tightly, raise their eyebrows, blow out their cheeks and purse their lips. 

 

Important to ask for changes in hearing in cranial nerve examination. 

https://geekymedics.com/cranial-nerve-exam/

Question: A 22 year old man crashes his bicycle into a van on Cathays Terrace. You arrive at the scene to find him complaining of a generalised numbness in his lower limbs. He is assessed by a neurologist who observes his various reflexes. One such reflex is the cremasteric reflex. This reflex is elicited by stroking the inner thigh of the male, causing contraction of the cremasteric muscle. This causes an ipslilateral rise of the testis. The sensory fibres of the ilioinguinal nerve are stimulated in this reflex. Which dermatome is this most likely to be?
Explanation: According the ASIA chart this dermatome is L1. The reflex utilizes sensory and motor fibers from two different nerves. When the inner thigh is stroked, sensory fibers of the ilioinguinal nerve are stimulated. These activate the motor fibers of the genital branch of the genitofemoral nerve which causes the cremaster muscle to contract and elevate the testis.

Question:
Acetazolamide is a drug that works by inhibiting the enzyme Carbonic Anhydrase. The drug lowers blood pH by causing a build-up of carbonic acid. It also causes diuresis by causing the excretion of predominantly bicarbonate ions which water then follows.  

This drug has a strong effect on a specific part of the nephron in the kidney. Which part of the nephron is it most likely to be?
OptionA: Ascending limb of the loop of Henle
OptionC: Descending limb of the loop of Henle
Explanation:
You do not need to know the drug so don't worry about that. 
The question involves understanding the re-absorption of bicarbonate.
Carbonic Anhyrdase is an enzyme used in the re-absoprtion of bicarbonate and is predominantly found in the proximal convoluted tubule.

The drug causes excretion of bicarbonate ions. 
Bicarbonate ions are mostly reabsorbed in the proximal convoluted tubule. 

There answer is therefore E

Question: Which cause of Down's syndrome is responsible for the highest percentage of cases?
Explanation:
Non-disjunction = 95% of all cases. Due to both chromatids going into one daughter cell during meiosis 1 or 2. It results in a trisomy and a monosomy 21 daughter cell.

Robertsonian Translocation - 4% of cases. Crossover of long arm of Ch21 (either with another 21 or 14) which causes trisomy 21. Parents are normally one carrier, one normal.

Mosaicism = 1%. Mixed cells, some have extra, some have 46chromosomes. Leads to a milder form of symptoms.

Question: How is a male who is affected by the disease shown on a family tree?
Explanation:
Square = male    Circle = female

Empty = unaffected

Filled in = affected

Slightly filled in = carrier

Question: Which of these aren't an autosomal recessive disorder?
Explanation:
Huntington = Chr 4 abnormality. It is autosomal dominant but only really shows in later life (30-40 years old)

The other 3 are all autosomal recessive. 

Cystic Fibrosis = Chr 7 abnormalities leading to dysfunctioning chloride channel

Sickle Cell Anaemia = Chr 11 abnormalities leading to sickle shaped red blood cells

Question: What is the equation to work out the risk of being affected by an autosomal dominant condition?
OptionA: 0.25 x mums carrier risk x dads carrier risk
OptionD: Mums carrier risk x dads carrier risk x 0.5
Explanation:
Penetrance is the known percentage of a disease. It is due to variable expression so not everyone who carries the mutation of a disease is affected. So Penetrance is needed in order to find out the chance of being affected.

 

0.25x mums carrier risk x dads carrier risk is the equation used to work out the risk of having a child with an autosomal recessive disorder.

Question: If your son has a Y-linked abnormality (which was due to a mutation so his father isn't affected), what is the likelihood of your biological grandson (his son) being affected?
Explanation:
The Y chromosome doesn't possess a lot of genes. However, when a mutation does occur, it normally causes infertility problems. 

Sadly in this instance, there would be a very low chance of her son having a biological child (through normal reproduction) as he would be infertile. However, he can always adopt, but this wouldn't pass on genes.

Question: What X linked recessive disorder can lead to an increased risk of cardiomyopathies females?
Explanation: Women who have an X linked Recessive (Carriers) aren't as affected due to the creation of a Barr Body. However, later in life Duchennes Muscle Dystrophy can lead to an increased risk of dilated cardiomyopathy in carriers.

Question: You are a 3rd-year student on the first day of your hospital front door placement. A young man has just been brought into A and E unit after slipping from the ladder as he was trying to trim the apple tree in his back garden. You hear one of the registrars on duty say anxiously to a consultant that there are changes on the patients ECG suggestive of a Cushing's response. What changes would most likely be sen on his ECG report?
Explanation:
Cushing's response is a triad of symptoms, high blood pressure, bradycardia and irregular breathing that occur due to raised intracranial pressure.

This question is looking at the bradycardia as a symptom and the types of symptoms that would be seen on an ECG.

Cushing's response can cause heart block leading to bradycardia

The patient may have

 

Longer PR interval- First-degree heart block

Non-conducted P waves- Second-degree heart block 

Multiple conducted P waves as well as longer PR interval- Complet heart block

Question: If one of your children has an autosomal recessive disorder (e.g. cystic fibrosis) what is the chance your next offspring will be a carrier and not affected by the disease
Explanation: It is always two thirds.

Question:
Mrs R is a 55 year old woman who comes into your General Practice. Even before she begins talking you can see that something is not normal.

 

This is Mrs R at presentation:

 

 

Even before she begins talking you can see that the left side of her face looks slack. She is alert and communicative as you take a history, but as she talks to you she gets embarrassed when she has to wipe away some dribble from the right corner of her mouth. Her phone goes off during the consultation and she winces - you question her further and she says she's found the normal day-to-day a lot louder, sometimes painfully so.

 

Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis for Mrs R?
Explanation:
'E' is the correct answer - of the given options it is most likely Mrs R has Bell's palsy.

 

  • Ramsay Hunt syndrome is a complication of shingles involving the facial nerve. It has generally similar neurological deficits but often shows a painful rash or blisters, which are on the scalp or in the mouth. It also sometimes presents with hearing loss, whereas Mrs R has heightened sensitivity to sound. This makes 'A' unlikely.
  • Common symptoms of Lyme disease include a red bullseye rash after the bite followed by fatigue and sometimes joint ache and pain. However, Mrs R does not mention a bite, a rash or these other symptoms so 'B' is also unlikely.
  • Mrs R has come in on her own, is speaking clearly (apart from the left sided droop to her mouth) and seems alert. Strokes often give rise to broader neurological deficits such as weakness in a limb, slurred speech and reduced alertness. 'C' is therefore not that likely.
  • Head trauma is unlikely because she has no obvious trauma and reports no accident, so 'D' is quite unlikely.

The increased sensitivity to sound Mrs R is experiencing is a consequence of her facial nerve palsy. It is caused by the absence of the stapedius reflex in her left ear - but it is not always part of the clinical picture of Bell's palsy.

Question: Which of the following voltages (mV) is the best estimate of the threshold potential of cells in the SA node?
Explanation: Phase 4 is the spontaneous depolarization (pacemaker potential) that triggers the action potential once the membrane potential reaches threshold between -40 and -30 mV)

Question:
A 28-year old primigravida comes into your clinic one morning, and discloses that she is worried about her child having Down's Syndrome, after something she read in the newspaper. The patient is 6 weeks pregnant.

 

You reassure the patient, and explain to her that there are several screening tests available to assess risk of the baby having Downs. One test in particular is called Nuchal Translucency. The patient asks when she will be able to have that test. How long will it be until she can have an NT screening test?
OptionA: She is able to have the test now
Explanation:
Nuchal Translucency (NT) – is the measurement of the depth of an area of translucency at the back of the fetal neck, measured between 11 -13 weeks, using ultrasound. Doesn’t work (inaccurate) in obese mothers.

 

As the patient is already 6 weeks pregnant, she will be eligible to have the screening test in around 5-7 weeks time.

 

Case 7 lecture on Antenatal screening.

Question:
A 17 year old girl comes into your GP surgery, and tells you that she thinks she is a few weeks pregnant. After confirming the pregnancy with a simple urine test, you explain to her that the urine will also need to be tested for 'other things'. 

 

What else should the urine be tested for in early pregnancy?
OptionA: Any bacteria that may put the patient at risk of a UTI
OptionB: Check for proteinuria and screen for asymptomatic bacteriuria
Explanation:
Along with booking bloods, urine tests to check for proteinuria and screen for asymptomatic bacteriuria should be done. Although the other options are all certainly of note, the specific factors to look for are detailed in option B.

 

Case 7 lecture on antenatal screening

Question:
A 32 year-old woman comes into your clinic, and asks advice about trying to conceive. She tells you she has been trying for a month, doesn't drink or smoke, and has epilepsy but controls this with medication.

After giving her every pregnancy pamphlet under the sun (including the fantastic infographic made by your case group during your 2nd year at medical school), you start telling her about pregnancy supplements. 

 

Open neural tube defects affect 7-15 babies in every 10,000 births. Folic acid can decrease the risk of this happening. Folic acid best pre conception – 12 weeks. How much folic acid would you prescribe to this patient per day?
Explanation:
Folic acid supplements are recommended (400 micrograms a day) from before pregnancy up to 12 weeks, in addition to eating folate-containing foods. This can help to prevent neural tube defects e.g. spina bifida.
Higher doses of folate are recommended for women that have an increased risk of having a pregnancy affected by a neural tube defect.
Also women on anti-epileptic medication are often advised to take higher doses of folic acid.

 

 Increase prescription of folic acid in epileptic women to 5mg due to their medication. 5mg = 5000 micrograms

 

From case 7 lecture on antenatal screening

Question:
Its a mild Monday evening, and after a long day boothin' it at Heath library, you get a message inviting you to go to the pub with a few friends from @2malspals for cheap drinks at the Woody.  You reply 'that would be absolutely nifty' to the group chat, and proceed to loudly pack up, disturbing literally everyone around you. 

 

On the walk home, you question your use of the word nifty, and remember it was mentioned in a different context in case 7. What is a NIFTY/NIPT test?
OptionA: Chorionic villi are aspirated through the abdomen under ultrasound guidance, sample sent to lab for analysis
OptionB: Taking a sample of amniotic fluid under ultrasound guidance. Can diagnose >100 conditions. Cells are analysed for chromosome and single gene
OptionC: Blood sample from mother taken to look at the levels of biochemical markers AFP, hCG, Inhibin-A, uE3
OptionD: Ultrasound scan to determine gestational age using CRL (at 10-13 weeks), and head circumference if CRL is >84mm.NIFTY/NIPT
OptionE: Looks at mother's peripheral blood to estimate the risk of fetal chromosomal aneuploidies that may be present in the foetus
Explanation:
A = CVS

B = amniocentesis

C = blood tests to screen for general foetal abnormalities

D = Used to determine gestational age

 

 

NIFTY/NIPT (non-invasive pregnancy test)
• NIFTY test examines peripheral blood from the mother to estimate the risk of fetal chromosomal aneuploidies carried in the unborn.
• Highly accurate The NIFTY test uses the next-generation sequencing technology to reach a detection rate >99.9%
• Simple The NIFTY test only requires 10 ml of maternal venous blood. Advantages 03 NIFTY
• Risk-free Testing peripheral maternal blood prevents intrauterine infection and the risk of miscarriage.
• Early-test The NIFTY test allows testing as early as 10 weeks of gestation
• Can be carried out in twin pregnancies

Question:
Aromatic acid decarboxylase (AADC) deficiency is an autosomal recessive condition. Infants may have a severe developmental delay, weak muscle tone (hypotonia), muscle stiffness, difficulty moving, and involuntary writhing movements of the limbs (athetosis).

Synthesis of which neurotransmitter is most likely to be compromised by the deficiency of this enzyme?
Explanation:
B - (CORRECT)

AADC is involved in the catecholamine synthesis pathway which converts L- DOPA to dopamine 

 

E- would have been correct if the question did not specify neurotransmitter as adrenaline is produced from noradrenaline which is produced from dopamine

 

The other three neurotransmitters are produced from other pathways which do not involve Aromatic acid decarboxylase.

Question:
A patient comes into your GP surgery complaining of recent onset of nausea, vomiting diarrhoea, and loss of appetite as well as drowsiness, dry mouth, visual blurring. When you ask if she is taking any medication, she mentions that she had been having to trouble sleeping so she bought some L-tryptophan of the internet. 

Overactivity of which substance is most likely to be causing her new symptoms?
Explanation:
D is the correct answer

The symptoms are suggestive serotonin syndrome which is a potential side effect of taking an overdose of L-tryptophan supplements

Tryptophan is an amino acid that is involved in the synthesis of serotonin.

Serotonin is converted to melatonin (important for sleep) in the pineal gland. This is why tryptophan can be taken as a remedy for insomnia.

Question:
An 18 year-old student comes into the sexual health clinic at the end of freshers week, and is worried that she is pregnant. She tells you that she went home with someone the other night, they did not use protection, and she is currently on no form of contraception. Despite disclosing this to her sexual partner, he apparently ignored her request to pull out and finished inside of her.

 

He told her she shouldn't worry about being pregnant, as he had heard his medical student flatmate say "freshly ejaculated sperm are not capable of fertilising the egg" anyway. Your patient is clearly distressed when talking about this experience. 

 

In addition to comforting her and thinking whether she would be eligible for some social support, you tell the girl that her partner was right in a sense, but she is still able to get pregnant. Explain why "freshly ejaculated sperm are not capable of fertilising the egg".
OptionA: The acrosome reaction has not occurred; so the sperm are unable to fertilise the oocyte
OptionB: Because the sperm are only viable for fertilisation 48 hours after ejaculation
OptionC: Because the oocyte will not yet have undergone its 2nd mitotic devision, so therefore cannot be fertilised
OptionD: Because immediately after ejaculation, the sperm have not undergone capacitation so cannot fertilise the oocyte
OptionE: The cortical reaction will not have occurred; so the sperm are unable to fertilise the oocyte
Explanation:
A - this is correct, but the capacitation reaction (Capacitation involves the removal of proteins from around the outside of the sperm head, so fertilisation can occur) has to occur first.

B - incorrect, an oocyte can be fertilised for about 24hrs after ovulation and sperm remain viable for up to 48hrs within the female reproductive tract

C - incorrect, the oocyte is in its second mitotic division immediately after ovulation, will have completed it by the time fertilisation occurs

D - correct

E - incorrect, the cortical reaction is after the sperm has fertilised the egg - formation of a ‘fertilisation membrane’, cortical reaction prevents further sperm entry

 

I know this can be a difficult topic, and the issue of consent especially to acts during/at the end of sexual intercourse can be a bit of a grey area. However it is important to be aware as I'm sure we will all speak to someone in our personal lives/professional careers that may have been in a similar situation.

 

If you have personally been in a similar situation or need to discuss this, Medic Support is available on 02920870686, and Cardiff nightline on 02920870555

Question: Mandy is a 17 year old female who suffers from a type of personality disorder. She tends to over-exaggerate and dramatize situations, is always seeking out the next exciting event and is constantly looking for appreciation and validation from those around her. Which type of personality disorder does Mandy have?
Explanation:
Anankastic - characterised by excessive doubt and caution, excessive attention to detail and an obsession with rules and order

Borderline - characterised by impulsive actions, anxiety, forming intense but short lived emotional attachments and self abuse

Dependent - patient wants others to make decisions for them, unwilling to make demands on others and has an intense fear of being abandoned

Histrionic - characterised by self dramatisation, theatricality, seeking of excitement and appreciation, shallow and labile emotions

Narcissistic - patient has an inflated sense of self importance, needs to be admired and is excessively arrogant

Question:
Mrs Jones presents to your clinic concerned about her 12 year old son, Ryan. She has very recently been diagnosed with Huntington's disease, and whilst she is still understandably upset about her diagnosis she is more concerned about the risk it poses to her son. Mrs Jones explains to you how her mother (Ryan's grandmother) also had Huntington's disease, but that she 'isn't sure if Ryan will inherit the condition because he is a boy' and so wants to know what the likelihood is that he will inherit the gene mutation. 

 

What is your answer to Mrs Jones?
OptionA: Ryan will not inherit the condition as he is male, and this particular pattern of inheritance only affects females.
OptionB: Huntington's disease is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that only one generation of the family is affected and therefore Ryan is not at risk of inheriting the gene mutation.
OptionC: Huntington's disease is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that only one generation of the family is affected and therefore Ryan is not at risk of inheriting the gene mutation.
OptionD: Huntington's disease is an autosomal recessive disorder, and so with this particular pattern of inheritance Ryan has a 50% risk of inheriting the gene mutation.
OptionE: Huntington's disease is an autosomal dominant condition that affects both males and females equally, and so with this particular pattern of inheritance Ryan has a 50% risk of inheriting the gene mutation.
Explanation:
Huntington's Disease is an autosomal dominant condition, where sufferers have a defect in chromosome 4 of the HTT gene, which under normal condition codes for glutamine. 

 

The age of onset is typically around 35-50, and the signs and symptoms include:

  • Involuntary, sharp muscle movements.
  • Gait problems.
  • Dystonia.
  • Personality changes.
  • Seizures. 
  • Difficulty concentrating.

Treatment is generally supportive care, with input from occupational therapists, speech and language therapists, physiotherapists etc. 

 

In this scenario, Mrs Jones' mother passed on the gene mutation to her, and now Ryan has a 50% risk of inheriting the gene mutation from his mother. 

 

The condition affects multiple generations, unlike autosomal recessive conditions (such as Cystic Fibrosis and Sickle Cell Anaemia) where it tends to be only one generation affected. The autosomal dominant conditions generally tend to appear later in adulthood, whereas autosomal recessive conditions are involved in some (but not all) childhood onset conditions. 

 

Both men and women are equally affected in the autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance, and so the fact that it has so far affected two generations of females is just coincidental in this scenario.

Question:
Mr and Mrs Thomas present at the GP with their 2 year old daughter, Anna. They are concerned about the chance of Anna developing Cystic Fibrosis. Mr Thomas tells you that whilst he is healthy, his 20 year old brother has Cystic Fibrosis, and that he has read online that this could potentially affect his own children. 

 

What is Mr Thomas' risk of being a carrier for Cystic Fibrosis?
OptionE: There is no chance that Mr Thomas could be a carrier
Explanation:
The answer is B, 2/3.

 

If your sibling has an autosomal recessive condition, regardless of whether or not you are totally healthy and have no signs/symptoms, your risk of carrying it is always 2/3. 

 

To calculate the inheritance risk for Anna in this scenario, you would do:

mum's carrier risk x dad's carrier risk (which would be 2/3) x 1/4

Question: Gross defects seen in achondroplasia can provide clues to the gene mutation that causes the condition. A mutation in which gene has been identified?
Explanation:
Acondroplasia = a hereditary condition in which the growth of long bones by ossification of cartilage is retarded, resulting in very short limbs and sometimes a face which is small in relation to the skull.

 

Gross defects seen in achondroplasia (autosomal dominant condition) that provide clues to the gene mutation that causes the condition:
- Shortened arms
- Flat nasal bridge
FGFR3, fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 gene mutation

 

A - correct

B - in lethal X-linked dominant conditions, women are affected, men are affected as foetuses but never survive birth (lethal) e.g. incontinentia pigmenti (NEMO gene), causes blistering and a wart-like rash, with later swirling macular hyperpigmentation

C - not a specific gene

D - A possible causing of conjoined twinning is the misexpression of goosecoid gene

E - can't find any specific mutations linked to VEGF-1

 

Case 7 anatomy practical

Question: In linked recognition, class switching occurs due to the upregulation of the enzyme cytidine deaminase. Cytidine deaminase converted cytosine to which base?
Explanation: In linked recognition, B cells through a CD40-CD40L and a MCHII-TcR interaction with T follicular helper cells leads to the up regulation of cytidine deaminase which converts cytosine to the uracil base. This base change is essential for both hyper mutation and class switching.

Question:
Whilst on a stroll around Roath park with your most bestest friend, you think about how you are rarely seen without one another, so much that your other friends say you may as well be 'joined at the hip'.

 

Getting lost in thought, you are startled by an angry goose waddling towards you. You remember geese actually have something to do with conjoined twins, what is it?
OptionA: A possible causing of conjoined twinning is the deletion of GOO-5E gene
OptionB: A possible causing of conjoined twinning is the deletion of goosecoid gene
OptionC: A possible causing of conjoined twinning is the misexpression of GOO-5E gene
OptionD: A possible causing of conjoined twinning is the misexpression of gooselan gene
OptionE: A possible causing of conjoined twinning is the misexpression of goosecoid gene
Explanation: Case 7 anatomy practical

Question:
Jack and Lauren present at clinic to discuss the risk of their baby inheriting a genetic mutation. Lauren is currently 6 months pregnant with her first child, and they have found out that they are having a boy. Jack is concerned as he has Haemophilia A, and so is unsure whether or not this will affect the baby.

 

What is the likelihood that their son will be affected as a direct result of Jack's genetic mutation (assuming that Lauren is not a carrier)?
OptionA: As the baby is a boy, he will not have Haemophilia A as all sons of affected men are unaffected by the condition.
OptionB: There is a 50% risk of their son inheriting the condition.
OptionC: It is likely that their son will be a carrier for the gene mutation.
OptionD: Their son will definitely inherit the gene mutation.
Explanation:
Haemophilia A is an example of an X-Linked Recessive condition. 

As men have one X and one Y chromosome, fathers pass on all of their X to their daughters (which contains the mutation), but pass on all of their Y to their sons (and the Y isn't affected). As a result, all daughters of affected men are carriers whereas all of their sons are unaffected, which is the case in this scenario as it is Jack that has Haemophilia A 

 

If a female is a carrier then they are usually asymptomatic - 50% of their sons will be affected, and 50% of their daughters will be carriers which means that in total, 25% of children will be affected. 

 

X-Linked Recessive conditions can actually arise due to a spontaneous mutation also.

Question:
Oliver presents at fertility clinic with his wife, Ivy. They have been trying to conceive for over 2 years, and so Oliver has come to clinic to have his sperm count tested. They currently have no children, and all of Ivy's tests so far have come back as normal. 

 

What percentage of sperm should be motile after 2 hours?
Explanation:
At least 40% of sperm should be motile after 2 hours, and some of these should still be motile after 24 hours.

 

Sperm make up less than 10% of the semen. The other 90% is made up of secretions from accessory sex glands of prostaglandins and fructose. The normal male has 100 million/ml of sperm, but 20-50 million/ml means a man is probably fertile.

Question:
A 28 year old lady, Rebecca, presents to A&E with severe pain and vomiting. She has been vomiting continuously for the last couple of hours, and says that every time she stands up she feels like she is going to faint. She says the pain feels like she's 'being stabbed', and she is clutching her lower stomach as she tells you this. 

 

She says that she missed her last period, although put this down to stress as she had recently changed jobs. 

 

After investigation, you diagnose Rebecca as having an ectopic pregnancy.

 

What percentage of ectopic pregnancies occur in the uterine tube?
Explanation:
There are a number of abnormal implantation sites:

  • The abdominal cavity (most frequently the Pouch of Douglas) 
  • The ampullary region of the uterine tube
  • Tubal implantation
  • Interstitial implantation
  • Internal os (which frequently results in placenta previa) 
  • Ovarian implantation

However, the most common place for ectopic pregnancies to occur is in the uterine tube.

Question: What is the approximate global prevalence of schizophrenia?
What is the first sign of gastrulation?
Explanation:
Gastrulation is the process of converting a bilayered blastula of epiblast and hypoblast into an embryo with 3 layers of ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm. It is also responsible for establishing the rudimentary body plan and the rudimentary gut tube. 

 

The process is facilitated by:

  • Cellular migration/movement
  • Cell-cell recognition and cell signalling
  • Selective adhesion (cells that behave similarly stick together)

 

The appearance of the primitive streak occurs around day 15.

Question: Which of the following options is a derivative of the mesoderm?
Explanation:
The answer is C, the primordial heart.

A and B are ectodermal derivatives, whilst D and E are endodermal derivatives.

Question:
Jessica, a 32 year old primigravida, has just been diagnosed with iron deficiency anaemia. She is currently 26 weeks pregnant. One of the reasons why some pregnant women develop iron deficiency anaemia is that plasma volume increases throughout pregnancy, whilst this is not the case for RBC volume which does not increase as much. 

 

The plasma volume reaches approximately 2600mL, although at what week does the plasma volume continue to rise to?
Explanation:
Whilst RBC volume does increase, plasma volume increases to a greater extent and so this results in an increased rate of iron deficiency anaemia amongst pregnant women. Many pregnant women are encouraged to eat foods such as lean red meat etc., which are good sources of heme iron which are readily available to the body.

 

Plasma volume continues to rise until around the 32 week mark, where there is a plateau and this then lasts until the baby is born. 

 

No woman should be iron deficient at the time of delivery. This is because the mother would be more likely to bleed in delivery, the baby may not have received enough iron and the mother may be fatigued already.

Question: A second year medical student comes in to your practice complaining of being tired all the time.  They want to know why they can feel so tired all day but are able to stay up until 3am.  You explain that one of the ways our body clock functions is via homeostatic control.  Which of the following best describes homeostatic control?
OptionA: Ach release from thalamus to cerebral cortex
OptionC: Adenosine accumulation triggering activity in ventrolateral preoptic nucleus (VLPO)
OptionE: VLPO activation leading to release of of GABA + galanin in hypothalamus and pons
Explanation:
Brain awakes due to 2 types of wake signals:

- branch 1 - neurones in upper pons produce ACh, activates areas of thalamus responsible for channelling signals to cerebral cortex (site of consciousness)

- branch 2 - NTs inc NA, 5HT, H + DA produced in pons, hypothalamus + nearby regions, prime cerebral cortex to receive signals from thalamus 

orexins are also produced in hypothalamus that reinforce arousal

 

brain then tires via 2 control mechanisms:

- homeostatic control - as ATP breaks down, adenosine accumulated and triggers activity in VLPO

- circadian control - neurones in the SCN fire in a 24hr cycle to influence VLPO, controlled by signals from retina during the day and melatonin from pineal gland at night

 

brain then sleeps and goes into shutdown:

VLPO neurones activated and release GABA + galanin, binds to receptors in hypothalamus + pons to inhibit ascending arousal system

 

They cycle then starts again.

 

**from the sleep lecture**
Tags: Depression, Mental health, case 12, neurotransmitter, sleep

Question:
Mrs King, a 26 year old lady, presents to her GP with symptoms of fatigue, weakness and dizziness. She is 24 weeks pregnant, and following a blood test she is diagnosed with iron deficiency anaemia. She is started on iron tablets, although returns to her GP as she wants some lifestyle advice in order to help get her iron levels back to normal. Mrs King tells you it is really getting in the way of her work (she is a teacher), as she is too tired to get up in the mornings and as a result feels 'distant' all day. Whilst she understands the iron tablets will work, she tells you that she has read online that there are ways of improving iron levels through lifestyle changes.

 

What is your advice for Mrs King?
OptionA: Start eating as many leafy green vegetables as she can as these will really help her iron levels to return to normal.
OptionB: Get in regular exercise and good levels of sleep.
OptionD: There is nothing else that she can do - just take the iron tablets as prescribed.
OptionE: Start her on an anti-depressant and sign her up for CBT as she is showing signs of depression.
Explanation:
The best answer in this scenario is C, eat more red meat.

 

Whilst green leafy vegetables are a source of iron, they are a source of non-heme iron which means they are not easily available to the body. This is unlike red meat, where the heme iron is readily available to the body and therefore a good source for pregnant women. There is more easily extracted iron in a small piece of steak than there is in lots of green leafy vegetables. However, this red meat needs to be part of a balanced diet.

 

Exercising and getting a good level of sleep is also good advice for Mrs King, although this does not directly relate to her iron deficiency.

Question: Excess iron in the body is mainly stored as ferritin. Where is ferritin found?
Explanation:
Ferritin is an intracellular iron storage protein. A small amount circulates, but it stores iron safely. Looking at the ferritin levels can also be used to diagnose iron deficiency anaemia. The levels are normally above 15mcg/L. Excess iron is stored principally in the liver, although there is some deposition in other organs.

 

Haemochromatosis is when there is too much deposition in major organs, and this causes major dysfunction. It is an inherited condition, and the iron levels in the body slowly build up over many years. Symptoms include tiredness, weight loss and fatigue, and the usual onset is between 30 and 60.

Question:
Keira, a 36 year old lady, presents at A&E with a severely painful left leg. The leg is really swollen, and is very warm to touch. She says her leg has been cramping for the past two hours, and she can barely walk from the pain. Keira is currently 30 weeks pregnant. She has a BMI of 32kg/m2, smokes 15 cigarettes a day and is currently immobile due to her recovering from a recent broken ankle. 

 

You diagnose her with Deep Vein Thrombosis. What vein has most likely been responsible for this?
Explanation:
90% of deep vein thromboses are on the left hand side. As the uterus grows during pregnancy, it compresses the right common iliac artery which then compresses the left common iliac vein, which runs underneath it. This then restricts blood flow.

 

DVTs typically occur higher up in the leg, and the closer the clot is to the inferior vena cava, the more likely it is to embolism and become a pulmonary embolism. 

 

In this scenario, Keira has a lot of risk factors for a DVT. She is over 35, has a very high BMI, smokes and is immobile.

Question:
A 27 year old man who is being operated on following a road traffic accident requires a red blood cell transfusion. The red blood cells are compatible with the recipients ABO type, and therefore can be used on the patient. 

 

On removal from storage, what is the maximum time that the RBCs can be left before being transfused?
OptionA: They need to be transfused immediately after removal from storage
Explanation:
RBCs are produced from whole blood donations after the plasma has been removed.

They are stored at 4oc, and have a shelf life of 35 days. They are stored in the fridge in order to prevent bacterial growth, and also keeps the RBCs metabolically quiet so that they aren't constantly metabolising.

 

They should be transfused within 4 hours of their removal from storage. 

 

The RBCs must be compatible with the recipients ABO type.

Question:
When carrying out a blood transfusion, it is really important to ensure that the patient's blood type is compatible with the red blood cell transfusion type to avoid intravascular destruction of the red blood cells as this can be life threatening.

 

In the serum there are naturally occurring antibodies to the antigens, which are absent on their red blood cells. What class of immunoglobulins do these naturally occurring antibodies belong to?
Explanation: IgM antibodies are really potent, and so even a small amount of the wrong blood can cause a massive problem. The naturally occurring antibodies would result in the immediate destruction of the transfused red blood cells, and this intravascular destruction may be life-threatening.

Question:
Sarah is a 30 year old primigravida who has come in for an elective C-section. 

Her blood type is A, and she is RhD-negative.

 

What does this mean if her baby is Rh-D positive?
OptionA: She needs to be given anti-D immediately as otherwise this baby could be at risk of haemolytic disease of the newborn.
OptionB: Nothing needs to be done at any stage.
OptionC: She should be given anti-D within 72 hours of childbirth if the baby is Rh-D positive, to protect against the risk of haemolytic disease of the newborn in future pregnancy.
OptionD: The baby needs to be given anti-D at birth.
OptionE: She should be given anti-D as a precaution at a follow up appointment.
Explanation:
Haemolytic disease of the newborn is intrauterine destruction of the foetal RBCs. 

 

In most instances, sensitisation to foetal RBCs takes place at childbirth. Therefore, in this situation the baby would not be affected as this is the first pregnancy, and so Sarah would not have been sensitised yet. However, she would need to have anti-D administered within 72h of childbirth (if the baby is RhD-positive) and after each potentially sensitising event during pregnancy. 

 

The administered anti-D destroys any RhD-positive foetal cells in the maternal circulation before the mother has the opportunity to make an anti-D response.

 

The reason why Rhesus D is so important is that it can result in stillbirth. 

 

Some women become sensitised despite the routine post-natal administration of anti-D (partly because all sensitising events are not recognised antenatally). Therefore, NICE has approved the routine administration of anti-D antenatally (at 28 weeks and again at 34 weeks) in addition to the usual postnatal administration.

Question: Patient presents to A and E with a severe headache and chest pain. During observation you notice papilloedema and blood pressure of 180/120 mmHg. You diagnose the patient with hypertensive crisis and begin a regime of antihypertensive treatment immediately. You take a patient history and find that they are currently taking selegiline (a MAOI) for clinical depression. You ask whether the patient has eaten anything to which she replies that her friend gave her some Stilton cheese at a party. Which of the following amino acids derivatives is she unable to metabolise as a result of taking MAOIs leading to this hypertensive crisis?
Explanation: The correct answer is tyramine. This is derived from the amino acid tyrosine. Monamine oxidase inhibitors are mitochondrial enzymes which inhibit the break down of sertonin and dopamine as well as tyramine. Excessive concentrations of tyramine in blood plasma can lead to hypertensive crisis by increasing the release of noradrenaline (NA), which causes blood vessels to constrict by activating alpha-1 adrenergic receptors. Ordinarily, MAO-A would destroy the excess NA; when MAO-A is inhibited, however, NA levels get too high, leading to dangerous increases in blood pressure.
Tags: Mental health, Neuroanatomy, case 12, Pharmacology, Psychology

Question: Patient comes into and A and E having sustained an injury to their spinal cord. The spinal cord has been incised from the right lateral side to the midline. The resultant injury is described as Brown-Sequard Syndrome. When conducting a neurological examination, you assess pain and temperature perception. Where would you expect to see a loss of pain and temperature sensation in a case of Brown-Sequard syndrome?
OptionA: Ipsilateral loss of pain sensation below the level of the lesion.
OptionB: Contralateral loss of pain sensation below the level of the lesion.
OptionC: Ipsilateral loss of pain sensation above the level of the lesion
OptionD: Contralateral loss of pain sensation above the level of the lesion
Explanation: The spinothalamic tract transmits impulses from receptors which measure crude touch, pain and temperature. The spinothalamic tract comprises the lateral and anterior spinothalamic tracts, the former typically transmits pain and temperature and the latter crude touch and pressure. Neurones transmitting these signals will typically ascend by one or two vertebral levels in Lissaurs tract prior to decussating in the spinal cord itself. Neurones then pass rostrally in the cord to connect at the thalamus.

Question: Where is angiotensinogen produced?

A patient with complex mental health problems who is on a variety of medications comes into the clinic complaining of weight gain. Which of the following medications is likely to be responsible for this side effect?
Explanation: A common side effect of antipsychotics is weight gain

Question: You diagnose a patient with metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation. In respiratory compensation, central chemoreceptors are sensitive to a certain stimulus which causes a response to increase the rate and depth of respiration. What is this stimulus?
Explanation:
Central chemoreceptors respond to a decrease in CSF pH.
Acidosis will increase the concentration of H+ ions in the blood. However, H+ cannot cross the blood brain barrier. 
The H+ ions are combined with bicarbonate to be converted to water and carbon dioxide.
Carbon dioxide can cross the BBB.
Here CO2 is converted back to H+ ions (and bicarbonate).
The increase in H+ ions in the CSF (and therefore decrease in pH) is what triggers central chemoreceptors.

Question:
You are doing some experience in radiology when your help is requested. Very recently A. Man was brought urgently into the hospital. He was given a CT head immediately, but by computer error his scan was mixed in with 4 other unmarked CT scans and you have to choose his correctly from the group. His symptoms on admission were the following:

  • very severe headache - the worst of his life, which came on suddenly and intensely
  • feeling sick/nauseous
  • blurred vision
  • stiff neck

 

Which scan belongs to Mr M?
Explanation:
Our patient's symptoms strongly suggest a subarachnoid haemorrhage, which is the pathology shown in 'B'.

 

  • 'A' is an abscess within the brain. Abscesses often have a brighter perimeter than centre and are self-contained.
  • 'B' is the correct pathology, a subarachnoid haemorrhage. Subarachnoid haemorrhages fill space that normally contains CSF. Instead of CSF, blood pools around the brain, and in an acute phase shows brightly on a CT scan. In 'B' we can see bright blood in the ventricles of the brain.
  • 'C' is a subdural haemorrhage. These are concave or crescent shaped pools of venous blood, not limited by skull sutures - they can extend quite far in a thin crescent shape close on the inside of the skull.
  • 'D' is an extra-dural or epidural haemorrhage. They are biconvex in shape and are limited by skull sutures.
  • 'E' shows a haemorrhagic stroke. The blood is still bright because it is in the acute phase.
Tags: Data interpretation, CT, Neuroanatomy, Case 16, Imaging

Question: During which stage of sleep are K complexes most present?
Explanation: K complexes show up on an EEG during the second stage of Non REM sleep - they help to keep the individual asleep and consolidate memories.

Question: You are in A and E monitoring a patient who has just received a blunt trauma to her occipital lobe. The patient complains of a violent headache, worse than any other headache she has had in her life. You check for papilloedema as a sign for raised intracranial pressure. In order to do so, you dilate the patient's pupils. Which of the following drugs can be used to cause papillary dilation?
Explanation: Tropicamide is a muscarinic receptor antagonist that blocks parasympathetic impulses, paralysing pupil constrictor response and ciliary muscle. This causes the pupil to dilate. The fundus is best viewed through a dilated pupil.

Question:
Dopamine, noradrenaline and adrenaline are sequential products of one biochemical pathway, and are all derived from the amino acid tyrosine in the diet (which can cross the blood brain barrier). 

 

In dopaminergic neurons, L-DOPA is converted to dopamine.

What is the enzyme responsible for this reaction?
Explanation:
The enzyme responsible for converting L-DOPA to dopamine is AADC. AADC is found in the cytoplasm of these neurons, and requires a co-factor derived from Vitamin B6.

 

  • In noradrenergic neurons, dopamine is converted to noradrenaline by DBH. This requires Cu2+ and vitamin C as co-factors. 
  • In the neurons in the adrenal medulla and brainstem that produce adrenaline, PNMT  is expressed and converts noradrenaline to adrenaline.

Question: A 36 year old primigravida women presents at A&E with sudden onset chest pain which is worse on inspiration, tachypnea, a new cough and dizziness. On examination you observe bibasal crackles. What test should you order to confirm the likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
These symptoms are typical of a VTE which pregnancy is a risk factor for because:

  • It's a hypercoagulative state due to increased clotting factors and fibrinogen and decreased fibrinolytic activity 
  • There might be hormone mediated venous distension of compression of the iliac veins, resulting in abnormal blood flow 

During pregnancy the specificity of a D-dimer test is compromised so imaging is needed, therefore A is incorrect 

As she is pregnant you wouldn't want to expose her to any ionising radiation, ruling out B & D 

A doppler ultrasound would be the correct answer if she had presented with symptoms indicating a DVT e.g. painful swelling of the legs, however as her symptoms coincide more with a PE a V/Q scan is the correct answer

Question: A 17-year-old female with a recent diagnosis of type 1 diabetes presents to her GP with her parents. They report that their daughter is less outgoing and assertive than she was prior to the diagnosis. What personality change following the diagnosis is most likely being described?
Explanation:
Her parents report that she is less sociable and assertive. Lowered extraversion meets the criteria described by her parents and is also common following a diagnosis of this nature. Lowered conscientiousness is usually associated with poor adherence to treatment

 

Case 12, Personality health and wellbeing workbook

Question: A public health research team is interested in studying the relationship between emotional instability and the presence of mental and/or physical health concerns. What personality trait would they most likely be interested in?
Explanation:
Emotional instability, vulnerability to stress, tendency towards anger and depression and excessive worry are associated with neuroticism. This personality trait has also been the centre of much public health research given its robust association with a number of mental and physical health problems.

 

Case 12, Personality health and wellbeing workbook

Question: A 30-year-old man is administered the Big 5 personality test and scores highly on neuroticism whilst scoring low on extraversion. Which temperament does this most accurately correspond to?
Explanation: Harm avoidance is directly associated with neuroticism whilst inversely related to extraversion

Question:
During adolescent brain development there is changes in the the densities of particular regions.

 

Which of these answers best describes the density in after post-puberty?
OptionA: White matter density decreases, Grey matter increases.
OptionB: White matter density decreases, Grey matter density increases.
OptionC: White matter density increases, Grey matter density increases.
OptionD: White matter density increases, Grey matter density decreases.
OptionE: White matter density increases, grey matter density unaffected.
Explanation:
Reason for grey matter density decrease is known = It increases until puberty. After puberty it decreases =may be experience-dependent process of synaptic overproduction followed by pruning.

 

White matter volume increases during adolescence linearly.

Question: Puberty is characterised by 3 endocrine events: adrenarche, gonadarche and activation of the growth axis.  which of the following best describes adrenarche?
OptionA: increase in DHEA + DHEAS leading to development of secondary sexual characteristics
OptionC: pulsatile secretion of GnRH from hypothalamus during sleep
OptionD: production of LH + FSH in anterior pituitary leading to secretion of oestrogen and testosterone
OptionE: secretion of growth hormone from anterior pituitary
Explanation:
adrenarche (6-9 in females) = activation of HPA axis, increase in adrenal androgens (DHEA + DHEAS), leading to development of secondary sexual characteristics

gonadarche (8-14 in females) = reactivation of HPA axia, pulsatile secretions of GnRH from hypothalamus during sleep, stimulates production of LH + FSH, leading to secretion of gonadal steroid oestrogen and testosterone

 

growth axis (~12 in females) = GH secreted from anterior pituitary during sleep resulting in linear growth spurt

 

males tend to go through the stages a little later than females

Question: Which syndrome is described as the delusional belief that different people are in fact a single person who changes appearance or is in disguise?
Explanation:
D is the correct answer

 

Couvade syndrome is a proposed condition in which a partner experiences some of the same symptoms and behaviour as an expectant mother. Men believing they are pregnant

 

Othello syndrome is sometimes called delusional or pathological jealousy and is a psychological disorder in which a person is preoccupied with the thought that their spouse or sexual partner is being unfaithful without having any real proof, along with socially unacceptable or abnormal behaviour related to these thoughts.

 

Capgras syndrome is psychiatric disorder in which a person holds a delusion that a friend, spouse, parent, or other close family member (or pet) has been replaced by an identical impostor. Feelings for that person might then be lost

 

Ekbom's syndrome is a delusional disorder in which individuals incorrectly believe they are infested with parasites, insects, or bugs, whereas in reality no such infestation is present. Individuals with delusional parasitosis usually report tactile hallucinations known as formication, a sensation resembling insects crawling on or under the skin.

Question: In which stage of sleep would you be most likely to see delta waves on an EEG?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer. Delta waves represent slow wave sleep which is seen in NREM stage 3, which is when we are fast asleep and less responsive to the environment. You are hard to wake in this stage of sleep and the higher the number of slow waves, the deeper the NREM sleep is.

Theta waves can bee seen in NREM stage 2 which is light sleep.

John, a 65 year old man, has recently been diagnosed with Parkinson's disease. 

As a 2nd year medical student on a home visit, he begins to tell you about some of the signs and symptoms he experienced as a result of the Parkinson's disease. He said that he had been experiencing tremors in his hands, his muscles had become stiff and he had found his movements slowing down. He said his wife had also started to notice changes in his speech, and that he found it difficult to walk any distance without falling over.

 

Dopamine neuronal degeneration results in Parkinson's disease, although what specific area of the brain does this occur in?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D, the substantial nigra. 

The substantial nigra is a nucleus in the midbrain, and is considered part of the basal ganglia. It has two parts: pars compact and pars reticulate. 

 

Most of the dopamine neurons of the brain originate in the midbrain, and are found in either the substantial nigra or the ventral tegmental area. 

 

Nucleus Accumbens

Found in the basal forebrain, and 95% of the medium spiny neurons in this region are GABA producing.

The mesolimbic pathway feeds into here from the VTA, and has a role in reward, pleasure and addiction.

 

Locus Coeruleus

In the rostral pons, and contains the largest cluster of noradrenergic neurons (but other clusters are also found in the medulla). It provides the majority of noradrenaline to the cerebral cortex, and has been implicated in arousal (wakefulness and alertness). 

 

Raphe Nuclei

5HT neutrons are confined here, with a mix of other neurons. However, they have extensive projections so that virtually every neuron in the brain may be contacted by a serotonergic fibre.

 

Ventral Tegmental Area

In the brainstem, close to the substantial nigra (the two regions of the brain that contain the majority of dopamine neurons). 

The VTA is part of two dopamine pathways:

Mesolimbic - connects the VTA to the nucleus accumbens

Mesocortical - connects the VTA to the cortical areas, the frontal lobes.

Question:
Lewis, an 18 year old man, visits his GP 4 months after starting a course of citalopram. He first presented to the GP with fatigue, low mood and had lost interest in his hobbies, when he was diagnosed with depression. He had also been having suicidal thoughts for a prolonged period of time.

 

On questioning him, these thoughts had not resolved and he was now feeling lower than ever, as he 'thought he couldn't be cured'. He starts asking for amitriptyline, saying that his father had been taking that specific type of anti-depressant and it had made a big difference with his depression.

 

What is the main reason why Lewis can't be prescribed amitriptyline?
OptionA: They cause lots of unpleasant side effects.
OptionB: They are dangerous as there a risk of increased blood pressure and heart rate.
OptionC: They are dangerous to people who may consider to overdose as it is a voltage-sensitive Na+ channel blocker, which can cause arrhythmia.
OptionD: Amitriptyline will be ineffective for him if citalopram didn't help, and so he requires a different course of treatment.
OptionE: Lewis is only 18 and you have to be 21 to be prescribed amitriptyline.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B - amitriptyline is a tricyclic antidepressant, and this class in particular should not be given to someone who is at risk of overdose due to the fact that they are voltage-sensitive Na+ channel blockers, and this can lead to arrhythmia. Lewis has expressed the fact that he has been having suicidal thoughts (which his father could not have been having if he had been prescribed amitriptyline), and so it would not be the best option to prescribe a TCA. 

 

Whilst A is correct, B is the best answer in this scenario as the unpleasant side effects would not be the most serious reason as to why amitriptyline should not be prescribed. These side effects depend on the receptors that they block:

  • mAch = drowsiness, blurred vision, dry mouth, constipation.
  • H1 (histamine)= weight gain, drowsiness.
  • a1 (adrenergic)= dizziness, hypotension.

 

It is SNRIs that are the class of antidepressants that have a risk of increased blood pressure and heart rate.

Question:
A 26 year-old woman (gravida 2, para 1) comes into the GP surgery in her first trimester, complaining of mild stomach cramps, back pain, and white-pink mucus in her pants when she goes to the toilet. After some more discussing and a test, you conclude that the woman has had a miscarriage.

 

The patient is a geneticist, and asks if there is any genetic reason as to why she could have had a miscarriage. You are thinking of a specific chromosomal abnormality that is most common trisomy leading to miscarriage and the second most common chromosomal cause of it. What condition are you thinking of?
Explanation:
A - trisomy 21

B - trisomy 18

C - trisomy 13

D - trisomy 16 (Trisomy 16 is a chromosomal abnormality in which there are 3 copies of chromosome 16 rather than two. It is the most common trisomy leading to miscarriage and the second most common chromosomal cause of it, closely following X-chromosome monosomy. About 6% of miscarriages have trisomy 16. Those mostly occur between 8 to 15 weeks after the last menstrual period.)

E - monosomy X (most common chromosomal cause of miscarriage but not a trisomy)

 

Half of first trimester miscarriages are due to chromosomal abnormalities (most common are trisomy 16, Turner syndrome, triploidy).
Trisomy often caused by non-disjunction = error with homologous chromosomes lining up.

 

Case 7 chromosomal abnormalities lecture

Question: From which germ layer is the Epidermis derived?
What is the cardiomyopathy characterised by fibro-fatty infiltration, ventricular dilatation and hyper-trabeculation?
Explanation:
A - A condition characterised by cardiac enlargement with reduced systolic function, absence of primary valve disease, and non-significant coronary artery disease

 

B - >15mm Wall thickness in one or more segments by any imaging modality. A condition causing ↑ wall thickness that is not explained solely by loading conditions.

 

C - Other types of cardiomyopathy that dont fit into the other subtypes e.g. Left ventricular non-compaction, tokosubo cardiomyopathy (probs dont need to know these)

 

D - Normal cardiac size, reduced systolic and diastolic function, and bi-atrial dilatation. Usually resulting from an MI

 

E - CORRECT

Question: Research has shown how Michael Jackson was able to pull of his gravity-defying lean in Smooth Criminal. What is even more impressive is that whilst trying to copy his move, some of the researchers actually ruptured their achilles tendons. If you smacked these people on the ankle with a tendon hammer, they would probably be quite cross, but it's likely their ankle jerk reflex would also be dampened. Disc herniation at which spinal level could cause the reflex to be absent completely?
Explanation:
Planter flexion is controlled by the S1 myotome. For a disc herniation to interrupt this reflex we are looking at the L5/S1 level.
