Question:
Your flatmate, an art student, has come home one day and is proudly showing off their new mosaic piece. You scoff and exclaim that that isn't even real mosaicism.

"What do you mean!?" the offended flatmate says. Provide one impressive (true) statement about mosaicism in genetics.
OptionB: Germline mosaicism’ is when the mutated cells are not present in a person’s testes or ovaries
OptionC: More obvious/severe features (if mosaic with normal karyotype)
OptionD: Mosaicism can allow severe chromosomal abnormalities to be viable
OptionE: Mosaicism is when an extra chromosome is present in all of someone's cells
Explanation:
A - actually Due to post-zygotic errors in mitosis

B - actually germline mosaicism’ is when the mutated cells are only present in a person’s testes or ovaries

C - actually milder features (if mosaic with normal karyotype)

D - correct e.g. mosaic trisomy 8, mosaic trisomy 22

E - actually mosaicism is when an extra chromosome is present in only a proportion of someone's cells

 

Case 7 lecture on chromosomal abnormalities

Question:
A 12 year-old male and his mother come into GP clinic one afternoon. The boy has just been diagnosed with a chromosomal aneuploidy. He is tall, and has normal levels of testosterone (and fertility).

 

His mother tells you she is worried because she has seen in the media that people with these traits often become increasingly aggressive and behave anti-socially, but her son has not yet shown any behavioural changes.

 

What chromosomal aneuploidy is he likely to have been diagnosed with?
Explanation:
A - Klinefelter syndrome (Pubertal gynaecomastia, Small testes, delayed/incomplete development of secondary sexual characteristics, Relatively tall stature, infertility)

B - Correct (XYY) syndrome

C - Turner's syndrome (Short stature, neck webbing, broad chest, Lack of sexual development at puberty, primary amenorrhoea, infertility, normal intelligence, Heart defects)

D - normal karyotype

E - few symptoms, normal intelligence, mild delay in motor/language/reading skills, tall. However this condition would be associated with having a daughter not a son, and this isn't related to perceived aggression.

Question:
A slim, 15-year-old boy presents at the GP with his mother, who explains that he has been very confused recently and has been drinking excessive amounts of water and going to the loo very frequently. You notice that his breath smells of pear-drops. You are instantly worried about him as you know what the diagnosis is from attending all your lectures. 

 

Given his condition, what will have happened to his anion gap?
OptionD: the anion gap is not relevant in this condition
Explanation:
This is a presentation of a type 1 diabetic with DKA.

 

Look at where the anion gap is labelled on the following diagram: 

 

In DKA there is increased ketones and lactate, which are unmeasured anions which make up the anion gap. This means that the anion gap will increase in this boy. 

 

An example of a time when you would have a normal anion gap despite having an acid-base problem would be if you had an increase in HCl. This is because the H+ ions react with the HCO3- to decrease this section and the Cl- ions enter the Cl- section (what a surprise) to increase this, and so they balance out and the anion gap remains the same.

 

I hope this is helpful, I'm still getting my head around it so if anyone has anything to add/any corrections please let me know!

Its a casual Thursday at WOW bar in Cardiff centre, and the drag queens are out in force. You've had a couple AbsolutTM  cocktails, and are loving one beautiful queen in particular. As she glides past, you scream 'YAAAAS FISH' in appreciation.

 

You are reminded that you actually have some coursework due tomorrow on 22q11.2 deletion syndrome, and how FISH is related to this condition. At this point, you're so tipsy, you can't actually remember what the acronym FISH stands for.

Question: Malformations are a type of genetic abnormality that result during the formation of structures. At what point in gestation do most malformations originate?
Explanation:
Malformations occur during formation of structures (e.g. organogenesis – critical period); causes are environmental/genetic factors acting independently or in concert (most originate during 3-8 weeks of gestation)

 

Case 7 lecture on congenital malformations

Question:
A 30-year old primiparous mother of Maori descent (New Zealand) brings her newborn baby into the clinic. The woman gave birth at home, and has not yet seen any healthcare professionals. She tells you that there is something wrong with her babies feet, as they are both rotated inwards and downwards.

 

You identify this as clubfoot, a type of congenital abnormality. What type of congenital abnormality is this?
Explanation:
A - Deformations are mechanical factors that mould foetal parts over prolonged periods (e.g. clubfeet result from compression in the amniotic cavity)

B - Disruptions are alterations of pre-existing structures due to destructive processes (e.g. amniotic band syndrome)

C - Malformations occur during formation of structures (e.g. organogenesis – critical period); causes are environmental/genetic factors acting independently or in concert (most originate during 3-8 weeks of gestation)

D - Sequence e.g. oligohydramnios: not always possible to determine what causes low levels of amniotic fluid

E - Syndrome = a pattern of malformations occurring together considered to have a specific common cause. Term indicates diagnosis made and risk of recurrence is known (e.g. amniotic band syndrome/FAS)

 

Clubfoot occurs in about one in 1,000 newborns. The condition is less common among the Chinese and more common among Maori. Males are affected about twice as often as females. Treatment can be carried out by a range of healthcare providers and can generally be achieved in the developing world with few resources.

 

From case 7 lecture on congenital malformations and teratology plenary.

Question: A deficiency in which Toll-like-receptor (TLR) signalling pathway is associated with recurrent herpes simplex encephalitis?
Explanation:
The primary site of infection for HSV-1 is oral mucosa. HSV-1 is then transported through sensory neurones to the trigeminal nerves and ganglia where it establishes a latent infection. Rarely, HSV invades the brain via trigeminal nerves causing Herpes simplex encephalitis (HSE).

 

Susceptibility to recurrent HSE is associated with TLR3 signalling pathway defects and a failure of neurones to produce type I interferons.

 

It may be confusing that HSV-1 is a DNA virus but TLR3 detects dsRNA...This is because HSV-1 produces a dsRNA intermediate during transcription, so can be detected by TLR3. 

 

(from case 9 immunology lecture 1)

Question:
A 20 year old primagravida, Miss Ding-Dong, presents to your surgery. She has recently been experiencing spells of dizziness and almost fainting and is worried that this is abnormal and harmful to the baby. You measure her blood pressure which shows a low blood pressure.

You go on to explain to her that this could be due to a certain hormone - related to her pregnancy - which is causing her blood vessels to dilate, so there is less resistance, causing a lower blood pressure. Which hormone associated with pregnancy is a has a vasodilatory effect on blood vessels?
Explanation: Progesterone has been found to modulate vasoconstriction tone during pregnancy and causes increased dilation of blood vessels. This increases blood flow to the foetus, which ultimately reduces blood flow to the mothers organs - hence the dizziness.

Question:
A 15 year-old girl comes into the GP surgery presenting with severe acne, and says that she has tried many other treatments, including over-the-counter and some from the pharmacy.

 

You think about prescribing the patient Isotretinoin/Accutane (13-cis-retinoic acid), which can be used for the treatment of acne and other similar dermatological problems. However it is highly teratogenic, and so you ask the patient "is there any possibility that you may be pregnant?"

She answers no, and at the end of the consultation you go onto prescribe the drug. Accutane is an analogue of which vitamin?
Explanation:
Isotretinoin/Accutane (13-cis-retinoic acid) is an analogue of Vitamin A (treatment of acne and similar dermatological problems).


It mustn’t be used by patients who are/may become pregnant:
- Extremely high risk; severe birth defects result if pregnancy occurs whilst taking Accutane in any amount, even for short periods of time
- Messes with developmental signaling molecules e.g. Sonic Hedgehog proteins
- Potentially any foetus exposed can be affected
- Birth defects include facial abnormalities, ears, eyes, skull, CNS, CV system
- Increased risk of spontaneous abortion/premature births reported

 

Case 7 congenital malformations and teratology lecture

Question: The corpus luteum is the primary source of oestrogen during pregnancy. What takes over from the CL?
Explanation:
The placenta takes over as the source of eostrogen and progesterone. 

Before pregnancy, oestrogen is produced by the ovaries, in response to FSH. It stimulates the granulosa cells. 

The synthesis starts in the theca interna cells, the synthesis of androstenedione from cholesterol. 

The granulosa cells then convert it into oestrogen (maybe via testosterone).

Question:
A couple (Mr and Mrs W) comes to visit the sexual health clinic, and tell you that they are having trouble conceiving, as they have been trying for a child for 6 months since the woman got her coil removed. The woman is a 34 year-old primary school teacher, and the man is 39 years-old and works in a bakery.

Mr W states how "it can't be a problem with my sperm, I've heard that at ejaculation 200-600 million sperm are deposited around the external os of the uterus and in the fornix of the vagina".

 

Apart from being surprised at his detailed anatomical knowledge of the vagina, you explain to Mr W that although this is true, only x number of sperm actually end up reaching the site of fertilisation (and this is in a healthy male with no fertility issues).

 

What is the best estimate of 'x'?
Explanation:
- At ejaculation 200-600 million sperms are deposited around the external os of the uterus and in the fornix of the vagina (ejaculate averages 3.5ml range 2-6ml)
- Sperm moves 2-3mm/min (pH affects rate)
- Motile sperm have been found at the ampulla 5 minutes after deposition at the external os (some take up to 45 min), only about 200 reach the site of fertilisation

 

- Normal male 100 million/ml of semen, but 20-50 million/ml = probably fertile
- Number and motility- at least 40% should be motile after 2 hours and some should still be motile after 24hrs

 

I also chucked in the fact Mr W worked in a bakery, just to draw attention to the fact that certain activities can affect male fertility e.g. working in a hot environment such as a bakery all day.

 

Case 7 early human development plenary

Question:
A 70-year-old patient presents to your clinic diagnosed recently with a heart arrhythmia.

 

Patient history notes show:

- Recently diagnosed with primary hypertension (165/92 mmHg), not treated.

- Chronic shoulder pain treated with chronic Ibuprofen.

- 9-10 alcoholic drinks/week. No smoking history.

- Recent diagnosis of liver Cirrhosis

- Occupation: Retired.

 

You preform a ECG to confirm the diagnosis for your-self before starting the patient on pharmacotherapy. The ECG strip on lead II shows:

 

Which of the following options is the best next course of action?
OptionA: Change pain management treatment, treat patient hypertension and prescribe bisoprolol and anti-coagulant.
OptionC: Preform INR check before prescribing an anti-coagulant.
OptionD: Prescribe the patient anti-coagulants due to high risk of stroke.
OptionE: Prescribe the patient anti-coagulant and bisoprolol as they have high risk of stroke.
Explanation:
A) Correct - Reduces HASBLED score, provides better benefit-to-harm ratio.

B) Incorrect - Patient has CHADVASC score of 2, so requires anti-coagulant medication as well. (This is a score of 1 or more).

C) Wrong - Whether INR is high or low, the patient has a very high HASBLED score. The patient has score of 5 already, and scores over 5 are rare.

D) Wrong - wrong as HASBLED score is very high

 

E) Incorrect - Without changes to the persons habit and hypertension, prescribing anti-coagulants immediately can be very risky.

 

Explanation: Patient has Atrial Fibrillation

CHADVASC score: 2/9 (Risk of stoke = 2.2%)

HASBLED score: 5/9 (Risk of annual bleeding = 9.1%)

However, treatment must not be withheld to those with high bleeding risk, due to benefits of anti-coagulants. Instead, the patient can reduce their hasbled risk by not taking NSAIDs, and being prescribed other pain killers. Encouraging reducation of alcohol intake, treating their untreated hypertension. All these factors can reduce the HASBLED score to 3, which is even more beneficial.

Question:
A 24 year-old woman comes in for her first pregnancy dating scan, which puts her at 9 weeks. She is confused, because she's sure she had her LMP more recently than that.

 

You explain to her that after fertilisation, during the process of implantation, specific cells can rupture some of the vessels, forming 'blood islands'. This can often be confused for a woman's last menstrual period (LMP).

 

Which 'specific cells' are you referring to?
Explanation:
Syncytiotrophoblasts have no cell boundaries. They give rise to Cytotrophoblasts. 

Syncytio-trophoblasts rupture vessels to form blood islands. Bleeds at this time can be confused for a woman’s most recent menstrual bleed.

Question:
A 65 year old man comes into clinic complaining of lower back and leg pain lasting 3 months. He tells you that the pain is worst on walking - particularly when walking down hills and says that the pain is sometimes accompanied by tingling in both legs. When asked if anything relieves his pain he replies ‘rest and sitting in a chair or crouching.’

 

You decide to complete a back examination. You notice the patient has good flexion of the lumbar spine but extension is limited. The straight leg raise test is negative.  

 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
A - this is worth considering as the patient complains of claudication (pain in the leg on activity). However, vascular claudication is usually relieved by standing up opposed to sitting down. You may also observe trophic changes to the skin during examination in vascular disease. 

 

B - this is the correct answer. Firstly the patient is over 50 which is an important risk factor for spinal stenosis. Moreover there is noticeable pain on extension. For example the patient says the pain is worst walking down hills but relieved by sittting. Extension of the lumbar spine narrows the spinal canal and can increase pressure on nervous tissue. This explains the patient’s neurogenic claudication.

 

C - although the patient complained of tingling in both legs the straight leg raise is negative. Moreover patients with prolapsed IV disc usually find it uncomfortable to sit.

 

D - the history does not fit with this diagnosis. Moreover metastatic cord compression is a medical emergency and the patient will often present acutely with ‘hard’ neurological signs such as loss of bowel control.

Question:
Long QT syndrome is a disorder of the heart's electrical activity. It can cause sudden, uncontrollable, dangerous arrhythmias in response to exercise or stress.

 

Long QT syndrome can be inherited. What kind of inheritance pattern does it display?
Explanation:
Autosomal dominant conditions: E.g. Huntington/Marfans/Familial hypercholesterolaemia/hereditary breast and ovarian cancer/long QT syndrome.
RISK: the risk of inheriting an autosomal dominant condition from an affected parent is 50/50, but the risk of being affected by the condition depends on the penetrance.
P(risk of child being affected by the same condition as the parent)

 

From case 7 lecture on family history and probabilities

Question: You are stationed in A&E when your senior adviser asks you to perform an emergency Fresh Frozen Plasma (FFP) transfusion to a road traffic accident patient. If the patient's blood group is A+, which of the following blood groups should NOT be administered to the patient in an FFP transfusion?
Explanation:
I found this confusing at first but it made sense when I got my head around it. 

 

Red blood cells express antigens reflecting their group (e.g. A expresses A); they will produce antibodies against other RBCs expressing different antigens (e.g. A produces anti-B); these antibodies will be present in the PLASMA. 

With RBC transfusions, O- is the universal donor (no antigens expressed) while AB+  is the universal receiver (both antigens expressed), because you don't want the patient's RBCs to produce antibodies against the donor's RBCs. 

However, FFP is the other way round, where AB- is the universal donor (no antibodies present) while O+ is the universal receiver (both antibodies present), because you don't want to give antibodies to the patient. 

 

Knowing that:

A) Same blood group is always fine. 

B) Guidelines do not require FFP to be Rh-compatible. 

C) AB+ is the universal donor for FFP.

 

Hope this makes sense :)

Question:
A man comes into your practice complaining of weight gain, feeling tired, constipation and depression. Examination reveals a large painless goitre on the man's neck. You send for a thyroid function tests. The test results reveal:

 

 

High TSH

Low FT3/FT4

Presence of anti-thyroglobulin Antibody 

Presence of anti-thyroid peroxidase Antibody. 

 

Which of the following most is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Based on the test results we know that the condition must be hypothyroidism. This can be inferred by the elevated levels of TSH, yet low levels of free T3 and free T4. This suggests a primary cause of hyperthyroidism as the thyroid gland isn't responding to the stimulus to secrete FT3 and FT4. 

 

The presents of the anti-thyroglobulin and anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies suggests an autoimmune condition. Hence the condition must be Hashimoto's. This fits with the signs and symptoms observed in the history and examination. 

 

Note, thyroglobulin is a precursor of the thyroid hormones T3 and T4. 

Also of note, T4 is far more abundant that T3. However, T3 is far more active, as such peripherally T4 is often converted to T3 and rT3 (reverse T3, inactive).

This is relevant as various conditions might skew such concentrations. 

The T3 to rT3 ratio is usually equal, however in pregnancy, liver/renal failure, fasting, beta blockers etc we can see this shift towards rT3. 

 

For more information I thoroughly recommend the following video along with the lecture relating to thyroid function in Case 10. This appears to be a popular topic in SBAs for the progress test.

Question: You are recalling some of the histology that you've been taught over the past two years. MHC 1 receptors are vital for the action of cytotoxic T cells in recognising pathogenic non-self antigens. Which of the following cells does not express MHC 1 receptors?
Explanation: MHC 1 receptors are expressed on all nucleated cells found in the body. Since erythrocytes do not have a nucleus, they do not express MHC 1. Whereas MHC 2 receptors are expressed only on antigen presenting cells (APCs).

Question: A 21 year old woman comes to your clinic complaining of dry eyes and scaling skin. On examination you note superficial foamy patches on her conjunctiva (Bitot spots) and thickening of the cornea. Which of the following fat soluble vitamins is the patient most likely deficient in?
Explanation:
Vitamin A deficiency causes keratinisation and subsequent drying of the eye, skin and mucous membranes. The foamy patches that develop in the conjunctiva are clumps of keratin debris. Corneal thickening occurs. 

 

Vitamin B12 is not a fat soluble vitamin.

Question: In an effort to procrastinate as much as possible, you taken up watching Star Trek on Netflix. You notice that Mr Spock has an affinity for abducting his fingers. Which myotome is primarily responsible for this movement?
Explanation:
Most muscles in the upper and lower limbs receive innervation from more than one spinal nerve root. They are therefore comprised of multiple myotomes. For example, the biceps brachii muscle performs flexion at the elbow. It is innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, which is derived from C5, C6 and C7 nerve roots. All three of these spinal nerve roots can be said to be associated with elbow flexion.

The list below details which movement is most strongly associated with each myotome:

 

C5 – Elbow flexion
C6 – Wrist extension
C7 – Elbow extension
C8 – Finger flexion
T1 – Finger abduction
L2 – Hip flexion
L3 – Knee extension
L4 – Ankle dorsiflexion
L5 – Great toe extension
S1 – Ankle plantarflexion
Tags: Myotomes, Case 14, ISCE, neurology, Clinical Tests

Question: Mrs Jones comes into hospital with a hip fracture. She is diagnosed with a bone disease. Her blood results show normal calcium, phosphate and PTH (parathyroid hormone) levels, however an elevation in alkaline phosphatase. What bone condition does she have?
Explanation:
• The answer is A, Paget's disease. There is osteoclast over activity followed by osteoblast compensatory over activity- which leads to release of more alkaline phosphatase.
  • In osteoporosis, calcium, phosphate, alk phos and PTH would be normal
  • In bone metastases, calcium, phosphate and alk phos would be high and PTH low.
  • In osteomalacia, calcium and phosphate would be low, whilst alk phos and PTH would be high/normal
  • Primary hyperparathyroidism would have high/normal calcium, low/normal phosphate, high/normal alk phos and high PTH.

Question:
A 74 year old female has presented at A&E with a wrist fracture. This is her 3rd fracture in the past 2 years which sets off alarm bells in your head. You decide to conduct a blood test and after struggling with her wriggly veins for an eternity you finally manage to get a sample. The results show the following: 

  • High PTH 
  • High ALP 
  • High Phosphate 
  • Normal Calcium

Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Renal osteodystrophy is when the kidney fails to regulate Ca and PO4 correctly

As the Kidneys are malfunctioning, no calcitriol is synthesised resulting in decreased Ca absorption in the duodenum. PTH increases to compensate, activating osteoclasts so more bone is resorbed and hence Ca & PO4 are released - this is why Ca levels are often normal or slightly low, and PTH & PO4 is high

 

The other differentials would have had different blood test results: 

  • Osteomalacia = low calcium and phosphate and high/normal ALP & PTH 
  • Bone metastases = high Ca, phosphate and ALP and low PTH 
  • Paget's disease = normal apart from raised ALP
  • Osteoporosis = all normal

Question:
You perform an ECG on Patient X, to reaffirm the type of cardiac arrhythmia you suspect the patient has. Lead II showed:

 

Today (2 month later) you call patient X into your clinic. You order another ECG to monitor the progression of their condition. Lead II shows:

 

The pathology in the most recent ECG compared to the previous indicates a progression towards which most probable condition?
Explanation:
Explanation: In the first ECG the patient shows atrial flutter.

  • Atrial flutter pathology = a condition which there is re-entrant conduction around the atria. However the AV node may still block excess signals and patients present with normal QRS. Resultantly, atria will beat faster due to this re-entrant signal and hence multiple p-waves may present with for one normal QRS.
  • Atrial flutter variations = A patient with AV node heart block, may hence present with more p-waves to 1 QRS. However, sympathetic stimulation may in fact reduce AV refractory period, and patients can present with 1:1 p-wave to QRS ratio. Therefore this presents as ventricular fibrillation, which is an emergency.

A) Incorrect - as the initial diagnoses was atrial flutter. Further, AF shows irregular irregular on ECG.

B) Incorrect - Wrong pathology for both ECG's. The shape shown in the ECG is similar to ST depression, however this is wrong.

C) Incorrect - Would present as an ST-elevation.

D) Correct - Patient has atrial flutter due to saw-tooth shape, with a 3:1 ratio. Second ECG you can see a 1:1 P-wave:QRS complex. This means AV block has reduced (cause is usually increased sympathetic drive). This can cause ventricular fibrillation, where ventricle beats 200-300bpm. Which is extremely dangerous.

E) Incorrect - Likely in the fact that we can see tachycardia, however, broad (wide) or narrow complex tachycardia's arise look different on ECG and arise from different pathology than atrial flutter.

Question: While one placement in a paediatric clinic you observe a paediatric exam of a baby born with incontinentia pigmenti. Your registrar says that this condition is only ever seen in female babies. Why is this?

OptionD: It is caused by there HPV virus

Explanation:
incontinentia pigmenti is caused by the mutation in the NEMO gene on the X chromosome. It is X linked dominant therefore males cannot survive as they only have 1 X so cannot compensate. Question: You are conducting a peripheral vascular examination on a patient with a history of diabetes mellitus. They complain of leg pain upon exertion and have developed an ulcer on one of their toes. Examination reveals a bruit in the popliteal fossa, a decreased capillary refill time and ABI of 0.3. Given this information, what is the most likely cause of the following ulcer in this patient?
Explanation:
The correct answer is arterial. Arterial ulcers form due to a poor perfusion of arterial blood to tissue. There will be little exudate, and the surrounding skin is more likely to be cool to the touch, pale, cyanotic (bluish due to lack of oxygen), and hairless.

 

Within the wound bed, you may find necrotic (dead) tissue as well as tissue that is pale because of the lack of blood. The wound itself will be deep and regular in shape, with a round, “punched-out” look. Arterial ulcers most often occur on the outer ankle (lateral malleolus), and around the toes including the tips, between the toes, and the phalangeal heads—areas that are subject to trauma and rubbing. The bottom line? If you recall that a lack of blood flow is the issue (through visualization), it’s easier to remember that this type of ulcer occurs on the farthest extremities.

 

Venous ulcers are caused by venous hypertension leading to a pooling of venous blood in the lower extremities. This tends to cause an exudative wound which is brown/purple in colour due to the accumulation of haemosiderin as RBC are pushed from the capillaries. Irregular wound margins, shallow wound.

http://blog.wcei.net/2017/07/venous-vs-arterial-ulcers-whats-the-difference

Question:
Kayleigh presents at the GP with her 1 year old daughter, Molly. She has come to ask some questions about the MMR vaccine, which Molly is due to have in a couple of days. She is concerned about some of the articles she has read on the internet about the safety of the vaccine, and is also worried because Molly has a cough.

 

Towards the end of the consultation, Kayleigh expresses her interest in the varicella vaccine. She has heard that it isn't on the routine vaccination schedule in the UK, although wants to know if Molly can have it the day after her MMR vaccine as she is concerned about Molly contracting chickenpox.

 

You explain to Kayleigh that Molly will not be able to have the varicella vaccine the day after the MMR vaccine, although what is the main reason for this?
OptionA: There is an increased risk of the MMR vaccine failing if the varicella vaccine is given close afterwards.
OptionB: Molly has a cough, and therefore both vaccines will not work and Kayleigh would be better bringing Molly in a few weeks instead when she is better.
OptionC: Molly is not old enough for the varicella vaccine.
OptionD: The varicella vaccine is not available at all in the UK.
OptionE: There is an increased risk of the varicella vaccine failing if it is given shortly after the MMR vaccine.
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. 

The immune response to one live virus vaccine may be impaired if administered within 30 days of another live virus vaccine. 

 

People who received the varicella vaccine less than 30 days after the MMR vaccination had an increased risk of the varicella vaccine failing.

 

As they are both live, attenuated vaccines they would each potentially generate an interferon response - the interferon response to the first vaccine (in this case, the MMR vaccine) would suppress the replication of the second vaccine (the varicella vaccine) and thereby diminish the immune response to this second vaccine. 

 

As in this case Molly would be having the MMR vaccine first followed by the varicella vaccine a few days later, it is likely that it would be the varicella vaccine that would fail.

 

  • B is incorrect as a cough would not prevent Molly from having her MMR vaccine. It is only if the child has a fever in illness that the vaccine should be postponed.
  • C is incorrect as the varicella vaccine can be given from age 1.
  • D is incorrect as the varicella vaccine is available in the UK, it just isn't routinely available on the vaccination schedule. The NHS guidelines state that it is recommended for non-immune healthcare workers and people who come into contact with others who have a weakened immune system. The vaccine should be avoided in those with a weakened immune system, in anyone who has a had a serious allergic reaction to a previous dose of the vaccine or to any of the ingredients in the vaccine, in pregnant women and anyone who is seriously unwell.

Question:
You are working in a pathology lab over the summer. You are presented with a 21 year old athlete who died suddenly in the gym. You are performing a post-mortem to find a potential cause of death. You look at some myocardium histology to reveal the following pattern:

 

 

You notice that the tissue appears to be in disarray. Which of the following cardiomyopathies best fits this histological presentation?
Explanation: The correct answer is hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. This is the most common cause of sudden death in young adults. It arises due to an excessive number of sarcomeres being inserted in parallel leading to hypertrophy. Commonly caused by an autosomal dominant genetic condition. Classical histological pattern reveals myocyte disarray as seen in the question stem. For more refer to the non-ischaemic cardiomyopathy lecture.
Tags: Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 15, Heart, Histology

Question: Amphetamine is a drug of abuse which causes locomotor stimulation, euphoria, insomnia, anorexia, and increased stamina. Which of these best describe its mechanism of action?
OptionB: Disrupts dopamine and noradrenaline packaging into vesicles
OptionD: Mimics the action of dopamine by binding to its receptors (dopamine agonist)
Explanation:
B is the MoA of amphetamine. It enters the nerve terminal of the presynaptic cell via DA and NA transporters and disrupts their packaging into vesicles. This increases the concentration of DA and NA in the cytosol, which causes the transporters to reverse and pump DA and NA out into the synaptic cleft. 

 

A is the MoA of cocaine. 

C is the MoA of MDMA. 

D is made up. 

E is the MoA of caffeine.

Question: Which is the most common type of brain herniation?
Explanation: Cingulate or subfalcine herniation is when the innermost part of the frontal lobe is scraped under the falx cerebri.

Question:
Blood tests from one of your patients has just come back confirming that the patient has tested positive for Hepatitis. The confirmed positive virus is a Flavivirus. 

 

What type of Hepatitis is your patient infected with?
Explanation:
C is correct. This is the same viral family as the Dengue and Yellow fever viruses. These are all (+) SS RNA viruses. 

 

A - Hep A is a Picornavirus. 

B - Hep B is a Hepadnavirus. It is also a DNA virus and is very very small in size. 

D - Hep D is also a Hepadnavirus and you can only get Hep D if you have Hep B.

E - Hep E is a Calicivirus and is only a worry in pregnant women.

Question:
You are a GP and your next patient is 18 year old male. He has just started out as a trainee mortician and his employer has told him that he thus requires a new immunisation. 

 

What immunisation is required?
Explanation: Hepatitis B immunisation is needed for certain occupations. These include HCW (health care workers), lab staff, prison officers, social workers and morticians

Question: Which of the following is not part of the 5 factor model of personality?
Explanation: Assertiveness is not one of the 'big five'. Extraversion is the missing factor. From the case 12 virtual workbooks

Question:
This child has a bow-legged (varus) deformity. 

 

 

What nutrient are they likely to be deficient in?
Explanation:
This child has rickets, which is caused by vitamin D deficiency. Vitamin D deficiency leads to insufficient calcium and phosphate levels, so new osteoid can't be mineralised. The same condition in adults is called osteomalacia. It is different in children because their growth plates haven't fused. In osteomalacia and rickets you get soft, pliable bones that are prone to deformity and fracture. 

 

Rickets is uncommon as food is fortified with vitamin D, but there are still cases in the UK https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/rickets-and-osteomalacia/. 

 

  • Vitamin A deficiency --> night blindness 
  • Vitamin B12 deficiency --> B12 deficiency anaemia and neurological symptoms (more common in vegans)
  • Vitamin C deficiency --> scurvy 
  • Zinc deficiency --> impaired immune function

Question:
You are on your way back from a match at Taly and instead of taking the direct route home you swerve into the macdonalds drive thru. Macdonalds monopoly is on and you manage to win a free apple pie!!!!!!!

Whilst eating your large meal and free apple pie you begin to think of how this *nutritious* meal is being processed in you body. You then think of the cute little I cells in your duodenum and how they release CCK.

Which of the following is not  an action of CCK (cholecystokinase)?
OptionA: Stimulates gall bladder emptying to release bile
OptionD: Stimulates the pancreatic acinar cells to release digestive enzymes
Explanation:
CCK is released from I cells in response to the arrival of chyme (predominantely fats) in the duodenum.

It causes the gall bladder to empty and release bile (via the common bile duct) into the duodenum.

It also causes the pancreatic acinar cells to release digestive enzyme such as pancreatic lipase and amylase.

It also slows gastric emptying - this is because it senses the high fat content, so needs a longer time in the small intestine to make sure it is all absorbed and processed.
Tags: Case 11, Function of GI, Case 3 revision

Question: A patient presents with a fixed, dilated pupil and a down and out gaze. Through which foramen does the cranial nerve injured in this patient exit the cranium?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E

A CN III palsy results in a down and out gaze and a fixed and dilated pupil. This is because CN III innervates the superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus and inferior oblique muscles of the eye. Damage to this nerve therefore results in the unopposed action of lateral rectus and superior oblique which abduct and pull the eye in and down respectively. Therefore their combined effects pull the eye down and out. CN III also innervates the eye lid so ptosis can occur if damage occurs, as well as pupil dilation as CN III innervates sphincter pupillae (muscles responsible for constriction of the pupil). 

CN III exists the cranium through the superior orbital fissure (along with CN IV, CN V1 and CN VI).

 

A - CN I

B - CNV3

C - CN VII, CN VIII

D - CN IX, X, XI

Question:
Mr Brown thinks that he is dead, however, his husband tells you that he is very much alive as he is being as irritating as ever.

Which of the following syndromes is Mr Brown most likely to be suffering from?
"The flaccid paralysis, areflexia, and lack of sensation secondary to physiological spinal cord shut down in response to injury" is referred to as which of the following?
Explanation:
Describes spinal shock

Usually resolves within 24 hours when reflex arcs caudal to injury return

Neurogenic Shock

State of in adequate tissue perfusion and oxygenation due to reduced sympathetic outflow (T1-L2) and therefore unopposed vagal tone.

Results in bradycardia and hypotension

 

Spinal Instability

The loss of the ability of the spine under physiological loads to maintain its pattern of displacement so that there is no initial or additional neurological deficit, no major deformity and no incapacitating pain

 

Spinal Cord Injury

Damage to the spinal cord that causes temporary (incomplete SCI) or permanent changes (complete SCI) in its function

Question: A stool sample has been sent to microbiology to investigate the cause of a diarrhoea case. Microscopy shows numerous curved rods with fast darting movements. There are no leukocytes present. Which infectious agent has most likely caused this case of diarrhoea?
Explanation:
Vibrio cholerae (Cholera)- are curved, flagellated, motile, gram negative rod bacteria. Detection is via stool culture. Cholera infection causes profuse, painless, watery stools (rice water stool). The cholera toxin activates adenylyl cyclase (Gs- PKA pathway) resulting in Cl- secretion, followed by water.

 

Norovirus- small round structure (+)ssRNA- detection via RT-PCR

 

E.coli- gram negative rod shaped bacteria 

 

Shigella- non-motile gram negative rod shaped bacteria. Detection via stool culture.

 

Campylobacter- curved/helical gram negative rod shaped bacteria. This is the most common cause of IID in the UK. Culture stool sample on a selective blood agar plate with antibiotics that inhibit most of normal fecal flora- incubated at warm temperature and often oxygen poor atmosphere (campylobacter does not grow in conventional culture conditions).

Question: You are on a ward where there has been an outbreak of clostridiumdififcile. The patient has been isolated and is being treated for the infection. However, other patients in the hospital seem to becoming infected suggesting that the bacteria is still able to spread. Which of the following might explain how the bacteria is still able to spread?
OptionA: Applying full PPE upon entering isolation room
OptionB: Washing hands after visiting patient with alcohol gel.
OptionD: Using proper non-touch aseptic technique with any procedure involving the patient.
OptionE: Stopping prescription of antibiotics which are killing commensal bacteria.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. Clostridium Difficile is a gram positive, anaerobic, spore forming rod bacteria. It is a toxin mediated disease which classically affects the large bowel. It can however, affect the small bowel as well. Organism is spread person to person via the faecal oral route. In a healthcare setting it is often spread through contaminated equipment, poor cleaning or poor hygiene. Key point to note, spores tend to adhere to alcoholic gel. As such, when dealing with a patient with C. Diff hot soapy water must be used to conduct effective hand hygiene. 

 

For more, see the lecture of infections of the GI tract.
Tags: Case 11, Function of GI, Infection, Infectious Diseases, Inflammation

Question: Which three muscles make up the erector spinae?
Explanation:
D is the correct answer. The Erector Spinae forms a layer of the deep muscles of the back.

 

The superficial muscles are- Levator scapulae, Rhomboid Minor, Rhomboid Major, Latissimus dorsi and Trapezius.

The intermediate muscles are- Serratus posterior superior, Serratus posterior inferior 

The Deep muscles can be split into:

-superficial: splenius capitis, Splenius cervicis 

-intermediate: Spinalis, Longissimus, Iliocostalis

-deep: Semispinalis, Multifidus, Rotatores

Question: You are at a BBQ enjoying a lovely chicken burger in the sun. A few days later, you develop violent diahorrea which is bloody and loose. You also develop a fever and experience severe abdominal pain. You suspect this might be a case of inflammatory infectious disease. Which of the following is the most common bacterial cause of inflammatory infectious disease and the most likely cause of your symptoms?
Explanation:
Campylobacter- Curved, motile, flagellate Gram –ve rods.

 

Two main forms C jejuni which tends to arise from poultry vs C coli which arises from pork. 

 

Usually self limiting. Erythromycin may limit duration of the infection. Prevention is best with proper kitchen hygiene. 

 

See case 11 lecture of infection in the GI tract for more.
Tags: Case 11, Function of GI, Infection, Infectious Diseases

Question:
Which ligament in the cervial spine: (1) prevents subluxation of C1 onto C2 and (2) holds the odontoid process in place against the posterior atlas.

 

Choose the correct answer.
Explanation:
A) Incorrect - The paired alar ligaments secure the apex of the odontoid to the anterior foramen magnum

B) Incorrect - Most anterior ligament of spine and does not touch with odontoid (as it is an external ligament).

C) Incorrect - Passes between the anterior margin of the foramen magnum above, and the upper border of the anterior arch of the atlas below.

D) Incorrect - Forming the anterior wall of the vertebral canal, this strong ligament spans from the body of the Axis (C2) to the posterior surface of the sacrum.

E) Correct - The transverse ligament holds the odontoid process in place against the posterior atlas, which prevents anterior subluxation of C1 on C2

Question: One of the following options correctly describes the function of joints of luschka (uncovertebral joints) by provides stability and mobility during cervical spine movement by:
OptionA: limiting lateral movements of the cervical vertebrae
Explanation: Explanation: Firstly joints of luschka are found between C3-C7. Secondly, they are formed between uncinate processes above, and the uncus below. Two lips project upward from the superior surface of the vertebral body below, and one projects downward from the inferior surface of vertebral body above. They allow for flexion and extension and limit lateral flexion in the cervical spine.

Question: You are on an Oncology block where a patient presents with Verner-Morrison syndrome. This is a pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour which results in profound diahorrea, hypokalemia and achlorhydria. You measure the plasma level of a particular peptide hormone and find it to be raised. This hormone is localised in the enteric nervous system and is responsible for smooth muscle relaxation as well as increasing electrolyte secretion in the gut. What is this hormone?
Explanation:
The correct answer is VIP. 

 

Histamine is released by the mast cells as part of the inflammatory response. Although it does stimulate Cl- secretion into the lumen, it is not found in the enteric nervous system and is not the correct answer. 

 

Somatostatin is released by delta cells in the pancreas, duodenum and pyloric antrum it acts to reduce stomach acid production both directly and indirectly. Also involved in absorption of electrolytes from the GI tract. 

 

Aldosterone this is a mineralcorticoid, it is responsible for increasing blood pressure as part of the RAAS system. In the GI tract, it increases Na+ absorption. 

 

VIP- This is secreted by the enteric nervous system. In Verner-Morrison syndrome it produces an excess of VIP leading to diahorrea as exccess Cl- is secreted into the lumen of the GI tract. 

 

Serotonin- Secreted by the enterochromaffin cells, responsible for controlling smooth muscle in the GI tract. In response to irritants in food, serotonin levels increase causing diahorrea as the bolus spends less time in the GI tract. If serotonin is released faster than it is absorbed by platelets then it activates 5-HT3 receptors in the chemoreceptor trigger zone that stimulate vomiting. This is why SSRIs can impact on GI motility. 

 

For more Dr Jeff Alan's lecture on GI physiology.
Tags: Case 11, Function of GI, Clinical Tests

Question: A patient comes into your practice complaining of diarrhoea associated with his Crohn's disease that he was diagnosed with. On top of his other pharmacological treatments, he was wondering if you could prescribe something for his diarrhoea. You suggest loperamide. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of action of this drug?
OptionA: Opioid-receptor agonist and acts on the μ-opioid receptors in the myenteric plexus of the large intestine.
OptionE: blocks the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from reaching the smooth muscle of the GI tract.
Explanation:
A- Correct answer. By stimulating opioid receptors, smooth muscle tone in the bowel is decreased, allowing for a delayed travel time for the stool in the bowel. This allows for increased absorption of water from the forming stool. 

B-5-3HT antagonist, these are drugs which are used in irritable bowel syndrome, they are also used as antiemetics by inhibiting centres in the brain responsible for nausea and vomiting. Used in chemotherapy.

C- Selective Serotonin reuptake inhibitors, responsible for causing a rise in serotonin in the GI tract and brain. They act to increase tone in the smooth muscles of the bowel leading to diarrhoea. 

D- This describes an additive such as Methyl cellulose. These are merely bulking agents which increase stool viscosity. 

E- These agents inhibit parasympathetic nerve impulses by selectively blocking the binding of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine to its receptor in nerve cells.

Question: A patient has been taking co-codamol for some back pain they have been having for 1 month. They are complaining that they have been constipated for 2 weeks. You explain to them that this might be due to the co-codamol that they've been taking. They look at you with a rather perplexed expression. Which of the following best describes the cause of constipation for those taking codeine?
OptionA: Binds to mu-opioid receptors causing decreased smooth muscle tone in bowel
OptionB: Inhibits the production of prostaglandins by inhibiting the action of COX enzyme.
OptionD: Reduces contractility of skeletal muscles preventing the build up of intra-abdominal pressure.
OptionE: Increases the threshold potential for mechano-receptors to signal in the submucosal plexus.
Explanation:
Codeine is an opiate used to treat pain, as a cough medicine, and for diarrhea.It is typically used to treat mild to moderate degrees of pain.Greater benefit may occur when combined with paracetamol (acetaminophen) or a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) such as aspirin or ibuprofen.

 

Answer A describes its mechanism of action. Answer B describes the mechanism of action of NSAIDs

The others were made up.

Question: A patient with Stage 4 Chronic Kidney Disease presents with bone pain. You suspect Renal Osteodystrophy and do a blood test to confirm this. Which of the following blood results would confirm Renal Osteodystrophy?
OptionA: Decreased calcium, decreased serum phosphate, increased alkaline phosphatase, increased parathyroid hormone
OptionB: Decreased calcium, increased serum phosphate, increased alkaline phosphatase, increased parathyroid hormone
OptionC: Increased calcium, normal serum phosphate, increased alkaline phosphatase, normal parathyroid hormone
OptionD: Decreased calcium, increased serum phosphate, normal alkaline phosphatase, decreased parathyroid hormone
OptionE: Increased calcium, normal serum phosphate, normal or high alkaline phosphatase, increased parathyroid hormone
Explanation:
Renal osteodystrophy is the most common type of secondary hyperparathyroidism, and occurs in CKD due to reduced renal hydroxylation of vitamin D.

Blood results most consistent with a diagnosis of high turnover renal osteodystrophy are decreased calcium, increased serum phosphate, increased alkaline phosphatase and increased parathyroid hormone.

Calcium may also be normal

Question: You are reviewing a patient with a history of diarrhoea and bloating. You conduct a screening test which reveals elevated levels of anti-tTG antibodies as well as anti-gliadin antibodies. You take a biopsy of the duodenum of the patient which reveals: villous atrophy, crypt hyperplasia and lymphocyte infiltration. Which of the following best describes the following pathology?
Tags: Case 11, Function of GI, Immunology, Inflammation

Question:
A patient X comes into the spinal clinic and you perform a back (spine) examination.

 

You jot down your notable findings:

 

  • X has difficulty laterally flexing their spine to the left.
  • X has difficulty extending their spine (leaning back unaided)
  • X can extend their head normally.
  • X can rotate their spine normally.

Which group of muscles are most likely affected in patient X?
OptionD: Minor deep intrinsic muscles of the back
Explanation:
Explanation

 

  • Unilateral contraction of Intermediate intrinsic muscles of the back control lateral flexion. Bilateral contraction of these muscles extends the spine. Both of these are the biggest signs and may affect either side.
  • Deep layer of the muscle controls rotation of the spine, extension of head/thoracic or cervical region of spine and contralateral rotation.
  • Minor deep layer also assists or aid with many of the other actions.

One key point: other muscles can compensate, however, you will a decrease in the capacity to perform these movements. Hence, patients usually have difficulties performing them rather than total loss of those actions.

Question: A patient presents having completed a MOCA test. The test result of 15/30 suggests severe cognitive impairment. Further history taking leads you to a diagnosis of Alzheimer’s disease after ruling out other causes of dementia . You prescribe donepezil for the patient. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of action of this drug?
Explanation: Reduced levels of acetylcholine are thought to play a role in the cognitive and memory decline associated with progression of AD. ACh is normally cleared rapidly from the synpatic cleft by acetylcholine esterases. In AD patients you want to prolong the halflife of ACh to improve cognition. Acetylcholine esterase inhibitors have a (limited) therapeutic effect in this context.

Question: what GI pathogen releases glutamate dehydrogenase
Explanation: GDH is produced by C.diff and is detected in a stool sample

Question: Which of the following is the inheritance pattern of MODY?

Uniparental disomy (UPD) occurs when non disjunction results in a gamete with two of the same chromosome from one parent. In the zygote, there may be trisomy rescue, meaning the resultant morula and later child will have the correct number of chromosomes.

 

There are 2 types:

  • Uniparental heterodisomy
  • Uniparental isodisomy

Which of the following is NOT at increased risk in uniparental disomy
Explanation:
Associated: Mosaic Aneuploidy is more likely in uniparental disomy if there is a failed trisomy/monosomy rescue in some cells.

 

Associated: Disease due to imprinting and therefore Silver-Russel syndrome (Maternal UPD 11) is also at increased risk. In Uniparental isodisomy a child may have two maternal chromosome 11s, both with the same imprinted genes switched 'off', causing Silver-Russel Syndrome.

 

Associated: Recessive disease is more likely, as you could inherit the disease with just one parent as a carrier upon receiving two copies of the parents mutated chromosome.

 

NOT Associated: Deletions are the only option not associated with UPD, and are caused by different mechanisms.

Question: When we eat food it has to be broken down into smaller molecules in order to be absorbed into the blood.  What protein is responsible for ensuring macromolecules can't cross the intestinal wall?
Explanation:
Intestinal epithelial permeability is largely a function of tight junction structure and resistance (resistance increases as you go through the intestines).

claudin = protein of tight junction - establishes paracellular barrier controlling flow into intracellular space

occludin = protein of tight junction - barrier against macromolecules as opposed to mall ions

junction adhesion molecule = in between tight junctions and act as an adhesive ligand for interacting with a variety of immune cell

 

connexons are proteins involved with gap junctions and cadherins are proteins involved with desmosomes

Question: During which stage of chronic kidney disease can microalbuminuria be first detected?

A young male patient registered to your surgery has recently died, it is thought that this was a sudden cardiac death due to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. An extensive investigation has been launched due to the high profile of the patient who was due to run 10,000m in the upcoming Olympic games. It is discovered from a team member that he occasionally fainted during training and had complained to his coach of palpitations. His coach however, told him it was probably nerves and told him to keep training.

 

A reporter of The Sun comes to interview you and asks how you could have helped the young athlete if you'd known this information.

 

What management would you offer a high risk patient with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy?
Explanation:
Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is reported historically as the most common cause of SCD in athletes younger than 35 years of age.

 

HCM is a common genetic cardiovascular disease that affects the left ventricle. HCM can appear at any age, with the majority of the patients remaining clinically stable. When patients complain of symptoms, these include: dyspnea, dizziness, syncope and angina. HCM can lead to sudden cardiac death (SCD), mainly due to ventricular tachyarrhythmia or ventricular tachycardia. High-risk patients benefit from implantable cardioverter-defibrillators.

Source: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2998829/

 

Risk factors for sudden cardiac death due to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy:

Young Adults

Athletes

Arrhythmia

 

ESC Risk Calculator

Source: Non-ischaemic causes of Heart Failure

Question: Manuel presents to the GP experiencing symptoms of dyspnoea, palpitations and fatigue when he does any gentle physical activity, but he explains he is comfortable at rest. The GP is worried that Manuel is describing symptoms associated with heart failure...what NYHA heart failure class are these symptoms associated with?
Explanation:
NYHA heart failure classes are: 

Class I - no limitation, normal physical exercise does not cause fatigue, dyspnoea, or palpitations

Class II - mild limitation, comfortable at rest but normal physical activity produces fatigue, dyspnoea or palpitations 

Class III - marked limitation, comfortable at rest but gentle physical activity produces marked symptoms of HF - and so the correct answer in this case

Class IV - symptoms of HF occur at rest and are exacerbated by any physical activity 

There is no class V in this classification

Question:
A patient comes into A&E after an incident which occurred two hours prior, BP: 115/76, Temp: 37.0. The patient had fell from a ladder onto his back and shows signs of spinal cord injury with oedema and electrolyte changes within his spinal cord.

 

Which type of injury are you now most likely to deal with as the patient enters A&E?
Explanation:
Explanation

The primary cause is the initial mechanical impact, compression, and contusion resulting in damage to nerve cells, myelin, blood vessels, and supporting bone structures. The secondary injury process involves swelling and hemorrhage, which leads to increased free radicals/electrolyte changes and decreased blood flow, causing even greater cell membrane dysfunction and cell death.

 

Secondary occurs minutes to hours/days after impact and it is more deadly. Further, it would not be neurogenic shock as the BP is stable.

Question: You are prescribing Furosemide for a patient with hypertension. Where in the kidney does this drug act?
OptionB: The descending limb of the loop of Henle
OptionC: The thick ascending limb of the loop Henle
Explanation: Furosemide is an example of a loop diuretic. It acts on the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle. It acts on the Na+/Cl-/K+ symporter, inhibiting the re-uptake of Na+ Cl- and K+ thereby reducing to osmotic drive to absorb water reducing the plasma volume. Side effects include hypokalaemia as K+ is lost in the urine.

Question:
A 45-year-old male is admitted after being found by the police unconscious on the street.

 

On examination, he is dishevelled and smelling of alcohol. No history is obtainable.

He has a temperature of 35°C, a blood pressure of 106/72 mmHg and a pulse of 52 bpm. He won't obey commands but on your attempting to insert a venflon he tries to grab your arm and utters a few odd incomprehensible sounds although his eyes remain closed.

What is his Glasgow coma scale score?
Explanation:
In this example the score would be E1 V2 M5:

 

No eye opening - E1
Some incomprehensible sounds - V2
Localising to pain - M5


This gives a GCS of 8.

Question: Mrs Diane A. Beaties has her ABPI measured. She is found to have an ABPI of 1.5. What does this indicate?
OptionA: She's got nothing to worry about, this is a normal measurement
OptionE: She has relatively advanced peripheral arterial disease
Explanation: Normal ABPI is 1.0-1.4. Above 1.4 implies that there is a vascular calcification artefact. The lower the ABPI the more severe the ischaemia.

Question: Leg ulcers are most likely to be...
Explanation: The vast majority of leg ulcers are venous in origin.

Question: In the initiation of puberty in girls, what is the first event?
Explanation:
The initial event is an increase in the nocturnal secretion of luteinising hormone (LH) which causes a gradual increase in the levels of sex hormone production. LH secretion begins predominantly at night, under the stimulation of gonadotropin releasing hormone (GnRH).

 

Sequence of events in females:

 

Increased secretion of GnRH, LH, FSH and oestrogen
Adrenarche - adrenal androgen production - causes acne, sexual hair production and body odour which starts around age 9-10 on average although changes may not be evident until age 11
Gonadarche - gonadal hormone production, causes thelarche (breast budding, ~11 years)
Menarche - beginning of menstrual cycles - usually follows several years after thelarche (breast development). Anovulatory menstrual cycles are common for the first two years after menarche.
Growth spurt starts mid-puberty with peak height velocity occurring around the age of 12.

Question: A patient comes into A and E having fallen off a ladder. They banged their head and have deteriorated rapidly. You observe Cushing's triad of irregular breathing, raised blood pressure and bradycardia. You quickly decide to administer mannitol in an effort to reduce intracranial pressure before the patient can be transferred to a neurosurgical unit for a craniotomy. Which of the following describes the mechanism of action of mannitol?
OptionA: Osmotic diuretic, increases solute concentration in nephron
OptionB: Loop diuretic, acts on the Na+/K+/Cl- symporter in the thick ascending limb
Explanation:
Because of its low molecular weight (182), mannitol is freely filtered through the renal tubules. However, as it is not reabsorbed, it continues to be osmotically active in the tubules and this accounts for its action as an osmotic diuretic. Mannitol also causes release of renal prostaglandins that lead to renal vasodilation and an increase in tubular urine flow that is believed to protect against renal injury by reducing tubular obstruction. It also acts as a free-radical scavenger and reduces the harmful effects of free radicals during ischaemia–reperfusion injury. 

 

Mannitol has many side-effects including initial volume expansion (increasing the risk of heart failure), subsequent hypovolaemia and hypotension, metabolic acidosis, and electrolyte imbalance, including hypernatraemia and hypokalaemia. In large doses, it can also cause renal failure because of intra-renal vasoconstriction and intravascular volume depletion. Repeated administration may result in unacceptably high serum osmolarity (>320 mOsm litre−1) and subsequent neurological complications.

Question:
You are on placement on the Cardiology ward when an F1 tries to teach you about JVP waveforms. 

Just when you think you've finally got the hang of it, she hands you this (crude) drawing of a waveform, showing a prominent a wave. 

 

Which of the following can cause a prominent a wave?
Explanation:
JVP Waveform:

The JVP graph is simply a measure of pressure (y axis) against time (x axis). 

 

a wave: As the atrium contracts, pressure increases (upward slope), until it relaxes again, causing the downward slope of the a wave

c wave: Tricuspid valve closure

x descent: Ventricular contraction

v wave: Passive filling of the atrium in diastole, increasing pressure again

y descent: The movement of blood into the ventricles as the tricuspid valve opens

 

(This table was taken from the JVP tutorial in Case 15)

 

As I understand it, pulmonary hypertension causes increased pressure. This increased pressure means the atrium is contracting harder against more resistance, causing the more prominent a wave. Another cause of a prominent a wave would be complete heart block. 

 

This is just what I understood from the tutorial but if anyone has any corrections (and any explanations for the other wave abnormalities?) it would be much appreciated xxxxxxxxx

Question:
You are shadowing a cardiologist at an outpatient clinic. Mr Spruzen takes beta blockers and a sodium channel blocker for his heart failure. He attends for a checkup and to discuss his recent ECG. The cardiologist is concerned that pharmacological treatment is no longer viable and wishes to proceed to surgical management. He describes to the patient a fairly non-intrusive surgery which involves pumping pure alcohol into one of the heart blood vessels.

 

What cardiomyopathy is likely responsible for Mr Spruzen's heart failure?
OptionC: Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy with high risk of Sudden Cardiac Death
OptionD: Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy with Left ventricular outflow tract obstruction
Explanation:
The procedure described is Alcohol Septal Ablation

  • Basically: This involves pumping pure alcohol into a small coronary artery supplying the septum effectively causing a small heart attack causing a reduction in left ventricular myocardium, both in the infarcted and non-infarcted muscle.
  • This reduces the obstruction and allows more blood to leave the ventricle increasing stroke volume.
  • More detail visit: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2780820/

The above cadiomyopathies and their management are all desciribed in the Non-ischaemic causes of Heart failure lecture.
Tags: Management of patient, Cardiology, Case 15, Heart

Question: Mrs C, a 59 year old with a diagnosis of schizophrenia, visits her GP reluctantly with her husband who explains that she doesn't seem to believe that he is her husband and thinks he is an impostor. What type of belief does Mrs C have?
Explanation:
A is the correct answer.

 

B - Couvade - a person believes they are pregnant when they are not and may experience some symptoms as if they were pregnant 

C - Ekbom - a person believes they have parasites under their skin

D - Erotomania - a person believes that someone is in love with them (unrealistically, and often of a higher social class / celebrity)

E - Fregoli - a person believe that one person is changing their appearance and inhabiting the bodies of different people they encounter (e.g. bus driver was the same guy as the check out guy etc.)

Question: John in a 29 year old male. His friends notice he is always over the top about everything and constantly seeking excitement and appreciation. They say his mood changes very quickly. What personality disorder could John have?
Explanation: Histrionic - self dramatization, theatricality, seeking of excitement and appreciation, shallow and labile emotions

Question:
Grace is always worried, overly cautious and obsessed with detail. You went for a walk with grace and accidentally stepped on the grass next to a 'don't walk on the grass' sign. Grace did not like this at all. 

What personality disorder could Grace have?
Explanation: Anankastic – excessive doubt, caution, excessive attention to detail and obsession with rules and order

Question: Which of these describes the explanation behind the positive symptoms seen in schizophrenia?
OptionA: Too little dopamine in the mesocortical pathway
OptionB: Too little dopamine in the mesolimbic pathway
OptionC: Too much dopamine in the mesocortical pathway
OptionD: Too much dopamine in the mesolimbic pathway
OptionE: Too much dopamine in the nigrostriatal pathay
Explanation:
Mesolimbic pathway - Increased dopamine in the mesolimbic pathway can be responsible for the positive symptoms of schizophrenia.
• Projections from ventral tegmental area (VTA) to nucleus accumbens.
• D2 receptors

Question:
(Corrected question):

 

It's the first day of your neurosurgery SSC and you're shadowing a consultant, A. Consultant, on their ward round. Dr Consultant describes five patient cases with five separate conditions:

  • Amy, a 25 year old accountant with a symptomatic Chiari type I malformation
  • Sam, a 4 year old boy with a small, communicating, lateral ventricle choroid plexus papilloma
  • Ariel, a 56 year old decorator with severe extradural haemorrhage following trauma
  • Rachel, a 18 year old first year university student with meningitis and a brain abscess
  • John, a retired 77 year old man with a large subdural haemorrhage after a car accident

After explaining the correct procedure and risks of a lumbar puncture, Consultant turns to you. Which of her five patients is not  at risk of tonsillar herniation (aka 'coning') if a lumbar puncture is performed?

 

 

above: Tonsillar herniation example
Explanation:
The correct answer is 'B' because it is the only scenario of the five where raised intracranial pressure can be communicated with the spinal canal. A lumbar puncture on Sam in 'B' would not create a pressure gradient between the point of puncture and the cranium whereas in all the others there is a risk of this occurring. Below is a little more information on why each case does or doesn't risk coning.

 

  • Chiari malformation means the cerebellum is abnormally shaped and positioned and extends into the spinal canal, which really raises the risk of compressing the brainstem; symptoms can manifest as caused by a raised ICP (feeling and being sick, severe headache, neck pain, blurred vision etc.).
  • Sam's choroid plexus papilloma is causing a communicating hydrocephalus; this means he will be producing too much CSF, but that it can still leave the cranium. If it was obstructive it may risk herniation because lumbar puncture in that instance might create a pressure gradient.
  • Ariel has a large extradural haemorrhage so there will be lots of blood raising the ICP. Because the extradural space does not communicate with the spinal canal a lumbar puncture would again create a pressure gradient.
  • Rachel's abscess counts as a space occupying lesion, which if big enough will raise the ICP.
  • John risks herniation for the same reason as Ariel; the blood is occupying space in the cranium and raising the pressure, and the subdural space created by the bleed doesn't communicate with the spinal canal. However, if John or Ariel was suffering from a subarachnoid haemorrhage I think it should communicate and not risk coning. With that said I don't know if or why you would perform lumbar puncture on someone with a subarachnoid haemorrhage.

Question: In your ISCE and you're asked to perform a back examination on a 45 year old male, who's said to of come in complaining of lower back pain radiating down his leg. The whole way through the examination your convinced it's Sciatica, until it comes to the straight leg raise which throws you off your game as it's not consistent with this diagnosis. What is your new differential diagnosis if the man doesn't show signs of pain until his leg is raised to 65 degrees?
Explanation:
• 0-30o = Hip pathology or an inflamed nerve root 
  • 30-50o = Sciatica 
  • 50-70o = Hamstrings
  • 70-80o = Sacroiliac joint stress 
  • 80-90o = Normal

In the body, the drug breaks down to Valsartan and Sacubitral.

Question:
A 14-year-old patient presents to your spine clinic with poor posture and back ache. The patient points to a dull non-radiating point midway up his spine. The patient has a family history of the presenting complaint and the parents say their child's posture is progressively getting worse. Past medical history shows the patient was previously diagnosed with osteochondrosis. Other information: Patient has certain breathing problems.

 

What is the most likely condition being presented in this patient?
Explanation:
Explanation: It is essentially osteochondrosis of the thoracic vertebral bodies which leads to wedge-shaped vertebrae.It causes increased kyphosis, poor posture and backache. It is the most common cause of structural kyphosis in 13 to 16 year olds. The cause is unknown but hereditary factors are thought to play a part in the pathophysiology.

 

In Scheuermann's disease there is a defect in the secondary ossification centres of the vertebral bodies. A few vertebral bodies may be involved or the whole thoracolumbar spine. This is the main point: it is due to osteochondrosis.

Question: What of the following vertebrae is also known by the name "vertebra prominens"?
Explanation:
C7 is the third atypical vertebra of the cervical spine (the other two being atlas and axis, a.k.a. C1 & C2). 

The name reflects the nature of C7 as it projects the most prominent, palpable spinous process at the lower neck.

Question:
Kate Langdon comes to A & E with her husband, Henry. Mr Langdon is 68 years old and complains of tingling, nausea and muscle weakness. On further questioning he has not passed urine for 7 hours, and has a history of kidney disease.

 

You decide to give Mr Langdon a 12-lead ECG. Which of those below most likely belongs to him?

 

-because the ECGs are blurry, below each is some information on rhythm, morphology and intervals that may not be clear.
OptionA:
• prolonged QT interval
  • polymorphic
OptionB:
• irregularly irregular
  • no P wave
OptionC:
• delta wave
  • broad QRS complex
  • short PR interval
OptionD:
• fast rate but regular rhythm
  • P waves appearing at different rate to QRS
OptionE:
• tented T waves
  • broad QRS complex
Explanation:
Mr Langdon's clinical presentation strongly suggests that he is hyperkalaemic. Kidney disease and his anuria mean he is not excreting potassium and it is now at a very high concentration in his blood.

Depending on how hyperkalaemic a patient is their ECG can vary in appearance. Expected features on a hyperkalaemic ECG are tented T waves, loss of the P wave and a broadening QRS (it gets broader the higher the potassium in the blood). This suggests 'E' as the best answer.

 

  • 'A' = Torsade de Pointes.
  • 'B' = atrial fibrillation, but it's really blurry.
  • 'C' = Wolff-Parkinson White syndrome (WPW).
  • 'D' = monomorphic ventricular tachycardia (VT). NB there are lots of different VT, not just this.
  • 'E' shows very tented T waves and a broad QRS complex so it is a good fit for suspected hyperkalaemia.

 

Here is a link to the article on hyperkalaemia and what to look for on a hyperkalaemic ECG from Life in the Fast Lane: https://lifeinthefastlane.com/hyperkalemia/
Tags: Tests, ECG, Cardiovascular system, Case 13, Case 15

Question: After consuming a large meal, your beta cells begin to secrete insulin. Which of the following molecules is responsible for initiating the pathway which leads to insulin secretion?
Explanation:
The pancreas contains a special form of hexokinase for converting glucose to glucose-6-phosphate. This enzyme cannot be inhibited allosterically/competitively. As a result this allows for the raised concentration gluc-6-phosphate. Hence when this substrate rises in concentration, it triggers the B cells to release insulin. 

 

Taken from the Andrew Shore plenary case 10.

Question:
Patient presents with dizziness, palpitations, lightheadedness. E.g reveals a polymorphic ventricular tachycardia, looks rather like the cover of an Arctic Monkeys album:

 

Which of the following underlying conditions is strongly associated with the development of Torsades de Pointes?
Explanation:
Long QT syndrome describes a prolonged interval between the Q and T waves. In a healthy person, it should be about half the length of the normal cardiac cycle. At 60bpm a QT interval longer than 440ms in males and 460 in females is considered long QT syndrome. 

 

Since heart rate varies, so too must QT interval. Using Bazett's formula we can find a corrected QT interval:

A Long QT interval can be due to a dysfunction in L-type Ca2+ channels. 

These are the channels that help maintain the plateau stage in ventricular depolarisation. 

This can result in early afterdepolarisation.

  

This can lead to premature ventricular contraction leading to reentrant tachycardia. Torsades de Pointes. 

 

To treat Long QT:

Stop any medications which might be causing it, eg VW class 1a and 3 drugs. 

Correct any electrolyte imbalances

Temporary pacing wire to correct bradycardia.
Tags: ECG, Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13, ISCE

Question: Neurotmesis of the posterior interosseous nerve (a deep branch of the radial nerve) will result in which of the following descriptions?
Explanation:
The wrist and the fingers cannot extend at the metacarpophalangeal joints. The wrist remains partially flexed due to an opposing action of flexor muscles of the forearm. As a result, the extensor muscles in the posterior compartment remain paralyzed.

 

Neurotmesis means the complete severing of a nerve.

 

E is incorrect as neurotmesis will mean complete severing. However, if there was neuropraxia or axonotmesis, this may be the correct answer.

Question: A patient is assessed in A&E following a road traffic accident, leaving them with severe facial injuries and unconsciousness. They are given a GCS of 6tc. What does this suggest about their motor response?
Explanation:
The 'c' indicates their eyes are closed due to structural or other reasons. In this case, it is likely due to severe swelling. Patients such as this can only receive a maximum of 1 for the eyes domain. The 't' indicates they are intubated, or have a tracheostomy. Such patients can only receive a maximum of 1 for the verbal domain. This leaves 4 for the motor domain-withdrawing to pain. 

 

Note that decorticate=flexing to pain. Problem in the midbrain

Decerebrate=extending to pain. Problem in the pons

Question: The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) is located within which region of the brain?
Explanation: The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) is located within the hypothalamus, and contains a group of neurons that control the body’s biological clock (circadian rhythm). The circadian rhythm controls many physiological and behavioural rhythms, for example the sleep-wake cycle.

Question: A 35 year old man presents with significant weight gain since starting antipsychotic medication three months ago. This side effect is likely to be due to blockade of which receptor?
Explanation: Weight gain is a side effect of a number of antipsychotic medications, thought to be due to blockade (antagonism) of the H1 (Histamine) receptor. It also occurs with antagonism of the specific 5HT2c receptor.

Question: A 19 year old student, under stress from her exams, hears a voice calling her name as she goes to sleep one night. There is no one else around. Which phenomenon is being described?
Explanation: It is relatively common for people to have hallucinations just as they are going to (hypnogogic) or waking from (hypnopompic) sleep.

Question:
A 25-year-male presents to the emergency department complaining of severe headache, neck stiffness, fever and increased sensitivity to light over the past few weeks. He is referred for a lumbar puncture to collect CSF for testing.

 

Results:

Glucose: 3 mmol/L (2.5 – 3.5 mmol/L)
Neutrophils: <20%
Lymphocytes: >50%
Protein: 4 g/L (0.15 - 0.45g/L)

CSF is cloudy and viscous in appearance and during the lumbar puncture, a very high opening pressure of 45 cm H20 is observed. Meningitis is suspected.

 

What is the most likely cause of the infection?
Explanation:
"The results are indicative of fungal meningits, which causes chronic mengitis and hence could explain the presence of these symptoms over the past few weeks. Glucose would need to be lower to suspect TB and Neiseseria. Lymphocytes would need to be > 90% for it to be viral."

 

Taken from Case 16 Quiz.

Question:
68 year old Mr Watson smokes regularly and has a history of unstable angina and high blood pressure.

 

He suffered a stroke three months ago due to partial occlusion to his left middle cerebral artery. He has come to hospital as an outpatient to discuss the lasting effects of the stroke.

 

Which of the following is an unlikely complication
OptionA: Inability to exert control over the movement (ataxia) of the right (contralateral) arm
OptionE: Aphasia (inability or impaired ability to produce or understand speech)
Explanation:
This question applies understanding of the territories of blood supply and the functions of the areas they supply.

 

MCA is the most common site of ischemic stroke.

  • Middle cerebral artery supplies most of the sensory and motor gyri as well as Wernicke's area and Broca's area. Therefore ischemia of these parts of the brain can effect speech and motor and sensory function. (Lower limb function is more likely to be spared due to dual supply with anterior cerebral artery)
  • These effects are contralateral as the ischemia causes an upper motor neurone lesion before the corticospinal tract has decussated in the pyramids of the medulla

 

The hippocampus in the medial temporal lobe is responsible for episodic memory and is supplied by the posterior cerebral artery.
