Question: What is the antidote of tenecteplase?
Explanation:
Tenecteplase is a fibrinolytic drug.  The indications for use are acute STEMI, stroke or a compromised pulmonary embolism.  It works by converting plasminogen to plasmin which then degrades the fibrin clot.  However, it can lead to haemorrhage and in this case, administration of antifibrinolytic tranexamic acid is required to reverse its effects.

 

Naloxone = opioid overdose antidote

Protamine Sulphate = reverses heparin 

Vit K = reverses warfarin

 

Ranolazine is an anti-anginal drug mentioned in the drug formulary.

Question: A child whose weight is average for their height will have a BMI between _____ and ______ centiles.
Explanation:
Interpretation
› A child whose weight is average for their height will have a BMI between the 25th and 75th centiles, whatever their height centile.

› BMI above the 91st centile suggests that the child is overweight; a child above the 98th centile is very overweight (clinically obese).
› BMI below the 2nd centile is unusual and may reflect under-nutrition.

Question:
The growth charts indicate a child’s size compared with children of the same age and maturity who have shown optimum growth. The chart also shows how quickly a child is growing.

 

Children come in all shapes and sizes, but 99 out of 100 children who are growing optimally will weigh between the two outer lines in the centile charts:

 

These centiles are between _____ and _____.
Explanation:
What do the centiles mean?

The new charts indicate a child’s size compared with children of the same age and maturity who have shown optimum growth. The chart also shows how quickly a child is growing.


The centile lines on the chart show the expected range of weights and heights (or lengths); each describes the number of children expected to be below that line, e.g. 50% below the 50th, 91% below the 91st.


Children come in all shapes and sizes, but 99 out of 100 children who are growing optimally will be between the two outer lines (0.4th and 99.6th centiles); half will lie between the 25th and 75th centile lines.


Being very small or very big can sometimes be associated with underlying illness. There is no single threshold below which a child’s weight or height is de nitely abnormal, but only 4 out of 1000 children who are growing optimally are below the 0.4th centile, so these children should be assessed to exclude any problems. Those above the 99.6th centile for height are almost always healthy.


If weight is above the 99.6th centile, calculate body mass index (BMI) (see page 17). Also calculate the BMI if the weight and height centiles appear very different.

Question: Which of the following is true of populations that are in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?

p2 + 2pq + q2 = 1

 

p + q = 1

Explanation:
p = dominant allele "A"
q = recessive allele "a"

p2 = individuals who are homozygous dominant ("AA")

2pq = individuals who are heterozygous ("Aa" and "aA" - hence the 2)

Question:
Phenylketonuria (PKU) is an autosomal recessive metabolic disorder that results in mental retardation if untreated during the newborn period.

 

In the United States, one out of 10,000 babies is born with PKU.

Given this incidence, what percent of the population are heterozygous carriers of the recessive PKU allele?

 

Assume the Hardy-Weinberg principle is applicable.
Explanation:
q2 = 1/10000
q = sqrt(1/10000) = 1/100
p = 1 – (1/100) = 99/100
2pq = 2 x (99/100) x (1/100) = 0.0198

 

Approximation of q to 1 can be done but best practice is to use exact figures, especially for smaller populations. This is why 0.0198 is a better answer than 0.0200.

If you answered A or B, you probably halved 2pq to get pq. Do not do that. 2pq (as a whole) represents homozygous individuals.

Question: What hormone is released when calcium is low?
Explanation:
Answer is B: Parathyroid hormone (PTH).

In the bone PTH stimulates osteoclasts - which release Ca2+ ions from bone

Calmodulin - binds to calcium inside cells

Aldosterone - increases reabsorption of Na+ by up-regulating Na+/K+ ATPase pumps in the DCT and collecting duct

Question:
The consultant at the emergency ward is treating a patient who has diabetes. To test your knowledge, the consultant does not tell you what type of diabetes the patient has.

 

Which of the following options is a key difference in the diagnoses of hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state and not found in diabetic ketoacidosis?
Explanation:
Diabetic KetoAcidosis (DKA) (usually seen in Type1D = characterised by hyperglycaemia, acidosis and ketonaemia.
= diagnosis via blood glucose over 11mmol/L, bicarbonate below 15mmol/L and or venous pH less than 7.3, ketonaemia 3mmol/L and over (+2 on dipstick).

 

Hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state
Most commonly occur in Type 2 DM. Higher mortality than DKA. often as the initial presentation of type 2 DM. Marked 30mmol/L, without significant hyperketonaemia & without acidosis (pH>7.3, bicarbonate >15mmol/L). Osmolality usually 320 mosmol/kg or more.

Question: A mother and child come into your practice for the infant's first round of vaccination at 8 weeks. https://geekymedics.com/child-development/

 

Child development can be split into 4 modalities. 

 

Gross motor: this includes things like being able to hold up its head briefly as seen at 6-8 weeks.

Fine motor/vision: Being able to form an immature pincer grip at 10 months.

Social: Such as socially smiling at 6-8 weeks, or stranger anxiety at 6 months.

Question:
Case 17

 

A patient with T2D who regularly attends his GP for checkups, is referred for the first time to an in-patient clinic with suspected renal disease caused by his diabetic pathology.

 

Which stage of diabetic nephropathy is the patient most likely at?
Explanation:
Stage I – hyperfiltration – increased blood flow through the kidney, early renal hypertrophy = no symptoms
Stage II – glomerular lesions without clinically evident disease = no symptoms
FIRST IDENTIFIABLE STAGE: Stage III – incipient nephropathy with microalbuminuria – alb/cr ratio 30/300 microgram/mg per day or albumin 20-200 mcg/min on timed specimen. (first identifiable stage).
Stage IV – overt diabetic nephropathy with protein uria >500mg/24 hr – creatinine clearance <70ml/L
Stage V – end stage renal disease (ESRD)

Question:
Whilst on placement, you are examining a newborn girl. The baby has a low birth weight, cleft lip and small eyes. You are aware that the baby has a heart defect and that the child also has holoprosencephaly. 

What is the most fitting karyotype for this child?
Explanation:
The correct answer is Patau's syndrome (A).

Holoprosencephaly (failure of the forebrain to divide properly) occurs in Patau's syndrome. This can lead to severe defects (cleft lip, abnormally small eyes, reduced distance between the eyes). 

Newborns will also be underweight due to IUGR and may also have microcephaly. 

80% of babies born with Patau's will have a heart defect. 

There is severe developmental problems in Patau's and there is a low survival rate (more than 9/10  newborns die within the first year).

Question:
Whilst on placement, you are examining a newborn boy. He is of low birth weight and has an abnormally shaped head, small jaw and small mouth. In addition to this, he also has a clenched fist with overlap of multiple fingers and underdeveloped thumbs as well as smooth feet with rounded soles. Explanation:
The answer is B (Edward's syndrome). 

Now I have difficulty differentiating between Patau's (A) and Edward's (B). From what I understand Patau's major symptoms come from failure of the forebrain to divide properly (haloprosencephaly) and so newborns present with more severe craniofacial and midline deficits. In Edwards, its defining features are clenched hands (with overlap of  2nd and 5th fingers amongst others), rocker bottom feet and arthrogryposis (multiple joint contractures which I tried to show in the question with misaligned feet and clenched hands).

Question:
You are at a family holiday park, where you are cycling in a designated cycling forest. You see a person in front fall from the bike onto the floor and blood pools around their thigh. The person does not respond when you ask their name and seems a sound can be heard when they exhale. However, there is no danger around you and you have told your son to call an ambulance.

 

What is the next immediate step?
Explanation:
DRScABC

 

Catastrophic haemorrhages (CH) must be treated before airway! This is as a person can die from blood loss faster than from oxygen deprivation.

 

Main sites of CH = femoral artery (only artery that supplies the whole leg). Brachial artery (for upper arm), Aorta (hard to treat in rural places).

Question:
You are a public health consultant. You come across data that shows children in schools with no breakfast club form 12% of those in the BMI>30 category at age 20. Meanwhile data from children in schools with breakfast clubs show that those in the BMI>30 category at age 20 only only form 8% of this group.

 

How schoolchildren would benefit from breakfast clubs to prevent one child becoming clinically obese (BMI>30).
Explanation:
This is a variation of number needed to treat (NNT).

 

So 12% risk in those with breakfast club, 8% risk in those without. 12-8 = 4% Absolute risk reduction. 1/4% = 1/0.04 = 25 children needed to swap groups.

Question:
A self administered cognitive screening test called TYM is being trialled for identifying patients who may need assessment for Alzheimer’s disease.

 

In the study, researchers perform the screening test on all patients enrolled, and then identify disease against a "gold standard test". Disease presence was determined using Addenbrooke’s cognitive exam and the Mini Mental Score. A hypothetical table of results is provided:

 

 

What is the NPV (negative predictive value) of the TYM screening test?
Explanation:
E is correct

93.3% is the NPV/PV- Negative prediction value i.e. the probability that a patient with a negative result doesn't have disease

(97 correctly identified negatives) / (the 104 negatives)

 

Be careful of the tutorial on NPV, I have emailed the maths department and they agree that the tutorial appears to be incorrect, as they divide the FALSE NEGATIVEs by the total negatives which is not NPV - hence I wrote this question off of an old one I did to let people know. Sharing is caring.

 

 

 

A) is Specificity - the ability of the screening test to correctly identify negatives i.e. patients without Alzheimer's disease. In this case, that is 97 patients out of the 100 participants without disease. 97/100 = 97.0%

 

B) is a made up calculation - just the number of correctly identified positives with a percentage stuck on the end

 

C) 92.6% is sensitivity (87 correctly identified with positives)/(94 total positives that could have been identified)

 

D) 53.6 is the percentage of patients in the study with negative screen results

Question: Which patient is most at risk of having a hypoglycaemic attack?
OptionA: Type 1 diabetic young female who isn't using her insulin because she wants to lose weight
OptionB: Prisoner with no medical history 5 weeks into a hunger strike
OptionC: Type 1 diabetic patient who has decreased their insulin dose to account for exercise today, but stopped halfway around the track for a sprained ankle
OptionD: Type 2 diabetic who has accidentally taken twice as much metformin this morning
OptionE: Type 1 diabetic who is fasting pre-op, taking medications as normal
Explanation:
A: This patient is at risk of DKA and hyperglycaemia
B: You can go a long time on hunger strike and maintain a glucose of 3.5mmol/l, until about 6 weeks, which is technically hypo, but it's not the SBA.
C: Exercise increases sensitivitiy to insulin, so a reduced dose without any exercise will probably result in HYPERglycaemia, not hypo
D: Metformin shouldn't cause hypoglycaemia, most of the other T2DM drugs do though.
E: Correct. Dangerous situation. They're taking insulin but have no sugars to account for it, so enter a hypoglycaemic state

Question:
You meet a patient while on placement shadowing Spine Dragon, and he asks you to assess the neurology of a patient's lower limbs. While you are testing the muscles in the patient's legs, you notice that when the patient is asked to extend their knee, they can only manage a flicker of movement in their quadriceps muscle. 

 

How would you record this finding on an ASIA chart?
Explanation:
The ASIA chart allows you to record MRC scores for each myotome in the upper and lower limb. There are 5 myotomes in each limb, and each can score a maximum of MRC grade 5. This means the maximum total for each limb is 25. 

 

MRC Grades:

0 = no movement at all 

1 = flicker 

2 = passive movement when you eliminate the force of gravity

3 = active movement against gravity

4 = active movement against gravity and resistance

5 = normal power

 

You assess pover at each of the following myotomes in the leg:

L2 = hip flexion

L3 = knee extension 

L4 = ankle dorsiflexion 

L5 = big toe extension 

S1 = ankle plantar flexion 

 

So this patient's L3 myotome has a power grading of 1

Question: Your next patient made an appointment over the phone, complaining of a rash that she is worried might be chicken pox. Chicken pox is caused by a primary infection with Varicella Zoster Virus. If the patient is correct, what will the rash look like when you examine her later?
Explanation:
This is based on the rash aspect of case 9:

Maculopapular rashes (made of flattened red macules and raised hemicircular papules) are caused by measles, enteroviruses, rubella, dengue fever, typhoid, CMV and HIV among others. 

Vesicular rashes (blister-like) are caused by VZV (in both chicken pox and shingles), hand foot and mouth disease, herpangina. 

Petechial and haemorrhagic (tiny red/purple spots) rashes are the same thing, and occur in meningococcal septicaemia and septicaemia with DIC. 

Erythematous (blotchy red skin) rashes are caused by scarlet fever, lyme disease, toxic shock syndrome and human erythrovirus.

Question:
While shadowing on the cardiology ward, you are handed an ECG by one of the consultants, that states... “you should be able to see what the problem is by now...”

 

Feeling worried and panicked, you gaze at the ECG and notice that the QT interval is longer, and that the QRS complex seems to be broader than usual.

 

Thinking back to your time in year 1 and 2, you try and recall some of the causes of abnormal ECG findings like this. Which on of the following is most likely?
Explanation:
In this question, I was trying to get you to think about the relations between ECG traces and the Ventricular Myocardial action potential graphs.

 

In ECG:

P wave = atrial systole/depolarisation

QRS complex = ventricular systole/depolarisation

T wave = ventricular repolarisation

 

Relating this to our action potentials:

 

Phase 1 is ventricular depolarisation - therefore QRS....

(so, an increase in QRS width tells us that there is something happening to slow down the rate of depolarisation)

 

Phase 2 is the time between depolarisation and repolarisation - so, it is represented by the isovolumteric line between the end of the QRS and the start of T wave. This is the ST Segment. Note, it is isocvolumetric because there is no net change in membrane potential in Phase 2.

 

Finally, Phase 3 = T wave.

 

So, Flecaininde is the most appropriate answer here because it is a drug that slows down depolarisation during phase 1. This would increase the width of the QRS.

 

Answers A and B would increase the length of Phase 3, affecting theT wave and the QT interval (hence, LONG QT). Note, LQT3 can also cause a similar outcome to flecainide use as it is a problem with the INa current in Phase 1. 

 

Please add any extra details I have forgotten!

Question: You are on placement in a genetics clinic, and the consultant you are shadowing starts to talk to you about the different kinds of gene testing we can do now compared to when he graduated. Which of the following the is most sensitive type of genetic test?
Explanation:
Taken from Chromosomal Abnormalities:

DNA sequencing is the most sensitive genetic test, followed by MLPA, and finally cytogenic tests that look at the whole genome - such as FISH and Array CGH. These less sensitive genetic tests are much less appropriate if you're looking for a tiny mutation because they scan the genome in at a much lower resolution (so can only pick up bigger abnormalities).

Question:
Patient X is a 45-year-old male with Hepatitis B. The consultant you shadow reminds you of the different phases of hep B infection as shown by the options below. The following blood test is also of patient X.

  • ALT: Normal
  • HBeAg: +Ve
  • Anti-HBeAg: -Ve
  • Hep B DNA levels: 26,000 (<2,000 UI/L)

Which stage of Hep B infection is Patient X most likely in?
Explanation:
Explanation (taken from BMJ)

 

Immune tolerance phase
The immune tolerance phase usually occurs during the initial 15-30 years of infection and is shown by positivity to hepatitis B e antigen (HBeAg), high hepatitis B virus DNA levels, but normal alanine aminotransferase levels. Treatment is not usually indicated, and children, adolescents, and young adults in particular can be monitored in general practice. Monitoring of alanine aminotransferase levels, HBeAg, and anti-HBe at least every six months has been recommended, with specialist referral if fluctuations in alanine aminotransferase levels are observed. Around 1.7-4.5% of children and adolescents infected at birth have cirrhosis at liver biopsy and hepatocellular carcinoma can occur.

 

Immune clearance phase
The immune clearance phase is associated with positivity for HBeAg, high levels of hepatitis B virus DNA (usually >20 000 IU/mL, and increased alanine aminotransferase levels. During this phase, patients may spontaneously seroconvert from being positive to negative for HBeAg with development of antibodies to HBeAg (anti-HBe). A prolonged immune clearance phase may be associated with progressive fibrosis and development of cirrhosis. These patients require specialist review and consideration of antiviral treatment with the aim of reducing progression to cirrhosis, liver failure, and hepatocellular carcinoma.

 

Immune control phase
The immune control phase is characterised by being negative for HBeAg, positive for anti-HBe, low or undetectable levels of hepatitis B virus DNA (usually <2000 IU/mL) and alanine aminotransferase levels within normal range. These patients usually do not require specialist review unless cirrhosis is a concern. Surveillance for liver cancer by ultrasonography every six months may be indicated. Patients in this phase are sometimes referred to as inactive carriers.

 

Immune escape phase
The immune escape phase represents reactivation of the hepatitis B virus and is characterised by chronic infection with negativity for HBeAg, increased levels of hepatitis B virus DNA (usually >2000 IU/mL), and fluctuating alanine aminotransferase levels. Such patients are at high risk of progression to cirrhosis, liver failure, and hepatocellular carcinoma, and require specialist review.

Question: What is wallerian degeneration?
OptionA: Degeneration due to overactivity of osteoblasts compared with osteoclasts, leading to disordered, weak and woven bone being played down. This increases the risk of fracture
OptionB: The process where a nerve is cut or crushed and the portion distal to the injury begins to degenerate.
OptionC: The process of autoimmune mediated break down of the parathyroid gland causing hypoparathyroidism
OptionD: Slow degeneration of the intervertebral disc beginning with chemical changes in the lubricant gel and sclerosis of the fibrous capsule.
OptionE: Degeneration of the bone associated with Osteomalacaemia (Rickets) where insufficient calcium and phosphate means osteoid cannot be mineralised, meaning bone is more soft and pliable.
Explanation:
A - Paget's disease

 

B - Correct

 

C - Made up

 

D - Spondylosis

 

E - Pathology of rickets but not called wallerian degeneration

Question:
You are sitting in the Main Building Library because you heard that there might a conference buffet you might be able to scavenge from downstairs. Having never entered this library before, you look around in bewilderment at how attractive a library it is. This being said, unlike the Cochrane building, there does seem to be a deficiency of sockets which makes you fear for your pathetic laptop battery life. You start thinking about your own heart's electrical current and start to wonder how an ECG works.

 

 

During a ventricular action potential phase2 represents the movement of K+ ions out of the heart and Ca2+ into the heart. Which of the following ECG features represents this?
Explanation:
Phase 2 of the ventricular action potential is represented by the ST interval. This is because there is no net movement ion due to influx of calcium and efflux of potassium. This means there is no change in potential difference, represented by the isoeletric ST interval. Changes to the length of the ST interval will correlate with changes in the length of the effective refractory period of the AP. For example, when given K+ channel blockers, one would expect to see an increase in the ST interval. http://www.cvpharmacology.com/antiarrhy/potassium-blockers

 

See the basis of cardiac arrhythmias for more.
Tags: Data interpretation, ECG, Cardiology, Cardiovascular system, Case 13

• The placenta at term is a disk about 20 cm in diameter, 3 cm thick, and weighs about 500 g (about one-sixth of the fetal weight). A ratio markedly different than this indicates a pathologic condition.

Question: Which cells produce hCG which maintains the corpus luteum by day 9 post-fertilistion?
Explanation:
If the egg is fertilized and implantation occurs, the syncytiotrophoblast (derived from trophoblast) cells of the blastocyst secrete the hormone human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG, or a similar hormone in other species) by day 9 post-fertilization.

 

Human chorionic gonadotropin signals the corpus luteum to continue progesterone secretion, thereby maintaining the thick lining (endometrium) of the uterus and providing an area rich in blood vessels in which the zygote(s) can develop. From this point on, the corpus luteum is called the corpus luteum graviditatis.

Question:
(corrected:)

 

Martin is a 47 year old man who presents at the GP with back pain. He normally works at a gardening centre and a few days ago was picking something up when he was distracted and turned; he "felt something buckle" in his back and has felt a lot of pain since, around his right buttock and generally the area around his right hip. When you ask him if he's noticed any changes - to his walking, for example - he says he's tripped going up the stairs once or twice and has banged his right foot. The pain has been pretty bad and he wants you help him as soon as possible.

 

On examination Martin has reduced sensation on the medial aspect of his leg below the knee and compared to his left foot, his right dorsiflexes quite weakly.

 

 

Which spinal nerve root is most likely affected?
Explanation:
(corrected myotomes:) Sensory and motor deficits are explicitly in the examination section which should tell you Martin is suffering with right L4 nerve compression (Answer 'C'). This is more or less practice reasoning from a lower limb neurological examination.

 

  • The actions I use as a mnemonic in this exam are 'kicking a football'. L2 for flexing at the hip; L3 for extending at the knee; L4 for dorsiflexing the foot; L5 for extending/dorsiflexing the big toe; S1 for plantarflexing the foot.
  • Since Martin cannot dorsiflex his foot with full power we should already be thinking L4; in addition the sensory deficit he is experiencing on the medial aspect of his shin should reinforce that it is L4 being affected.
  • Finally, if Martin is having trouble feeling and plantarflexing his right foot it's reasonable that he's banged it and that it could have caused him to trip going up the stairs - he might have caught it on the lip of the steps.

NB clinically L5/S1 disc slippages with a trapped S1 spinal nerve root (and consequent sciatica) are the most common.
Tags: back pain, Case 14, neurology, Spine, Clinical skills

Question: What abnormality does this ECG show?
Explanation:
Sorry about the size of the ECG, but I wanted to make sure it was clear enough

 

This ECG shows LVH:

Markedly increased LV voltages: huge R and S waves that overlap with the adjacent leads (SV2 + RV6 >> 35 mm - Soklov-Lyon Criteria).
R-wave peak time > 50 ms in V5-6 with associated QRS broadening.
LV strain pattern with ST depression and T-wave inversions in I, aVL and V5-6.
ST elevation in V1-3.
Prominent U waves in V1-3.
Left axis deviation.

(https://lifeinthefastlane.com/ecg-library/basics/left-ventricular-hypertrophy/)

 

Note: In severe LVH, the ECG is similar to that of LBBB - you can tell its LVH due to the excessively high voltages in the LV.

 

Soklov-Lyon criteria:

Depth of the deepest S wave in V1

Height of the tallest R wave in V5 or V6

If the sum of these two figures exceeds 35mm, then LVH is present.

Question: The synacthen test is used to diagnose which endocrine condition?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer. It involves administering synthetic ACH to check response of adrenal glands. Patients with Addison's would not respond well (measured by low cortisol after 30 and 60 minutes).

 

Cushing's diagnose can be confirmed by Dexamethasone suppression test. Dexamethasone is given at night (approx. 10pm) and cortisol is measure in the morning. If its higher than normal ranges -->positive for Cushing's

 

A-Fabry's is not an endocrine disorder. It's an x-linked recessive condition linked with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.

 

Grave's is diagnosed by bloods: high T4 and T3, Low TSH, and anti-TSHR antibodies

 

Acromegaly diagnosis is confirmed by oral glucose tolerance test whilst measuring insulin-like growth factor. Glucose drink given and Growth hormone measured - if stays well above baseline after the 2 hour measurement -->acromegaly.

Question:
A 24 year-old patient presents to your GP surgery with a history of major depression and has previously been placed on citalopram (which he has stopped taking). He reports feeling low, tired and anxious. He is concerned that God is acting against him after his train was delayed. 

 

This is an example of what type of delusion:
Explanation:
https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/delusion

 

"The notion of a primary delusion arising from a preceding primary delusion (delusional mood) is confusing but as Sims (1995) points out, the core of a primary delusion is that it is not understandable (and not any temporal relationship). Sudden delusional ideas are also classified as primary delusions (Fish 1967).

 

Secondary delusions are easier to understand as they arise from other affects, such as depression, and from phenomena, such as hallucinations. Thus, secondary delusions are always interpretations, and are psychologically reducible, for example grandiose delusions in mania or persecutory delusions secondary to hallucinations."

 

A) incorrect: primary delusion is one with no reasonable basis and is hard to determine where the patient has comer from with there ideas

B) corrected: secondary delusion is based on the patient's experience and has be derived from another cause for example having a delusional belief after a hallucination. In this case the patient's low mood and anxiety has caused him to become delusion about his experience

C) incorrect: tertiary delusions don't exist 

D) incorrect: illusions are sensory information that is misinterpreted and perceived to be something it is not

E) incorrect: hallucination is when a patients senses something that is not present

Question: How many vertebrae are in the human spine?
Explanation: In humans vertebral column there are normally thirty-three vertebrae; the upper twenty-four are articulating and separated from each other by intervertebral discs, and the lower nine are fused in adults, five in the sacrum and four in the coccyx or tailbone. The articulating vertebrae are named according to their region of the spine. There are seven cervical vertebrae, twelve thoracic vertebrae and five lumbar vertebrae. The number of vertebrae in a region can vary but overall the number remains the same. The number of those in the cervical region however is only rarely changed.

Question:
The result of a patients blood test comes in. However, the biochem departments printer was not working properly and missed out one test and its result, but showed the reference range for all tests. What is the most likely option to have caused these results?

 

Blood results

  • Na+ = 134 (Reference range: 135-145 meQ/L)
  • K+ = 4 (3.5-5 meQ/L)
  • Cl- = 105 (98 -106 meQ/L)
  • HCO3- = 17 (22-28 meQ/L)
  • Anion GAP = missing result (reference range: 3-11 meQ/L)
Explanation:
Explanation:

  • Firstly you must find the anion gap, since you have all the data you need to calculate this. This is all positive ions - negative ions.
  • Hence, (134+4)-(105+17) = 138-122 = 16 meQ/L. This level is over the reference range, hence you have a raised anion gap.
  • A raised anion gap is an indicator of metabolic acidosis.
  • A normal anion gap is an indicator of chloride excess or bicarbonate loss with replacement of negative ions.

A, B, C and E are examples of normal anion GAP.

Hypoxia can induce lactate formation, which would give rise to metabolic acidosis and raised anion GAP.

 

I didn't understand anion gaps, but this video on youtube was a life saver: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sQnEFVNrY74
